"{\n    \"[1, 2]\": [\n        [\n            48497,\n            \"\\u201d CHAPTER XIII The Honourable John Yates, this new friend, had not much to recommend him beyond habits of fashion and expense, and being the younger son of a lord with a tolerable independence;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48535,\n            \"and Sir Thomas would probably have thought his introduction at Mansfield by no means desirable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48551,\n            \"Mr. Bertram\\u2019s acquaintance with him had begun at Weymouth, where they had spent ten days together in the same society, and the friendship, if friendship it might be called, had been proved and perfected by Mr. Yates\\u2019 s being invited to take Mansfield in his way, whenever he could, and by his promising to come;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48683,\n            \"and the play in which he had borne a part was within two days of representation, when the sudden death of one of the nearest connexions of the family had destroyed the scheme and dispersed the performers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48834,\n            \"Happily for him, a love of the theatre is so general, an itch for acting so strong among young people, that he could hardly out-talk the interest of his hearers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48909,\n            \"The play had been Lovers\\u2019 Vows, and Mr. Yates was to have been Count Cassel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48967,\n            \"Lord Ravenshaw and the duke had appropriated the only two characters worth playing before I reached Ecclesford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48985,\n            \"and though Lord Ravenshaw offered to resign his to me, it was impossible to take it, you know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49006,\n            \"I was sorry for _ him _ that he should have so mistaken his powers, for he was no more equal to the Baron \\u2014 a little man with a weak voice, always hoarse after the first ten minutes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49369,\n            \"and to make _ you _ amends, Yates, I think we must raise a little theatre at Mansfield, and ask you to be our manager.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50190,\n            \"Maria, Julia, Henry Crawford, and Mr. Yates were in the billiard-room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53253,\n            \"Here are two capital tragic parts for Yates and Crawford, and here is the rhyming Butler for me, if nobody else wants it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53368,\n            \"Mr. Yates was particularly pleased: he had been sighing and longing to do the Baron at Ecclesford, had grudged every rant of Lord Ravenshaw\\u2019s, and been forced to re-rant it all in his own room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53412,\n            \"The storm through Baron Wildenheim was the height of his theatrical ambition;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53454,\n            \"To do him justice, however, he did not resolve to appropriate it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53469,\n            \"for remembering that there was some very good ranting-ground in Frederick, he professed an equal willingness for that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53519,\n            \"Miss Bertram, feeling all the interest of an Agatha in the question, took on her to decide it, by observing to Mr. Yates that this was a point in which height and figure ought to be considered, and that _ his _ being the tallest, seemed to fit him peculiarly for the Baron.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53674,\n            \"Amelia and Agatha may do for Maria and me, but here is nothing for your sister, Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53696,\n            \"\\u201d Mr. Crawford desired _ that _ might not be thought of: he was very sure his sister had no wish of acting but as she might be useful, and that she would not allow herself to be considered in the present case.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55222,\n            \"but her brother soon returned to business and Lovers\\u2019 Vows, and was eagerly looking over the play, with Mr. Yates\\u2019 s help, to ascertain what scenery would be necessary \\u2014 while Maria and Henry Crawford conversed together in an under-voice, and the declaration with which she began of, \\u201cI am sure I would give up the part to Julia most willingly, but that though I shall probably do it very ill, I feel persuaded _ she _ would do it worse,\\u201dwas doubtless receiving all the compliments it called for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55328,\n            \"When this had lasted some time, the division of the party was completed by Tom Bertram and Mr. Yates walking off together to consult farther in the room now beginning to be called _ the _ _ Theatre _, and Miss Bertram\\u2019s resolving to go down to the Parsonage herself with the offer of Amelia to Miss Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57618,\n            \"Mr. Yates, who was trying to make himself agreeable to Julia, found her gloom less impenetrable on any topic than that of his regret at her secession from their company;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57707,\n            \"and the spirits of evening giving fresh courage, Tom, Maria, and Mr. Yates, soon after their being reassembled in the drawing-room, seated themselves in committee at a separate table, with the play open before them, and were just getting deep in the subject when a most welcome interruption was given by the entrance of Mr. and Miss Crawford, who, late and dark and dirty as it was, could not help coming, and were received with the most grateful joy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70250,\n            \"The Crawfords were more warm on the subject than Mr. Yates, from better understanding the family, and judging more clearly of the mischief that must ensue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70366,\n            \"and having soon agreed on the propriety of their walking quietly home and leaving the family to themselves, proposed Mr. Yates\\u2019 s accompanying them and spending the evening at the Parsonage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70433,\n            \"and therefore, thanking them, said, \\u201che preferred remaining where he was, that he might pay his respects to the old gentleman handsomely since he _ was _ come;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70467,\n            \"and besides, he did not think it would be fair by the others to have everybody run away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71439,\n            \"Not that _ she _ was incommoded by many fears of Sir Thomas\\u2019 s disapprobation when the present state of his house should be known, for her judgment had been so blinded that, except by the instinctive caution with which she had whisked away Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s pink satin cloak as her brother-in-law entered, she could hardly be said to shew any sign of alarm;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72344,\n            \"\\u201cIt is time to think of our visitors,\\u201dsaid Maria, still feeling her hand pressed to Henry Crawford\\u2019s heart, and caring little for anything else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72431,\n            \"\\u201d To the theatre he went, and reached it just in time to witness the first meeting of his father and his friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72567,\n            \"He stepped to the door, rejoicing at that moment in having the means of immediate communication, and, opening it, found himself on the stage of a theatre, and opposed to a ranting young man, who appeared likely to knock him down backwards.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72668,\n            \"His father\\u2019s looks of solemnity and amazement on this his first appearance on any stage, and the gradual metamorphosis of the impassioned Baron Wildenheim into the well-bred and easy Mr. Yates, making his bow and apology to Sir Thomas Bertram, was such an exhibition, such a piece of true acting, as he would not have lost upon any account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72817,\n            \"Sir Thomas received Mr. Yates with all the appearance of cordiality which was due to his own character, but was really as far from pleased with the necessity of the acquaintance as with the manner of its commencement.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72858,\n            \"Mr. Yates\\u2019 s family and connexions were sufficiently known to him to render his introduction as the \\u201cparticular friend,\\u201danother of the hundred particular friends of his son, exceedingly unwelcome;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72895,\n            \"and it needed all the felicity of being again at home, and all the forbearance it could supply, to save Sir Thomas from anger on finding himself thus bewildered in his own house, making part of a ridiculous exhibition in the midst of theatrical nonsense, and forced in so untoward a moment to admit the acquaintance of a young man whom he felt sure of disapproving, and whose easy indifference and volubility in the course of the first five minutes seemed to mark him the most at home of the two.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73100,\n            \"and Sir Thomas having exerted himself so far as to speak a few words of calm approbation in reply to an eager appeal of Mr. Yates, as to the happiness of the arrangement, the three gentlemen returned to the drawing-room together, Sir Thomas with an increase of gravity which was not lost on all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73187,\n            \"Its vicinity to my own room \\u2014 but in every respect, indeed, it took me by surprise, as I had not the smallest suspicion of your acting having assumed so serious a character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73273,\n            \"but Mr. Yates, without discernment to catch Sir Thomas\\u2019 s meaning, or diffidence, or delicacy, or discretion enough to allow him to lead the discourse while he mingled among the others with the least obtrusiveness himself, would keep him on the topic of the theatre, would torment him with questions and remarks relative to it, and finally would make him hear the whole history of his disappointment at Ecclesford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73352,\n            \"Sir Thomas listened most politely, but found much to offend his ideas of decorum, and confirm his ill-opinion of Mr. Yates\\u2019 s habits of thinking, from the beginning to the end of the story;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76162,\n            \"Mr. Yates was beginning now to understand Sir Thomas\\u2019 s intentions, though as far as ever from understanding their source.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76186,\n            \"He and his friend had been out with their guns the chief of the morning, and Tom had taken the opportunity of explaining, with proper apologies for his father\\u2019s particularity, what was to be expected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76259,\n            \"and his indignation was such, that had it not been for delicacy towards his friend, and his friend\\u2019s youngest sister, he believed he should certainly attack the baronet on the absurdity of his proceedings, and argue him into a little more rationality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76326,\n            \"but there was a something in Sir Thomas, when they sat round the same table, which made Mr. Yates think it wiser to let him pursue his own way, and feel the folly of it without opposition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76368,\n            \"He had known many disagreeable fathers before, and often been struck with the inconveniences they occasioned, but never, in the whole course of his life, had he seen one of that class so unintelligibly moral, so infamously tyrannical as Sir Thomas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77620,\n            \"In _ his _ departure Sir Thomas felt the chief interest: wanting to be alone with his family, the presence of a stranger superior to Mr. Yates must have been irksome;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77673,\n            \"In himself he was wearisome, but as the friend of Tom and the admirer of Julia he became offensive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77694,\n            \"Sir Thomas had been quite indifferent to Mr. Crawford\\u2019s going or staying: but his good wishes for Mr. Yates\\u2019 s having a pleasant journey, as he walked with him to the hall-door, were given with genuine satisfaction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77780,\n            \"and Sir Thomas hoped, in seeing him out of it, to be rid of the worst object connected with the scheme, and the last that must be inevitably reminding him of its existence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89606,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd Mr. Yates, I presume, is not far off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89629,\n            \"we hear nothing of Mr. Yates.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89637,\n            \"I do not imagine he figures much in the letters to Mansfield Park;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89657,\n            \"I think my friend Julia knows better than to entertain her father with Mr. Yates.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188392,\n            \"and had not her sister\\u2019s conduct burst forth as it did, and her increased dread of her father and of home, on that event, imagining its certain consequence to herself would be greater severity and restraint, made her hastily resolve on avoiding such immediate horrors at all risks, it is probable that Mr. Yates would never have succeeded.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 3]\": [\n        [\n            64835,\n            \"I often think of Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s property and independence, and wish them in other hands;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64855,\n            \"but I never think of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64884,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI dare say he _ will _ be in parliament soon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65171,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI would not give much for Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s chance if Henry stept in before the articles were signed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79616,\n            \"Not all his good-will for Mr. Rushworth, not all Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s deference for him, could prevent him from soon discerning some part of the truth \\u2014 that Mr. Rushworth was an inferior young man, as ignorant in business as in books, with opinions in general unfixed, and without seeming much aware of it himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80335,\n            \"and retired in proud resolve, determined only to behave more cautiously to Mr. Rushworth in future, that her father might not be again suspecting her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80922,\n            \"Nothing could be objected to when it came under the discussion of the neighbourhood, except that the carriage which conveyed the bride and bridegroom and Julia from the church-door to Sotherton was the same chaise which Mr. Rushworth had used for a twelvemonth before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81255,\n            \"Some other companion than Mr. Rushworth was of the first consequence to his lady;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81513,\n            \"In that house, which she had hardly entered twice a year since Mr. Norris\\u2019 s death, she became a welcome, an invited guest, and in the gloom and dirt of a November day, most acceptable to Mary Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81954,\n            \"The two sisters were so kind to her, and so pleasant, that Fanny might have enjoyed her visit could she have believed herself not in the way, and could she have foreseen that the weather would certainly clear at the end of the hour, and save her from the shame of having Dr. Grant\\u2019s carriage and horses out to take her home, with which she was threatened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89566,\n            \"Rushworth and his fair bride are at Brighton, I understand;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89757,\n            \"\\u201d And then changing his tone again to one of gentle gallantry, and addressing Fanny, he said, \\u201cYou were Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s best friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170540,\n            \"I saw him draw back surprised, and I was sorry that Mrs. Rushworth should resent any former supposed slight to Miss Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170599,\n            \"I dined twice in Wimpole Street, and might have been there oftener, but it is mortifying to be with Rushworth as a brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176519,\n            \"I am sure it will be all hushed up, and nothing proved but Rushworth\\u2019s folly.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 4]\": [\n        [\n            38859,\n            \"but she had just satisfied herself that it was not those she wanted, when Miss Bertram, Mr. Rushworth, and Mr. Crawford issued from the same path which she had trod herself, and were before her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39060,\n            \"After some minutes spent in this way, Miss Bertram, observing the iron gate, expressed a wish of passing through it into the park, that their views and their plans might be more comprehensive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39228,\n            \"and as Miss Bertram\\u2019s inclination for so doing did by no means lessen, it ended in Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s declaring outright that he would go and fetch the key.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39360,\n            \"And to tell you the truth,\\u201dspeaking rather lower, \\u201cI do not think that _ I _ shall ever see Sotherton again with so much pleasure as I do now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39404,\n            \"\\u201d After a moment\\u2019s embarrassment the lady replied, \\u201cYou are too much a man of the world not to see with the eyes of the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39435,\n            \"If other people think Sotherton improved, I have no doubt that you will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39534,\n            \"I was glad to see you so well entertained.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39640,\n            \"I could not have hoped to entertain you with Irish anecdotes during a ten miles\\u2019 drive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40378,\n            \"Why, child, I have but this moment escaped from his horrible mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40901,\n            \"\\u201cMiss Bertram thought you would follow her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41372,\n            \"She followed their steps along the bottom walk, and had just turned up into another, when the voice and the laugh of Miss Crawford once more caught her ear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41875,\n            \"It was late before the Miss Bertrams and the two gentlemen came in, and their ramble did not appear to have been more than partially agreeable, or at all productive of anything useful with regard to the object of the day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42006,\n            \"Mr. Crawford and Miss Bertram were much more gay, and she thought that he was taking particular pains, during dinner, to do away any little resentment of the other two, and restore general good-humour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42223,\n            \"but her conviction of being really the one preferred comforted her under it, and enabled her to receive Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s parting attentions as she ought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72668,\n            \"His father\\u2019s looks of solemnity and amazement on this his first appearance on any stage, and the gradual metamorphosis of the impassioned Baron Wildenheim into the well-bred and easy Mr. Yates, making his bow and apology to Sir Thomas Bertram, was such an exhibition, such a piece of true acting, as he would not have lost upon any account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75284,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI know how great, how justly great, your influence is with Lady Bertram and her children, and am the more concerned that it should not have been \\u2014\\u201d\\u201cMy dear Sir Thomas, if you had seen the state of the roads _ that _ day!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89284,\n            \"She could not compliment the newly arrived gentleman, however, with any appearance of interest, in a scheme for extending his stay at Mansfield, and sending for his hunters from Norfolk, which, suggested by Dr. Grant, advised by Edmund, and warmly urged by the two sisters, was soon in possession of his mind, and which he seemed to want to be encouraged even by her to resolve on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89408,\n            \"Her two absent cousins, especially Maria, were much in her thoughts on seeing him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89435,\n            \"Here he was again on the same ground where all had passed before, and apparently as willing to stay and be happy without the Miss Bertrams, as if he had never known Mansfield in any other state.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89475,\n            \"She heard them spoken of by him only in a general way, till they were all re-assembled in the drawing-room, when Edmund, being engaged apart in some matter of business with Dr. Grant, which seemed entirely to engross them, and Mrs. Grant occupied at the tea-table, he began talking of them with more particularity to his other sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89657,\n            \"I think my friend Julia knows better than to entertain her father with Mr. Yates.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90125,\n            \"Not that we would have endangered his safety by any tremendous weather \\u2014 but only by a steady contrary wind, or a calm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90182,\n            \"and Fanny, averting her face, said, with a firmer tone than usual, \\u201cAs far as _ I _ am concerned, sir, I would not have delayed his return for a day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90221,\n            \"My uncle disapproved it all so entirely when he did arrive, that in my opinion everything had gone quite far enough.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90244,\n            \"\\u201d She had never spoken so much at once to him in her life before, and never so angrily to any one;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90428,\n            \"Dr. Grant is giving Bertram instructions about the living he is to step into so soon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90446,\n            \"I find he takes orders in a few weeks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90466,\n            \"I am glad to hear Bertram will be so well off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90498,\n            \"I apprehend he will not have less than seven hundred a year.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90656,\n            \"Bertram is certainly well off for a cadet of even a baronet\\u2019s family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90752,\n            \"\\u201cBertram,\\u201dsaid Henry Crawford, \\u201cI shall make a point of coming to Mansfield to hear you preach your first sermon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90795,\n            \"Miss Price, will not you join me in encouraging your cousin?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90808,\n            \"Will not you engage to attend with your eyes steadily fixed on him the whole time \\u2014 as I shall do \\u2014 not to lose a word;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90864,\n            \"You must preach at Mansfield, you know, that Sir Thomas and Lady Bertram may hear you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96145,\n            \"\\u201cI told you I lost my way after passing that old farmhouse with the yew-trees, because I can never bear to ask;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96172,\n            \"but I have not told you that, with my usual luck \\u2014 for I never do wrong without gaining by it \\u2014 I found myself in due time in the very place which I had a curiosity to see.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97767,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMr. Bertram,\\u201dsaid Miss Crawford, a few minutes afterwards, \\u201cyou know Henry to be such a capital improver, that you cannot possibly engage in anything of the sort at Thornton Lacey without accepting his help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97906,\n            \"With something of consciousness he shook his head at his sister, and laughingly replied, \\u201cI cannot say there was much done at Sotherton;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163769,\n            \"for as to any partnership in Thornton Lacey, as Edmund Bertram once good-humouredly proposed, I hope I foresee two objections: two fair, excellent, irresistible objections to that plan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163812,\n            \"though when the moment was passed, could regret that she had not forced herself into the acknowledged comprehension of one half of his meaning, and encouraged him to say something more of his sister and Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172660,\n            \"not even Mrs. Price, beyond a brief question or two, if she saw her daughter with a letter in her hand, and now and then the quiet observation of, \\u201cMy poor sister Bertram must be in a great deal of trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172765,\n            \"Three or four Prices might have been swept away, any or all except Fanny and William, and Lady Bertram would have thought little about it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172948,\n            \"Lady Bertram could think nothing less, and Fanny shared her aunt\\u2019s security, till she received a few lines from Edmund, written purposely to give her a clearer idea of his brother\\u2019s situation, and acquaint her with the apprehensions which he and his father had imbibed from the physician with respect to some strong hectic symptoms, which seemed to seize the frame on the departure of the fever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174273,\n            \"and were it only in supporting the spirits of her aunt Bertram, keeping her from the evil of solitude, or the still greater evil of a restless, officious companion, too apt to be heightening danger in order to enhance her own importance, her being there would have been a general good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174804,\n            \"and from what I hear, poor Mr. Bertram has a bad chance of ultimate recovery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174822,\n            \"I thought little of his illness at first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174831,\n            \"I looked upon him as the sort of person to be made a fuss with, and to make a fuss himself in any trifling disorder, and was chiefly concerned for those who had to nurse him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175212,\n            \"I put it to your conscience, whether \\u2018 Sir Edmund\\u2019would not do more good with all the Bertram property than any other possible \\u2018 Sir.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182189,\n            \"Tom\\u2019s complaints had been greatly heightened by the shock of his sister\\u2019s conduct, and his recovery so much thrown back by it, that even Lady Bertram had been struck by the difference, and all her alarms were regularly sent off to her husband;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184868,\n            \"As soon as I could speak, I replied that I had not supposed it possible, coming in such a state of mind into that house as I had done, that anything could occur to make me suffer more, but that she had been inflicting deeper wounds in almost every sentence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184923,\n            \"That though I had, in the course of our acquaintance, been often sensible of some difference in our opinions, on points, too, of some moment, it had not entered my imagination to conceive the difference could be such as she had now proved it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184974,\n            \"That the manner in which she treated the dreadful crime committed by her brother and my sister (with whom lay the greater seduction I pretended not to say), but the manner in which she spoke of the crime itself, giving it every reproach but the right;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185048,\n            \"and last of all, and above all, recommending to us a compliance, a compromise, an acquiescence in the continuance of the sin, on the chance of a marriage which, thinking as I now thought of her brother, should rather be prevented than sought;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185099,\n            \"all this together most grievously convinced me that I had never understood her before, and that, as far as related to mind, it had been the creature of my own imagination, not Miss Crawford, that I had been too apt to dwell on for many months past.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185189,\n            \"And yet, that I must and would confess that, could I have restored her to what she had appeared to me before, I would infinitely prefer any increase of the pain of parting, for the sake of carrying with me the right of tenderness and esteem.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185251,\n            \"but, as you may imagine, not spoken so collectedly or methodically as I have repeated it to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185283,\n            \"I saw her change countenance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185383,\n            \"and when I hear of you next, it may be as a celebrated preacher in some great society of Methodists, or as a missionary into foreign parts.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185432,\n            \"I only said in reply, that from my heart I wished her well, and earnestly hoped that she might soon learn to think more justly, and not owe the most valuable knowledge we could any of us acquire, the knowledge of ourselves and of our duty, to the lessons of affliction, and immediately left the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185513,\n            \"\\u2018 Mr. Bertram,\\u2019said she.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185526,\n            \"\\u2018 Mr. Bertram,\\u2019said she, with a smile;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185594,\n            \"I have since, sometimes, for a moment, regretted that I did not go back, but I know I was right, and such has been the end of our acquaintance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185673,\n            \"\\u201d And such was Fanny\\u2019s dependence on his words, that for five minutes she thought they _ had _ done.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 5]\": [\n        [\n            8132,\n            \"But Tom\\u2019s extravagance had, previous to that event, been so great as to render a different disposal of the next presentation necessary, and the younger brother must help to pay for the pleasures of the elder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8267,\n            \"\\u201cI blush for the expedient which I am driven on, and I trust I may pity your feelings as a brother on the occasion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8322,\n            \"It may hereafter be in my power, or in yours (I hope it will), to procure him better preferment;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8346,\n            \"but it must not be forgotten that no benefit of that sort would have been beyond his natural claims on us, and that nothing can, in fact, be an equivalent for the certain advantage which he is now obliged to forego through the urgency of your debts.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8407,\n            \"but escaping as quickly as possible, could soon with cheerful selfishness reflect, firstly, that he had not been half so much in debt as some of his friends;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14073,\n            \"Sir Thomas\\u2019 s sending away his son seemed to her so like a parent\\u2019s care, under the influence of a foreboding of evil to himself, that she could not help feeling dreadful presentiments;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17927,\n            \"She acknowledged, however, that the Mr. Bertrams were very fine young men, that two such young men were not often seen together even in London, and that their manners, particularly those of the eldest, were very good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18011,\n            \"She had felt an early presentiment that she _ should _ like the eldest best.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18129,\n            \"She looked about her with due consideration, and found almost everything in his favour: a park, a real park, five miles round, a spacious modern-built house, so well placed and well screened as to deserve to be in any collection of engravings of gentlemen\\u2019s seats in the kingdom, and wanting only to be completely new furnished \\u2014 pleasant sisters, a quiet mother, and an agreeable man himself \\u2014 with the advantage of being tied up from much gaming at present by a promise to his father, and of being Sir Thomas hereafter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18242,\n            \"she believed she should accept him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18249,\n            \"and she began accordingly to interest herself a little about the horse which he had to run at the B \\u2014 \\u2014 races.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18273,\n            \"These races were to call him away not long after their acquaintance began;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18321,\n            \"Much was said on his side to induce her to attend the races, and schemes were made for a large party to them, with all the eagerness of inclination, but it would only do to be talked of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18823,\n            \"Mr. Bertram, I dare say _ you _ have sometimes met with such changes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19005,\n            \"When Anderson first introduced me to his family, about two years ago, his sister was not _ out _, and I could not get her to speak to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19928,\n            \"\\u201d CHAPTER VI Mr. Bertram set off for \\u2014 \\u2014 \\u2014 \\u2014, and Miss Crawford was prepared to find a great chasm in their society, and to miss him decidedly in the meetings which were now becoming almost daily between the families;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19974,\n            \"and on their all dining together at the Park soon after his going, she retook her chosen place near the bottom of the table, fully expecting to feel a most melancholy difference in the change of masters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20812,\n            \"but if dear Sir Thomas were here, he could tell you what improvements we made: and a great deal more would have been done, but for poor Mr. Norris\\u2019 s sad state of health.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20852,\n            \"He could hardly ever get out, poor man, to enjoy anything, and _ that _ disheartened me from doing several things that Sir Thomas and I used to talk of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21026,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cSir, it is a Moor Park, we bought it as a Moor Park, and it cost us \\u2014 that is, it was a present from Sir Thomas, but I saw the bill \\u2014 and I know it cost seven shillings, and was charged as a Moor Park.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47262,\n            \"I wonder my son did not propose it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48058,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy dear Tom,\\u201dcried his aunt soon afterwards, \\u201cas you are not dancing, I dare say you will have no objection to join us in a rubber;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48096,\n            \"\\u201d Then leaving her seat, and coming to him to enforce the proposal, added in a whisper, \\u201cWe want to make a table for Mrs. Rushworth, you know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48155,\n            \"Now, you and I and Dr. Grant will just do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48168,\n            \"and though _ we _ play but half-crowns, you know, you may bet half-guineas with _ him _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48255,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny was led off very willingly, though it was impossible for her to feel much gratitude towards her cousin, or distinguish, as he certainly did, between the selfishness of another person and his own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48295,\n            \"\\u201cA pretty modest request upon my word,\\u201dhe indignantly exclaimed as they walked away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48313,\n            \"\\u201cTo want to nail me to a card-table for the next two hours with herself and Dr. Grant, who are always quarrelling, and that poking old woman, who knows no more of whist than of algebra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48357,\n            \"I wish my good aunt would be a little less busy!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48497,\n            \"\\u201d CHAPTER XIII The Honourable John Yates, this new friend, had not much to recommend him beyond habits of fashion and expense, and being the younger son of a lord with a tolerable independence;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50087,\n            \"and though nothing was settled but that Tom Bertram would prefer a comedy, and his sisters and Henry Crawford a tragedy, and that nothing in the world could be easier than to find a piece which would please them all, the resolution to act something or other seemed so decided as to make Edmund quite uncomfortable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50208,\n            \"Tom, returning from them into the drawing-room, where Edmund was standing thoughtfully by the fire, while Lady Bertram was on the sofa at a little distance, and Fanny close beside her arranging her work, thus began as he entered \\u2014 \\u201cSuch a horribly vile billiard-table as ours is not to be met with, I believe, above ground.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50946,\n            \"Well, Edmund,\\u201dhe continued, returning to the former subject, posture, and voice, as soon as Lady Bertram began to nod again, \\u201cbut _ this _ I _ will _ maintain, that we shall be doing no harm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50994,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI cannot agree with you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51002,\n            \"I am convinced that my father would totally disapprove it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51209,\n            \"\\u201cI know my father as well as you do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51220,\n            \"and I\\u2019ll take care that his daughters do nothing to distress him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51235,\n            \"Manage your own concerns, Edmund, and I\\u2019ll take care of the rest of the family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51255,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf you are resolved on acting,\\u201dreplied the persevering Edmund, \\u201cI must hope it will be in a very small and quiet way;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51345,\n            \"I have quite as great an interest in being careful of his house as you can have;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51363,\n            \"and as to such alterations as I was suggesting just now, such as moving a bookcase, or unlocking a door, or even as using the billiard-room for the space of a week without playing at billiards in it, you might just as well suppose he would object to our sitting more in this room, and less in the breakfast-room, than we did before he went away, or to my sister\\u2019s pianoforte being moved from one side of the room to the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51644,\n            \"\\u201d Tom walked out of the room as he said it, and Edmund was left to sit down and stir the fire in thoughtful vexation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51789,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI dare say she would, but she has no influence with either Tom or my sisters that could be of any use;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51859,\n            \"\\u201d His sisters, to whom he had an opportunity of speaking the next morning, were quite as impatient of his advice, quite as unyielding to his representation, quite as determined in the cause of pleasure, as Tom.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52614,\n            \"on the comic, Tom Bertram, not _ quite _ alone, because it was evident that Mary Crawford\\u2019s wishes, though politely kept back, inclined the same way: but his determinateness and his power seemed to make allies unnecessary;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52905,\n            \"I shall be happy to be of any use, but I think we could not chuse worse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53081,\n            \"I take any part you chuse to give me, so as it be comic.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53109,\n            \"\\u201d For about the fifth time he then proposed the Heir at Law, doubting only whether to prefer Lord Duberley or Dr. Pangloss for himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53253,\n            \"Here are two capital tragic parts for Yates and Crawford, and here is the rhyming Butler for me, if nobody else wants it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55835,\n            \"but when he entered the drawing-room before dinner, the buzz of discussion was high between Tom, Maria, and Mr. Yates;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56974,\n            \"it is too far settled, everybody would be so disappointed, Tom would be quite angry;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57130,\n            \"I only wish Tom had known his own mind when the carpenters began, for there was the loss of half a day\\u2019s work about those side-doors.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57243,\n            \"I forgot to tell Tom of something that happened to me this very day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57707,\n            \"and the spirits of evening giving fresh courage, Tom, Maria, and Mr. Yates, soon after their being reassembled in the drawing-room, seated themselves in committee at a separate table, with the play open before them, and were just getting deep in the subject when a most welcome interruption was given by the entrance of Mr. and Miss Crawford, who, late and dark and dirty as it was, could not help coming, and were received with the most grateful joy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58365,\n            \"\\u201cDo not you think he would?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58373,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201c_ I _ shall not ask him,\\u201dreplied Tom, in a cold, determined manner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59320,\n            \"Her entreaty had no effect on Tom: he only said again what he had said before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59338,\n            \"and it was not merely Tom, for the requisition was now backed by Maria, and Mr. Crawford, and Mr. Yates, with an urgency which differed from his but in being more gentle or more ceremonious, and which altogether was quite overpowering to Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59945,\n            \"The consultation upon the play still went on, and Miss Crawford\\u2019s attention was first called from Fanny by Tom Bertram\\u2019s telling her, with infinite regret, that he found it absolutely impossible for him to undertake the part of Anhalt in addition to the Butler: he had been most anxiously trying to make it out to be feasible, but it would not do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60055,\n            \"I could name, at this moment, at least six young men within six miles of us, who are wild to be admitted into our company, and there are one or two that would not disgrace us: I should not be afraid to trust either of the Olivers or Charles Maddox.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60111,\n            \"Tom Oliver is a very clever fellow, and Charles Maddox is as gentlemanlike a man as you will see anywhere, so I will take my horse early to-morrow morning and ride over to Stoke, and settle with one of them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60157,\n            \"\\u201d While he spoke, Maria was looking apprehensively round at Edmund in full expectation that he must oppose such an enlargement of the plan as this: so contrary to all their first protestations;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60308,\n            \"Tom repeated his resolution of going to him early on the morrow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60481,\n            \"When the evening was over, she went to bed full of it, her nerves still agitated by the shock of such an attack from her cousin Tom, so public and so persevered in, and her spirits sinking under her aunt\\u2019s unkind reflection and reproach.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60642,\n            \"and if she were applied to again among themselves with all the authoritative urgency that Tom and Maria were capable of, and Edmund perhaps away, what should she do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61809,\n            \"The table between the windows was covered with work-boxes and netting-boxes which had been given her at different times, principally by Tom;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61994,\n            \"They have chosen almost as bad a play as they could, and now, to complete the business, are going to ask the help of a young man very slightly known to any of us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62057,\n            \"but the excessive intimacy which must spring from his being admitted among us in this manner is highly objectionable, the _ more _ than intimacy \\u2014 the familiarity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62789,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf you are against me, I ought to distrust myself, and yet \\u2014 But it is absolutely impossible to let Tom go on in this way, riding about the country in quest of anybody who can be persuaded to act \\u2014 no matter whom: the look of a gentleman is to be enough.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63058,\n            \"If Tom is up, I shall go to him directly and get it over, and when we meet at breakfast we shall be all in high good-humour at the prospect of acting the fool together with such unanimity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63760,\n            \"\\u201cPerhaps,\\u201dsaid Tom, \\u201cFanny may be more disposed to oblige us now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69121,\n            \"Tom, as Cottager, was in despair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72668,\n            \"His father\\u2019s looks of solemnity and amazement on this his first appearance on any stage, and the gradual metamorphosis of the impassioned Baron Wildenheim into the well-bred and easy Mr. Yates, making his bow and apology to Sir Thomas Bertram, was such an exhibition, such a piece of true acting, as he would not have lost upon any account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72992,\n            \"Tom understood his father\\u2019s thoughts, and heartily wishing he might be always as well disposed to give them but partial expression, began to see, more clearly than he had ever done before, that there might be some ground of offence, that there might be some reason for the glance his father gave towards the ceiling and stucco of the room;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73415,\n            \"\\u201cThis was, in fact, the origin of _ our _ acting,\\u201dsaid Tom, after a moment\\u2019s thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76186,\n            \"He and his friend had been out with their guns the chief of the morning, and Tom had taken the opportunity of explaining, with proper apologies for his father\\u2019s particularity, what was to be expected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76259,\n            \"and his indignation was such, that had it not been for delicacy towards his friend, and his friend\\u2019s youngest sister, he believed he should certainly attack the baronet on the absurdity of his proceedings, and argue him into a little more rationality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76793,\n            \"Her sensations were indefinable, and so were they a few minutes afterwards upon hearing Henry Crawford, who had a chair between herself and Tom, ask the latter in an undervoice whether there were any plans for resuming the play after the present happy interruption (with a courteous glance at Sir Thomas), because, in that case, he should make a point of returning to Mansfield at any time required by the party: he was going away immediately, being to meet his uncle at Bath without delay;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76965,\n            \"\\u201cI will attend you from any place in England, at an hour\\u2019s notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77001,\n            \"He could immediately say with easy fluency, \\u201cI am sorry you are going;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77081,\n            \"You will find nobody there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152715,\n            \"then there was a squabble between Sam and Rebecca about the manner of carrying up his sister\\u2019s trunk, which he would manage all his own way;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157455,\n            \"Fanny was very anxious to be useful, and not to appear above her home, or in any way disqualified or disinclined, by her foreign education, from contributing her help to its comforts, and therefore set about working for Sam immediately;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157555,\n            \"Sam, loud and overbearing as he was, she rather regretted when he went, for he was clever and intelligent, and glad to be employed in any errand in the town;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157631,\n            \"and she found that the best of the three younger ones was gone in him: Tom and Charles being at least as many years as they were his juniors distant from that age of feeling and reason, which might suggest the expediency of making friends, and of endeavouring to be less disagreeable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157816,\n            \"Her continual disagreements with her mother, her rash squabbles with Tom and Charles, and petulance with Betsey, were at least so distressing to Fanny that, though admitting they were by no means without provocation, she feared the disposition that could push them to such length must be far from amiable, and from affording any repose to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171690,\n            \"This was a great deal better than to have to take up the pen to acquaint her with all the particulars of the Grants\\u2019 intended journey, for the present intelligence was of a nature to promise occupation for the pen for many days to come, being no less than the dangerous illness of her eldest son, of which they had received notice by express a few hours before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171763,\n            \"Tom had gone from London with a party of young men to Newmarket, where a neglected fall and a good deal of drinking had brought on a fever;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171793,\n            \"and when the party broke up, being unable to move, had been left by himself at the house of one of these young men to the comforts of sickness and solitude, and the attendance only of servants.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171834,\n            \"Instead of being soon well enough to follow his friends, as he had then hoped, his disorder increased considerably, and it was not long before he thought so ill of himself as to be as ready as his physician to have a letter despatched to Mansfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171938,\n            \"and Edmund kindly proposes attending his brother immediately, but I am happy to add that Sir Thomas will not leave me on this distressing occasion, as it would be too trying for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171974,\n            \"We shall greatly miss Edmund in our small circle, but I trust and hope he will find the poor invalid in a less alarming state than might be apprehended, and that he will be able to bring him to Mansfield shortly, which Sir Thomas proposes should be done, and thinks best on every account, and I flatter myself the poor sufferer will soon be able to bear the removal without material inconvenience or injury.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172266,\n            \"and she wrote very comfortably about agitation, and anxiety, and poor invalids, till Tom was actually conveyed to Mansfield, and her own eyes had beheld his altered appearance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172335,\n            \"\\u201cHe is just come, my dear Fanny, and is taken upstairs;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172350,\n            \"and I am so shocked to see him, that I do not know what to do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172368,\n            \"I am sure he has been very ill.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172380,\n            \"I am quite grieved for him, and very much frightened, and so is Sir Thomas;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172412,\n            \"But Sir Thomas hopes he will be better to-morrow, and says we must consider his journey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172558,\n            \"Without any particular affection for her eldest cousin, her tenderness of heart made her feel that she could not spare him, and the purity of her principles added yet a keener solicitude, when she considered how little useful, how little self-denying his life had (apparently) been.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172832,\n            \"CHAPTER XLV At about the week\\u2019s end from his return to Mansfield, Tom\\u2019s immediate danger was over, and he was so far pronounced safe as to make his mother perfectly easy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172870,\n            \"for being now used to the sight of him in his suffering, helpless state, and hearing only the best, and never thinking beyond what she heard, with no disposition for alarm and no aptitude at a hint, Lady Bertram was the happiest subject in the world for a little medical imposition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172948,\n            \"Lady Bertram could think nothing less, and Fanny shared her aunt\\u2019s security, till she received a few lines from Edmund, written purposely to give her a clearer idea of his brother\\u2019s situation, and acquaint her with the apprehensions which he and his father had imbibed from the physician with respect to some strong hectic symptoms, which seemed to seize the frame on the departure of the fever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173063,\n            \"They were apprehensive for his lungs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173136,\n            \"She could do nothing but glide in quietly and look at him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173371,\n            \"\\u201cOn the subject of my last, I had actually begun a letter when called away by Tom\\u2019s illness, but I have now changed my mind, and fear to trust the influence of friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173551,\n            \"She supposed he could not yet leave his son, but it was a cruel, a terrible delay to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180269,\n            \"Fanny began to dread the meeting with her aunts and Tom, under so dreadful a humiliation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182189,\n            \"Tom\\u2019s complaints had been greatly heightened by the shock of his sister\\u2019s conduct, and his recovery so much thrown back by it, that even Lady Bertram had been struck by the difference, and all her alarms were regularly sent off to her husband;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 6]\": [\n        [\n            15156,\n            \"Admiral and Mrs. Crawford, though agreeing in nothing else, were united in affection for these children, or, at least, were no farther adverse in their feelings than that each had their favourite, to whom they showed the greatest fondness of the two.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15206,\n            \"The Admiral delighted in the boy, Mrs. Crawford doted on the girl;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15434,\n            \"Miss Crawford was not entirely free from similar apprehensions, though they arose principally from doubts of her sister\\u2019s style of living and tone of society;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15584,\n            \"Miss Crawford found a sister without preciseness or rusticity, a sister\\u2019s husband who looked the gentleman, and a house commodious and well fitted up;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15799,\n            \"Miss Crawford was glad to find a family of such consequence so very near them, and not at all displeased either at her sister\\u2019s early care, or the choice it had fallen on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16447,\n            \"Miss Crawford\\u2019s beauty did her no disservice with the Miss Bertrams.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17821,\n            \"but Mansfield promised well, and there was nothing to call him elsewhere.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17835,\n            \"It delighted Mrs. Grant to keep them both with her, and Dr. Grant was exceedingly well contented to have it so: a talking pretty young woman like Miss Crawford is always pleasant society to an indolent, stay-at-home man;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17883,\n            \"and Mr. Crawford\\u2019s being his guest was an excuse for drinking claret every day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17901,\n            \"The Miss Bertrams\\u2019 admiration of Mr. Crawford was more rapturous than anything which Miss Crawford\\u2019s habits made her likely to feel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17927,\n            \"She acknowledged, however, that the Mr. Bertrams were very fine young men, that two such young men were not often seen together even in London, and that their manners, particularly those of the eldest, were very good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19385,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI do not know,\\u201dreplied Miss Crawford hesitatingly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24266,\n            \"and as Miss Bertram caught at the idea likewise, and gave it her full support, declaring that, in her opinion, it was infinitely better to consult with friends and disinterested advisers, than immediately to throw the business into the hands of a professional man, Mr. Rushworth was very ready to request the favour of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s assistance;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24334,\n            \"and Mr. Crawford, after properly depreciating his own abilities, was quite at his service in any way that could be useful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24359,\n            \"Mr. Rushworth then began to propose Mr. Crawford\\u2019s doing him the honour of coming over to Sotherton, and taking a bed there;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24387,\n            \"when Mrs. Norris, as if reading in her two nieces\\u2019 minds their little approbation of a plan which was to take Mr. Crawford away, interposed with an amendment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24453,\n            \"Here are many that would be interested in your improvements, my dear Mr. Rushworth, and that would like to hear Mr. Crawford\\u2019s opinion on the spot, and that might be of some small use to you with _ their _ opinions;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24599,\n            \"I dare say Mr. Crawford would take my two nieces and me in his barouche, and Edmund can go on horseback, you know, sister, and Fanny will stay at home with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24720,\n            \"I like to hear her talk.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24727,\n            \"She entertains me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24731,\n            \"and she is so extremely pretty, that I have great pleasure in looking at her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24790,\n            \"she ought not to have spoken of her uncle as she did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24808,\n            \"An uncle with whom she has been living so many years, and who, whatever his faults may be, is so very fond of her brother, treating him, they say, quite like a son.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24889,\n            \"I do not know that her uncle has any claim to her _ gratitude _;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24910,\n            \"and it is the warmth of her respect for her aunt\\u2019s memory which misleads her here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24934,\n            \"With such warm feelings and lively spirits it must be difficult to do justice to her affection for Mrs. Crawford, without throwing a shade on the Admiral.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24996,\n            \"but it is natural and amiable that Miss Crawford should acquit her aunt entirely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25011,\n            \"I do not censure her _ opinions _;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25032,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo not you think,\\u201dsaid Fanny, after a little consideration, \\u201cthat this impropriety is a reflection itself upon Mrs. Crawford, as her niece has been entirely brought up by her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25072,\n            \"She cannot have given her right notions of what was due to the Admiral.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25095,\n            \"Yes, we must suppose the faults of the niece to have been those of the aunt;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25127,\n            \"But I think her present home must do her good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25500,\n            \"for the lady could not be unwilling to have a listener, and every thing was soon in a fair train.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25684,\n            \"and to the credit of the lady it may be added that, without his being a man of the world or an elder brother, without any of the arts of flattery or the gaieties of small talk, he began to be agreeable to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25963,\n            \"She was a little surprised that he could spend so many hours with Miss Crawford, and not see more of the sort of fault which he had already observed, and of which _ she _ was almost always reminded by a something of the same nature whenever she was in her company;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26511,\n            \"and in Dr. Grant\\u2019s meadow she immediately saw the group \\u2014 Edmund and Miss Crawford both on horse-back, riding side by side, Dr. and Mrs. Grant, and Mr. Crawford, with two or three grooms, standing about and looking on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26638,\n            \"At first Miss Crawford and her companion made the circuit of the field, which was not small, at a foot\\u2019s pace;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26781,\n            \"She could not but think, indeed, that Mr. Crawford might as well have saved him the trouble;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29687,\n            \"He was ashamed to think that for four days together she had not had the power of riding, and very seriously resolved, however unwilling he must be to check a pleasure of Miss Crawford\\u2019s, that it should never happen again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29953,\n            \"Mrs. Norris and her nieces were all well pleased with its revival, and an early day was named and agreed to, provided Mr. Crawford should be disengaged: the young ladies did not forget that stipulation, and though Mrs. Norris would willingly have answered for his being so, they would neither authorise the liberty nor run the risk;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30019,\n            \"and at last, on a hint from Miss Bertram, Mr. Rushworth discovered that the properest thing to be done was for him to walk down to the Parsonage directly, and call on Mr. Crawford, and inquire whether Wednesday would suit him or not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30069,\n            \"Before his return Mrs. Grant and Miss Crawford came in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30102,\n            \"Comfortable hopes, however, were given that he would find Mr. Crawford at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30536,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Rushworth proceeded next, under the conviction that everybody must be wanting to see Sotherton, to include Miss Crawford in the invitation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30727,\n            \"The Miss Bertrams laughed at the idea, assuring her that the barouche would hold four perfectly well, independent of the box, on which _ one _ might go with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30877,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBesides,\\u201dsaid Maria, \\u201cI know that Mr. Crawford depends upon taking us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31995,\n            \"Wednesday was fine, and soon after breakfast the barouche arrived, Mr. Crawford driving his sisters;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32348,\n            \"That was the only point of resemblance between her and the lady who sat by her: in everything but a value for Edmund, Miss Crawford was very unlike her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32479,\n            \"For the first seven miles Miss Bertram had very little real comfort: her prospect always ended in Mr. Crawford and her sister sitting side by side, full of conversation and merriment;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32716,\n            \"She had Rushworth feelings, and Crawford feelings, and in the vicinity of Sotherton the former had considerable effect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32746,\n            \"She could not tell Miss Crawford that \\u201cthose woods belonged to Sotherton,\\u201dshe could not carelessly observe that \\u201cshe believed that it was now all Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s property on each side of the road,\\u201dwithout elation of heart;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32831,\n            \"\\u201cNow we shall have no more rough road, Miss Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33703,\n            \"On the present occasion she addressed herself chiefly to Miss Crawford and Fanny, but there was no comparison in the willingness of their attention;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35375,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Crawford\\u2019s countenance, as Julia spoke, might have amused a disinterested observer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35409,\n            \"\\u201cHow distressed she will be at what she said just now,\\u201dpassed across her mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35466,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Crawford, rallying her spirits, and recovering her complexion, replied only, \\u201cIf I had known this before, I would have spoken of the cloth with more respect,\\u201dand turned the subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36050,\n            \"and when, after a little time, the others began to form into parties, these three were found in busy consultation on the terrace by Edmund, Miss Crawford, and Fanny, who seemed as naturally to unite, and who, after a short participation of their regrets and difficulties, left them and walked on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36305,\n            \"\\u201cThis is insufferably hot,\\u201dsaid Miss Crawford, when they had taken one turn on the terrace, and were drawing a second time to the door in the middle which opened to the wilderness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36515,\n            \"At length, after a short pause, Miss Crawford began with, \\u201cSo you are to be a clergyman, Mr. Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37230,\n            \"And with regard to their influencing public manners, Miss Crawford must not misunderstand me, or suppose I mean to call them the arbiters of good-breeding, the regulators of refinement and courtesy, the masters of the ceremonies of life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37363,\n            \"\\u201cThere,\\u201dcried Miss Crawford, \\u201cyou have quite convinced Miss Price already.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38173,\n            \"\\u201cI am afraid you are very tired, Fanny,\\u201dsaid Edmund, observing her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38453,\n            \"\\u201cI must move,\\u201dsaid she;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38510,\n            \"\\u201cNow, Miss Crawford, if you will look up the walk, you will convince yourself that it cannot be half a mile long, or half half a mile.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40086,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny was again left to her solitude, and with no increase of pleasant feelings, for she was sorry for almost all that she had seen and heard, astonished at Miss Bertram, and angry with Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40182,\n            \"She could almost have thought that Edmund and Miss Crawford had left it, but that it was impossible for Edmund to forget her so entirely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40272,\n            \"I thought Maria and Mr. Crawford were with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40937,\n            \"After another pause, he went on \\u2014 \\u201cPray, Miss Price, are you such a great admirer of this Mr. Crawford as some people are?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40978,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI do not think him at all handsome.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43178,\n            \"Miss Crawford, on walking up with her brother to spend the evening at Mansfield Park, heard the good news;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43251,\n            \"but after tea, as Miss Crawford was standing at an open window with Edmund and Fanny looking out on a twilight scene, while the Miss Bertrams, Mr. Rushworth, and Henry Crawford were all busy with candles at the pianoforte, she suddenly revived it by turning round towards the group, and saying, \\u201cHow happy Mr. Rushworth looks!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43405,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDon\\u2019t be affronted,\\u201dsaid she, laughing, \\u201cbut it does put me in mind of some of the old heathen heroes, who, after performing great exploits in a foreign land, offered sacrifices to the gods on their safe return.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44220,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere are such clergymen, no doubt, but I think they are not so common as to justify Miss Crawford in esteeming it their general character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44339,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI speak what appears to me the general opinion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44496,\n            \"\\u201cI have been so little addicted to take my opinions from my uncle,\\u201dsaid Miss Crawford, \\u201cthat I can hardly suppose \\u2014 and since you push me so hard, I must observe, that I am not entirely without the means of seeing what clergymen are, being at this present time the guest of my own brother, Dr. Grant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44670,\n            \"To own the truth, Henry and I were partly driven out this very evening by a disappointment about a green goose, which he could not get the better of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44713,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI do not wonder at your disapprobation, upon my word.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44747,\n            \"and to see your sister suffering from it must be exceedingly painful to such feelings as yours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44825,\n            \"and as he must, either in the navy or army, have had a great many more people under his command than he has now, I think more would have been made unhappy by him as a sailor or soldier than as a clergyman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45012,\n            \"and I have no doubt that he oftener endeavours to restrain himself than he would if he had been anything but a clergyman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45049,\n            \"but I wish you a better fate, Miss Price, than to be the wife of a man whose amiableness depends upon his own sermons;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45802,\n            \"and by the end of August he arrived himself, to be gay, agreeable, and gallant again as occasion served, or Miss Crawford demanded;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46005,\n            \"The season and duties which brought Mr. Bertram back to Mansfield took Mr. Crawford into Norfolk.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46036,\n            \"He went for a fortnight \\u2014 a fortnight of such dullness to the Miss Bertrams as ought to have put them both on their guard, and made even Julia admit, in her jealousy of her sister, the absolute necessity of distrusting his attentions, and wishing him not to return;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46165,\n            \"The sisters, handsome, clever, and encouraging, were an amusement to his sated mind;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46223,\n            \"Maria, with only Mr. Rushworth to attend to her, and doomed to the repeated details of his day\\u2019s sport, good or bad, his boast of his dogs, his jealousy of his neighbours, his doubts of their qualifications, and his zeal after poachers, subjects which will not find their way to female feelings without some talent on one side or some attachment on the other, had missed Mr. Crawford grievously;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46330,\n            \"Julia might be justified in so doing by the hints of Mrs. Grant, inclined to credit what she wished, and Maria by the hints of Mr. Crawford himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46794,\n            \"Crawford has too much sense to stay here if he found himself in any danger from Maria;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47349,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Bertram did indeed look happy, her eyes were sparkling with pleasure, and she was speaking with great animation, for Julia and her partner, Mr. Crawford, were close to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47585,\n            \"Four thousand a year is a pretty estate, and he seems a very genteel, steady young man, so I hope Miss Julia will be very happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49535,\n            \"\\u201cI really believe,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cI could be fool enough at this moment to undertake any character that ever was written, from Shylock or Richard III down to the singing hero of a farce in his scarlet coat and cocked hat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53253,\n            \"Here are two capital tragic parts for Yates and Crawford, and here is the rhyming Butler for me, if nobody else wants it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53877,\n            \"\\u201cI must entreat Miss _ Julia _ Bertram,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cnot to engage in the part of Agatha, or it will be the ruin of all my solemnity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53941,\n            \"The many laughs we have had together would infallibly come across me, and Frederick and his knapsack would be obliged to run away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54150,\n            \"Cottager\\u2019s wife is a very pretty part, I assure you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54593,\n            \"I have seen good actresses fail in the part.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54665,\n            \"but while she hesitated what to say, her brother again interposed with Miss Crawford\\u2019s better claim.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54750,\n            \"She looks the part, and I am persuaded will do it admirably.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55328,\n            \"When this had lasted some time, the division of the party was completed by Tom Bertram and Mr. Yates walking off together to consult farther in the room now beginning to be called _ the _ _ Theatre _, and Miss Bertram\\u2019s resolving to go down to the Parsonage herself with the offer of Amelia to Miss Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56131,\n            \"Maria blushed in spite of herself as she answered, \\u201cI take the part which Lady Ravenshaw was to have done, and\\u201d(with a bolder eye) \\u201cMiss Crawford is to be Amelia.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57707,\n            \"and the spirits of evening giving fresh courage, Tom, Maria, and Mr. Yates, soon after their being reassembled in the drawing-room, seated themselves in committee at a separate table, with the play open before them, and were just getting deep in the subject when a most welcome interruption was given by the entrance of Mr. and Miss Crawford, who, late and dark and dirty as it was, could not help coming, and were received with the most grateful joy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58019,\n            \"and standing by them, seemed to interest herself in their arrangements till, as if struck by a sudden recollection, she exclaimed, \\u201cMy good friends, you are most composedly at work upon these cottages and alehouses, inside and out;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59608,\n            \"but Miss Crawford, looking for a moment with astonished eyes at Mrs. Norris, and then at Fanny, whose tears were beginning to shew themselves, immediately said, with some keenness, \\u201cI do not like my situation: this _ place _ is too hot for me,\\u201dand moved away her chair to the opposite side of the table, close to Fanny, saying to her, in a kind, low whisper, as she placed herself, \\u201cNever mind, my dear Miss Price, this is a cross evening: everybody is cross and teasing, but do not let us mind them \\u201d;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59751,\n            \"By a look at her brother she prevented any farther entreaty from the theatrical board, and the really good feelings by which she was almost purely governed were rapidly restoring her to all the little she had lost in Edmund\\u2019s favour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59803,\n            \"but she felt very much obliged to her for her present kindness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59816,\n            \"and when, from taking notice of her work, and wishing _ she _ could work as well, and begging for the pattern, and supposing Fanny was now preparing for her _ appearance _, as of course she would come out when her cousin was married, Miss Crawford proceeded to inquire if she had heard lately from her brother at sea, and said that she had quite a curiosity to see him, and imagined him a very fine young man, and advised Fanny to get his picture drawn before he went to sea again \\u2014 she could not help admitting it to be very agreeable flattery, or help listening, and answering with more animation than she had intended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59945,\n            \"The consultation upon the play still went on, and Miss Crawford\\u2019s attention was first called from Fanny by Tom Bertram\\u2019s telling her, with infinite regret, that he found it absolutely impossible for him to undertake the part of Anhalt in addition to the Butler: he had been most anxiously trying to make it out to be feasible, but it would not do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60231,\n            \"Have I ever seen either of the gentlemen?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60268,\n            \"I remember him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60272,\n            \"Let _ him _ be applied to, if you please, for it will be less unpleasant to me than to have a perfect stranger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60381,\n            \"\\u201cI am not very sanguine as to our play,\\u201dsaid Miss Crawford, in an undervoice to Fanny, after some consideration;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60407,\n            \"\\u201cand I can tell Mr. Maddox that I shall shorten some of _ his _ speeches, and a great many of _ my _ _ own _, before we rehearse together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60632,\n            \"Miss Crawford had protected her only for the time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62382,\n            \"Put yourself in Miss Crawford\\u2019s place, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62421,\n            \"I heard enough of what she said to you last night to understand her unwillingness to be acting with a stranger;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62443,\n            \"and as she probably engaged in the part with different expectations \\u2014 perhaps without considering the subject enough to know what was likely to be \\u2014 it would be ungenerous, it would be really wrong to expose her to it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62504,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sorry for Miss Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62849,\n            \"I thought _ you _ would have entered more into Miss Crawford\\u2019s feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62895,\n            \"\\u201cShe never appeared more amiable than in her behaviour to you last night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62921,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cShe _ was _ very kind, indeed, and I am glad to have her spared \\u201d.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63324,\n            \"She had seen her influence in every speech, and was miserable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63920,\n            \"One advantage resulted from it to Fanny: at the earnest request of Miss Crawford, Mrs. Grant had, with her usual good-humour, agreed to undertake the part for which Fanny had been wanted;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63976,\n            \"and even this, when imparted by Edmund, brought a pang with it, for it was Miss Crawford to whom she was obliged \\u2014 it was Miss Crawford whose kind exertions were to excite her gratitude, and whose merit in making them was spoken of with a glow of admiration.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66324,\n            \"As far as she could judge, Mr. Crawford was considerably the best actor of all: he had more confidence than Edmund, more judgment than Tom, more talent and taste than Mr. Yates.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66363,\n            \"She did not like him as a man, but she must admit him to be the best actor, and on this point there were not many who differed from her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66396,\n            \"Mr. Yates, indeed, exclaimed against his tameness and insipidity;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66445,\n            \"For the life and soul of me, I cannot admire him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66458,\n            \"and, between ourselves, to see such an undersized, little, mean-looking man, set up for a fine actor, is very ridiculous in my opinion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66490,\n            \"\\u201d From this moment there was a return of his former jealousy, which Maria, from increasing hopes of Crawford, was at little pains to remove;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67230,\n            \"Fanny did not share her aunt\\u2019s composure: she thought of the morrow a great deal, for if the three acts were rehearsed, Edmund and Miss Crawford would then be acting together for the first time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67431,\n            \"and about noon she made her escape with her work to the East room, that she might have no concern in another, and, as she deemed it, most unnecessary rehearsal of the first act, which Henry Crawford was just proposing, desirous at once of having her time to herself, and of avoiding the sight of Mr. Rushworth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68344,\n            \"and as Edmund was come on the very same business that had brought Miss Crawford, consciousness and pleasure were likely to be more than momentary in _ them _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68375,\n            \"He too had his book, and was seeking Fanny, to ask her to rehearse with him, and help him to prepare for the evening, without knowing Miss Crawford to be in the house;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68490,\n            \"Edmund proposed, urged, entreated it, till the lady, not very unwilling at first, could refuse no longer, and Fanny was wanted only to prompt and observe them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72377,\n            \"\\u201cWhere did you leave Miss Crawford, Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75723,\n            \"There is nothing very striking in Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s manners, but I was pleased last night with what appeared to be his opinion on one subject: his decided preference of a quiet family party to the bustle and confusion of acting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75841,\n            \"\\u2018 Upon my word, Mrs. Norris,\\u2019said Mrs. Grant the other day, \\u2018 if Mr. Rushworth were a son of your own, he could not hold Sir Thomas in greater respect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79015,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMiss Crawford was very right in what she said of you the other day: that you seemed almost as fearful of notice and praise as other women were of neglect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79049,\n            \"We were talking of you at the Parsonage, and those were her words.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79086,\n            \"She certainly understands _ you _ better than you are understood by the greater part of those who have known you so long;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79110,\n            \"and with regard to some others, I can perceive, from occasional lively hints, the unguarded expressions of the moment, that she could define _ many _ as accurately, did not delicacy forbid it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79149,\n            \"I wonder what she thinks of my father!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79158,\n            \"She must admire him as a fine-looking man, with most gentlemanlike, dignified, consistent manners;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79398,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny could have said a great deal, but it was safer to say nothing, and leave untouched all Miss Crawford\\u2019s resources \\u2014 her accomplishments, her spirits, her importance, her friends, lest it should betray her into any observations seemingly unhandsome.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81735,\n            \"and to poor Miss Crawford, who had just been contemplating the dismal rain in a very desponding state of mind, sighing over the ruin of all her plan of exercise for that morning, and of every chance of seeing a single creature beyond themselves for the next twenty-four hours, the sound of a little bustle at the front door, and the sight of Miss Price dripping with wet in the vestibule, was delightful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82204,\n            \"but Miss Crawford, calling to mind an early expressed wish on the subject, was concerned at her own neglect;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82321,\n            \"\\u201cAnother quarter of an hour,\\u201dsaid Miss Crawford, \\u201cand we shall see how it will be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82616,\n            \"Such was the origin of the sort of intimacy which took place between them within the first fortnight after the Miss Bertrams\\u2019 going away \\u2014 an intimacy resulting principally from Miss Crawford\\u2019s desire of something new, and which had little reality in Fanny\\u2019s feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82667,\n            \"Fanny went to her every two or three days: it seemed a kind of fascination: she could not be easy without going, and yet it was without loving her, without ever thinking like her, without any sense of obligation for being sought after now when nobody else was to be had;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84133,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI grant you the name is good in itself, and _ Lord _ Edmund or _ Sir _ Edmund sound delightfully;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85107,\n            \"Miss Crawford may chuse her degree of wealth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89039,\n            \"and the smiles and pleased looks of the three others standing round him, shewed how welcome was his sudden resolution of coming to them for a few days on leaving Bath.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89139,\n            \"for though she must submit, as her own propriety of mind directed, in spite of her aunt Norris\\u2019 s opinion, to being the principal lady in company, and to all the little distinctions consequent thereon, she found, while they were at table, such a happy flow of conversation prevailing, in which she was not required to take any part \\u2014 there was so much to be said between the brother and sister about Bath, so much between the two young men about hunting, so much of politics between Mr. Crawford and Dr. Grant, and of everything and all together between Mr. Crawford and Mrs. Grant, as to leave her the fairest prospect of having only to listen in quiet, and of passing a very agreeable day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90697,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Crawford _ could _ have said that there would be a something to do and to suffer for it, which she could not think lightly of;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90883,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI shall keep clear of you, Crawford, as long as I can,\\u201dsaid Edmund;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92384,\n            \"for although there doubtless are such unconquerable young ladies of eighteen (or one should not read about them) as are never to be persuaded into love against their judgment by all that talent, manner, attention, and flattery can do, I have no inclination to believe Fanny one of them, or to think that with so much tenderness of disposition, and so much taste as belonged to her, she could have escaped heart-whole from the courtship (though the courtship only of a fortnight) of such a man as Crawford, in spite of there being some previous ill opinion of him to be overcome, had not her affection been engaged elsewhere.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92636,\n            \"and at the end of those few days, circumstances arose which had a tendency rather to forward his views of pleasing her, inasmuch as they gave her a degree of happiness which must dispose her to be pleased with everybody.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92737,\n            \"and when Crawford walked up with the newspaper in his hand, which he had hoped would bring the first tidings, he found her trembling with joy over this letter, and listening with a glowing, grateful countenance to the kind invitation which her uncle was most collectedly dictating in reply.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92871,\n            \"and the good luck which attended his early examination of ship news the next morning seemed the reward of his ingenuity in finding out such a method of pleasing her, as well as of his dutiful attention to the Admiral, in having for many years taken in the paper esteemed to have the earliest naval intelligence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92940,\n            \"All those fine first feelings, of which he had hoped to be the exciter, were already given.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94018,\n            \"and when Mrs. Brown, and the other women at the Commissioner\\u2019s at Gibraltar, appeared in the same trim, I thought they were mad;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94150,\n            \"He was no longer in doubt of the capabilities of her heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94193,\n            \"She interested him more than he had foreseen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94496,\n            \"His heart was warmed, his fancy fired, and he felt the highest respect for a lad who, before he was twenty, had gone through such bodily hardships and given such proofs of mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94560,\n            \"and he wished he had been a William Price, distinguishing himself and working his way to fortune and consequence with so much self-respect and happy ardour, instead of what he was!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94604,\n            \"He was roused from the reverie of retrospection and regret produced by it, by some inquiry from Edmund as to his plans for the next day\\u2019s hunting;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94635,\n            \"and he found it was as well to be a man of fortune at once with horses and grooms at his command.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94699,\n            \"and Crawford could mount him without the slightest inconvenience to himself, and with only some scruples to obviate in Sir Thomas, who knew better than his nephew the value of such a loan, and some alarms to reason away in Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94818,\n            \"nor till he returned safe and well, without accident or discredit, could she be reconciled to the risk, or feel any of that obligation to Mr. Crawford for lending the horse which he had fully intended it should produce.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95048,\n            \"and though infinitely above scheming or contriving for any the most advantageous matrimonial establishment that could be among the apparent possibilities of any one most dear to him, and disdaining even as a littleness the being quick-sighted on such points, he could not avoid perceiving, in a grand and careless way, that Mr. Crawford was somewhat distinguishing his niece \\u2014 nor perhaps refrain (though unconsciously) from giving a more willing assent to invitations on that account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95186,\n            \"\\u201d proceeded from good-breeding and goodwill alone, and had nothing to do with Mr. Crawford, but as being one in an agreeable group: for it was in the course of that very visit that he first began to think that any one in the habit of such idle observations _ would _ _ have _ _ thought _ that Mr. Crawford was the admirer of Fanny Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95631,\n            \"but upon everybody\\u2019s assuring her that nothing could be so easy, that it was the easiest game on the cards, and Henry Crawford\\u2019s stepping forward with a most earnest request to be allowed to sit between her ladyship and Miss Price, and teach them both, it was so settled;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96453,\n            \"\\u201d Thornton Lacey was the name of his impending living, as Miss Crawford well knew;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96953,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Crawford, a little suspicious and resentful of a certain tone of voice, and a certain half-look attending the last expression of his hope, made a hasty finish of her dealings with William Price;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96994,\n            \"and securing his knave at an exorbitant rate, exclaimed, \\u201cThere, I will stake my last like a woman of spirit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97085,\n            \"\\u201cMy plan may not be the best possible: I had not many minutes to form it in;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97654,\n            \"but Crawford pursued with \\u201cNo, no, you must not part with the queen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97767,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMr. Bertram,\\u201dsaid Miss Crawford, a few minutes afterwards, \\u201cyou know Henry to be such a capital improver, that you cannot possibly engage in anything of the sort at Thornton Lacey without accepting his help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98984,\n            \"But, Crawford, though I refuse you as a tenant, come to me as a friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99094,\n            \"It is perfectly natural that you should not have thought much on the subject, Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99276,\n            \"\\u201d Mr. Crawford bowed his acquiescence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99364,\n            \"\\u201d Whatever effect Sir Thomas\\u2019 s little harangue might really produce on Mr. Crawford, it raised some awkward sensations in two of the others, two of his most attentive listeners \\u2014 Miss Crawford and Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99683,\n            \"Henry Crawford\\u2019s chair was the first to be given a direction towards them, and he sat silently observing them for a few minutes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102479,\n            \"He had seen her eyes sparkle as she spoke of the dear friend\\u2019s letter, which claimed a long visit from her in London, and of the kindness of Henry, in engaging to remain where he was till January, that he might convey her thither;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102591,\n            \"He had since heard her express herself differently, with other feelings, more chequered feelings: he had heard her tell Mrs. Grant that she should leave her with regret;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102984,\n            \"She met Miss Crawford within a few yards of the Parsonage, just setting out to call on her, and as it seemed to her that her friend, though obliged to insist on turning back, was unwilling to lose her walk, she explained her business at once, and observed, that if she would be so kind as to give her opinion, it might be all talked over as well without doors as within.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103065,\n            \"Miss Crawford appeared gratified by the application, and after a moment\\u2019s thought, urged Fanny\\u2019s returning with her in a much more cordial manner than before, and proposed their going up into her room, where they might have a comfortable coze, without disturbing Dr. and Mrs. Grant, who were together in the drawing-room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103174,\n            \"Miss Crawford, pleased with the appeal, gave her all her best judgment and taste, made everything easy by her suggestions, and tried to make everything agreeable by her encouragement.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103245,\n            \"\\u201d And as she spoke she was undoing a small parcel, which Fanny had observed in her hand when they met.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103323,\n            \"Such had been the parcel with which Miss Crawford was provided, and such the object of her intended visit: and in the kindest manner she now urged Fanny\\u2019s taking one for the cross and to keep for her sake, saying everything she could think of to obviate the scruples which were making Fanny start back at first with a look of horror at the proposal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103461,\n            \"But Miss Crawford persevered, and argued the case with so much affectionate earnestness through all the heads of William and the cross, and the ball, and herself, as to be finally successful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103583,\n            \"and though Fanny would have preferred a longer and a plainer chain as more adapted for her purpose, she hoped, in fixing on this, to be chusing what Miss Crawford least wished to keep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103701,\n            \"Miss Crawford had anticipated her wants with a kindness which proved her a real friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103717,\n            \"\\u201cWhen I wear this necklace I shall always think of you,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cand feel how very kind you were.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103743,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou must think of somebody else too, when you wear that necklace,\\u201dreplied Miss Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103781,\n            \"He gave it to me, and with the necklace I make over to you all the duty of remembering the original giver.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103867,\n            \"and with an eagerness and embarrassment quite diverting to her companion, she laid down the necklace again on its cotton, and seemed resolved either to take another or none at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103912,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear child,\\u201dsaid she, laughing, \\u201cwhat are you afraid of?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103930,\n            \"Do you think Henry will claim the necklace as mine, and fancy you did not come honestly by it?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103989,\n            \"or perhaps\\u201d\\u2014 looking archly \\u2014 \\u201cyou suspect a confederacy between us, and that what I am now doing is with his knowledge and at his desire?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104032,\n            \"\\u201cWell, then,\\u201dreplied Miss Crawford more seriously, but without at all believing her, \\u201cto convince me that you suspect no trick, and are as unsuspicious of compliment as I have always found you, take the necklace and say no more about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104258,\n            \"and with renewed but less happy thanks accepted the necklace again, for there was an expression in Miss Crawford\\u2019s eyes which she could not be satisfied with.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104289,\n            \"It was impossible for her to be insensible of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s change of manners.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104358,\n            \"and whether he might not have some concern in this necklace \\u2014 she could not be convinced that he had not, for Miss Crawford, complaisant as a sister, was careless as a woman and a friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105173,\n            \"for Edmund was so struck with the circumstance, so delighted with what Miss Crawford had done, so gratified by such a coincidence of conduct between them, that Fanny could not but admit the superior power of one pleasure over his own mind, though it might have its drawback.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105583,\n            \"Miss Crawford\\u2019s attentions to you have been \\u2014 not more than you were justly entitled to \\u2014 I am the last person to think that _ could _ _ be _, but they have been invariable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105925,\n            \"Could she believe Miss Crawford to deserve him, it would be \\u2014 oh, how different would it be \\u2014 how far more tolerable!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106084,\n            \"To think of him as Miss Crawford might be justified in thinking, would in her be insanity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106148,\n            \"She would endeavour to be rational, and to deserve the right of judging of Miss Crawford\\u2019s character, and the privilege of true solicitude for him by a sound intellect and an honest heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106529,\n            \"and opened with more kindness to Fanny than such self-willed, unmanageable days often volunteer, for soon after breakfast a very friendly note was brought from Mr. Crawford to William, stating that as he found himself obliged to go to London on the morrow for a few days, he could not help trying to procure a companion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106625,\n            \"Mr. Crawford meant to be in town by his uncle\\u2019s accustomary late dinner-hour, and William was invited to dine with him at the Admiral\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106771,\n            \"and though this offer of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s would rob her of many hours of his company, she was too happy in having William spared from the fatigue of such a journey, to think of anything else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107056,\n            \"To dance without much observation or any extraordinary fatigue, to have strength and partners for about half the evening, to dance a little with Edmund, and not a great deal with Mr. Crawford, to see William enjoy himself, and be able to keep away from her aunt Norris, was the height of her ambition, and seemed to comprehend her greatest possibility of happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107569,\n            \"\\u201cI wished to engage Miss Crawford for the two first dances,\\u201dwas the explanation that followed, and brought Fanny to life again, enabling her, as she found she was expected to speak, to utter something like an inquiry as to the result.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107690,\n            \"She never has danced with a clergyman, she says, and she never _ will _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107917,\n            \"I know her disposition to be as sweet and faultless as your own, but the influence of her former companions makes her seem \\u2014 gives to her conversation, to her professed opinions, sometimes a tinge of wrong.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108256,\n            \"\\u201d cried Edmund, pressing her hand to his lips with almost as much warmth as if it had been Miss Crawford\\u2019s, \\u201cyou are all considerate thought!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108408,\n            \"but you have always known my opinion of her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108433,\n            \"How many a time have we talked over her little errors!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108677,\n            \"Since the first joy from Mr. Crawford\\u2019s note to William had worn away, she had been in a state absolutely the reverse;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108792,\n            \"and when she came to the necklaces again, her good fortune seemed complete, for upon trial the one given her by Miss Crawford would by no means go through the ring of the cross.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108858,\n            \"and having, with delightful feelings, joined the chain and the cross \\u2014 those memorials of the two most beloved of her heart, those dearest tokens so formed for each other by everything real and imaginary \\u2014 and put them round her neck, and seen and felt how full of William and Edmund they were, she was able, without an effort, to resolve on wearing Miss Crawford\\u2019s necklace too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111592,\n            \"\\u201cWell, then,\\u201dreplied Miss Crawford, laughing, \\u201cI must suppose it to be purely for the pleasure of conveying your brother, and of talking of you by the way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111642,\n            \"while Miss Crawford wondered she did not smile, and thought her over-anxious, or thought her odd, or thought her anything rather than insensible of pleasure in Henry\\u2019s attentions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112690,\n            \"\\u201d After a short consideration, Sir Thomas asked Crawford to join the early breakfast party in that house instead of eating alone: he should himself be of it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114918,\n            \"Angry as she was with Edmund for adhering to his own notions, and acting on them in defiance of her (and she had been so angry that they had hardly parted friends at the ball), she could not help thinking of him continually when absent, dwelling on his merit and affection, and longing again for the almost daily meetings they lately had.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115029,\n            \"She wished she had not spoken so warmly in their last conversation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115042,\n            \"She was afraid she had used some strong, some contemptuous expressions in speaking of the clergy, and that should not have been.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115126,\n            \"and when, through the slight communication with the other family which Sunday produced, she learned that he had actually written home to defer his return, having promised to remain some days longer with his friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116175,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Crawford turned her eye on her, as if wanting to hear or see more, and then laughingly said, \\u201cOh yes!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116275,\n            \"\\u201d Now Fanny could not bring herself to speak, and Miss Crawford was disappointed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116318,\n            \"\\u201cThe Miss Owens,\\u201dsaid she, soon afterwards;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116587,\n            \"Her companion looked at her keenly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116626,\n            \"CHAPTER XXX Miss Crawford\\u2019s uneasiness was much lightened by this conversation, and she walked home again in spirits which might have defied almost another week of the same small party in the same bad weather, had they been put to the proof;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120097,\n            \"While her hand was trembling under these letters, her eye running from one to the other, and her heart swelling with emotion, Crawford thus continued, with unfeigned eagerness, to express his interest in the event \\u2014 \\u201cI will not talk of my own happiness,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cgreat as it is, for I think only of yours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120422,\n            \"I would not allow myself yesterday to say how delighted, or to repeat half that the Admiral said in his praise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120445,\n            \"I deferred it all till his praise should be proved the praise of a friend, as this day _ does _ prove it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120605,\n            \"His last journey to London had been undertaken with no other view than that of introducing her brother in Hill Street, and prevailing on the Admiral to exert whatever interest he might have for getting him on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122362,\n            \"and when Sir Thomas good-humouredly observed that joy had taken away her appetite, she was ready to sink with shame, from the dread of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s interpretation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122793,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cSir Thomas told me \\u00a310 would be enough.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122900,\n            \"take them all together, I dare say nobody would believe what a sum they cost Sir Thomas every year, to say nothing of what _ I _ do for them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122954,\n            \"and you know it makes very little difference to Sir Thomas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123024,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny, meanwhile, speaking only when she could not help it, was very earnestly trying to understand what Mr. and Miss Crawford were at.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123053,\n            \"There was everything in the world _ against _ their being serious but his words and manner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123165,\n            \"who was everything to everybody, and seemed to find no one essential to him?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123249,\n            \"She had quite convinced herself of this before Sir Thomas and Mr. Crawford joined them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123330,\n            \"But she still tried to believe it no more than what he might often have expressed towards her cousins and fifty other women.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123354,\n            \"She thought he was wishing to speak to her unheard by the rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123368,\n            \"She fancied he was trying for it the whole evening at intervals, whenever Sir Thomas was out of the room, or at all engaged with Mrs. Norris, and she carefully refused him every opportunity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123434,\n            \"but the comfort of the sound was impaired by his turning to her the next moment, and saying, \\u201cHave you nothing to send to Mary?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123557,\n            \"She had read Miss Crawford\\u2019s note only once, and how to reply to anything so imperfectly understood was most distressing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123617,\n            \"and with only one decided feeling, that of wishing not to appear to think anything really intended, she wrote thus, in great trembling both of spirits and hand \\u2014 \\u201cI am very much obliged to you, my dear Miss Crawford, for your kind congratulations, as far as they relate to my dearest William.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123678,\n            \"The rest of your note I know means nothing;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123688,\n            \"but I am so unequal to anything of the sort, that I hope you will excuse my begging you to take no farther notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123714,\n            \"I have seen too much of Mr. Crawford not to understand his manners;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123729,\n            \"if he understood me as well, he would, I dare say, behave differently.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123746,\n            \"I do not know what I write, but it would be a great favour of you never to mention the subject again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123770,\n            \"With thanks for the honour of your note, I remain, dear Miss Crawford, & c.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123793,\n            \"\\u201d The conclusion was scarcely intelligible from increasing fright, for she found that Mr. Crawford, under pretence of receiving the note, was coming towards her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123823,\n            \"\\u201cYou cannot think I mean to hurry you,\\u201dsaid he, in an undervoice, perceiving the amazing trepidation with which she made up the note, \\u201cyou cannot think I have any such object.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123863,\n            \"Do not hurry yourself, I entreat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123875,\n            \"I thank you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123895,\n            \"I am very much obliged to you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123931,\n            \"and as she instantly and with averted eyes walked towards the fireplace, where sat the others, he had nothing to do but to go in good earnest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124049,\n            \"but at least it would assure them both of her being neither imposed on nor gratified by Mr. Crawford\\u2019s attentions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124073,\n            \"CHAPTER XXXII Fanny had by no means forgotten Mr. Crawford when she awoke the next morning;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124126,\n            \"That was what she most earnestly desired: go and take his sister with him, as he was to do, and as he returned to Mansfield on purpose to do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124159,\n            \"And why it was not done already she could not devise, for Miss Crawford certainly wanted no delay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124199,\n            \"but he had only spoken of their journey as what would take place ere long.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124215,\n            \"Having so satisfactorily settled the conviction her note would convey, she could not but be astonished to see Mr. Crawford, as she accidentally did, coming up to the house again, and at an hour as early as the day before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124261,\n            \"His coming might have nothing to do with her, but she must avoid seeing him if possible;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124280,\n            \"and being then on her way upstairs, she resolved there to remain, during the whole of his visit, unless actually sent for;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124350,\n            \"but as no footsteps approached the East room, she grew gradually composed, could sit down, and be able to employ herself, and able to hope that Mr. Crawford had come and would go without her being obliged to know anything of the matter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124447,\n            \"she knew it as well as his voice;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124456,\n            \"she had trembled at it as often, and began to tremble again, at the idea of his coming up to speak to her, whatever might be the subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124488,\n            \"It was indeed Sir Thomas who opened the door and asked if she were there, and if he might come in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124511,\n            \"The terror of his former occasional visits to that room seemed all renewed, and she felt as if he were going to examine her again in French and English.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124542,\n            \"She was all attention, however, in placing a chair for him, and trying to appear honoured;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124562,\n            \"and, in her agitation, had quite overlooked the deficiencies of her apartment, till he, stopping short as he entered, said, with much surprise, \\u201cWhy have you no fire to-day?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124621,\n            \"\\u201cI am not cold, sir: I never sit here long at this time of year.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124669,\n            \"I understood that you had the use of this room by way of making you perfectly comfortable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124687,\n            \"In your bedchamber I know you _ cannot _ have a fire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124882,\n            \"I know what her sentiments have always been.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124891,\n            \"The principle was good in itself, but it may have been, and I believe _ has _ _ been _, carried too far in your case.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124938,\n            \"but I think too well of you, Fanny, to suppose you will ever harbour resentment on that account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125075,\n            \"I am sure you will not disappoint my opinion of you, by failing at any time to treat your aunt Norris with the respect and attention that are due to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125119,\n            \"I must speak to you for a few minutes, but I will not detain you long.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125168,\n            \"\\u201cYou are not aware, perhaps, that I have had a visitor this morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125206,\n            \"His errand you may probably conjecture.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125223,\n            \"and her uncle, perceiving that she was embarrassed to a degree that made either speaking or looking up quite impossible, turned away his own eyes, and without any farther pause proceeded in his account of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s visit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125268,\n            \"Mr. Crawford\\u2019s business had been to declare himself the lover of Fanny, make decided proposals for her, and entreat the sanction of the uncle, who seemed to stand in the place of her parents;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125309,\n            \"and he had done it all so well, so openly, so liberally, so properly, that Sir Thomas, feeling, moreover, his own replies, and his own remarks to have been very much to the purpose, was exceedingly happy to give the particulars of their conversation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125363,\n            \"and little aware of what was passing in his niece\\u2019s mind, conceived that by such details he must be gratifying her far more than himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125434,\n            \"and, with her eyes fixed intently on one of the windows, was listening to her uncle in the utmost perturbation and dismay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125459,\n            \"For a moment he ceased, but she had barely become conscious of it, when, rising from his chair, he said, \\u201cAnd now, Fanny, having performed one part of my commission, and shewn you everything placed on a basis the most assured and satisfactory, I may execute the remainder by prevailing on you to accompany me downstairs, where, though I cannot but presume on having been no unacceptable companion myself, I must submit to your finding one still better worth listening to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125554,\n            \"Mr. Crawford, as you have perhaps foreseen, is yet in the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125570,\n            \"He is in my room, and hoping to see you there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125603,\n            \"but what was his increase of astonishment on hearing her exclaim \\u2014 \\u201cOh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125618,\n            \"no, sir, I cannot, indeed I cannot go down to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125633,\n            \"Mr. Crawford ought to know \\u2014 he must know that: I told him enough yesterday to convince him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125654,\n            \"he spoke to me on this subject yesterday, and I told him without disguise that it was very disagreeable to me, and quite out of my power to return his good opinion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125689,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI do not catch your meaning,\\u201dsaid Sir Thomas, sitting down again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125707,\n            \"\\u201cOut of your power to return his good opinion?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125723,\n            \"I know he spoke to you yesterday, and (as far as I understand) received as much encouragement to proceed as a well-judging young woman could permit herself to give.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125758,\n            \"I was very much pleased with what I collected to have been your behaviour on the occasion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125785,\n            \"But now, when he has made his overtures so properly, and honourably \\u2014 what are your scruples _ now _?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125808,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou are mistaken, sir,\\u201dcried Fanny, forced by the anxiety of the moment even to tell her uncle that he was wrong;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125853,\n            \"I gave him no encouragement yesterday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125860,\n            \"On the contrary, I told him, I cannot recollect my exact words, but I am sure I told him that I would not listen to him, that it was very unpleasant to me in every respect, and that I begged him never to talk to me in that manner again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125928,\n            \"and I should have said still more, if I had been quite certain of his meaning anything seriously;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125970,\n            \"I thought it might all pass for nothing with _ him _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125996,\n            \"\\u201cAm I to understand,\\u201dsaid Sir Thomas, after a few moments\\u2019 silence, \\u201cthat you mean to _ refuse _ Mr. Crawford?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126058,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI \\u2014 I cannot like him, sir, well enough to marry him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126107,\n            \"Here is a young man wishing to pay his addresses to you, with everything to recommend him: not merely situation in life, fortune, and character, but with more than common agreeableness, with address and conversation pleasing to everybody.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126163,\n            \"you have now known him some time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126171,\n            \"His sister, moreover, is your intimate friend, and he has been doing _ that _ for your brother, which I should suppose would have been almost sufficient recommendation to you, had there been no other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126251,\n            \"and she did feel almost ashamed of herself, after such a picture as her uncle had drawn, for not liking Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126277,\n            \"\\u201cYou must have been aware,\\u201dcontinued Sir Thomas presently, \\u201cyou must have been some time aware of a particularity in Mr. Crawford\\u2019s manners to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126319,\n            \"You must have observed his attentions;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126386,\n            \"His attentions were always \\u2014 what I did not like.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126864,\n            \"and getting up and walking about the room with a frown, which Fanny could picture to herself, though she dared not lift up her eyes, he shortly afterwards, and in a voice of authority, said, \\u201cHave you any reason, child, to think ill of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s temper?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126930,\n            \"\\u201d She longed to add, \\u201cBut of his principles I have \\u201d;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126964,\n            \"Her ill opinion of him was founded chiefly on observations, which, for her cousins\\u2019 sake, she could scarcely dare mention to their father.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126992,\n            \"Maria and Julia, and especially Maria, were so closely implicated in Mr. Crawford\\u2019s misconduct, that she could not give his character, such as she believed it, without betraying them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127574,\n            \"Gladly would I have bestowed either of my own daughters on him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127592,\n            \"but had Mr. Crawford sought Julia\\u2019s hand, I should have given it to him with superior and more heartfelt satisfaction than I gave Maria\\u2019s to Mr. Rushworth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127794,\n            \"Her heart was almost broke by such a picture of what she appeared to him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127934,\n            \"\\u201cbut I am so perfectly convinced that I could never make him happy, and that I should be miserable myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128037,\n            \"and thought it not improbable that her mind might be in such a state as a little time, a little pressing, a little patience, and a little impatience, a judicious mixture of all on the lover\\u2019s side, might work their usual effect on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128185,\n            \"You must give him your own answer: we cannot expect him to be satisfied with less;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128203,\n            \"and you only can explain to him the grounds of that misconception of your sentiments, which, unfortunately for himself, he certainly has imbibed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128485,\n            \"She could not but feel some resentment against Mr. Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128497,\n            \"yet, if he really loved her, and were unhappy too!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128599,\n            \"I do not want to add to anything you may now be feeling, by an account of what he has felt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128655,\n            \"Upon my representation of what you were suffering, he immediately, and with the greatest delicacy, ceased to urge to see you for the present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128696,\n            \"\\u201cOf course,\\u201dcontinued her uncle, \\u201cit cannot be supposed but that he should request to speak with you alone, be it only for five minutes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129013,\n            \"She wished to prove to him that she did desire his comfort, and sought to regain his favour;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129149,\n            \"She wondered that Sir Thomas could have leisure to think of such a trifle again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129361,\n            \"\\u201cIf I had known you were going out, I should have got you just to go as far as my house with some orders for Nanny,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cwhich I have since, to my very great inconvenience, been obliged to go and carry myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129414,\n            \"I could very ill spare the time, and you might have saved me the trouble, if you would only have been so good as to let us know you were going out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129533,\n            \"Fanny would have had quite as good a walk there, I assure you, with the advantage of being of some use, and obliging her aunt: it is all her fault.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129568,\n            \"If she would but have let us know she was going out but there is a something about Fanny, I have often observed it before \\u2014 she likes to go her own way to work;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129697,\n            \"for Mrs. Norris had not discernment enough to perceive, either now, or at any other time, to what degree he thought well of his niece, or how very far he was from wishing to have his own children\\u2019s merits set off by the depreciation of hers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129900,\n            \"When the meeting with which she was threatened for the morrow was past, she could not but flatter herself that the subject would be finally concluded, and Mr. Crawford once gone from Mansfield, that everything would soon be as if no such subject had existed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129950,\n            \"She would not, could not believe, that Mr. Crawford\\u2019s affection for her could distress him long;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129987,\n            \"In London he would soon learn to wonder at his infatuation, and be thankful for the right reason in her which had saved him from its evil consequences.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130044,\n            \"an occurrence too common to strike her, and she thought nothing of it till the butler reappeared ten minutes afterwards, and advancing decidedly towards herself, said, \\u201cSir Thomas wishes to speak with you, ma\\u2019am, in his own room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130200,\n            \"What should Sir Thomas want you for?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130233,\n            \"Sir Thomas wants me, not Miss Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130314,\n            \"and Fanny, walking off in agitating consciousness, found herself, as she anticipated, in another minute alone with Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130378,\n            \"He had vanity, which strongly inclined him in the first place to think she did love him, though she might not know it herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130405,\n            \"and which, secondly, when constrained at last to admit that she did know her own present feelings, convinced him that he should be able in time to make those feelings what he wished.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130452,\n            \"and it was a love which, operating on an active, sanguine spirit, of more warmth than delicacy, made her affection appear of greater consequence because it was withheld, and determined him to have the glory, as well as the felicity, of forcing her to love him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130527,\n            \"he knew her to have all the worth that could justify the warmest hopes of lasting happiness with her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130547,\n            \"her conduct at this very time, by speaking the disinterestedness and delicacy of her character (qualities which he believed most rare indeed), was of a sort to heighten all his wishes, and confirm all his resolutions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130612,\n            \"He considered her rather as one who had never thought on the subject enough to be in danger;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130648,\n            \"whose modesty had prevented her from understanding his attentions, and who was still overpowered by the suddenness of addresses so wholly unexpected, and the novelty of a situation which her fancy had never taken into account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130734,\n            \"and he had so much delight in the idea of obliging her to love him in a very short time, that her not loving him now was scarcely regretted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130828,\n            \"She found that he did mean to persevere;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130837,\n            \"but how he could, after such language from her as she felt herself obliged to use, was not to be understood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130861,\n            \"She told him that she did not love him, could not love him, was sure she never should love him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130901,\n            \"that she must entreat him never to mention it again, to allow her to leave him at once, and let it be considered as concluded for ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130985,\n            \"yet this was not enough, for he immediately denied there being anything uncongenial in their characters, or anything unfriendly in their situations;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131081,\n            \"seem, at least, to be giving nearly as much pain to herself as to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131099,\n            \"Mr. Crawford was no longer the Mr. Crawford who, as the clandestine, insidious, treacherous admirer of Maria Bertram, had been her abhorrence, whom she had hated to see or to speak to, in whom she could believe no good quality to exist, and whose power, even of being agreeable, she had barely acknowledged.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131164,\n            \"He was now the Mr. Crawford who was addressing herself with ardent, disinterested love;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131206,\n            \"who was pouring out his sense of her merits, describing and describing again his affection, proving as far as words could prove it, and in the language, tone, and spirit of a man of talent too, that he sought her for her gentleness and her goodness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131295,\n            \"She might have disdained him in all the dignity of angry virtue, in the grounds of Sotherton, or the theatre at Mansfield Park;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131321,\n            \"but he approached her now with rights that demanded different treatment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131371,\n            \"The effect of the whole was a manner so pitying and agitated, and words intermingled with her refusal so expressive of obligation and concern, that to a temper of vanity and hope like Crawford\\u2019s, the truth, or at least the strength of her indifference, might well be questionable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131455,\n            \"It was with reluctance that he suffered her to go;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131466,\n            \"but there was no look of despair in parting to belie his words, or give her hopes of his being less unreasonable than he professed himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131588,\n            \"Had her own affections been as free \\u2014 as perhaps they ought to have been \\u2014 he never could have engaged them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131645,\n            \"wondering at what was yet to come, and in a nervous agitation which made nothing clear to her but the persuasion of her being never under any circumstances able to love Mr. Crawford, and the felicity of having a fire to sit over and think of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131696,\n            \"Sir Thomas was obliged, or obliged himself, to wait till the morrow for a knowledge of what had passed between the young people.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131746,\n            \"he had thought that an hour\\u2019s entreaty from a young man like Crawford could not have worked so little change on a gentle-tempered girl like Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131956,\n            \"Satisfied that the cause was now on a footing the most proper and hopeful, Sir Thomas resolved to abstain from all farther importunity with his niece, and to shew no open interference.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131991,\n            \"Upon her disposition he believed kindness might be the best way of working.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132043,\n            \"Accordingly, on this principle, Sir Thomas took the first opportunity of saying to her, with a mild gravity, intended to be overcoming, \\u201cWell, Fanny, I have seen Mr. Crawford again, and learn from him exactly how matters stand between you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132094,\n            \"He is a most extraordinary young man, and whatever be the event, you must feel that you have created an attachment of no common character;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132122,\n            \"though, young as you are, and little acquainted with the transient, varying, unsteady nature of love, as it generally exists, you cannot be struck as I am with all that is wonderful in a perseverance of this sort against discouragement.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132220,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed, sir,\\u201dsaid Fanny, \\u201cI am very sorry that Mr. Crawford should continue to \\u2014 I know that it is paying me a very great compliment, and I feel most undeservedly honoured;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132262,\n            \"but I am so perfectly convinced, and I have told him so, that it never will be in my power \\u2014\\u201d\\u201cMy dear,\\u201dinterrupted Sir Thomas, \\u201cthere is no occasion for this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132303,\n            \"Your feelings are as well known to me as my wishes and regrets must be to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132373,\n            \"Your happiness and advantage are all that I have in view, and nothing is required of you but to bear with Mr. Crawford\\u2019s endeavours to convince you that they may not be incompatible with his.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132426,\n            \"I have engaged for your seeing him whenever he calls, as you might have done had nothing of this sort occurred.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132449,\n            \"You will see him with the rest of us, in the same manner, and, as much as you can, dismissing the recollection of everything unpleasant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132621,\n            \"She could not, though only eighteen, suppose Mr. Crawford\\u2019s attachment would hold out for ever;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132776,\n            \"It was all known at the Parsonage, where he loved to talk over the future with both his sisters, and it would be rather gratifying to him to have enlightened witnesses of the progress of his success.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133672,\n            \"The first that occurred was not least in interest: the appearance of Henry Crawford and his sister walking together through the village as he rode into it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133728,\n            \"He was returning to Mansfield with spirits ready to feed on melancholy remembrances, and tender associations, when her own fair self was before him, leaning on her brother\\u2019s arm, and he found himself receiving a welcome, unquestionably friendly, from the woman whom, two moments before, he had been thinking of as seventy miles off, and as farther, much farther, from him in inclination than any distance could express.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134176,\n            \"His surprise was not so great as his father\\u2019s at her refusing Crawford, because, so far from supposing her to consider him with anything like a preference, he had always believed it to be rather the reverse, and could imagine her to be taken perfectly unprepared, but Sir Thomas could not regard the connexion as more desirable than he did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134420,\n            \"Crawford called the next day, and on the score of Edmund\\u2019s return, Sir Thomas felt himself more than licensed to ask him to stay dinner;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134457,\n            \"He staid of course, and Edmund had then ample opportunity for observing how he sped with Fanny, and what degree of immediate encouragement for him might be extracted from her manners;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134517,\n            \"if there was not hope in her confusion, there was hope in nothing else \\u2014 that he was almost ready to wonder at his friend\\u2019s perseverance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134600,\n            \"He was very willing to hope that Crawford saw clearer, and this was the most comfortable conclusion for his friend that he could come to from all that he observed to pass before, and at, and after dinner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134962,\n            \"To _ good _ reading, however, she had been long used: her uncle read well, her cousins all, Edmund very well, but in Mr. Crawford\\u2019s reading there was a variety of excellence beyond what she had ever met with.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135154,\n            \"Edmund watched the progress of her attention, and was amused and gratified by seeing how she gradually slackened in the needlework, which at the beginning seemed to occupy her totally: how it fell from her hand while she sat motionless over it, and at last, how the eyes which had appeared so studiously to avoid him throughout the day were turned and fixed on Crawford \\u2014 fixed on him for minutes, fixed on him, in short, till the attraction drew Crawford\\u2019s upon her, and the book was closed, and the charm was broken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135277,\n            \"but it had been enough to give Edmund encouragement for his friend, and as he cordially thanked him, he hoped to be expressing Fanny\\u2019s secret feelings too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136256,\n            \"and upon this being understood, he had a variety of questions from Crawford as to his feelings and success;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136323,\n            \"and when Crawford proceeded to ask his opinion and give his own as to the properest manner in which particular passages in the service should be delivered, shewing it to be a subject on which he had thought before, and thought with judgment, Edmund was still more and more pleased.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136995,\n            \"\\u201d Here Fanny, who could not but listen, involuntarily shook her head, and Crawford was instantly by her side again, entreating to know her meaning;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137025,\n            \"and as Edmund perceived, by his drawing in a chair, and sitting down close by her, that it was to be a very thorough attack, that looks and undertones were to be well tried, he sank as quietly as possible into a corner, turned his back, and took up a newspaper, very sincerely wishing that dear little Fanny might be persuaded into explaining away that shake of the head to the satisfaction of her ardent lover;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137160,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny, meanwhile, vexed with herself for not having been as motionless as she was speechless, and grieved to the heart to see Edmund\\u2019s arrangements, was trying by everything in the power of her modest, gentle nature, to repulse Mr. Crawford, and avoid both his looks and inquiries;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137330,\n            \"\\u201d In vain was her \\u201cPray, sir, don\\u2019t;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137404,\n            \"You quite astonish me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137409,\n            \"I wonder how you can \\u2014\\u201d\\u201cDo I astonish you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137577,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cPerhaps, sir,\\u201dsaid Fanny, wearied at last into speaking \\u2014 \\u201cperhaps, sir, I thought it was a pity you did not always know yourself as well as you seemed to do at that moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137641,\n            \"and poor Fanny, who had hoped to silence him by such an extremity of reproof, found herself sadly mistaken, and that it was only a change from one object of curiosity and one set of words to another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137699,\n            \"None such had occurred since his seeing her in her uncle\\u2019s room, none such might occur again before his leaving Mansfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138347,\n            \"CHAPTER XXXV Edmund had determined that it belonged entirely to Fanny to chuse whether her situation with regard to Crawford should be mentioned between them or not;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138394,\n            \"but after a day or two of mutual reserve, he was induced by his father to change his mind, and try what his influence might do for his friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138444,\n            \"and Sir Thomas thought it might be as well to make one more effort for the young man before he left Mansfield, that all his professions and vows of unshaken attachment might have as much hope to sustain them as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138507,\n            \"He wished him to be a model of constancy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138976,\n            \"I dare say that, on a comparison of our opinions, they would be found as much alike as they have been used to be: to the point \\u2014 I consider Crawford\\u2019s proposals as most advantageous and desirable, if you could return his affection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139043,\n            \"but that, as you cannot, you have done exactly as you ought in refusing him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139241,\n            \"You did not love him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139247,\n            \"nothing could have justified your accepting him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139402,\n            \"he never will succeed with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139497,\n            \"I think I never shall return his regard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139514,\n            \"I am aware, more aware than Crawford can be, that the man who means to make you love him (you having due notice of his intentions) must have very uphill work, for there are all your early attachments and habits in battle array;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139563,\n            \"and before he can get your heart for his own use he has to unfasten it from all the holds upon things animate and inanimate, which so many years\\u2019 growth have confirmed, and which are considerably tightened for the moment by the very idea of separation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139613,\n            \"I know that the apprehension of being forced to quit Mansfield will for a time be arming you against him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139634,\n            \"I wish he had not been obliged to tell you what he was trying for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139650,\n            \"I wish he had known you as well as I do, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139695,\n            \"I must hope, however, that time, proving him (as I firmly believe it will) to deserve you by his steady affection, will give him his reward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139728,\n            \"I cannot suppose that you have not the _ wish _ to love him \\u2014 the natural wish of gratitude.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139767,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWe are so totally unlike,\\u201dsaid Fanny, avoiding a direct answer, \\u201cwe are so very, very different in all our inclinations and ways, that I consider it as quite impossible we should ever be tolerably happy together, even if I _ could _ like him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139891,\n            \"and, Fanny, who that heard him read, and saw you listen to Shakespeare the other night, will think you unfitted as companions?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139934,\n            \"He is lively, you are serious;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139942,\n            \"but so much the better: his spirits will support yours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139977,\n            \"He sees difficulties nowhere: and his pleasantness and gaiety will be a constant support to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140145,\n            \"\\u201d Full well could Fanny guess where his thoughts were now: Miss Crawford\\u2019s power was all returning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140166,\n            \"He had been speaking of her cheerfully from the hour of his coming home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140181,\n            \"His avoiding her was quite at an end.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140201,\n            \"After leaving him to his happier thoughts for some minutes, Fanny, feeling it due to herself, returned to Mr. Crawford, and said, \\u201cIt is not merely in _ temper _ that I consider him as totally unsuited to myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140248,\n            \"though, in _ that _ respect, I think the difference between us too great, infinitely too great: his spirits often oppress me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140275,\n            \"but there is something in him which I object to still more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140288,\n            \"I must say, cousin, that I cannot approve his character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140301,\n            \"I have not thought well of him from the time of the play.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140315,\n            \"I then saw him behaving, as it appeared to me, so very improperly and unfeelingly \\u2014 I may speak of it now because it is all over \\u2014 so improperly by poor Mr. Rushworth, not seeming to care how he exposed or hurt him, and paying attentions to my cousin Maria, which \\u2014 in short, at the time of the play, I received an impression which will never be got over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140448,\n            \"Maria was wrong, Crawford was wrong, we were all wrong together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140571,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBefore the play, I am much mistaken if _ Julia _ did not think he was paying her attentions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140598,\n            \"I have heard before from some one of his being in love with Julia;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140622,\n            \"And, Fanny, though I hope I do justice to my sisters\\u2019 good qualities, I think it very possible that they might, one or both, be more desirous of being admired by Crawford, and might shew that desire rather more unguardedly than was perfectly prudent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140674,\n            \"I can remember that they were evidently fond of his society;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140777,\n            \"It proves him unspoilt by his uncle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140810,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am persuaded that he does not think, as he ought, on serious subjects.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140929,\n            \"and a most fortunate man he is to attach himself to such a creature \\u2014 to a woman who, firm as a rock in her own principles, has a gentleness of character so well adapted to recommend them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140970,\n            \"He has chosen his partner, indeed, with rare felicity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141201,\n            \"but yet I was afraid of her not estimating your worth to her brother quite as it deserved, and of her regretting that he had not rather fixed on some woman of distinction or fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141394,\n            \"and when once we had begun, we had not done with you, Fanny, till Crawford and Dr. Grant came in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141692,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, she was agreeing exactly with her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141718,\n            \"That you could refuse such a man as Henry Crawford seems more than they can understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141855,\n            \"Let him have all the perfections in the world, I think it ought not to be set down as certain that a man must be acceptable to every woman he may happen to like himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141892,\n            \"But, even supposing it is so, allowing Mr. Crawford to have all the claims which his sisters think he has, how was I to be prepared to meet him with any feeling answerable to his own?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141933,\n            \"He took me wholly by surprise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141940,\n            \"I had not an idea that his behaviour to me before had any meaning;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141955,\n            \"and surely I was not to be teaching myself to like him only because he was taking what seemed very idle notice of me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141980,\n            \"In my situation, it would have been the extreme of vanity to be forming expectations on Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142001,\n            \"I am sure his sisters, rating him as they do, must have thought it so, supposing he had meant nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142025,\n            \"How, then, was I to be \\u2014 to be in love with him the moment he said he was with me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142049,\n            \"How was I to have an attachment at his service, as soon as it was asked for?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142068,\n            \"His sisters should consider me as well as him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142078,\n            \"The higher his deserts, the more improper for me ever to have thought of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142175,\n            \"You have now given exactly the explanation which I ventured to make for you to your friend and Mrs. Grant, and they were both better satisfied, though your warm-hearted friend was still run away with a little by the enthusiasm of her fondness for Henry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142309,\n            \"Miss Crawford made us laugh by her plans of encouragement for her brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142323,\n            \"She meant to urge him to persevere in the hope of being loved in time, and of having his addresses most kindly received at the end of about ten years\\u2019 happy marriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142775,\n            \"You and Miss Crawford have made me too nice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142864,\n            \"It had been, as he before presumed, too hasty a measure on Crawford\\u2019s side, and time must be given to make the idea first familiar, and then agreeable to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142960,\n            \"but that everything should be left to Crawford\\u2019s assiduities, and the natural workings of her own mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143103,\n            \"The promised visit from \\u201cher friend,\\u201das Edmund called Miss Crawford, was a formidable threat to Fanny, and she lived in continual terror of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143249,\n            \"She was safe in the breakfast-room, with her aunt, when Miss Crawford did come;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143268,\n            \"and the first misery over, and Miss Crawford looking and speaking with much less particularity of expression than she had anticipated, Fanny began to hope there would be nothing worse to be endured than a half-hour of moderate agitation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143440,\n            \"She immediately shook her head at Fanny with arch, yet affectionate reproach, and taking her hand, seemed hardly able to help beginning directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143481,\n            \"I do not know when I shall have done scolding you,\\u201dand had discretion enough to reserve the rest till they might be secure of having four walls to themselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145917,\n            \"I had not, Miss Crawford, been an inattentive observer of what was passing between him and some part of this family in the summer and autumn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146795,\n            \"Her disposition was peculiarly calculated to value a fond treatment, and from having hitherto known so little of it, she was the more overcome by Miss Crawford\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146827,\n            \"Besides, there was gratitude towards her, for having made their _ t\\u00eate-\\u00e0-t\\u00eate _ so much less painful than her fears had predicted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147384,\n            \"but the more she recollected and observed, the more deeply was she convinced that everything was now in a fairer train for Miss Crawford\\u2019s marrying Edmund than it had ever been before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147584,\n            \"In their very last conversation, Miss Crawford, in spite of some amiable sensations, and much personal kindness, had still been Miss Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147663,\n            \"and she may be forgiven by older sages for looking on the chance of Miss Crawford\\u2019s future improvement as nearly desperate, for thinking that if Edmund\\u2019s influence in this season of love had already done so little in clearing her judgment, and regulating her notions, his worth would be finally wasted on her even in years of matrimony.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147729,\n            \"Experience might have hoped more for any young people so circumstanced, and impartiality would not have denied to Miss Crawford\\u2019s nature that participation of the general nature of women which would lead her to adopt the opinions of the man she loved and respected as her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162101,\n            \"She could not have a doubt of the manner in which Mr. Crawford must be struck.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162386,\n            \"The conclusion of the two gentlemen\\u2019s civilities was an offer of Mr. Price\\u2019s to take Mr. Crawford into the dockyard, which Mr. Crawford, desirous of accepting as a favour what was intended as such, though he had seen the dockyard again and again, and hoping to be so much the longer with Fanny, was very gratefully disposed to avail himself of, if the Miss Prices were not afraid of the fatigue;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163902,\n            \"and in the course of their walk back, Mr. Crawford contrived a minute\\u2019s privacy for telling Fanny that his only business in Portsmouth was to see her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163970,\n            \"and yet in spite of this and the two or three other things which she wished he had not said, she thought him altogether improved since she had seen him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166699,\n            \"and though, in one light, glad to have him gone, it seemed as if she was now deserted by everybody;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166733,\n            \"and she could not think of his returning to town, and being frequently with Mary and Edmund, without feelings so near akin to envy as made her hate herself for having them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166833,\n            \"The wonderful improvement which she still fancied in Mr. Crawford was the nearest to administering comfort of anything within the current of her thoughts.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166859,\n            \"Not considering in how different a circle she had been just seeing him, nor how much might be owing to contrast, she was quite persuaded of his being astonishingly more gentle and regardful of others than formerly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166914,\n            \"So anxious for her health and comfort, so very feeling as he now expressed himself, and really seemed, might not it be fairly supposed that he would not much longer persevere in a suit so distressing to her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168033,\n            \"How Miss Crawford really felt, how she meant to act, or might act without or against her meaning;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168054,\n            \"whether his importance to her were quite what it had been before the last separation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168112,\n            \"The idea that returned the oftenest was that Miss Crawford, after proving herself cooled and staggered by a return to London habits, would yet prove herself in the end too much attached to him to give him up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168343,\n            \"That Miss Crawford should endeavour to secure a meeting between him and Mrs. Rushworth, was all in her worst line of conduct, and grossly unkind and ill-judged;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168477,\n            \"If Mr. Crawford remembered her message to her cousin, she thought it very likely, most likely, that he would write to her at all events;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169001,\n            \"And had it been possible for her to return Mr. Crawford\\u2019s regard, the probability of his being very far from objecting to such a measure would have been the greatest increase of all her own comforts.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169042,\n            \"She thought he was really good-tempered, and could fancy his entering into a plan of that sort most pleasantly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169100,\n            \"As she opened, and saw its length, she prepared herself for a minute detail of happiness and a profusion of love and praise towards the fortunate creature who was now mistress of his fate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169157,\n            \"Crawford told me that you were wishing to hear from me, but I found it impossible to write from London, and persuaded myself that you would understand my silence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169246,\n            \"So very fond of you as Miss Crawford is, it is most natural that she should tell you enough of her own feelings to furnish a tolerable guess at mine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169305,\n            \"There is something soothing in the idea that we have the same friend, and that whatever unhappy differences of opinion may exist between us, we are united in our love of you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169378,\n            \"I was three weeks in London, and saw her (for London) very often.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169444,\n            \"Had she been different when I did see her, I should have made no complaint, but from the very first she was altered: my first reception was so unlike what I had hoped, that I had almost resolved on leaving London again directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169497,\n            \"You know the weak side of her character, and may imagine the sentiments and expressions which were torturing me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169518,\n            \"She was in high spirits, and surrounded by those who were giving all the support of their own bad sense to her too lively mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169545,\n            \"I do not like Mrs. Fraser.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169639,\n            \"I look upon her intimacy with those two sisters as the greatest misfortune of her life and mine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169658,\n            \"They have been leading her astray for years.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169667,\n            \"Could she be detached from them!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169695,\n            \"They are very fond of her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169702,\n            \"but I am sure she does not love them as she loves you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169716,\n            \"When I think of her great attachment to you, indeed, and the whole of her judicious, upright conduct as a sister, she appears a very different creature, capable of everything noble, and I am ready to blame myself for a too harsh construction of a playful manner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169770,\n            \"I cannot give her up, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169778,\n            \"She is the only woman in the world whom I could ever think of as a wife.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169796,\n            \"If I did not believe that she had some regard for me, of course I should not say this, but I do believe it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169823,\n            \"I am convinced that she is not without a decided preference.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169868,\n            \"Her ideas are not higher than her own fortune may warrant, but they are beyond what our incomes united could authorise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169900,\n            \"I could better bear to lose her because not rich enough, than because of my profession.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169918,\n            \"That would only prove her affection not equal to sacrifices, which, in fact, I am scarcely justified in asking;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169959,\n            \"Her prejudices, I trust, are not so strong as they were.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170022,\n            \"I cannot give her up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170028,\n            \"Connected as we already are, and, I hope, are to be, to give up Mary Crawford would be to give up the society of some of those most dear to me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170087,\n            \"The loss of Mary I must consider as comprehending the loss of Crawford and of Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170104,\n            \"Were it a decided thing, an actual refusal, I hope I should know how to bear it, and how to endeavour to weaken her hold on my heart, and in the course of a few years \\u2014 but I am writing nonsense.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170160,\n            \"and till I am, I can never cease to try for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170194,\n            \"I have sometimes thought of going to London again after Easter, and sometimes resolved on doing nothing till she returns to Mansfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170232,\n            \"but June is at a great distance, and I believe I shall write to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170293,\n            \"I shall be able to write much that I could not say, and shall be giving her time for reflection before she resolves on her answer, and I am less afraid of the result of reflection than of an immediate hasty impulse;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170343,\n            \"My greatest danger would lie in her consulting Mrs. Fraser, and I at a distance unable to help my own cause.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170439,\n            \"The last time I saw Crawford was at Mrs. Fraser\\u2019s party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170454,\n            \"I am more and more satisfied with all that I see and hear of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170478,\n            \"He thoroughly knows his own mind, and acts up to his resolutions: an inestimable quality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171348,\n            \"Everybody at all addicted to letter-writing, without having much to say, which will include a large proportion of the female world at least, must feel with Lady Bertram that she was out of luck in having such a capital piece of Mansfield news as the certainty of the Grants going to Bath, occur at a time when she could make no advantage of it, and will admit that it must have been very mortifying to her to see it fall to the share of her thankless son, and treated as concisely as possible at the end of a long letter, instead of having it to spread over the largest part of a page of her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173291,\n            \"The family were not consumptive, and she was more inclined to hope than fear for her cousin, except when she thought of Miss Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173318,\n            \"but Miss Crawford gave her the idea of being the child of good luck, and to her selfishness and vanity it would be good luck to have Edmund the only son.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174542,\n            \"She saw the proof of it in Miss Crawford, as well as in her cousins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174593,\n            \"It was so long since Fanny had had any letter from her, that she had some reason to think lightly of the friendship which had been so dwelt on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174624,\n            \"It was weeks since she had heard anything of Miss Crawford or of her other connexions in town, except through Mansfield, and she was beginning to suppose that she might never know whether Mr. Crawford had gone into Norfolk again or not till they met, and might never hear from his sister any more this spring, when the following letter was received to revive old and create some new sensations \\u2014 \\u201cForgive me, my dear Fanny, as soon as you can, for my long silence, and behave as if you could forgive me directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176376,\n            \"and before she had opened the letter, the possibility of Mr. and Miss Crawford\\u2019s having applied to her uncle and obtained his permission was giving her ease.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176615,\n            \"She could only perceive that it must relate to Wimpole Street and Mr. Crawford, and only conjecture that something very imprudent had just occurred in that quarter to draw the notice of the world, and to excite her jealousy, in Miss Crawford\\u2019s apprehension, if she heard it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176670,\n            \"Miss Crawford need not be alarmed for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176706,\n            \"If the Rushworths were gone themselves to Mansfield, as was to be inferred from what Miss Crawford said, it was not likely that anything unpleasant should have preceded them, or at least should make any impression.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176746,\n            \"As to Mr. Crawford, she hoped it might give him a knowledge of his own disposition, convince him that he was not capable of being steadily attached to any one woman in the world, and shame him from persisting any longer in addressing herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176800,\n            \"She had begun to think he really loved her, and to fancy his affection for her something more than common;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176822,\n            \"and his sister still said that he cared for nobody else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176834,\n            \"Yet there must have been some marked display of attentions to her cousin, there must have been some strong indiscretion, since her correspondent was not of a sort to regard a slight one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176870,\n            \"Very uncomfortable she was, and must continue, till she heard from Miss Crawford again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176925,\n            \"she might have trusted to her sense of what was due to her cousin.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177886,\n            \"Miss Crawford\\u2019s letter, which she had read so often as to make every line her own, was in frightful conformity with it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177946,\n            \"and if there was a woman of character in existence, who could treat as a trifle this sin of the first magnitude, who would try to gloss it over, and desire to have it unpunished, she could believe Miss Crawford to be the woman!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178028,\n            \"it was Mrs. Rushworth and Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178211,\n            \"_ His _ unsettled affections, wavering with his vanity, _ Maria\\u2019s _ decided attachment, and no sufficient principle on either side, gave it possibility: Miss Crawford\\u2019s letter stampt it a fact.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178281,\n            \"Miss Crawford, herself, Edmund;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182659,\n            \"and, having reason to think that one interview with Miss Crawford had taken place, from which Edmund derived only increased distress, had been as anxious on that account as on others to get him out of town, and had engaged him in taking Fanny home to her aunt, with a view to his relief and benefit, no less than theirs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182726,\n            \"Fanny was not in the secret of her uncle\\u2019s feelings, Sir Thomas not in the secret of Miss Crawford\\u2019s character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182752,\n            \"Had he been privy to her conversation with his son, he would not have wished her to belong to him, though her twenty thousand pounds had been forty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182947,\n            \"Long, long would it be ere Miss Crawford\\u2019s name passed his lips again, or she could hope for a renewal of such confidential intercourse as had been.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183221,\n            \"He had seen Miss Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183227,\n            \"He had been invited to see her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183249,\n            \"and regarding it as what was meant to be the last, last interview of friendship, and investing her with all the feelings of shame and wretchedness which Crawford\\u2019s sister ought to have known, he had gone to her in such a state of mind, so softened, so devoted, as made it for a few moments impossible to Fanny\\u2019s fears that it should be the last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183338,\n            \"She had met him, he said, with a serious \\u2014 certainly a serious \\u2014 even an agitated air;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183359,\n            \"but before he had been able to speak one intelligible sentence, she had introduced the subject in a manner which he owned had shocked him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183386,\n            \"\\u201c\\u2018 I heard you were in town,\\u2019said she;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183399,\n            \"\\u2018 I wanted to see you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185099,\n            \"all this together most grievously convinced me that I had never understood her before, and that, as far as related to mind, it had been the creature of my own imagination, not Miss Crawford, that I had been too apt to dwell on for many months past.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186150,\n            \"she was safe from Mr. Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186188,\n            \"and happy as all this must make her, she would still have been happy without any of it, for Edmund was no longer the dupe of Miss Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188601,\n            \"Her influence over him had already given him some influence over her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189714,\n            \"Scarcely had he done regretting Mary Crawford, and observing to Fanny how impossible it was that he should ever meet with such another woman, before it began to strike him whether a very different kind of woman might not do just as well, or a great deal better: whether Fanny herself were not growing as dear, as important to him in all her smiles and all her ways, as Mary Crawford had ever been;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189872,\n            \"I only entreat everybody to believe that exactly at the time when it was quite natural that it should be so, and not a week earlier, Edmund did cease to care about Miss Crawford, and became as anxious to marry Fanny as Fanny herself could desire.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 8]\": [\n        [\n            1629,\n            \"Suppose her a pretty girl, and seen by Tom or Edmund for the first time seven years hence, and I dare say there would be mischief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4923,\n            \"A week had passed in this way, and no suspicion of it conveyed by her quiet passive manner, when she was found one morning by her cousin Edmund, the youngest of the sons, sitting crying on the attic stairs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4967,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear little cousin,\\u201dsaid he, with all the gentleness of an excellent nature, \\u201cwhat can be the matter?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4993,\n            \"\\u201d And sitting down by her, he was at great pains to overcome her shame in being so surprised, and persuade her to speak openly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5041,\n            \"or was she puzzled about anything in her lesson that he could explain?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5055,\n            \"Did she, in short, want anything he could possibly get her, or do for her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5105,\n            \"and no sooner had he begun to revert to her own home, than her increased sobs explained to him where the grievance lay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5130,\n            \"He tried to console her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5136,\n            \"\\u201cYou are sorry to leave Mama, my dear little Fanny,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cwhich shows you to be a very good girl;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5188,\n            \"Let us walk out in the park, and you shall tell me all about your brothers and sisters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5208,\n            \"\\u201d On pursuing the subject, he found that, dear as all these brothers and sisters generally were, there was one among them who ran more in her thoughts than the rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5314,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut William will write to you, I dare say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5378,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf that be all your difficulty, I will furnish you with paper and every other material, and you may write your letter whenever you choose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5433,\n            \"Come with me into the breakfast-room, we shall find everything there, and be sure of having the room to ourselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5518,\n            \"\\u201cYes, when you have written the letter, I will take it to my father to frank.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5552,\n            \"and they went together into the breakfast-room, where Edmund prepared her paper, and ruled her lines with all the goodwill that her brother could himself have felt, and probably with somewhat more exactness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5591,\n            \"He continued with her the whole time of her writing, to assist her with his penknife or his orthography, as either were wanted;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5642,\n            \"He wrote with his own hand his love to his cousin William, and sent him half a guinea under the seal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5833,\n            \"She felt that she had a friend, and the kindness of her cousin Edmund gave her better spirits with everybody else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7451,\n            \"He was to be a clergyman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7688,\n            \"Luckily the visit happened in the Christmas holidays, when she could directly look for comfort to her cousin Edmund;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7709,\n            \"and he told her such charming things of what William was to do, and be hereafter, in consequence of his profession, as made her gradually admit that the separation might have some use.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7746,\n            \"Edmund\\u2019s friendship never failed her: his leaving Eton for Oxford made no change in his kind dispositions, and only afforded more frequent opportunities of proving them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7777,\n            \"Without any display of doing more than the rest, or any fear of doing too much, he was always true to her interests, and considerate of her feelings, trying to make her good qualities understood, and to conquer the diffidence which prevented their being more apparent;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7838,\n            \"Kept back as she was by everybody else, his single support could not bring her forward;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7856,\n            \"but his attentions were otherwise of the highest importance in assisting the improvement of her mind, and extending its pleasures.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7878,\n            \"He knew her to be clever, to have a quick apprehension as well as good sense, and a fondness for reading, which, properly directed, must be an education in itself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7930,\n            \"but he recommended the books which charmed her leisure hours, he encouraged her taste, and corrected her judgment: he made reading useful by talking to her of what she read, and heightened its attraction by judicious praise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7972,\n            \"In return for such services she loved him better than anybody in the world except William: her heart was divided between the two.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8102,\n            \"and, had his uncle died a few years sooner, it would have been duly given to some friend to hold till he were old enough for orders.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8267,\n            \"\\u201cI blush for the expedient which I am driven on, and I trust I may pity your feelings as a brother on the occasion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8322,\n            \"It may hereafter be in my power, or in yours (I hope it will), to procure him better preferment;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8591,\n            \"The time was now come when Sir Thomas expected his sister-in-law to claim her share in their niece, the change in Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s situation, and the improvement in Fanny\\u2019s age, seeming not merely to do away any former objection to their living together, but even to give it the most decided eligibility;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8657,\n            \"and as his own circumstances were rendered less fair than heretofore, by some recent losses on his West India estate, in addition to his eldest son\\u2019s extravagance, it became not undesirable to himself to be relieved from the expense of her support, and the obligation of her future provision.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8713,\n            \"In the fullness of his belief that such a thing must be, he mentioned its probability to his wife;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9064,\n            \"As soon as she met with Edmund she told him her distress.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9077,\n            \"\\u201cCousin,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201csomething is going to happen which I do not like at all;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9098,\n            \"and though you have often persuaded me into being reconciled to things that I disliked at first, you will not be able to do it now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11905,\n            \"but, in Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s watchful attention, and in Edmund\\u2019s judgment, he had sufficient confidence to make him go without fears for their conduct.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12403,\n            \"and Lady Bertram was soon astonished to find how very well they did even without his father, how well Edmund could supply his place in carving, talking to the steward, writing to the attorney, settling with the servants, and equally saving her from all possible fatigue or exertion in every particular but that of directing her letters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12486,\n            \"though not before Mrs. Norris had been indulging in very dreadful fears, and trying to make Edmund participate them whenever she could get him alone;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12957,\n            \"As to her cousins\\u2019 gaieties, she loved to hear an account of them, especially of the balls, and whom Edmund had danced with;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13305,\n            \"and that \\u201cFanny must have a horse\\u201dwas the resolute declaration with which he opposed whatever could be urged by the supineness of his mother, or the economy of his aunt, to make it appear unimportant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13601,\n            \"Though Edmund was much more displeased with his aunt than with his mother, as evincing least regard for her niece, he could not help paying more attention to what she said;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13635,\n            \"and at length determined on a method of proceeding which would obviate the risk of his father\\u2019s thinking he had done too much, and at the same time procure for Fanny the immediate means of exercise, which he could not bear she should be without.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13685,\n            \"He had three horses of his own, but not one that would carry a woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13708,\n            \"the third, a useful road-horse: this third he resolved to exchange for one that his cousin might ride;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13895,\n            \"Her sentiments towards him were compounded of all that was respectful, grateful, confiding, and tender.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13914,\n            \"As the horse continued in name, as well as fact, the property of Edmund, Mrs. Norris could tolerate its being for Fanny\\u2019s use;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14804,\n            \"but no representation of his aunt\\u2019s could induce him to find Mr. Rushworth a desirable companion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14854,\n            \"nor could he refrain from often saying to himself, in Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s company \\u2014 \\u201cIf this man had not twelve thousand a year, he would be a very stupid fellow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15463,\n            \"and it was not till after she had tried in vain to persuade her brother to settle with her at his own country house, that she could resolve to hazard herself among her other relations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18984,\n            \"Edmund, you have heard me mention Charles Anderson.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19398,\n            \"\\u201cYes, I cannot agree with you there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19551,\n            \"My friend Sneyd \\u2014 you have heard me speak of Sneyd, Edmund \\u2014 his father, and mother, and sisters, were there, all new to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20026,\n            \"In comparison with his brother, Edmund would have nothing to say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21663,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny, who was sitting on the other side of Edmund, exactly opposite Miss Crawford, and who had been attentively listening, now looked at him, and said in a low voice \\u2014 \\u201cCut down an avenue!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21710,\n            \"Does it not make you think of Cowper?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22387,\n            \"\\u201d Edmund was sorry to hear Miss Crawford, whom he was much disposed to admire, speak so freely of her uncle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22441,\n            \"\\u201cMr. Bertram,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cI have tidings of my harp at last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23042,\n            \"\\u201d Edmund spoke of the harp as his favourite instrument, and hoped to be soon allowed to hear her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23144,\n            \"Now, Mr. Bertram, if you write to your brother, I entreat you to tell him that my harp is come: he heard so much of my misery about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23179,\n            \"And you may say, if you please, that I shall prepare my most plaintive airs against his return, in compassion to his feelings, as I know his horse will lose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23477,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMiss Price has a brother at sea,\\u201dsaid Edmund, \\u201cwhose excellence as a correspondent makes her think you too severe upon us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23524,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny would rather have had Edmund tell the story, but his determined silence obliged her to relate her brother\\u2019s situation: her voice was animated in speaking of his profession, and the foreign stations he had been on;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23677,\n            \"Of various admirals I could tell you a great deal: of them and their flags, and the gradation of their pay, and their bickerings and jealousies.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23707,\n            \"But, in general, I can assure you that they are all passed over, and all very ill used.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23842,\n            \"\\u201d Edmund reverted to the harp, and was again very happy in the prospect of hearing her play.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23985,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNothing could be so gratifying to me as to hear your opinion of it,\\u201dwas his answer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24599,\n            \"I dare say Mr. Crawford would take my two nieces and me in his barouche, and Edmund can go on horseback, you know, sister, and Fanny will stay at home with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24644,\n            \"and every one concerned in the going was forward in expressing their ready concurrence, excepting Edmund, who heard it all and said nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25341,\n            \"I am glad you saw it all as I did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25352,\n            \"\\u201d Having formed her mind and gained her affections, he had a good chance of her thinking like him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25373,\n            \"though at this period, and on this subject, there began now to be some danger of dissimilarity, for he was in a line of admiration of Miss Crawford, which might lead him where Fanny could not follow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25684,\n            \"and to the credit of the lady it may be added that, without his being a man of the world or an elder brother, without any of the arts of flattery or the gaieties of small talk, he began to be agreeable to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25782,\n            \"There was a charm, perhaps, in his sincerity, his steadiness, his integrity, which Miss Crawford might be equal to feel, though not equal to discuss with herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25816,\n            \"She did not think very much about it, however: he pleased her for the present;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25834,\n            \"she liked to have him near her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25881,\n            \"neither could she wonder that, when the evening stroll was over, and the two families parted again, he should think it right to attend Mrs. Grant and her sister to their home, while Mr. Crawford was devoted to the ladies of the Park;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25963,\n            \"She was a little surprised that he could spend so many hours with Miss Crawford, and not see more of the sort of fault which he had already observed, and of which _ she _ was almost always reminded by a something of the same nature whenever she was in her company;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26023,\n            \"Edmund was fond of speaking to her of Miss Crawford, but he seemed to think it enough that the Admiral had since been spared;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26070,\n            \"The first actual pain which Miss Crawford occasioned her was the consequence of an inclination to learn to ride, which the former caught, soon after her being settled at Mansfield, from the example of the young ladies at the Park, and which, when Edmund\\u2019s acquaintance with her increased, led to his encouraging the wish, and the offer of his own quiet mare for the purpose of her first attempts, as the best fitted for a beginner that either stable could furnish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26267,\n            \"Edmund, who had taken down the mare and presided at the whole, returned with it in excellent time, before either Fanny or the steady old coachman, who always attended her when she rode without her cousins, were ready to set forward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26363,\n            \"and to the pure genuine pleasure of the exercise, something was probably added in Edmund\\u2019s attendance and instructions, and something more in the conviction of very much surpassing her sex in general by her early progress, to make her unwilling to dismount.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26411,\n            \"Fanny was ready and waiting, and Mrs. Norris was beginning to scold her for not being gone, and still no horse was announced, no Edmund appeared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26511,\n            \"and in Dr. Grant\\u2019s meadow she immediately saw the group \\u2014 Edmund and Miss Crawford both on horse-back, riding side by side, Dr. and Mrs. Grant, and Mr. Crawford, with two or three grooms, standing about and looking on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26606,\n            \"she wondered that Edmund should forget her, and felt a pang.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26705,\n            \"Edmund was close to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26711,\n            \"he was speaking to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26717,\n            \"he was evidently directing her management of the bridle;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26727,\n            \"he had hold of her hand;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26757,\n            \"what could be more natural than that Edmund should be making himself useful, and proving his good-nature by any one?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26781,\n            \"She could not but think, indeed, that Mr. Crawford might as well have saved him the trouble;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26802,\n            \"that it would have been particularly proper and becoming in a brother to have done it himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26883,\n            \"Her feelings for one and the other were soon a little tranquillised by seeing the party in the meadow disperse, and Miss Crawford still on horseback, but attended by Edmund on foot, pass through a gate into the lane, and so into the park, and make towards the spot where she stood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27059,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny\\u2019s answer was extremely civil, and Edmund added his conviction that she could be in no hurry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27081,\n            \"\\u201cFor there is more than time enough for my cousin to ride twice as far as she ever goes,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cand you have been promoting her comfort by preventing her from setting off half an hour sooner: clouds are now coming up, and she will not suffer from the heat as she would have done then.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27160,\n            \"I wish you had saved yourself this walk home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27170,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo part of it fatigues me but getting off this horse, I assure you,\\u201dsaid she, as she sprang down with his help;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27325,\n            \"nor did her attendant do her much good by his comments on Miss Crawford\\u2019s great cleverness as a horse-woman, which he had been watching with an interest almost equal to her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27521,\n            \"Her figure is as neat as her brother\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27574,\n            \"\\u201d When they parted at night Edmund asked Fanny whether she meant to ride the next day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27592,\n            \"\\u201cNo, I do not know \\u2014 not if you want the mare,\\u201dwas her answer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27612,\n            \"\\u201cI do not want her at all for myself,\\u201dsaid he;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27627,\n            \"\\u201cbut whenever you are next inclined to stay at home, I think Miss Crawford would be glad to have her a longer time \\u2014 for a whole morning, in short.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27661,\n            \"She has a great desire to get as far as Mansfield Common: Mrs. Grant has been telling her of its fine views, and I have no doubt of her being perfectly equal to it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27772,\n            \"You know I am strong enough now to walk very well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27784,\n            \"\\u201d Edmund looked pleased, which must be Fanny\\u2019s comfort, and the ride to Mansfield Common took place the next morning: the party included all the young people but herself, and was much enjoyed at the time, and doubly enjoyed again in the evening discussion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28212,\n            \"For a few minutes the brother and sister were too eager in their praise of the night and their remarks on the stars, to think beyond themselves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28520,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cFanny,\\u201dsaid Edmund, after looking at her attentively, \\u201cI am sure you have the headache.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28558,\n            \"\\u201cI can hardly believe you,\\u201dhe replied;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28569,\n            \"\\u201cI know your looks too well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28614,\n            \"to be sure she did,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris: \\u201cwould you have her stay within such a fine day as this?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28991,\n            \"\\u201cbut when the roses were gathered, your aunt wished to have them, and then you know they must be taken home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29074,\n            \"\\u201d Edmund got up and walked about the room, saying, \\u201cAnd could nobody be employed on such an errand but Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29432,\n            \"Between ourselves, Edmund,\\u201dnodding significantly at his mother, \\u201cit was cutting the roses, and dawdling about in the flower-garden, that did the mischief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29632,\n            \"His own forgetfulness of her was worse than anything which they had done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29687,\n            \"He was ashamed to think that for four days together she had not had the power of riding, and very seriously resolved, however unwilling he must be to check a pleasure of Miss Crawford\\u2019s, that it should never happen again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29820,\n            \"and the sudden change which Edmund\\u2019s kindness had then occasioned, made her hardly know how to support herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29854,\n            \"and as it was a pleasant fresh-feeling morning, less hot than the weather had lately been, Edmund trusted that her losses, both of health and pleasure, would be soon made good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29892,\n            \"While she was gone Mr. Rushworth arrived, escorting his mother, who came to be civil and to shew her civility especially, in urging the execution of the plan for visiting Sotherton, which had been started a fortnight before, and which, in consequence of her subsequent absence from home, had since lain dormant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29953,\n            \"Mrs. Norris and her nieces were all well pleased with its revival, and an early day was named and agreed to, provided Mr. Crawford should be disengaged: the young ladies did not forget that stipulation, and though Mrs. Norris would willingly have answered for his being so, they would neither authorise the liberty nor run the risk;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30377,\n            \"He can go on horseback, you know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30637,\n            \"and Edmund made his appearance just in time to learn what had been settled for Wednesday, to attend Mrs. Rushworth to her carriage, and walk half-way down the park with the two other ladies.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30803,\n            \"I could not, when the scheme was first mentioned the other day, understand why a visit from the family were not to be made in the carriage of the family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31061,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere is no hardship, I suppose, nothing unpleasant,\\u201dsaid Edmund, \\u201cin going on the barouche box.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31175,\n            \"\\u201cmy dear Edmund, there is no idea of her going with us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31208,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou can have no reason, I imagine, madam,\\u201dsaid he, addressing his mother, \\u201cfor wishing Fanny _ not _ to be of the party, but as it relates to yourself, to your own comfort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31287,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou can, if I stay at home with you, as I mean to do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31575,\n            \"When Edmund, therefore, told her in reply, as he did when she would give him the hearing, that she need not distress herself on Mrs. Rushworth\\u2019s account, because he had taken the opportunity, as he walked with her through the hall, of mentioning Miss Price as one who would probably be of the party, and had directly received a very sufficient invitation for his cousin, Mrs. Norris was too much vexed to submit with a very good grace, and would only say, \\u201cVery well, very well, just as you chuse, settle it your own way, I am sure I do not care about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31841,\n            \"but that he should forego any enjoyment on her account gave her pain, and her own satisfaction in seeing Sotherton would be nothing without him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32292,\n            \"and, in observing the appearance of the country, the bearings of the roads, the difference of soil, the state of the harvest, the cottages, the cattle, the children, she found entertainment that could only have been heightened by having Edmund to speak to of what she felt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32348,\n            \"That was the only point of resemblance between her and the lady who sat by her: in everything but a value for Edmund, Miss Crawford was very unlike her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32425,\n            \"In looking back after Edmund, however, when there was any stretch of road behind them, or when he gained on them in ascending a considerable hill, they were united, and a \\u201cthere he is\\u201dbroke at the same moment from them both, more than once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32514,\n            \"and to see only his expressive profile as he turned with a smile to Julia, or to catch the laugh of the other, was a perpetual source of irritation, which her own sense of propriety could but just smooth over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34029,\n            \"\\u201cI am disappointed,\\u201dsaid she, in a low voice, to Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34206,\n            \"\\u201cThis chapel was fitted up as you see it, in James the Second\\u2019s time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34687,\n            \"The young Mrs. Eleanors and Mrs. Bridgets \\u2014 starched up into seeming piety, but with heads full of something very different \\u2014 especially if the poor chaplain were not worth looking at \\u2014 and, in those days, I fancy parsons were very inferior even to what they are now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34765,\n            \"and he needed a little recollection before he could say, \\u201cYour lively mind can hardly be serious even on serious subjects.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35436,\n            \"\\u201cwhat, are you to be a clergyman?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35450,\n            \"I shall take orders soon after my father\\u2019s return \\u2014 probably at Christmas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36050,\n            \"and when, after a little time, the others began to form into parties, these three were found in busy consultation on the terrace by Edmund, Miss Crawford, and Fanny, who seemed as naturally to unite, and who, after a short participation of their regrets and difficulties, left them and walked on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36515,\n            \"At length, after a short pause, Miss Crawford began with, \\u201cSo you are to be a clergyman, Mr. Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36557,\n            \"You must suppose me designed for some profession, and might perceive that I am neither a lawyer, nor a soldier, nor a sailor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36601,\n            \"And you know there is generally an uncle or a grandfather to leave a fortune to the second son.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36657,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut why are you to be a clergyman?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37641,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy dear Fanny,\\u201dcried Edmund, immediately drawing her arm within his, \\u201chow thoughtless I have been!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37695,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThank you, but I am not at all tired.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37708,\n            \"\\u201d She took it, however, as she spoke, and the gratification of having her do so, of feeling such a connexion for the first time, made him a little forgetful of Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37746,\n            \"\\u201cYou scarcely touch me,\\u201dsaid he.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37844,\n            \"Do not you think we have?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37889,\n            \"you do not consider how much we have wound about.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37942,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut if you remember, before we left that first great path, we saw directly to the end of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37998,\n            \"I know nothing of your furlongs, but I am sure it is a very long wood, and that we have been winding in and out ever since we came into it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38053,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWe have been exactly a quarter of an hour here,\\u201dsaid Edmund, taking out his watch.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38091,\n            \"do not attack me with your watch.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38173,\n            \"\\u201cI am afraid you are very tired, Fanny,\\u201dsaid Edmund, observing her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38233,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHow abominable in you, then, to let me engross her horse as I did all last week!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38255,\n            \"I am ashamed of you and of myself, but it shall never happen again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38288,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s interest seems in safer hands with you than with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38718,\n            \"Edmund urged her remaining where she was with an earnestness which she could not resist, and she was left on the bench to think with pleasure of her cousin\\u2019s care, but with great regret that she was not stronger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38782,\n            \"CHAPTER X A quarter of an hour, twenty minutes, passed away, and Fanny was still thinking of Edmund, Miss Crawford, and herself, without interruption from any one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40182,\n            \"She could almost have thought that Edmund and Miss Crawford had left it, but that it was impossible for Edmund to forget her so entirely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41171,\n            \"\\u201d He got up and walked to the gate again, and \\u201cwished he had had the key about him at the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41513,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s best consolation was in being assured that Edmund had wished for her very much, and that he should certainly have come back for her, had she not been tired already;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41549,\n            \"but this was not quite sufficient to do away with the pain of having been left a whole hour, when he had talked of only a few minutes, nor to banish the sort of curiosity she felt to know what they had been conversing about all that time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43251,\n            \"but after tea, as Miss Crawford was standing at an open window with Edmund and Fanny looking out on a twilight scene, while the Miss Bertrams, Mr. Rushworth, and Henry Crawford were all busy with candles at the pianoforte, she suddenly revived it by turning round towards the group, and saying, \\u201cHow happy Mr. Rushworth looks!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43324,\n            \"\\u201d Edmund looked round at Mr. Rushworth too, but had nothing to say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43528,\n            \"My other sacrifice, of course, you do not understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43540,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy taking orders, I assure you, is quite as voluntary as Maria\\u2019s marrying.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45109,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI think the man who could often quarrel with Fanny,\\u201dsaid Edmund affectionately, \\u201cmust be beyond the reach of any sermons.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45177,\n            \"when, being earnestly invited by the Miss Bertrams to join in a glee, she tripped off to the instrument, leaving Edmund looking after her in an ecstasy of admiration of all her many virtues, from her obliging manners down to her light and graceful tread.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45304,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny agreed to it, and had the pleasure of seeing him continue at the window with her, in spite of the expected glee;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45331,\n            \"and of having his eyes soon turned, like hers, towards the scene without, where all that was solemn, and soothing, and lovely, appeared in the brilliancy of an unclouded night, and the contrast of the deep shade of the woods.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45776,\n            \"The approach of September brought tidings of Mr. Bertram, first in a letter to the gamekeeper and then in a letter to Edmund;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46597,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt is to his credit,\\u201dwas Edmund\\u2019s answer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46656,\n            \"Mrs. Grant, I believe, suspects him of a preference for Julia;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46753,\n            \"for I believe it often happens that a man, before he has quite made up his own mind, will distinguish the sister or intimate friend of the woman he is really thinking of more than the woman herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46854,\n            \"but with all that submission to Edmund could do, and all the help of the coinciding looks and hints which she occasionally noticed in some of the others, and which seemed to say that Julia was Mr. Crawford\\u2019s choice, she knew not always what to think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47395,\n            \"How she had looked before, Fanny could not recollect, for she had been dancing with Edmund herself, and had not thought about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49965,\n            \"\\u201cNobody loves a play better than you do, or can have gone much farther to see one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50087,\n            \"and though nothing was settled but that Tom Bertram would prefer a comedy, and his sisters and Henry Crawford a tragedy, and that nothing in the world could be easier than to find a piece which would please them all, the resolution to act something or other seemed so decided as to make Edmund quite uncomfortable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50147,\n            \"He was determined to prevent it, if possible, though his mother, who equally heard the conversation which passed at table, did not evince the least disapprobation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50208,\n            \"Tom, returning from them into the drawing-room, where Edmund was standing thoughtfully by the fire, while Lady Bertram was on the sofa at a little distance, and Fanny close beside her arranging her work, thus began as he entered \\u2014 \\u201cSuch a horribly vile billiard-table as ours is not to be met with, I believe, above ground.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50946,\n            \"Well, Edmund,\\u201dhe continued, returning to the former subject, posture, and voice, as soon as Lady Bertram began to nod again, \\u201cbut _ this _ I _ will _ maintain, that we shall be doing no harm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51209,\n            \"\\u201cI know my father as well as you do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51235,\n            \"Manage your own concerns, Edmund, and I\\u2019ll take care of the rest of the family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51599,\n            \"Don\\u2019t act yourself, if you do not like it, but don\\u2019t expect to govern everybody else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51622,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo, as to acting myself,\\u201dsaid Edmund, \\u201c_ that _ I absolutely protest against.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51644,\n            \"\\u201d Tom walked out of the room as he said it, and Edmund was left to sit down and stir the fire in thoughtful vexation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51671,\n            \"Fanny, who had heard it all, and borne Edmund company in every feeling throughout the whole, now ventured to say, in her anxiety to suggest some comfort, \\u201cPerhaps they may not be able to find any play to suit them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51731,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have no hope there, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52055,\n            \"Edmund had little to hope, but he was still urging the subject when Henry Crawford entered the room, fresh from the Parsonage, calling out, \\u201cNo want of hands in our theatre, Miss Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52140,\n            \"\\u201d Maria gave Edmund a glance, which meant, \\u201cWhat say you now?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55537,\n            \"and longed to have them roused as soon as possible by the remonstrance which Edmund would certainly make.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55835,\n            \"but when he entered the drawing-room before dinner, the buzz of discussion was high between Tom, Maria, and Mr. Yates;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55862,\n            \"and Mr. Rushworth stepped forward with great alacrity to tell him the agreeable news.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55988,\n            \"\\u201d in a tone of the greatest amazement, was his only reply to Mr. Rushworth, and he turned towards his brother and sisters as if hardly doubting a contradiction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56170,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI should not have thought it the sort of play to be so easily filled up, with _ us _,\\u201dreplied Edmund, turning away to the fire, where sat his mother, aunt, and Fanny, and seating himself with a look of great vexation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56224,\n            \"Mr. Rushworth followed him to say, \\u201cI come in three times, and have two-and-forty speeches.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56285,\n            \"\\u201d Edmund could not answer him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56313,\n            \"and being accompanied by Mr. Yates, and followed soon afterwards by Mr. Rushworth, Edmund almost immediately took the opportunity of saying, \\u201cI cannot, before Mr. Yates, speak what I feel as to this play, without reflecting on his friends at Ecclesford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56436,\n            \"It will not be necessary to send you to your _ father\\u2019s _ judgment, I am convinced.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56840,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am convinced, madam,\\u201dsaid Edmund, preventing Fanny, \\u201cthat Sir Thomas would not like it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56864,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere, my dear, do you hear what Edmund says?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56907,\n            \"\\u201d cried Edmund, \\u201cif she knew your reasons!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56963,\n            \"you must excuse me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57105,\n            \"We must not be over-precise, Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57539,\n            \"and Edmund found that to have endeavoured to set them right must be his only satisfaction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57560,\n            \"Mrs. Norris related again her triumph over Dick Jackson, but neither play nor preparation were otherwise much talked of, for Edmund\\u2019s disapprobation was felt even by his brother, though he would not have owned it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57932,\n            \"and I do sincerely give you joy, madam, as well as Mrs. Norris, and everybody else who is in the same predicament,\\u201dglancing half fearfully, half slyly, beyond Fanny to Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57972,\n            \"She was very civilly answered by Lady Bertram, but Edmund said nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58441,\n            \"Mr. Edmund Bertram, as you do not act yourself, you will be a disinterested adviser;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58460,\n            \"and, therefore, I apply to _ you _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58496,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy advice,\\u201dsaid he calmly, \\u201cis that you change the play.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58561,\n            \"but as they do not chuse to hear your advice at _ that _ _ table _\\u201d(looking round), \\u201cit certainly will not be taken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58598,\n            \"\\u201cIf _ any _ part could tempt _ you _ to act, I suppose it would be Anhalt,\\u201dobserved the lady archly, after a short pause;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58630,\n            \"\\u201cfor he is a clergyman, you know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58640,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201c_ That _ circumstance would by no means tempt me,\\u201dhe replied, \\u201cfor I should be sorry to make the character ridiculous by bad acting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59100,\n            \"You have only two scenes, and as I shall be Cottager, I\\u2019ll put you in and push you about, and you will do it very well, I\\u2019ll answer for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59139,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo, indeed, Mr. Bertram, you must excuse me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59168,\n            \"If I were to undertake it, I should only disappoint you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59266,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou must excuse me, indeed you must excuse me,\\u201dcried Fanny, growing more and more red from excessive agitation, and looking distressfully at Edmund, who was kindly observing her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59304,\n            \"but unwilling to exasperate his brother by interference, gave her only an encouraging smile.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59751,\n            \"By a look at her brother she prevented any farther entreaty from the theatrical board, and the really good feelings by which she was almost purely governed were rapidly restoring her to all the little she had lost in Edmund\\u2019s favour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60157,\n            \"\\u201d While he spoke, Maria was looking apprehensively round at Edmund in full expectation that he must oppose such an enlargement of the plan as this: so contrary to all their first protestations;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60240,\n            \"Yes, Mr. Charles Maddox dined at my sister\\u2019s one day, did not he, Henry?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60272,\n            \"Let _ him _ be applied to, if you please, for it will be less unpleasant to me than to have a perfect stranger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60321,\n            \"and though Julia, who had scarcely opened her lips before, observed, in a sarcastic manner, and with a glance first at Maria and then at Edmund, that \\u201cthe Mansfield theatricals would enliven the whole neighbourhood exceedingly,\\u201dEdmund still held his peace, and shewed his feelings only by a determined gravity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60642,\n            \"and if she were applied to again among themselves with all the authoritative urgency that Tom and Maria were capable of, and Edmund perhaps away, what should she do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61278,\n            \"though she had known the pains of tyranny, of ridicule, and neglect, yet almost every recurrence of either had led to something consolatory: her aunt Bertram had spoken for her, or Miss Lee had been encouraging, or, what was yet more frequent or more dear, Edmund had been her champion and her friend: he had supported her cause or explained her meaning, he had told her not to cry, or had given her some proof of affection which made her tears delightful;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61559,\n            \"To this nest of comforts Fanny now walked down to try its influence on an agitated, doubting spirit, to see if by looking at Edmund\\u2019s profile she could catch any of his counsel, or by giving air to her geraniums she might inhale a breeze of mental strength herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61718,\n            \"And would Edmund\\u2019s judgment, would his persuasion of Sir Thomas\\u2019 s disapprobation of the whole, be enough to justify her in a determined denial in spite of all the rest?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61902,\n            \"Her eyes brightened at the sight of Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61911,\n            \"\\u201cCan I speak with you, Fanny, for a few minutes?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61941,\n            \"I want your opinion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62215,\n            \"After being known to oppose the scheme from the beginning, there is absurdity in the face of my joining them _ now _, when they are exceeding their first plan in every respect;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62285,\n            \"I see your judgment is not with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62300,\n            \"Perhaps you are not so much aware as I am of the mischief that _ may _, of the unpleasantness that _ must _ arise from a young man\\u2019s being received in this manner: domesticated among us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62421,\n            \"I heard enough of what she said to you last night to understand her unwillingness to be acting with a stranger;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62513,\n            \"but I am more sorry to see you drawn in to do what you had resolved against, and what you are known to think will be disagreeable to my uncle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62555,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThey will not have much cause of triumph when they see how infamously I act.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62589,\n            \"But if I can be the means of restraining the publicity of the business, of limiting the exhibition, of concentrating our folly, I shall be well repaid.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62620,\n            \"As I am now, I have no influence, I can do nothing: I have offended them, and they will not hear me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62647,\n            \"but when I have put them in good-humour by this concession, I am not without hopes of persuading them to confine the representation within a much smaller circle than they are now in the high road for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62695,\n            \"My object is to confine it to Mrs. Rushworth and the Grants.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62737,\n            \"Can you mention any other measure by which I have a chance of doing equal good?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62765,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cGive me your approbation, then, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62789,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf you are against me, I ought to distrust myself, and yet \\u2014 But it is absolutely impossible to let Tom go on in this way, riding about the country in quest of anybody who can be persuaded to act \\u2014 no matter whom: the look of a gentleman is to be enough.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62849,\n            \"I thought _ you _ would have entered more into Miss Crawford\\u2019s feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62952,\n            \"Her conscience stopt her in the middle, but Edmund was satisfied.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62987,\n            \"And now, dear Fanny, I will not interrupt you any longer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63007,\n            \"But I could not be easy till I had spoken to you, and come to a decision.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63058,\n            \"If Tom is up, I shall go to him directly and get it over, and when we meet at breakfast we shall be all in high good-humour at the prospect of acting the fool together with such unanimity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63169,\n            \"I admire your little establishment exceedingly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63176,\n            \"and as soon as I am gone, you will empty your head of all this nonsense of acting, and sit comfortably down to your table.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63231,\n            \"He had told her the most extraordinary, the most inconceivable, the most unwelcome news;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63272,\n            \"After all that she had heard him say, and seen him look, and known him to be feeling.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63337,\n            \"The doubts and alarms as to her own conduct, which had previously distressed her, and which had all slept while she listened to him, were become of little consequence now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63442,\n            \"Such a victory over Edmund\\u2019s discretion had been beyond their hopes, and was most delightful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63528,\n            \"their point was gained: he was to act, and he was driven to it by the force of selfish inclinations only.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63552,\n            \"Edmund had descended from that moral elevation which he had maintained before, and they were both as much the better as the happier for the descent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63580,\n            \"They behaved very well, however, to _ him _ on the occasion, betraying no exultation beyond the lines about the corners of the mouth, and seemed to think it as great an escape to be quit of the intrusion of Charles Maddox, as if they had been forced into admitting him against their inclination.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63672,\n            \"and when Edmund, pursuing that idea, gave a hint of his hope as to the limitation of the audience, they were ready, in the complaisance of the moment, to promise anything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63718,\n            \"Mrs. Norris offered to contrive his dress, Mr. Yates assured him that Anhalt\\u2019s last scene with the Baron admitted a good deal of action and emphasis, and Mr. Rushworth undertook to count his speeches.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63976,\n            \"and even this, when imparted by Edmund, brought a pang with it, for it was Miss Crawford to whom she was obliged \\u2014 it was Miss Crawford whose kind exertions were to excite her gratitude, and whose merit in making them was spoken of with a glow of admiration.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64071,\n            \"Her heart and her judgment were equally against Edmund\\u2019s decision: she could not acquit his unsteadiness, and his happiness under it made her wretched.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64330,\n            \"and that, had she received even the greatest, she could never have been easy in joining a scheme which, considering only her uncle, she must condemn altogether.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65615,\n            \"Edmund, between his theatrical and his real part, between Miss Crawford\\u2019s claims and his own conduct, between love and consistency, was equally unobservant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65802,\n            \"Entirely against _ his _ judgment, a scene-painter arrived from town, and was at work, much to the increase of the expenses, and, what was worse, of the eclat of their proceedings;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66324,\n            \"As far as she could judge, Mr. Crawford was considerably the best actor of all: he had more confidence than Edmund, more judgment than Tom, more talent and taste than Mr. Yates.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67230,\n            \"Fanny did not share her aunt\\u2019s composure: she thought of the morrow a great deal, for if the three acts were rehearsed, Edmund and Miss Crawford would then be acting together for the first time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67686,\n            \"I came here to-day intending to rehearse it with Edmund \\u2014 by ourselves \\u2014 against the evening, but he is not in the way;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67714,\n            \"and if he _ were _, I do not think I could go through it with _ him _, till I have hardened myself a little;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67846,\n            \"How am I ever to look him in the face and say such things?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67866,\n            \"But then he is your cousin, which makes all the difference.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67879,\n            \"You must rehearse it with me, that I may fancy _ you _ him, and get on by degrees.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67901,\n            \"You _ have _ a look of _ his _ sometimes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68294,\n            \"and they had got through half the scene, when a tap at the door brought a pause, and the entrance of Edmund, the next moment, suspended it all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68344,\n            \"and as Edmund was come on the very same business that had brought Miss Crawford, consciousness and pleasure were likely to be more than momentary in _ them _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68375,\n            \"He too had his book, and was seeking Fanny, to ask her to rehearse with him, and help him to prepare for the evening, without knowing Miss Crawford to be in the house;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68490,\n            \"Edmund proposed, urged, entreated it, till the lady, not very unwilling at first, could refuse no longer, and Fanny was wanted only to prompt and observe them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69356,\n            \"and as they all persevered, as Edmund repeated his wish, and with a look of even fond dependence on her good-nature, she must yield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70826,\n            \"He inquired next after her family, especially William: and his kindness altogether was such as made her reproach herself for loving him so little, and thinking his return a misfortune;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72130,\n            \"The first day I went over Mansfield Wood, and Edmund took the copses beyond Easton, and we brought home six brace between us, and might each have killed six times as many, but we respect your pheasants, sir, I assure you, as much as you could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73589,\n            \"of unquietness, but prevented him even from seeing the expression of the face on which his own eyes were fixed \\u2014 from seeing Sir Thomas\\u2019 s dark brow contract as he looked with inquiring earnestness at his daughters and Edmund, dwelling particularly on the latter, and speaking a language, a remonstrance, a reproof, which _ he _ felt at his heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73658,\n            \"Not less acutely was it felt by Fanny, who had edged back her chair behind her aunt\\u2019s end of the sofa, and, screened from notice herself, saw all that was passing before her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73698,\n            \"Such a look of reproach at Edmund from his father she could never have expected to witness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73731,\n            \"Sir Thomas\\u2019 s look implied, \\u201cOn your judgment, Edmund, I depended;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73754,\n            \"\\u201d She knelt in spirit to her uncle, and her bosom swelled to utter, \\u201cOh, not to _ him _!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74447,\n            \"CHAPTER XX Edmund\\u2019s first object the next morning was to see his father alone, and give him a fair statement of the whole acting scheme, defending his own share in it as far only as he could then, in a soberer moment, feel his motives to deserve, and acknowledging, with perfect ingenuousness, that his concession had been attended with such partial good as to make his judgment in it very doubtful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74684,\n            \"and having shaken hands with Edmund, meant to try to lose the disagreeable impression, and forget how much he had been forgotten himself as soon as he could, after the house had been cleared of every object enforcing the remembrance, and restored to its proper state.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74869,\n            \"and, excepting Edmund, he believed, of unsteady characters;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75008,\n            \"She had a great deal to insinuate in her own praise as to _ general _ attention to the interest and comfort of his family, much exertion and many sacrifices to glance at in the form of hurried walks and sudden removals from her own fireside, and many excellent hints of distrust and economy to Lady Bertram and Edmund to detail, whereby a most considerable saving had always arisen, and more than one bad servant been detected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77987,\n            \"Edmund did not wonder that such should be his father\\u2019s feelings, nor could he regret anything but the exclusion of the Grants.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78013,\n            \"\\u201cBut they,\\u201dhe observed to Fanny, \\u201chave a claim.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78043,\n            \"I could wish my father were more sensible of their very great attention to my mother and sisters while he was away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78066,\n            \"I am afraid they may feel themselves neglected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78128,\n            \"We are sometimes a little in want of animation among ourselves: my sisters seem out of spirits, and Tom is certainly not at his ease.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82415,\n            \"And besides, I want to play something more to you \\u2014 a very pretty piece \\u2014 and your cousin Edmund\\u2019s prime favourite.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82459,\n            \"and though she had not waited for that sentence to be thinking of Edmund, such a memento made her particularly awake to his idea, and she fancied him sitting in that room again and again, perhaps in the very spot where she sat now, listening with constant delight to the favourite air, played, as it appeared to her, with superior tone and expression;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84133,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI grant you the name is good in itself, and _ Lord _ Edmund or _ Sir _ Edmund sound delightfully;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84158,\n            \"but sink it under the chill, the annihilation of a Mr., and Mr. Edmund is no more than Mr. John or Mr. Thomas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84358,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cPerhaps I might have scolded,\\u201dsaid Edmund, \\u201cif either of you had been sitting down alone;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84433,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd really,\\u201dadded Edmund, \\u201cthe day is so mild, that your sitting down for a few minutes can be hardly thought imprudent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85500,\n            \"No, Miss Crawford,\\u201dhe added, in a more serious tone, \\u201cthere _ are _ distinctions which I should be miserable if I thought myself without any chance \\u2014 absolutely without chance or possibility of obtaining \\u2014 but they are of a different character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85550,\n            \"\\u201d A look of consciousness as he spoke, and what seemed a consciousness of manner on Miss Crawford\\u2019s side as she made some laughing answer, was sorrowfull food for Fanny\\u2019s observation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85695,\n            \"and Edmund began at the same time to recollect that his mother had been inquiring for her, and that he had walked down to the Parsonage on purpose to bring her back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85777,\n            \"Dr. Grant was in the vestibule, and as they stopt to speak to him she found, from Edmund\\u2019s manner, that he _ did _ mean to go with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85947,\n            \"But Edmund, delighted with her having such an happiness offered, and ascertaining with half a look, and half a sentence, that she had no objection but on her aunt\\u2019s account, could not imagine that his mother would make any difficulty of sparing her, and therefore gave his decided open advice that the invitation should be accepted;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86349,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf you put such a question to her,\\u201dcried Edmund, preventing his cousin\\u2019s speaking, \\u201cFanny will immediately say No;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86378,\n            \"but I am sure, my dear mother, she would like to go;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86512,\n            \"So I will, Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86552,\n            \"but I meant my father\\u2019s opinion as to the _ propriety _ of the invitation\\u2019s being accepted or not;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86576,\n            \"and I think he will consider it a right thing by Mrs. Grant, as well as by Fanny, that being the _ first _ invitation it should be accepted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86985,\n            \"\\u201d Edmund found himself obliged to speak and fill up the blanks in his mother\\u2019s story.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87030,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut is it not very natural,\\u201dobserved Edmund, \\u201cthat Mrs. Grant should wish to procure so agreeable a visitor for her sister?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87281,\n            \"Edmund knocked at her door in his way to his own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87327,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThank you, I am _ so _ glad,\\u201dwas Fanny\\u2019s instinctive reply;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87347,\n            \"though when she had turned from him and shut the door, she could not help feeling, \\u201cAnd yet why should I be glad?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87490,\n            \"for Lady Bertram never thought of being useful to anybody, and Mrs. Norris, when she came on the morrow, in consequence of an early call and invitation from Sir Thomas, was in a very ill humour, and seemed intent only on lessening her niece\\u2019s pleasure, both present and future, as much as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87554,\n            \"\\u201cUpon my word, Fanny, you are in high luck to meet with such attention and indulgence!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88198,\n            \"And as to coming away at night, you are to stay just as long as Edmund chuses.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88357,\n            \"and when Sir Thomas soon afterwards, just opening the door, said, \\u201cFanny, at what time would you have the carriage come round?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88496,\n            \"and not bearing to remain with her in what might seem a state of triumph, she followed her uncle out of the room, having staid behind him only long enough to hear these words spoken in angry agitation \\u2014 \\u201cQuite unnecessary!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88561,\n            \"I observed he was hoarse on Thursday night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88579,\n            \"She felt that the carriage was for herself, and herself alone: and her uncle\\u2019s consideration of her, coming immediately after such representations from her aunt, cost her some tears of gratitude when she was alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88678,\n            \"\\u201cNow I must look at you, Fanny,\\u201dsaid Edmund, with the kind smile of an affectionate brother, \\u201cand tell you how I like you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88710,\n            \"and as well as I can judge by this light, you look very nicely indeed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88790,\n            \"I hope you do not think me too fine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88816,\n            \"No, I see no finery about you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89139,\n            \"for though she must submit, as her own propriety of mind directed, in spite of her aunt Norris\\u2019 s opinion, to being the principal lady in company, and to all the little distinctions consequent thereon, she found, while they were at table, such a happy flow of conversation prevailing, in which she was not required to take any part \\u2014 there was so much to be said between the brother and sister about Bath, so much between the two young men about hunting, so much of politics between Mr. Crawford and Dr. Grant, and of everything and all together between Mr. Crawford and Mrs. Grant, as to leave her the fairest prospect of having only to listen in quiet, and of passing a very agreeable day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89284,\n            \"She could not compliment the newly arrived gentleman, however, with any appearance of interest, in a scheme for extending his stay at Mansfield, and sending for his hunters from Norfolk, which, suggested by Dr. Grant, advised by Edmund, and warmly urged by the two sisters, was soon in possession of his mind, and which he seemed to want to be encouraged even by her to resolve on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89475,\n            \"She heard them spoken of by him only in a general way, till they were all re-assembled in the drawing-room, when Edmund, being engaged apart in some matter of business with Dr. Grant, which seemed entirely to engross them, and Mrs. Grant occupied at the tea-table, he began talking of them with more particularity to his other sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90027,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWe were unlucky, Miss Price,\\u201dhe continued, in a lower tone, to avoid the possibility of being heard by Edmund, and not at all aware of her feelings, \\u201cwe certainly were very unlucky.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91092,\n            \"The assurance of Edmund\\u2019s being so soon to take orders, coming upon her like a blow that had been suspended, and still hoped uncertain and at a distance, was felt with resentment and mortification.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91132,\n            \"She was very angry with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91146,\n            \"She _ had _ begun to think of him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91171,\n            \"but she would now meet him with his own cool feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91183,\n            \"It was plain that he could have no serious views, no true attachment, by fixing himself in a situation which he must know she would never stoop to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91214,\n            \"She would learn to match him in his indifference.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91224,\n            \"She would henceforth admit his attentions without any idea beyond immediate amusement.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91237,\n            \"If _ he _ could so command his affections, _ hers _ should do her no harm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93237,\n            \"This was exactly what Sir Thomas and Edmund had been separately conniving at, as each proved to the other by the sympathetic alacrity with which they both advised Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s continuing where she was, instead of rushing out into the hall as soon as the noises of the arrival reached them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94604,\n            \"He was roused from the reverie of retrospection and regret produced by it, by some inquiry from Edmund as to his plans for the next day\\u2019s hunting;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96484,\n            \"\\u201cWell,\\u201dcontinued Edmund, \\u201cand how did you like what you saw?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96857,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd I have two or three ideas also,\\u201dsaid Edmund, \\u201cand one of them is, that very little of your plan for Thornton Lacey will ever be put in practice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98515,\n            \"and not being able to catch Edmund\\u2019s ear, was detailing it to his fair neighbour with a look of considerable earnestness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98862,\n            \"May I hope for your acquiescence, and for your not influencing your son against such a tenant?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99056,\n            \"\\u201cHis going, though only eight miles, will be an unwelcome contraction of our family circle;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99194,\n            \"he might be the clergyman of Thornton Lacey every seventh day, for three or four hours, if that would content him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99238,\n            \"and that if he does not live among his parishioners, and prove himself, by constant attention, their well-wisher and friend, he does very little either for their good or his own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99331,\n            \"\\u201cSir Thomas,\\u201dsaid Edmund, \\u201cundoubtedly understands the duty of a parish priest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99349,\n            \"We must hope his son may prove that _ he _ knows it too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99404,\n            \"One of whom, having never before understood that Thornton was so soon and so completely to be his home, was pondering with downcast eyes on what it would be _ not _ to see Edmund every day;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100736,\n            \"My dear Sir Thomas, we have settled it that the carriage should come back for you, and Edmund and William.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100803,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s last feeling in the visit was disappointment: for the shawl which Edmund was quietly taking from the servant to bring and put round her shoulders was seized by Mr. Crawford\\u2019s quicker hand, and she was obliged to be indebted to his more prominent attention.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101371,\n            \"Edmund, William, and Fanny did, in their different ways, look and speak as much grateful pleasure in the promised ball as Sir Thomas could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101401,\n            \"Edmund\\u2019s feelings were for the other two.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102012,\n            \"\\u201d Edmund was at this time particularly full of cares: his mind being deeply occupied in the consideration of two important events now at hand, which were to fix his fate in life \\u2014 ordination and matrimony \\u2014 events of such a serious character as to make the ball, which would be very quickly followed by one of them, appear of less moment in his eyes than in those of any other person in the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102093,\n            \"On the 23rd he was going to a friend near Peterborough, in the same situation as himself, and they were to receive ordination in the course of the Christmas week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102479,\n            \"He had seen her eyes sparkle as she spoke of the dear friend\\u2019s letter, which claimed a long visit from her in London, and of the kindness of Henry, in engaging to remain where he was till January, that he might convey her thither;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102591,\n            \"He had since heard her express herself differently, with other feelings, more chequered feelings: he had heard her tell Mrs. Grant that she should leave her with regret;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102736,\n            \"Independent of his two cousins\\u2019 enjoyment in it, the evening was to him of no higher value than any other appointed meeting of the two families might be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102807,\n            \"To engage her early for the two first dances was all the command of individual happiness which he felt in his power, and the only preparation for the ball which he could enter into, in spite of all that was passing around him on the subject, from morning till night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102917,\n            \"and as Edmund and William were gone to Northampton, and she had reason to think Mr. Crawford likewise out, she walked down to the Parsonage without much fear of wanting an opportunity for private discussion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104481,\n            \"but on opening the door, what was her surprise to find her cousin Edmund there writing at the table!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104519,\n            \"\\u201cFanny,\\u201dsaid he directly, leaving his seat and his pen, and meeting her with something in his hand, \\u201cI beg your pardon for being here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104552,\n            \"I came to look for you, and after waiting a little while in hope of your coming in, was making use of your inkstand to explain my errand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104594,\n            \"but I can now speak my business, which is merely to beg your acceptance of this little trifle \\u2014 a chain for William\\u2019s cross.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104622,\n            \"You ought to have had it a week ago, but there has been a delay from my brother\\u2019s not being in town by several days so soon as I expected;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104667,\n            \"I hope you will like the chain itself, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104688,\n            \"but, at any rate, I know you will be kind to my intentions, and consider it, as it really is, a token of the love of one of your oldest friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104782,\n            \"\\u201cI cannot attempt to thank you,\\u201dshe continued, in a very agitated manner;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104818,\n            \"Your goodness in thinking of me in such a way is beyond \\u2014\\u201d\\u201cIf that is all you have to say, Fanny\\u201dsmiling and turning away again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104859,\n            \"I want to consult you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104865,\n            \"\\u201d Almost unconsciously she had now undone the parcel he had just put into her hand, and seeing before her, in all the niceness of jewellers\\u2019 packing, a plain gold chain, perfectly simple and neat, she could not help bursting forth again, \\u201cOh, this is beautiful indeed!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105003,\n            \"I am most happy that you like the chain, and that it should be here in time for to-morrow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105093,\n            \"but Edmund, after waiting a moment, obliged her to bring down her mind from its heavenly flight by saying, \\u201cBut what is it that you want to consult me about?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105128,\n            \"\\u201d It was about the necklace, which she was now most earnestly longing to return, and hoped to obtain his approbation of her doing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105173,\n            \"for Edmund was so struck with the circumstance, so delighted with what Miss Crawford had done, so gratified by such a coincidence of conduct between them, that Fanny could not but admit the superior power of one pleasure over his own mind, though it might have its drawback.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105226,\n            \"It was some time before she could get his attention to her plan, or any answer to her demand of his opinion: he was in a reverie of fond reflection, uttering only now and then a few half-sentences of praise;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105272,\n            \"but when he did awake and understand, he was very decided in opposing what she wished.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105389,\n            \"but being her brother\\u2019s present, is not it fair to suppose that she would rather not part with it, when it is not wanted?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105418,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cShe must not suppose it not wanted, not acceptable, at least: and its having been originally her brother\\u2019s gift makes no difference;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105556,\n            \"I am sure you will, upon consideration, make that sacrifice rather than give pain to one who has been so studious of your comfort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105583,\n            \"Miss Crawford\\u2019s attentions to you have been \\u2014 not more than you were justly entitled to \\u2014 I am the last person to think that _ could _ _ be _, but they have been invariable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105623,\n            \"and to be returning them with what must have something the _ air _ of ingratitude, though I know it could never have the _ meaning _, is not in your nature, I am sure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105815,\n            \"She was one of his two dearest \\u2014 that must support her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105835,\n            \"She had never heard him speak so openly before, and though it told her no more than what she had long perceived, it was a stab, for it told of his own convictions and views.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105898,\n            \"and she was obliged to repeat again and again, that she was one of his two dearest, before the words gave her any sensation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105925,\n            \"Could she believe Miss Crawford to deserve him, it would be \\u2014 oh, how different would it be \\u2014 how far more tolerable!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105951,\n            \"But he was deceived in her: he gave her merits which she had not;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105967,\n            \"her faults were what they had ever been, but he saw them no longer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106019,\n            \"It was her intention, as she felt it to be her duty, to try to overcome all that was excessive, all that bordered on selfishness, in her affection for Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106084,\n            \"To think of him as Miss Crawford might be justified in thinking, would in her be insanity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106148,\n            \"She would endeavour to be rational, and to deserve the right of judging of Miss Crawford\\u2019s character, and the privilege of true solicitude for him by a sound intellect and an honest heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106202,\n            \"but having also many of the feelings of youth and nature, let her not be much wondered at, if, after making all these good resolutions on the side of self-government, she seized the scrap of paper on which Edmund had begun writing to her, as a treasure beyond all her hopes, and reading with the tenderest emotion these words, \\u201cMy very dear Fanny, you must do me the favour to accept\\u201dlocked it up with the chain, as the dearest part of the gift.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106300,\n            \"It was the only thing approaching to a letter which she had ever received from him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106403,\n            \"Never were such characters cut by any other human being as Edmund\\u2019s commonest handwriting gave!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106436,\n            \"and there was a felicity in the flow of the first four words, in the arrangement of \\u201cMy very dear Fanny,\\u201dwhich she could have looked at for ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106529,\n            \"and opened with more kindness to Fanny than such self-willed, unmanageable days often volunteer, for soon after breakfast a very friendly note was brought from Mr. Crawford to William, stating that as he found himself obliged to go to London on the morrow for a few days, he could not help trying to procure a companion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106625,\n            \"Mr. Crawford meant to be in town by his uncle\\u2019s accustomary late dinner-hour, and William was invited to dine with him at the Admiral\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106771,\n            \"and though this offer of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s would rob her of many hours of his company, she was too happy in having William spared from the fatigue of such a journey, to think of anything else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106835,\n            \"The Admiral, he believed, had interest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107056,\n            \"To dance without much observation or any extraordinary fatigue, to have strength and partners for about half the evening, to dance a little with Edmund, and not a great deal with Mr. Crawford, to see William enjoy himself, and be able to keep away from her aunt Norris, was the height of her ambition, and seemed to comprehend her greatest possibility of happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107191,\n            \"Edmund, she had too much reason to suppose, was at the Parsonage;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107308,\n            \"it had been about the same hour that she had returned from the Parsonage, and found Edmund in the East room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107331,\n            \"\\u201cSuppose I were to find him there again to-day!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107370,\n            \"Starting and looking up, she saw, across the lobby she had just reached, Edmund himself, standing at the head of a different staircase.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107398,\n            \"He came towards her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107468,\n            \"and though he looked at her with his usual kindness, she believed he had soon ceased to think of her countenance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107535,\n            \"\\u201cYou may guess my errand there, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107545,\n            \"\\u201d And he looked so conscious, that Fanny could think but of one errand, which turned her too sick for speech.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107569,\n            \"\\u201cI wished to engage Miss Crawford for the two first dances,\\u201dwas the explanation that followed, and brought Fanny to life again, enabling her, as she found she was expected to speak, to utter something like an inquiry as to the result.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107742,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny struggled for speech, and said, \\u201cI am very sorry that anything has occurred to distress you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107863,\n            \"and could tell me, perhaps better than I could tell you, how and why I am vexed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107883,\n            \"Let me talk to you a little.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107917,\n            \"I know her disposition to be as sweet and faultless as your own, but the influence of her former companions makes her seem \\u2014 gives to her conversation, to her professed opinions, sometimes a tinge of wrong.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108027,\n            \"for sometimes, Fanny, I own to you, it does appear more than manner: it appears as if the mind itself was tainted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108054,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny imagined this to be an appeal to her judgment, and therefore, after a moment\\u2019s consideration, said, \\u201cIf you only want me as a listener, cousin, I will be as useful as I can;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108171,\n            \"and few, I imagine, do ask it, but when they want to be influenced against their conscience.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108192,\n            \"I only want to talk to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108210,\n            \"but take care _ how _ you talk to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108221,\n            \"Do not tell me anything now, which hereafter you may be sorry for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108256,\n            \"\\u201d cried Edmund, pressing her hand to his lips with almost as much warmth as if it had been Miss Crawford\\u2019s, \\u201cyou are all considerate thought!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108326,\n            \"and even if it should, there will be nothing to be remembered by either you or me that we need be afraid of, for I can never be ashamed of my own scruples;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108391,\n            \"You are the only being upon earth to whom I should say what I have said;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108408,\n            \"but you have always known my opinion of her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108418,\n            \"you can bear me witness, Fanny, that I have never been blinded.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108445,\n            \"You need not fear me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108462,\n            \"but I must be a blockhead indeed, if, whatever befell me, I could think of your kindness and sympathy without the sincerest gratitude.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108501,\n            \"He had said enough to give Fanny some happier feelings than she had lately known, and with a brighter look, she answered, \\u201cYes, cousin, I am convinced that _ you _ would be incapable of anything else, though perhaps some might not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108551,\n            \"I cannot be afraid of hearing anything you wish to say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108568,\n            \"Tell me whatever you like.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108643,\n            \"But as it was, they parted with looks on his side of grateful affection, and with some very precious sensations on hers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108677,\n            \"Since the first joy from Mr. Crawford\\u2019s note to William had worn away, she had been in a state absolutely the reverse;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108721,\n            \"William\\u2019s good fortune returned again upon her mind, and seemed of greater value than at first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108829,\n            \"She had, to oblige Edmund, resolved to wear it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108858,\n            \"and having, with delightful feelings, joined the chain and the cross \\u2014 those memorials of the two most beloved of her heart, those dearest tokens so formed for each other by everything real and imaginary \\u2014 and put them round her neck, and seen and felt how full of William and Edmund they were, she was able, without an effort, to resolve on wearing Miss Crawford\\u2019s necklace too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110364,\n            \"He was not near, he was attending a party of ladies out of the room;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111885,\n            \"and she was happy in having the two dances with Edmund still to look forward to, during the greatest part of the evening, her hand being so eagerly sought after that her indefinite engagement with _ him _ was in continual perspective.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114184,\n            \"As to Edmund, we must learn to do without him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114196,\n            \"This will be the last winter of his belonging to us, as he has done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114823,\n            \"He could not have devised anything more likely to raise his consequence than this week\\u2019s absence, occurring as it did at the very time of her brother\\u2019s going away, of William Price\\u2019s going too, and completing the sort of general break-up of a party which had been so animated.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114918,\n            \"Angry as she was with Edmund for adhering to his own notions, and acting on them in defiance of her (and she had been so angry that they had hardly parted friends at the ball), she could not help thinking of him continually when absent, dwelling on his merit and affection, and longing again for the almost daily meetings they lately had.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115126,\n            \"and when, through the slight communication with the other family which Sunday produced, she learned that he had actually written home to defer his return, having promised to remain some days longer with his friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115229,\n            \"he might find them attractive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115396,\n            \"But at last Lady Bertram left the room, and then almost immediately Miss Crawford thus began, with a voice as well regulated as she could \\u2014 \\u201cAnd how do _ you _ like your cousin Edmund\\u2019s staying away so long?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115517,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHe did not, the only time he went to see Mr. Owen before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115547,\n            \"He is a very \\u2014 a very pleasing young man himself, and I cannot help being rather concerned at not seeing him again before I go to London, as will now undoubtedly be the case.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118016,\n            \"Was there one of the family, excepting Edmund, who had not in some way or other continually exercised her patience and forbearance?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119551,\n            \"True, I believe he is, generally speaking, kind to her, and so is Sir Thomas in his way;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119592,\n            \"What can Sir Thomas and Edmund together do, what _ do _ they do for her happiness, comfort, honour, and dignity in the world, to what I _ shall _ do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120301,\n            \"But though my uncle entered into my wishes with all the warmth I could desire, and exerted himself immediately, there were difficulties from the absence of one friend, and the engagements of another, which at last I could no longer bear to stay the end of, and knowing in what good hands I left the cause, I came away on Monday, trusting that many posts would not pass before I should be followed by such very letters as these.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120388,\n            \"My uncle, who is the very best man in the world, has exerted himself, as I knew he would, after seeing your brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120422,\n            \"I would not allow myself yesterday to say how delighted, or to repeat half that the Admiral said in his praise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126770,\n            \"_ He _, indeed, I have lately thought, has seen the woman he could love, which, I am convinced, my eldest son has not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133518,\n            \"\\u201cI will tell you what, Fanny,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cI am sure he fell in love with you at the ball;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133672,\n            \"The first that occurred was not least in interest: the appearance of Henry Crawford and his sister walking together through the village as he rode into it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133701,\n            \"He had concluded \\u2014 he had meant them to be far distant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133714,\n            \"His absence had been extended beyond a fortnight purposely to avoid Miss Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133728,\n            \"He was returning to Mansfield with spirits ready to feed on melancholy remembrances, and tender associations, when her own fair self was before him, leaning on her brother\\u2019s arm, and he found himself receiving a welcome, unquestionably friendly, from the woman whom, two moments before, he had been thinking of as seventy miles off, and as farther, much farther, from him in inclination than any distance could express.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133810,\n            \"Her reception of him was of a sort which he could not have hoped for, had he expected to see her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133952,\n            \"After dinner, when he and his father were alone, he had Fanny\\u2019s history;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134025,\n            \"and when tea at last brought them away, and she was to be seen by Edmund again, she felt dreadfully guilty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134049,\n            \"He came to her, sat down by her, took her hand, and pressed it kindly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134101,\n            \"He was not intending, however, by such action, to be conveying to her that unqualified approbation and encouragement which her hopes drew from it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134129,\n            \"It was designed only to express his participation in all that interested her, and to tell her that he had been hearing what quickened every feeling of affection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134159,\n            \"He was, in fact, entirely on his father\\u2019s side of the question.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134176,\n            \"His surprise was not so great as his father\\u2019s at her refusing Crawford, because, so far from supposing her to consider him with anything like a preference, he had always believed it to be rather the reverse, and could imagine her to be taken perfectly unprepared, but Sir Thomas could not regard the connexion as more desirable than he did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134362,\n            \"With such powers as his, however, and such a disposition as hers, Edmund trusted that everything would work out a happy conclusion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134420,\n            \"Crawford called the next day, and on the score of Edmund\\u2019s return, Sir Thomas felt himself more than licensed to ask him to stay dinner;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134457,\n            \"He staid of course, and Edmund had then ample opportunity for observing how he sped with Fanny, and what degree of immediate encouragement for him might be extracted from her manners;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134714,\n            \"\\u201cFanny has been reading to me, and only put the book down upon hearing you coming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134795,\n            \"\\u2014 when we heard your footsteps.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134962,\n            \"To _ good _ reading, however, she had been long used: her uncle read well, her cousins all, Edmund very well, but in Mr. Crawford\\u2019s reading there was a variety of excellence beyond what she had ever met with.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135154,\n            \"Edmund watched the progress of her attention, and was amused and gratified by seeing how she gradually slackened in the needlework, which at the beginning seemed to occupy her totally: how it fell from her hand while she sat motionless over it, and at last, how the eyes which had appeared so studiously to avoid him throughout the day were turned and fixed on Crawford \\u2014 fixed on him for minutes, fixed on him, in short, till the attraction drew Crawford\\u2019s upon her, and the book was closed, and the charm was broken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135277,\n            \"but it had been enough to give Edmund encouragement for his friend, and as he cordially thanked him, he hoped to be expressing Fanny\\u2019s secret feelings too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135468,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo doubt one is familiar with Shakespeare in a degree,\\u201dsaid Edmund, \\u201cfrom one\\u2019s earliest years.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136074,\n            \"\\u201cEven in my profession,\\u201dsaid Edmund, with a smile, \\u201chow little the art of reading has been studied!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136243,\n            \"\\u201d Edmund had already gone through the service once since his ordination;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136277,\n            \"questions, which being made, though with the vivacity of friendly interest and quick taste, without any touch of that spirit of banter or air of levity which Edmund knew to be most offensive to Fanny, he had true pleasure in satisfying;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136323,\n            \"and when Crawford proceeded to ask his opinion and give his own as to the properest manner in which particular passages in the service should be delivered, shewing it to be a subject on which he had thought before, and thought with judgment, Edmund was still more and more pleased.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137025,\n            \"and as Edmund perceived, by his drawing in a chair, and sitting down close by her, that it was to be a very thorough attack, that looks and undertones were to be well tried, he sank as quietly as possible into a corner, turned his back, and took up a newspaper, very sincerely wishing that dear little Fanny might be persuaded into explaining away that shake of the head to the satisfaction of her ardent lover;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137160,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny, meanwhile, vexed with herself for not having been as motionless as she was speechless, and grieved to the heart to see Edmund\\u2019s arrangements, was trying by everything in the power of her modest, gentle nature, to repulse Mr. Crawford, and avoid both his looks and inquiries;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138300,\n            \"But though the conference had seemed full long to him, and though on looking at Fanny he saw rather a flush of vexation, he inclined to hope that so much could not have been said and listened to without some profit to the speaker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138347,\n            \"CHAPTER XXXV Edmund had determined that it belonged entirely to Fanny to chuse whether her situation with regard to Crawford should be mentioned between them or not;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138375,\n            \"and that if she did not lead the way, it should never be touched on by him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138394,\n            \"but after a day or two of mutual reserve, he was induced by his father to change his mind, and try what his influence might do for his friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138444,\n            \"and Sir Thomas thought it might be as well to make one more effort for the young man before he left Mansfield, that all his professions and vows of unshaken attachment might have as much hope to sustain them as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138507,\n            \"He wished him to be a model of constancy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138556,\n            \"She had been used to consult him in every difficulty, and he loved her too well to bear to be denied her confidence now;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138582,\n            \"he hoped to be of service to her, he thought he must be of service to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138642,\n            \"a state which he must break through, and which he could easily learn to think she was wanting him to break through.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138666,\n            \"\\u201cI will speak to her, sir: I will take the first opportunity of speaking to her alone,\\u201dwas the result of such thoughts as these;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138697,\n            \"and upon Sir Thomas\\u2019 s information of her being at that very time walking alone in the shrubbery, he instantly joined her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138722,\n            \"\\u201cI am come to walk with you, Fanny,\\u201dsaid he.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138741,\n            \"\\u201d Drawing her arm within his.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138810,\n            \"You must talk to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138816,\n            \"I know you have something on your mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138825,\n            \"I know what you are thinking of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138833,\n            \"You cannot suppose me uninformed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138839,\n            \"Am I to hear of it from everybody but Fanny herself?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138851,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny, at once agitated and dejected, replied, \\u201cIf you hear of it from everybody, cousin, there can be nothing for me to tell.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138896,\n            \"No one but you can tell me them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138905,\n            \"I do not mean to press you, however.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138915,\n            \"If it is not what you wish yourself, I have done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138976,\n            \"I dare say that, on a comparison of our opinions, they would be found as much alike as they have been used to be: to the point \\u2014 I consider Crawford\\u2019s proposals as most advantageous and desirable, if you could return his affection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139026,\n            \"I consider it as most natural that all your family should wish you could return it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139075,\n            \"But I thought you blamed me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139082,\n            \"I thought you were against me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139112,\n            \"But how could you possibly suppose me against you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139122,\n            \"How could you imagine me an advocate for marriage without love?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139134,\n            \"Were I even careless in general on such matters, how could you imagine me so where your happiness was at stake?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139175,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAs far as you have gone, Fanny, I think you perfectly right.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139192,\n            \"I may be sorry, I may be surprised \\u2014 though hardly _ that _, for you had not had time to attach yourself \\u2014 but I think you perfectly right.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139372,\n            \"and then you will be the perfect model of a woman which I have always believed you born for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139409,\n            \"\\u201d And she spoke with a warmth which quite astonished Edmund, and which she blushed at the recollection of herself, when she saw his look, and heard him reply, \\u201cNever!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139514,\n            \"I am aware, more aware than Crawford can be, that the man who means to make you love him (you having due notice of his intentions) must have very uphill work, for there are all your early attachments and habits in battle array;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139613,\n            \"I know that the apprehension of being forced to quit Mansfield will for a time be arming you against him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139634,\n            \"I wish he had not been obliged to tell you what he was trying for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139650,\n            \"I wish he had known you as well as I do, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139664,\n            \"Between us, I think we should have won you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139695,\n            \"I must hope, however, that time, proving him (as I firmly believe it will) to deserve you by his steady affection, will give him his reward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139728,\n            \"I cannot suppose that you have not the _ wish _ to love him \\u2014 the natural wish of gratitude.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139918,\n            \"You forget yourself: there is a decided difference in your tempers, I allow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140288,\n            \"I must say, cousin, that I cannot approve his character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140395,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy dear Fanny,\\u201dreplied Edmund, scarcely hearing her to the end, \\u201clet us not, any of us, be judged by what we appeared at that period of general folly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140489,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAs a bystander,\\u201dsaid Fanny, \\u201cperhaps I saw more than you did;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140598,\n            \"I have heard before from some one of his being in love with Julia;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140622,\n            \"And, Fanny, though I hope I do justice to my sisters\\u2019 good qualities, I think it very possible that they might, one or both, be more desirous of being admired by Crawford, and might shew that desire rather more unguardedly than was perfectly prudent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140674,\n            \"I can remember that they were evidently fond of his society;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141201,\n            \"but yet I was afraid of her not estimating your worth to her brother quite as it deserved, and of her regretting that he had not rather fixed on some woman of distinction or fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141277,\n            \"She desires the connexion as warmly as your uncle or myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141376,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, when I reached the house I found the two sisters together by themselves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141551,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy dearest Fanny,\\u201dcried Edmund, pressing her arm closer to him, \\u201cdo not let the idea of her anger distress you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141604,\n            \"I wish you could have overheard her tribute of praise;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141615,\n            \"I wish you could have seen her countenance, when she said that you _ should _ be Henry\\u2019s wife.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141638,\n            \"And I observed that she always spoke of you as \\u2018 Fanny,\\u2019which she was never used to do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141735,\n            \"I said what I could for you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142160,\n            \"I had attributed them to you before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142168,\n            \"I thought I could understand you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142175,\n            \"You have now given exactly the explanation which I ventured to make for you to your friend and Mrs. Grant, and they were both better satisfied, though your warm-hearted friend was still run away with a little by the enthusiasm of her fondness for Henry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142226,\n            \"I told them that you were of all human creatures the one over whom habit had most power and novelty least;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142485,\n            \"On this principle, he soon afterwards observed \\u2014 \\u201cThey go on Monday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142594,\n            \"Had I received any letter from Mansfield, to tell me how you were all going on, I believe I should certainly have staid;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142677,\n            \"I doubt their finding me so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142775,\n            \"You and Miss Crawford have made me too nice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142834,\n            \"CHAPTER XXXVI Edmund now believed himself perfectly acquainted with all that Fanny could tell, or could leave to be conjectured of her sentiments, and he was satisfied.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142864,\n            \"It had been, as he before presumed, too hasty a measure on Crawford\\u2019s side, and time must be given to make the idea first familiar, and then agreeable to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142990,\n            \"Edmund\\u2019s account of Fanny\\u2019s disposition he could believe to be just;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143103,\n            \"The promised visit from \\u201cher friend,\\u201das Edmund called Miss Crawford, was a formidable threat to Fanny, and she lived in continual terror of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147190,\n            \"and therefore applied to Edmund to tell him how she stood affected on the present occasion, and whether she were more or less happy than she had been.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147220,\n            \"Edmund did not discern any symptoms of regret, and thought his father a little unreasonable in supposing the first three or four days could produce any.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147248,\n            \"What chiefly surprised Edmund was, that Crawford\\u2019s sister, the friend and companion who had been so much to her, should not be more visibly regretted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147329,\n            \"If she could have believed Mary\\u2019s future fate as unconnected with Mansfield as she was determined the brother\\u2019s should be, if she could have hoped her return thither to be as distant as she was much inclined to think his, she would have been light of heart indeed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147384,\n            \"but the more she recollected and observed, the more deeply was she convinced that everything was now in a fairer train for Miss Crawford\\u2019s marrying Edmund than it had ever been before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147420,\n            \"On his side the inclination was stronger, on hers less equivocal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147433,\n            \"His objections, the scruples of his integrity, seemed all done away, nobody could tell how;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147480,\n            \"His good and her bad feelings yielded to love, and such love must unite them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147546,\n            \"Her acceptance must be as certain as his offer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147635,\n            \"She might love, but she did not deserve Edmund by any other sentiment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147663,\n            \"and she may be forgiven by older sages for looking on the chance of Miss Crawford\\u2019s future improvement as nearly desperate, for thinking that if Edmund\\u2019s influence in this season of love had already done so little in clearing her judgment, and regulating her notions, his worth would be finally wasted on her even in years of matrimony.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147729,\n            \"Experience might have hoped more for any young people so circumstanced, and impartiality would not have denied to Miss Crawford\\u2019s nature that participation of the general nature of women which would lead her to adopt the opinions of the man she loved and respected as her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148064,\n            \"So reasoned Edmund, till his father made him the confidant of a scheme which placed Fanny\\u2019s chance of seeing the second lieutenant of H.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148622,\n            \"Afterwards, when familiarised with the visions of enjoyment so suddenly opened, she could speak more largely to William and Edmund of what she felt;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148803,\n            \"Edmund, too \\u2014 to be two months from _ him _ (and perhaps she might be allowed to make her absence three) must do her good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148833,\n            \"At a distance, unassailed by his looks or his kindness, and safe from the perpetual irritation of knowing his heart, and striving to avoid his confidence, she should be able to reason herself into a properer state;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148875,\n            \"she should be able to think of him as in London, and arranging everything there, without wretchedness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149013,\n            \"and now by dint of long talking on the subject, explaining and dwelling on the duty of Fanny\\u2019s sometimes seeing her family, he did induce his wife to let her go;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149049,\n            \"obtaining it rather from submission, however, than conviction, for Lady Bertram was convinced of very little more than that Sir Thomas thought Fanny ought to go, and therefore that she must.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149085,\n            \"In the calmness of her own dressing-room, in the impartial flow of her own meditations, unbiassed by his bewildering statements, she could not acknowledge any necessity for Fanny\\u2019s ever going near a father and mother who had done without her so long, while she was so useful to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149191,\n            \"He called it a sacrifice, and demanded it of her goodness and self-command as such.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149741,\n            \"and for part of one of those days the young travellers were in a good deal of alarm on the subject of their journey, for when the mode of it came to be talked of, and Mrs. Norris found that all her anxiety to save her brother-in-law\\u2019s money was vain, and that in spite of her wishes and hints for a less expensive conveyance of Fanny, they were to travel post;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149824,\n            \"when she saw Sir Thomas actually give William notes for the purpose, she was struck with the idea of there being room for a third in the carriage, and suddenly seized with a strong inclination to go with them, to go and see her poor dear sister Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150063,\n            \"that she was a great deal too necessary to Sir Thomas and Lady Bertram for her to be able to answer it to herself to leave them even for a week, and therefore must certainly sacrifice every other pleasure to that of being useful to them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150223,\n            \"but he could not leave his father and mother just when everybody else of most importance to their comfort was leaving them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151100,\n            \"Miss Crawford\\u2019s style of writing, lively and affectionate, was itself an evil, independent of what she was thus forced into reading from the brother\\u2019s pen, for Edmund would never rest till she had read the chief of the letter to him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151268,\n            \"When no longer under the same roof with Edmund, she trusted that Miss Crawford would have no motive for writing strong enough to overcome the trouble, and that at Portsmouth their correspondence would dwindle into nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151342,\n            \"They entered Oxford, but she could take only a hasty glimpse of Edmund\\u2019s college as they passed along, and made no stop anywhere till they reached Newbury, where a comfortable meal, uniting dinner and supper, wound up the enjoyments and fatigues of the day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160868,\n            \"There were three different conclusions to be drawn from his silence, between which her mind was in fluctuation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160899,\n            \"Either his going had been again delayed, or he had yet procured no opportunity of seeing Miss Crawford alone, or he was too happy for letter-writing!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165059,\n            \"and considering he was not Edmund, Fanny could not but allow that he was sufficiently open to the charms of nature, and very well able to express his admiration.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167652,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI had almost forgot (it was Edmund\\u2019s fault: he gets into my head more than does me good) one very material thing I had to say from Henry and myself \\u2014 I mean about our taking you back into Northamptonshire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167821,\n            \"Only keep your cousin Edmund from me at such a time: I should not like to be tempted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170975,\n            \"She was almost vexed into displeasure and anger against Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171031,\n            \"He will marry her, and be poor and miserable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171042,\n            \"God grant that her influence do not make him cease to be respectable!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171212,\n            \"\\u2019 Edmund, you do not know me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171290,\n            \"His warm regard, his kind expressions, his confidential treatment, touched her strongly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171306,\n            \"He was only too good to everybody.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171637,\n            \"Within a few days from the receipt of Edmund\\u2019s letter, Fanny had one from her aunt, beginning thus \\u2014 \\u201cMy Dear Fanny, \\u2014 I take up my pen to communicate some very alarming intelligence, which I make no doubt will give you much concern \\u201d.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171938,\n            \"and Edmund kindly proposes attending his brother immediately, but I am happy to add that Sir Thomas will not leave me on this distressing occasion, as it would be too trying for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171974,\n            \"We shall greatly miss Edmund in our small circle, but I trust and hope he will find the poor invalid in a less alarming state than might be apprehended, and that he will be able to bring him to Mansfield shortly, which Sir Thomas proposes should be done, and thinks best on every account, and I flatter myself the poor sufferer will soon be able to bear the removal without material inconvenience or injury.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172145,\n            \"She could just find selfishness enough to wonder whether Edmund _ had _ written to Miss Crawford before this summons came, but no sentiment dwelt long with her that was not purely affectionate and disinterestedly anxious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172196,\n            \"they were receiving frequent accounts from Edmund, and these accounts were as regularly transmitted to Fanny, in the same diffuse style, and the same medley of trusts, hopes, and fears, all following and producing each other at haphazard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172948,\n            \"Lady Bertram could think nothing less, and Fanny shared her aunt\\u2019s security, till she received a few lines from Edmund, written purposely to give her a clearer idea of his brother\\u2019s situation, and acquaint her with the apprehensions which he and his father had imbibed from the physician with respect to some strong hectic symptoms, which seemed to seize the frame on the departure of the fever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173318,\n            \"but Miss Crawford gave her the idea of being the child of good luck, and to her selfishness and vanity it would be good luck to have Edmund the only son.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173371,\n            \"\\u201cOn the subject of my last, I had actually begun a letter when called away by Tom\\u2019s illness, but I have now changed my mind, and fear to trust the influence of friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173441,\n            \"A line occasionally added by Edmund to his mother\\u2019s letter was enough for Fanny\\u2019s information.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175459,\n            \"Do not you think Edmund would have been in town again long ago, but for this illness?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175540,\n            \"Now do not make yourself uneasy with any queer fancies because he has been spending a few days at Richmond.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175567,\n            \"Be assured he cares for nobody but you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175576,\n            \"At this very moment he is wild to see you, and occupied only in contriving the means for doing so, and for making his pleasure conduce to yours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175607,\n            \"In proof, he repeats, and more eagerly, what he said at Portsmouth about our conveying you home, and I join him in it with all my soul.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175914,\n            \"To have him still the acquaintance, the flirt perhaps, of Mrs. Rushworth!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176164,\n            \"Edmund would be forgiven for being a clergyman, it seemed, under certain conditions of wealth;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178281,\n            \"Miss Crawford, herself, Edmund;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178380,\n            \"Sir Thomas\\u2019 s parental solicitude and high sense of honour and decorum, Edmund\\u2019s upright principles, unsuspicious temper, and genuine strength of feeling, made her think it scarcely possible for them to support life and reason under such disgrace;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178721,\n            \"and I write, by his desire, to propose your returning home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178749,\n            \"I shall be at Portsmouth the morning after you receive this, and hope to find you ready to set off for Mansfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178800,\n            \"I am sure you will feel such an instance of his kindness at such a moment!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178817,\n            \"Do justice to his meaning, however I may confuse it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178850,\n            \"You will see me early by the mail.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179462,\n            \"The girls heard his entrance from above, and Fanny went down.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179475,\n            \"The idea of immediately seeing him, with the knowledge of what he must be suffering, brought back all her own first feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179500,\n            \"He so near her, and in misery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179520,\n            \"He was alone, and met her instantly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179529,\n            \"and she found herself pressed to his heart with only these words, just articulate, \\u201cMy Fanny, my only sister;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179702,\n            \"He had already ate, and declined staying for their meal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179714,\n            \"He would walk round the ramparts, and join them with the carriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179777,\n            \"and he entered the house again at the same moment, just in time to spend a few minutes with the family, and be a witness \\u2014 but that he saw nothing \\u2014 of the tranquil manner in which the daughters were parted with, and just in time to prevent their sitting down to the breakfast-table, which, by dint of much unusual activity, was quite and completely ready as the carriage drove from the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179860,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s last meal in her father\\u2019s house was in character with her first: she was dismissed from it as hospitably as she had been welcomed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179958,\n            \"Had he been alone with her, his heart must have opened in spite of every resolution;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180001,\n            \"Fanny watched him with never-failing solicitude, and sometimes catching his eye, revived an affectionate smile, which comforted her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180025,\n            \"but the first day\\u2019s journey passed without her hearing a word from him on the subjects that were weighing him down.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180096,\n            \"and Edmund, particularly struck by the alteration in Fanny\\u2019s looks, and from his ignorance of the daily evils of her father\\u2019s house, attributing an undue share of the change, attributing _ all _ to the recent event, took her hand, and said in a low, but very expressive tone, \\u201cNo wonder \\u2014 you must feel it \\u2014 you must suffer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180182,\n            \"But _ yours _ \\u2014 your regard was new compared with \\u2014 \\u2014 Fanny, think of _ me _!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180482,\n            \"She looked at him, but he was leaning back, sunk in a deeper gloom than ever, and with eyes closed, as if the view of cheerfulness oppressed him, and the lovely scenes of home must be shut out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180726,\n            \"The being left with her sister and nephew, and all the house under her care, had been an advantage entirely thrown away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182528,\n            \"She was mistaken, however, in supposing that Edmund gave his father no present pain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182624,\n            \"He was aware of what Edmund must be suffering on his own behalf, in addition to all the rest, when they were in town: he had seen or conjectured his feelings;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182659,\n            \"and, having reason to think that one interview with Miss Crawford had taken place, from which Edmund derived only increased distress, had been as anxious on that account as on others to get him out of town, and had engaged him in taking Fanny home to her aunt, with a view to his relief and benefit, no less than theirs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182985,\n            \"They reached Mansfield on Thursday, and it was not till Sunday evening that Edmund began to talk to her on the subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183692,\n            \"\\u201cI will tell you everything, and then have done for ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183934,\n            \"\\u2019 My dearest Fanny, I am giving you, I hope, more pleasure than pain by this retrospect of what might have been \\u2014 but what never can be now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183967,\n            \"You do not wish me to be silent?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183976,\n            \"If you do, give me but a look, a word, and I have done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184243,\n            \"I do not consider her as meaning to wound my feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184321,\n            \"She would not voluntarily give unnecessary pain to any one, and though I may deceive myself, I cannot but think that for me, for my feelings, she would \\u2014.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184394,\n            \"Gladly would I submit to all the increased pain of losing her, rather than have to think of her as I do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184418,\n            \"I told her so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184432,\n            \"when I left her I told her so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184481,\n            \"She spoke of it, Fanny, with a steadier voice than I can.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184509,\n            \"\\u201c\\u2018 We must persuade Henry to marry her,\\u2019said she;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184555,\n            \"I do not think that even _ he _ could now hope to succeed with one of her stamp, and therefore I hope we may find no insuperable difficulty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184748,\n            \"I know how he is likely to be influenced.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185731,\n            \"Till that happened, they continued to talk of Miss Crawford alone, and how she had attached him, and how delightful nature had made her, and how excellent she would have been, had she fallen into good hands earlier.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185775,\n            \"Fanny, now at liberty to speak openly, felt more than justified in adding to his knowledge of her real character, by some hint of what share his brother\\u2019s state of health might be supposed to have in her wish for a complete reconciliation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185870,\n            \"He submitted to believe that Tom\\u2019s illness had influenced her, only reserving for himself this consoling thought, that considering the many counteractions of opposing habits, she had certainly been _ more _ attached to him than could have been expected, and for his sake been more near doing right.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185932,\n            \"and they were also quite agreed in their opinion of the lasting effect, the indelible impression, which such a disappointment must make on his mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185987,\n            \"and as to his ever meeting with any other woman who could \\u2014 it was too impossible to be named but with indignation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186188,\n            \"and happy as all this must make her, she would still have been happy without any of it, for Edmund was no longer the dupe of Miss Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186752,\n            \"After wandering about and sitting under trees with Fanny all the summer evenings, he had so well talked his mind into submission as to be very tolerably cheerful again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189594,\n            \"for Mary, though perfectly resolved against ever attaching herself to a younger brother again, was long in finding among the dashing representatives, or idle heir-apparents, who were at the command of her beauty, and her \\u00a320, 000, any one who could satisfy the better taste she had acquired at Mansfield, whose character and manners could authorise a hope of the domestic happiness she had there learned to estimate, or put Edmund Bertram sufficiently out of her head.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189714,\n            \"Scarcely had he done regretting Mary Crawford, and observing to Fanny how impossible it was that he should ever meet with such another woman, before it began to strike him whether a very different kind of woman might not do just as well, or a great deal better: whether Fanny herself were not growing as dear, as important to him in all her smiles and all her ways, as Mary Crawford had ever been;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189795,\n            \"and whether it might not be a possible, a hopeful undertaking to persuade her that her warm and sisterly regard for him would be foundation enough for wedded love.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189872,\n            \"I only entreat everybody to believe that exactly at the time when it was quite natural that it should be so, and not a week earlier, Edmund did cease to care about Miss Crawford, and became as anxious to marry Fanny as Fanny herself could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189922,\n            \"With such a regard for her, indeed, as his had long been, a regard founded on the most endearing claims of innocence and helplessness, and completed by every recommendation of growing worth, what could be more natural than the change?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189968,\n            \"Loving, guiding, protecting her, as he had been doing ever since her being ten years old, her mind in so great a degree formed by his care, and her comfort depending on his kindness, an object to him of such close and peculiar interest, dearer by all his own importance with her than any one else at Mansfield, what was there now to add, but that he should learn to prefer soft light eyes to sparkling dark ones.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190056,\n            \"And being always with her, and always talking confidentially, and his feelings exactly in that favourable state which a recent disappointment gives, those soft light eyes could not be very long in obtaining the pre-eminence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190216,\n            \"She was of course only too good for him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190226,\n            \"but as nobody minds having what is too good for them, he was very steadily earnest in the pursuit of the blessing, and it was not possible that encouragement from her should be long wanting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190264,\n            \"Timid, anxious, doubting as she was, it was still impossible that such tenderness as hers should not, at times, hold out the strongest hope of success, though it remained for a later period to tell him the whole delightful and astonishing truth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190313,\n            \"His happiness in knowing himself to have been so long the beloved of such a heart, must have been great enough to warrant any strength of language in which he could clothe it to her or to himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190505,\n            \"and the joyful consent which met Edmund\\u2019s application, the high sense of having realised a great acquisition in the promise of Fanny for a daughter, formed just such a contrast with his early opinion on the subject when the poor little girl\\u2019s coming had been first agitated, as time is for ever producing between the plans and decisions of mortals, for their own instruction, and their neighbours\\u2019 entertainment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190923,\n            \"In _ her _ usefulness, in Fanny\\u2019s excellence, in William\\u2019s continued good conduct and rising fame, and in the general well-doing and success of the other members of the family, all assisting to advance each other, and doing credit to his countenance and aid, Sir Thomas saw repeated, and for ever repeated, reason to rejoice in what he had done for them all, and acknowledge the advantages of early hardship and discipline, and the consciousness of being born to struggle and endure.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 9]\": [\n        [\n            502,\n            \"but Mrs. Norris had a spirit of activity, which could not be satisfied till she had written a long and angry letter to Fanny, to point out the folly of her conduct, and threaten her with all its possible ill consequences.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            609,\n            \"Their homes were so distant, and the circles in which they moved so distinct, as almost to preclude the means of ever hearing of each other\\u2019s existence during the eleven following years, or, at least, to make it very wonderful to Sir Thomas that Mrs. Norris should ever have it in her power to tell them, as she now and then did, in an angry voice, that Fanny had got another child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3717,\n            \"Fanny Price was at this time just ten years old, and though there might not be much in her first appearance to captivate, there was, at least, nothing to disgust her relations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4684,\n            \"Fanny, whether near or from her cousins, whether in the schoolroom, the drawing-room, or the shrubbery, was equally forlorn, finding something to fear in every person and place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5665,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s feelings on the occasion were such as she believed herself incapable of expressing;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6012,\n            \"and they could not but own, when their aunt inquired into her faults, or their brother Edmund urged her claims to their kindness, that \\u201cFanny was good-natured enough.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6211,\n            \"Fanny could read, work, and write, but she had been taught nothing more;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6696,\n            \"But I must tell you another thing of Fanny, so odd and so stupid.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7070,\n            \"As for Fanny\\u2019s being stupid at learning, \\u201cshe could only say it was very unlucky, but some people _ were _ stupid, and Fanny must take more pains: she did not know what else was to be done;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7155,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny, with all her faults of ignorance and timidity, was fixed at Mansfield Park, and learning to transfer in its favour much of her attachment to her former home, grew up there not unhappily among her cousins.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7210,\n            \"and though Fanny was often mortified by their treatment of her, she thought too lowly of her own claims to feel injured by it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7510,\n            \"and Fanny, though almost totally separated from her family, was sensible of the truest satisfaction in hearing of any kindness towards them, or of anything at all promising in their situation or conduct.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7997,\n            \"CHAPTER III The first event of any importance in the family was the death of Mr. Norris, which happened when Fanny was about fifteen, and necessarily introduced alterations and novelties.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8591,\n            \"The time was now come when Sir Thomas expected his sister-in-law to claim her share in their niece, the change in Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s situation, and the improvement in Fanny\\u2019s age, seeming not merely to do away any former objection to their living together, but even to give it the most decided eligibility;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8734,\n            \"and the first time of the subject\\u2019s occurring to her again happening to be when Fanny was present, she calmly observed to her, \\u201cSo, Fanny, you are going to leave us, and live with my sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8785,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny was too much surprised to do more than repeat her aunt\\u2019s words, \\u201cGoing to leave you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8946,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI hope I am not ungrateful, aunt,\\u201dsaid Fanny modestly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9272,\n            \"I hope it does not distress you very much, Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9764,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny sighed, and said, \\u201cI cannot see things as you do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9856,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThe place, Fanny, is what you will not quit, though you quit the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10281,\n            \"Lady Bertram soon brought the matter to a certainty by carelessly observing to Mrs. Norris \\u2014 \\u201cI think, sister, we need not keep Miss Lee any longer, when Fanny goes to live with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10342,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIs she not to live with you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10384,\n            \"Fanny live with me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10415,\n            \"what could I do with Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10442,\n            \"what could I do with a girl at her time of life?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10550,\n            \"He could not say he _ wished _ me to take Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10630,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDear sister, if you consider my unhappy state, how can she be any comfort to me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10651,\n            \"Here am I, a poor desolate widow, deprived of the best of husbands, my health gone in attending and nursing him, my spirits still worse, all my peace in this world destroyed, with hardly enough to support me in the rank of a gentlewoman, and enable me to live so as not to disgrace the memory of the dear departed \\u2014 what possible comfort could I have in taking such a charge upon me as Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10735,\n            \"If I could wish it for my own sake, I would not do so unjust a thing by the poor girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11123,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, Lady Bertram,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris, moving to go, \\u201cI can only say that my sole desire is to be of use to your family: and so, if Sir Thomas should ever speak again about my taking Fanny, you will be able to say that my health and spirits put it quite out of the question;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11192,\n            \"besides that, I really should not have a bed to give her, for I must keep a spare room for a friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11267,\n            \"He could not but wonder at her refusing to do anything for a niece whom she had been so forward to adopt;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12086,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s relief, and her consciousness of it, were quite equal to her cousins \\u2019;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12234,\n            \"\\u201d and would he only have smiled upon her, and called her \\u201cmy dear Fanny,\\u201dwhile he said it, every former frown or cold address might have been forgotten.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12326,\n            \"though, I fear, he must find his sister at sixteen in some respects too much like his sister at ten.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12852,\n            \"but she enjoyed being avowedly useful as her aunt\\u2019s companion when they called away the rest of the family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12874,\n            \"and, as Miss Lee had left Mansfield, she naturally became everything to Lady Bertram during the night of a ball or a party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13200,\n            \"and Fanny either sat at home the whole day with one aunt, or walked beyond her strength at the instigation of the other: Lady Bertram holding exercise to be as unnecessary for everybody as it was unpleasant to herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13305,\n            \"and that \\u201cFanny must have a horse\\u201dwas the resolute declaration with which he opposed whatever could be urged by the supineness of his mother, or the economy of his aunt, to make it appear unimportant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13404,\n            \"She could not but consider it as absolutely unnecessary, and even improper, that Fanny should have a regular lady\\u2019s horse of her own, in the style of her cousins.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13635,\n            \"and at length determined on a method of proceeding which would obviate the risk of his father\\u2019s thinking he had done too much, and at the same time procure for Fanny the immediate means of exercise, which he could not bear she should be without.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13765,\n            \"with a very little trouble she became exactly calculated for the purpose, and Fanny was then put in almost full possession of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13914,\n            \"As the horse continued in name, as well as fact, the property of Edmund, Mrs. Norris could tolerate its being for Fanny\\u2019s use;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14309,\n            \"but as there was nothing disagreeable in his figure or address, the young lady was well pleased with her conquest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14350,\n            \"and as a marriage with Mr. Rushworth would give her the enjoyment of a larger income than her father\\u2019s, as well as ensure her the house in town, which was now a prime object, it became, by the same rule of moral obligation, her evident duty to marry Mr. Rushworth if she could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15017,\n            \"and Fanny had just reached her eighteenth year, when the society of the village received an addition in the brother and sister of Mrs. Grant, a Mr. and Miss Crawford, the children of her mother by a second marriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15221,\n            \"and it was the lady\\u2019s death which now obliged her _ protegee _, after some months\\u2019 further trial at her uncle\\u2019s house, to find another home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15378,\n            \"The arrival, therefore, of a sister whom she had always loved, and now hoped to retain with her as long as she remained single, was highly agreeable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15410,\n            \"and her chief anxiety was lest Mansfield should not satisfy the habits of a young woman who had been mostly used to London.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15739,\n            \"the eldest son of a baronet was not too good for a girl of twenty thousand pounds, with all the elegance and accomplishments which Mrs. Grant foresaw in her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16686,\n            \"Miss Bertram\\u2019s engagement made him in equity the property of Julia, of which Julia was fully aware;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18378,\n            \"and what was _ her _ opinion of the newcomers?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18389,\n            \"Few young ladies of eighteen could be less called on to speak their opinion than Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18429,\n            \"but as she still continued to think Mr. Crawford very plain, in spite of her two cousins having repeatedly proved the contrary, she never mentioned _ him _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18518,\n            \"She dined at the Parsonage, with the rest of you, which seemed like being _ out _;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18538,\n            \"and yet she says so little, that I can hardly suppose she _ is _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19885,\n            \"My mother seldom goes into company herself, and dines nowhere but with Mrs. Grant, and Fanny stays at home with _ her _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21816,\n            \"I wish we could contrive it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23144,\n            \"Now, Mr. Bertram, if you write to your brother, I entreat you to tell him that my harp is come: he heard so much of my misery about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23353,\n            \"Henry, who is in every other respect exactly what a brother should be, who loves me, consults me, confides in me, and will talk to me by the hour together, has never yet turned the page in a letter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23446,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWhen they are at a distance from all their family,\\u201dsaid Fanny, colouring for William\\u2019s sake, \\u201cthey can write long letters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23477,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMiss Price has a brother at sea,\\u201dsaid Edmund, \\u201cwhose excellence as a correspondent makes her think you too severe upon us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23524,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny would rather have had Edmund tell the story, but his determined silence obliged her to relate her brother\\u2019s situation: her voice was animated in speaking of his profession, and the foreign stations he had been on;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23597,\n            \"\\u201cDo you know anything of my cousin\\u2019s captain?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23617,\n            \"You have a large acquaintance in the navy, I conclude?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24599,\n            \"I dare say Mr. Crawford would take my two nieces and me in his barouche, and Edmund can go on horseback, you know, sister, and Fanny will stay at home with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25032,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo not you think,\\u201dsaid Fanny, after a little consideration, \\u201cthat this impropriety is a reflection itself upon Mrs. Crawford, as her niece has been entirely brought up by her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25373,\n            \"though at this period, and on this subject, there began now to be some danger of dissimilarity, for he was in a line of admiration of Miss Crawford, which might lead him where Fanny could not follow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25881,\n            \"neither could she wonder that, when the evening stroll was over, and the two families parted again, he should think it right to attend Mrs. Grant and her sister to their home, while Mr. Crawford was devoted to the ladies of the Park;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25963,\n            \"She was a little surprised that he could spend so many hours with Miss Crawford, and not see more of the sort of fault which he had already observed, and of which _ she _ was almost always reminded by a something of the same nature whenever she was in her company;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26023,\n            \"Edmund was fond of speaking to her of Miss Crawford, but he seemed to think it enough that the Admiral had since been spared;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26070,\n            \"The first actual pain which Miss Crawford occasioned her was the consequence of an inclination to learn to ride, which the former caught, soon after her being settled at Mansfield, from the example of the young ladies at the Park, and which, when Edmund\\u2019s acquaintance with her increased, led to his encouraging the wish, and the offer of his own quiet mare for the purpose of her first attempts, as the best fitted for a beginner that either stable could furnish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26249,\n            \"Miss Crawford made her first essay with great credit to herself, and no inconvenience to Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26267,\n            \"Edmund, who had taken down the mare and presided at the whole, returned with it in excellent time, before either Fanny or the steady old coachman, who always attended her when she rode without her cousins, were ready to set forward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26411,\n            \"Fanny was ready and waiting, and Mrs. Norris was beginning to scold her for not being gone, and still no horse was announced, no Edmund appeared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26679,\n            \"and to Fanny\\u2019s timid nature it was most astonishing to see how well she sat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27059,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny\\u2019s answer was extremely civil, and Edmund added his conviction that she could be in no hurry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27262,\n            \"\\u201d The old coachman, who had been waiting about with his own horse, now joining them, Fanny was lifted on hers, and they set off across another part of the park;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27574,\n            \"\\u201d When they parted at night Edmund asked Fanny whether she meant to ride the next day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27627,\n            \"\\u201cbut whenever you are next inclined to stay at home, I think Miss Crawford would be glad to have her a longer time \\u2014 for a whole morning, in short.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27707,\n            \"She would be extremely sorry to interfere with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27740,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI shall not ride to-morrow, certainly,\\u201dsaid Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27784,\n            \"\\u201d Edmund looked pleased, which must be Fanny\\u2019s comfort, and the ride to Mansfield Common took place the next morning: the party included all the young people but herself, and was much enjoyed at the time, and doubly enjoyed again in the evening discussion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28291,\n            \"\\u201d Her own gentle voice speaking from the other end of the room, which was a very long one, told them that she was on the sofa.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28447,\n            \"\\u201d Before half this was said, Fanny was returned to her seat at the table, and had taken up her work again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28520,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cFanny,\\u201dsaid Edmund, after looking at her attentively, \\u201cI am sure you have the headache.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28751,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cFanny has been cutting roses, has she?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29047,\n            \"and, unluckily, Fanny forgot to lock the door of the room and bring away the key, so she was obliged to go again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29074,\n            \"\\u201d Edmund got up and walked about the room, saying, \\u201cAnd could nobody be employed on such an errand but Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29320,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf Fanny would be more regular in her exercise, she would not be knocked up so soon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29552,\n            \"but going quietly to another table, on which the supper-tray yet remained, brought a glass of Madeira to Fanny, and obliged her to drink the greater part.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29733,\n            \"Fanny went to bed with her heart as full as on the first evening of her arrival at the Park.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30530,\n            \"I cannot do without Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31135,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere can be no objection, then, to Fanny\\u2019s going with you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31153,\n            \"there can be no doubt of your having room for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31175,\n            \"\\u201cmy dear Edmund, there is no idea of her going with us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31190,\n            \"She stays with her aunt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31208,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou can have no reason, I imagine, madam,\\u201dsaid he, addressing his mother, \\u201cfor wishing Fanny _ not _ to be of the party, but as it relates to yourself, to your own comfort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31254,\n            \"If you could do without her, you would not wish to keep her at home?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31271,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cTo be sure not, but I _ cannot _ do without her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31357,\n            \"She has not often a gratification of the kind, and I am sure, ma\\u2019am, you would be glad to give her the pleasure now?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31402,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Norris was very ready with the only objection which could remain \\u2014 their having positively assured Mrs. Rushworth that Fanny could not go, and the very strange appearance there would consequently be in taking her, which seemed to her a difficulty quite impossible to be got over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31841,\n            \"but that he should forego any enjoyment on her account gave her pain, and her own satisfaction in seeing Sotherton would be nothing without him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32261,\n            \"She was not often invited to join in the conversation of the others, nor did she desire it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32292,\n            \"and, in observing the appearance of the country, the bearings of the roads, the difference of soil, the state of the harvest, the cottages, the cattle, the children, she found entertainment that could only have been heightened by having Edmund to speak to of what she felt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32348,\n            \"That was the only point of resemblance between her and the lady who sat by her: in everything but a value for Edmund, Miss Crawford was very unlike her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33703,\n            \"On the present occasion she addressed herself chiefly to Miss Crawford and Fanny, but there was no comparison in the willingness of their attention;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33729,\n            \"for Miss Crawford, who had seen scores of great houses, and cared for none of them, had only the appearance of civilly listening, while Fanny, to whom everything was almost as interesting as it was new, attended with unaffected earnestness to all that Mrs. Rushworth could relate of the family in former times, its rise and grandeur, regal visits and loyal efforts, delighted to connect anything with history already known, or warm her imagination with scenes of the past.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33837,\n            \"and while Fanny and some of the others were attending Mrs. Rushworth, Henry Crawford was looking grave and shaking his head at the windows.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33975,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s imagination had prepared her for something grander than a mere spacious, oblong room, fitted up for the purpose of devotion: with nothing more striking or more solemn than the profusion of mahogany, and the crimson velvet cushions appearing over the ledge of the family gallery above.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34109,\n            \"\\u2019\\u201d\\u201cYou forget, Fanny, how lately all this has been built, and for how confined a purpose, compared with the old chapels of castles and monasteries.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37611,\n            \"but the next time we come to a seat, if it is not disagreeable to you, I should be glad to sit down for a little while.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37641,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy dear Fanny,\\u201dcried Edmund, immediately drawing her arm within his, \\u201chow thoughtless I have been!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37665,\n            \"I hope you are not very tired.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37708,\n            \"\\u201d She took it, however, as she spoke, and the gratification of having her do so, of feeling such a connexion for the first time, made him a little forgetful of Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38173,\n            \"\\u201cI am afraid you are very tired, Fanny,\\u201dsaid Edmund, observing her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38407,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI shall soon be rested,\\u201dsaid Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38700,\n            \"Fanny said she was rested, and would have moved too, but this was not suffered.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38718,\n            \"Edmund urged her remaining where she was with an earnestness which she could not resist, and she was left on the bench to think with pleasure of her cousin\\u2019s care, but with great regret that she was not stronger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38782,\n            \"CHAPTER X A quarter of an hour, twenty minutes, passed away, and Fanny was still thinking of Edmund, Miss Crawford, and herself, without interruption from any one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38928,\n            \"\\u201cPoor dear Fanny,\\u201dcried her cousin, \\u201chow ill you have been used by them!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40086,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny was again left to her solitude, and with no increase of pleasant feelings, for she was sorry for almost all that she had seen and heard, astonished at Miss Bertram, and angry with Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40641,\n            \"The sort of dread in which Fanny now sat of seeing Mr. Rushworth prevented her thinking so much of their continued absence, however, as she might have done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40835,\n            \"\\u201d And he sat down with a most gloomy countenance by Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41052,\n            \"\\u201d A small sigh escaped Fanny here, and she did not know how to contradict him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41196,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny thought she discerned in his standing there an indication of relenting, which encouraged her to another attempt, and she said, therefore, \\u201cIt is a pity you should not join them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41339,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s thoughts were now all engrossed by the two who had left her so long ago, and getting quite impatient, she resolved to go in search of them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41418,\n            \"They were just returned into the wilderness from the park, to which a sidegate, not fastened, had tempted them very soon after their leaving her, and they had been across a portion of the park into the very avenue which Fanny had been hoping the whole morning to reach at last, and had been sitting down under one of the trees.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41513,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s best consolation was in being assured that Edmund had wished for her very much, and that he should certainly have come back for her, had she not been tired already;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41919,\n            \"By their own accounts they had been all walking after each other, and the junction which had taken place at last seemed, to Fanny\\u2019s observation, to have been as much too late for re-establishing harmony, as it confessedly had been for determining on any alteration.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41973,\n            \"She felt, as she looked at Julia and Mr. Rushworth, that hers was not the only dissatisfied bosom amongst them: there was gloom on the face of each.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42282,\n            \"\\u201cWell, Fanny, this has been a fine day for you, upon my word,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris, as they drove through the park.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42430,\n            \"but if it is in your way, I will have it in my lap directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42447,\n            \"There, Fanny, you shall carry that parcel for me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43251,\n            \"but after tea, as Miss Crawford was standing at an open window with Edmund and Fanny looking out on a twilight scene, while the Miss Bertrams, Mr. Rushworth, and Henry Crawford were all busy with candles at the pianoforte, she suddenly revived it by turning round towards the group, and saying, \\u201cHow happy Mr. Rushworth looks!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43603,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut _ that _ I am sure it has not,\\u201dcried Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43620,\n            \"\\u201cThank you for your good word, Fanny, but it is more than I would affirm myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43753,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt is the same sort of thing,\\u201dsaid Fanny, after a short pause, \\u201cas for the son of an admiral to go into the navy, or the son of a general to be in the army, and nobody sees anything wrong in that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44458,\n            \"He has met with great kindness from the chaplain of the Antwerp,\\u201dwas a tender apostrophe of Fanny\\u2019s, very much to the purpose of her own feelings if not of the conversation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44496,\n            \"\\u201cI have been so little addicted to take my opinions from my uncle,\\u201dsaid Miss Crawford, \\u201cthat I can hardly suppose \\u2014 and since you push me so hard, I must observe, that I am not entirely without the means of seeing what clergymen are, being at this present time the guest of my own brother, Dr. Grant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44765,\n            \"Fanny, it goes against us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44781,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo,\\u201dreplied Fanny, \\u201cbut we need not give up his profession for all that;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45304,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny agreed to it, and had the pleasure of seeing him continue at the window with her, in spite of the expected glee;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45379,\n            \"Fanny spoke her feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45496,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI like to hear your enthusiasm, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45664,\n            \"\\u201cWe will stay till this is finished, Fanny,\\u201dsaid he, turning his back on the window;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45734,\n            \"Fanny sighed alone at the window till scolded away by Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s threats of catching cold.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46700,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf Miss Bertram were not engaged,\\u201dsaid Fanny cautiously, \\u201cI could sometimes almost think that he admired her more than Julia.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46728,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWhich is, perhaps, more in favour of his liking Julia best, than you, Fanny, may be aware;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46837,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny supposed she must have been mistaken, and meant to think differently in future;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47018,\n            \"It was Fanny\\u2019s first ball, though without the preparation or splendour of many a young lady\\u2019s first ball, being the thought only of the afternoon, built on the late acquisition of a violin player in the servants\\u2019 hall, and the possibility of raising five couple with the help of Mrs. Grant and a new intimate friend of Mr. Bertram\\u2019s just arrived on a visit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47096,\n            \"It had, however, been a very happy one to Fanny through four dances, and she was quite grieved to be losing even a quarter of an hour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47199,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, ma\\u2019am, indeed,\\u201dreplied the other, with a stately simper, \\u201cthere will be some satisfaction in looking on _ now _, and I think it was rather a pity they should have been obliged to part.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47395,\n            \"How she had looked before, Fanny could not recollect, for she had been dancing with Edmund herself, and had not thought about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47686,\n            \"and though feeling it would be a great honour to be asked by him, she thought it must happen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47714,\n            \"but instead of asking her to dance, drew a chair near her, and gave her an account of the present state of a sick horse, and the opinion of the groom, from whom he had just parted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47783,\n            \"When he had told of his horse, he took a newspaper from the table, and looking over it, said in a languid way, \\u201cIf you want to dance, Fanny, I will stand up with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47916,\n            \"If you look at them you may see they are so many couple of lovers \\u2014 all but Yates and Mrs. Grant \\u2014 and, between ourselves, she, poor woman, must want a lover as much as any one of them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47962,\n            \"A desperate dull life hers must be with the doctor,\\u201dmaking a sly face as he spoke towards the chair of the latter, who proving, however, to be close at his elbow, made so instantaneous a change of expression and subject necessary, as Fanny, in spite of everything, could hardly help laughing at.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48042,\n            \"I always come to you to know what I am to think of public matters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48255,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny was led off very willingly, though it was impossible for her to feel much gratitude towards her cousin, or distinguish, as he certainly did, between the selfishness of another person and his own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48551,\n            \"Mr. Bertram\\u2019s acquaintance with him had begun at Weymouth, where they had spent ten days together in the same society, and the friendship, if friendship it might be called, had been proved and perfected by Mr. Yates\\u2019 s being invited to take Mansfield in his way, whenever he could, and by his promising to come;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50208,\n            \"Tom, returning from them into the drawing-room, where Edmund was standing thoughtfully by the fire, while Lady Bertram was on the sofa at a little distance, and Fanny close beside her arranging her work, thus began as he entered \\u2014 \\u201cSuch a horribly vile billiard-table as ours is not to be met with, I believe, above ground.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50728,\n            \"for the expectation of his return must be a very anxious period to my mother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50744,\n            \"and if we can be the means of amusing that anxiety, and keeping up her spirits for the next few weeks, I shall think our time very well spent, and so, I am sure, will he.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50931,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cOh dear, no, ma\\u2019am, nobody suspected you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51363,\n            \"and as to such alterations as I was suggesting just now, such as moving a bookcase, or unlocking a door, or even as using the billiard-room for the space of a week without playing at billiards in it, you might just as well suppose he would object to our sitting more in this room, and less in the breakfast-room, than we did before he went away, or to my sister\\u2019s pianoforte being moved from one side of the room to the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51671,\n            \"Fanny, who had heard it all, and borne Edmund company in every feeling throughout the whole, now ventured to say, in her anxiety to suggest some comfort, \\u201cPerhaps they may not be able to find any play to suit them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51731,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have no hope there, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51775,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI should think my aunt Norris would be on your side.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51789,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI dare say she would, but she has no influence with either Tom or my sisters that could be of any use;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51815,\n            \"and if I cannot convince them myself, I shall let things take their course, without attempting it through her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52055,\n            \"Edmund had little to hope, but he was still urging the subject when Henry Crawford entered the room, fresh from the Parsonage, calling out, \\u201cNo want of hands in our theatre, Miss Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52924,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny looked on and listened, not unamused to observe the selfishness which, more or less disguised, seemed to govern them all, and wondering how it would end.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53629,\n            \"when Julia, meaning, like her sister, to be Agatha, began to be scrupulous on Miss Crawford\\u2019s account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53674,\n            \"Amelia and Agatha may do for Maria and me, but here is nothing for your sister, Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53696,\n            \"\\u201d Mr. Crawford desired _ that _ might not be thought of: he was very sure his sister had no wish of acting but as she might be useful, and that she would not allow herself to be considered in the present case.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55480,\n            \"Agatha and Amelia appeared to her in their different ways so totally improper for home representation \\u2014 the situation of one, and the language of the other, so unfit to be expressed by any woman of modesty, that she could hardly suppose her cousins could be aware of what they were engaging in;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56170,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI should not have thought it the sort of play to be so easily filled up, with _ us _,\\u201dreplied Edmund, turning away to the fire, where sat his mother, aunt, and Fanny, and seating himself with a look of great vexation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56840,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am convinced, madam,\\u201dsaid Edmund, preventing Fanny, \\u201cthat Sir Thomas would not like it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57932,\n            \"and I do sincerely give you joy, madam, as well as Mrs. Norris, and everybody else who is in the same predicament,\\u201dglancing half fearfully, half slyly, beyond Fanny to Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58754,\n            \"\\u201cFanny,\\u201dcried Tom Bertram, from the other table, where the conference was eagerly carrying on, and the conversation incessant, \\u201cwe want your services.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58824,\n            \"we do not want to disturb you from your seat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58835,\n            \"We do not want your _ present _ services.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58845,\n            \"We shall only want you in our play.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58854,\n            \"You must be Cottager\\u2019s wife.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58879,\n            \"\\u201cIndeed you must excuse me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58908,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed, but you must, for we cannot excuse you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58922,\n            \"It need not frighten you: it is a nothing of a part, a mere nothing, not above half a dozen speeches altogether, and it will not much signify if nobody hears a word you say;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58962,\n            \"so you may be as creep-mouse as you like, but we must have you to look at.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58983,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf you are afraid of half a dozen speeches,\\u201dcried Mr. Rushworth, \\u201cwhat would you do with such a part as mine?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59021,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt is not that I am afraid of learning by heart,\\u201dsaid Fanny, shocked to find herself at that moment the only speaker in the room, and to feel that almost every eye was upon her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59071,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, yes, you can act well enough for _ us _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59087,\n            \"Learn your part, and we will teach you all the rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59100,\n            \"You have only two scenes, and as I shall be Cottager, I\\u2019ll put you in and push you about, and you will do it very well, I\\u2019ll answer for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59215,\n            \"You must get a brown gown, and a white apron, and a mob cap, and we must make you a few wrinkles, and a little of the crowsfoot at the corner of your eyes, and you will be a very proper, little old woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59266,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou must excuse me, indeed you must excuse me,\\u201dcried Fanny, growing more and more red from excessive agitation, and looking distressfully at Edmund, who was kindly observing her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59338,\n            \"and it was not merely Tom, for the requisition was now backed by Maria, and Mr. Crawford, and Mr. Yates, with an urgency which differed from his but in being more gentle or more ceremonious, and which altogether was quite overpowering to Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59389,\n            \"and before she could breathe after it, Mrs. Norris completed the whole by thus addressing her in a whisper at once angry and audible \\u2014 \\u201cWhat a piece of work here is about nothing: I am quite ashamed of you, Fanny, to make such a difficulty of obliging your cousins in a trifle of this sort \\u2014 so kind as they are to you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59816,\n            \"and when, from taking notice of her work, and wishing _ she _ could work as well, and begging for the pattern, and supposing Fanny was now preparing for her _ appearance _, as of course she would come out when her cousin was married, Miss Crawford proceeded to inquire if she had heard lately from her brother at sea, and said that she had quite a curiosity to see him, and imagined him a very fine young man, and advised Fanny to get his picture drawn before he went to sea again \\u2014 she could not help admitting it to be very agreeable flattery, or help listening, and answering with more animation than she had intended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59945,\n            \"The consultation upon the play still went on, and Miss Crawford\\u2019s attention was first called from Fanny by Tom Bertram\\u2019s telling her, with infinite regret, that he found it absolutely impossible for him to undertake the part of Anhalt in addition to the Butler: he had been most anxiously trying to make it out to be feasible, but it would not do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60381,\n            \"\\u201cI am not very sanguine as to our play,\\u201dsaid Miss Crawford, in an undervoice to Fanny, after some consideration;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60940,\n            \"The East room, as it had been called ever since Maria Bertram was sixteen, was now considered Fanny\\u2019s, almost as decidedly as the white attic: the smallness of the one making the use of the other so evidently reasonable that the Miss Bertrams, with every superiority in their own apartments which their own sense of superiority could demand, were entirely approving it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61011,\n            \"and Mrs. Norris, having stipulated for there never being a fire in it on Fanny\\u2019s account, was tolerably resigned to her having the use of what nobody else wanted, though the terms in which she sometimes spoke of the indulgence seemed to imply that it was the best room in the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61559,\n            \"To this nest of comforts Fanny now walked down to try its influence on an agitated, doubting spirit, to see if by looking at Edmund\\u2019s profile she could catch any of his counsel, or by giving air to her geraniums she might inhale a breeze of mental strength herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61911,\n            \"\\u201cCan I speak with you, Fanny, for a few minutes?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62260,\n            \"Can you, Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62382,\n            \"Put yourself in Miss Crawford\\u2019s place, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62492,\n            \"Does it not strike you so, Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62765,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cGive me your approbation, then, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63760,\n            \"\\u201cPerhaps,\\u201dsaid Tom, \\u201cFanny may be more disposed to oblige us now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63920,\n            \"One advantage resulted from it to Fanny: at the earnest request of Miss Crawford, Mrs. Grant had, with her usual good-humour, agreed to undertake the part for which Fanny had been wanted;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64285,\n            \"and Fanny was at first in some danger of envying her the character she had accepted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64362,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s heart was not absolutely the only saddened one amongst them, as she soon began to acknowledge to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65540,\n            \"They were two solitary sufferers, or connected only by Fanny\\u2019s consciousness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65737,\n            \"but though no other great impediments arose, Fanny found, before many days were past, that it was not all uninterrupted enjoyment to the party themselves, and that she had not to witness the continuance of such unanimity and delight as had been almost too much for her at first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66076,\n            \"She knew, also, that poor Mr. Rushworth could seldom get anybody to rehearse with him: _ his _ complaint came before her as well as the rest;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66108,\n            \"and so decided to her eye was her cousin Maria\\u2019s avoidance of him, and so needlessly often the rehearsal of the first scene between her and Mr. Crawford, that she had soon all the terror of other complaints from _ him _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66156,\n            \"So far from being all satisfied and all enjoying, she found everybody requiring something they had not, and giving occasion of discontent to the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66223,\n            \"Fanny believed herself to derive as much innocent enjoyment from the play as any of them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66294,\n            \"and after the first rehearsal or two, Fanny began to be their only audience;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66324,\n            \"As far as she could judge, Mr. Crawford was considerably the best actor of all: he had more confidence than Edmund, more judgment than Tom, more talent and taste than Mr. Yates.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66363,\n            \"She did not like him as a man, but she must admit him to be the best actor, and on this point there were not many who differed from her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66409,\n            \"and the day came at last, when Mr. Rushworth turned to her with a black look, and said, \\u201cDo you think there is anything so very fine in all this?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66634,\n            \"Fanny, in her pity and kindheartedness, was at great pains to teach him how to learn, giving him all the helps and directions in her power, trying to make an artificial memory for him, and learning every word of his part herself, but without his being much the forwarder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66701,\n            \"but with all these, and other claims on her time and attention, she was as far from finding herself without employment or utility amongst them, as without a companion in uneasiness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66801,\n            \"and that Mrs. Norris thought her quite as well off as the rest, was evident by the manner in which she claimed it \\u2014 \\u201cCome, Fanny,\\u201dshe cried, \\u201cthese are fine times for you, but you must not be always walking from one room to the other, and doing the lookings-on at your ease, in this way;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66872,\n            \"I want you here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66903,\n            \"and now I think you may give me your help in putting it together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66949,\n            \"_ You _ are best off, I can tell you: but if nobody did more than _ you _, we should not get on very fast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66992,\n            \"but her kinder aunt Bertram observed on her behalf \\u2014 \\u201cOne cannot wonder, sister, that Fanny _ should _ be delighted: it is all new to her, you know;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67027,\n            \"you and I used to be very fond of a play ourselves, and so am I still;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67078,\n            \"you have never told me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67088,\n            \"sister, pray do not ask her now;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67121,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI believe,\\u201dsaid Fanny to her aunt Bertram, \\u201cthere will be three acts rehearsed to-morrow evening, and that will give you an opportunity of seeing all the actors at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67230,\n            \"Fanny did not share her aunt\\u2019s composure: she thought of the morrow a great deal, for if the three acts were rehearsed, Edmund and Miss Crawford would then be acting together for the first time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67271,\n            \"the third act would bring a scene between them which interested her most particularly, and which she was longing and dreading to see how they would perform.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67335,\n            \"She had read and read the scene again with many painful, many wondering emotions, and looked forward to their representation of it as a circumstance almost too interesting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67366,\n            \"She did not _ believe _ they had yet rehearsed it, even in private.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67406,\n            \"She worked very diligently under her aunt\\u2019s directions, but her diligence and her silence concealed a very absent, anxious mind;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67431,\n            \"and about noon she made her escape with her work to the East room, that she might have no concern in another, and, as she deemed it, most unnecessary rehearsal of the first act, which Henry Crawford was just proposing, desirous at once of having her time to herself, and of avoiding the sight of Mr. Rushworth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67497,\n            \"A glimpse, as she passed through the hall, of the two ladies walking up from the Parsonage made no change in her wish of retreat, and she worked and meditated in the East room, undisturbed, for a quarter of an hour, when a gentle tap at the door was followed by the entrance of Miss Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67598,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny, quite surprised, endeavoured to shew herself mistress of the room by her civilities, and looked at the bright bars of her empty grate with concern.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67763,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny was most civil in her assurances, though she could not give them in a very steady voice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68375,\n            \"He too had his book, and was seeking Fanny, to ask her to rehearse with him, and help him to prepare for the evening, without knowing Miss Crawford to be in the house;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68490,\n            \"Edmund proposed, urged, entreated it, till the lady, not very unwilling at first, could refuse no longer, and Fanny was wanted only to prompt and observe them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68704,\n            \"At last the scene was over, and Fanny forced herself to add her praise to the compliments each was giving the other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69335,\n            \"Fanny, I am sure you know the part.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69345,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny could not say she did _ not _;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70049,\n            \"She had been quite overlooked by her cousins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70058,\n            \"and as her own opinion of her claims on Sir Thomas\\u2019 s affection was much too humble to give her any idea of classing herself with his children, she was glad to remain behind and gain a little breathing-time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70102,\n            \"Her agitation and alarm exceeded all that was endured by the rest, by the right of a disposition which not even innocence could keep from suffering.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70175,\n            \"She had found a seat, where in excessive trembling she was enduring all these fearful thoughts, while the other three, no longer under any restraint, were giving vent to their feelings of vexation, lamenting over such an unlooked-for premature arrival as a most untoward event, and without mercy wishing poor Sir Thomas had been twice as long on his passage, or were still in Antigua.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70487,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny was just beginning to collect herself, and to feel that if she staid longer behind it might seem disrespectful, when this point was settled, and being commissioned with the brother and sister\\u2019s apology, saw them preparing to go as she quitted the room herself to perform the dreadful duty of appearing before her uncle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70563,\n            \"and after pausing a moment for what she knew would not come, for a courage which the outside of no door had ever supplied to her, she turned the lock in desperation, and the lights of the drawing-room, and all the collected family, were before her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70826,\n            \"He inquired next after her family, especially William: and his kindness altogether was such as made her reproach herself for loving him so little, and thinking his return a misfortune;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70860,\n            \"and when, on having courage to lift her eyes to his face, she saw that he was grown thinner, and had the burnt, fagged, worn look of fatigue and a hot climate, every tender feeling was increased, and she was miserable in considering how much unsuspected vexation was probably ready to burst on him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71912,\n            \"but the pause was not long: in the elation of her spirits Lady Bertram became talkative, and what were the sensations of her children upon hearing her say, \\u201cHow do you think the young people have been amusing themselves lately, Sir Thomas?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72130,\n            \"The first day I went over Mansfield Wood, and Edmund took the copses beyond Easton, and we brought home six brace between us, and might each have killed six times as many, but we respect your pheasants, sir, I assure you, as much as you could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72185,\n            \"I do not think you will find your woods by any means worse stocked than they were.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72221,\n            \"I hope you will take a day\\u2019s sport there yourself, sir, soon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72377,\n            \"\\u201cWhere did you leave Miss Crawford, Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72387,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny told of their departure, and delivered their message.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74564,\n            \"\\u201cWe have all been more or less to blame,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cevery one of us, excepting Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74630,\n            \"You will find Fanny everything you could wish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74809,\n            \"He could not help giving Mrs. Norris a hint of his having hoped that her advice might have been interposed to prevent what her judgment must certainly have disapproved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74881,\n            \"and with greater surprise, therefore, he must regard her acquiescence in their wrong measures, her countenance of their unsafe amusements, than that such measures and such amusements should have been suggested.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74938,\n            \"for she was ashamed to confess having never seen any of the impropriety which was so glaring to Sir Thomas, and would not have admitted that her influence was insufficient \\u2014 that she might have talked in vain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74978,\n            \"Her only resource was to get out of the subject as fast as possible, and turn the current of Sir Thomas\\u2019 s ideas into a happier channel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75008,\n            \"She had a great deal to insinuate in her own praise as to _ general _ attention to the interest and comfort of his family, much exertion and many sacrifices to glance at in the form of hurried walks and sudden removals from her own fireside, and many excellent hints of distrust and economy to Lady Bertram and Edmund to detail, whereby a most considerable saving had always arisen, and more than one bad servant been detected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75098,\n            \"Her greatest support and glory was in having formed the connexion with the Rushworths.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75120,\n            \"She took to herself all the credit of bringing Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s admiration of Maria to any effect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75141,\n            \"\\u201cIf I had not been active,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cand made a point of being introduced to his mother, and then prevailed on my sister to pay the first visit, I am as certain as I sit here that nothing would have come of it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77545,\n            \"Mrs. Norris began to look about her, and wonder that his falling in love with Julia had come to nothing;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77817,\n            \"Mrs. Norris contrived to remove one article from his sight that might have distressed him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78013,\n            \"\\u201cBut they,\\u201dhe observed to Fanny, \\u201chave a claim.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78357,\n            \"\\u201cI believe you are right, Fanny,\\u201dwas his reply, after a short consideration.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78430,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI suppose I am graver than other people,\\u201dsaid Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78539,\n            \"But when did you, or anybody, ever get a compliment from me, Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78715,\n            \"\\u2014 and your figure \\u2014 nay, Fanny, do not turn away about it \\u2014 it is but an uncle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78787,\n            \"don\\u2019t talk so, don\\u2019t talk so,\\u201dcried Fanny, distressed by more feelings than he was aware of;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78872,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut I do talk to him more than I used.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79245,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cShe must know herself too secure of the regard of all the rest of you,\\u201dsaid Fanny, with half a sigh, \\u201cto have any such apprehension.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79398,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny could have said a great deal, but it was safer to say nothing, and leave untouched all Miss Crawford\\u2019s resources \\u2014 her accomplishments, her spirits, her importance, her friends, lest it should betray her into any observations seemingly unhandsome.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81396,\n            \"CHAPTER XXII Fanny\\u2019s consequence increased on the departure of her cousins.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81410,\n            \"Becoming, as she then did, the only young woman in the drawing-room, the only occupier of that interesting division of a family in which she had hitherto held so humble a third, it was impossible for her not to be more looked at, more thought of and attended to, than she had ever been before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81480,\n            \"\\u201d became no uncommon question, even without her being wanted for any one\\u2019s convenience.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81513,\n            \"In that house, which she had hardly entered twice a year since Mr. Norris\\u2019 s death, she became a welcome, an invited guest, and in the gloom and dirt of a November day, most acceptable to Mary Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81572,\n            \"Mrs. Grant, really eager to get any change for her sister, could, by the easiest self-deceit, persuade herself that she was doing the kindest thing by Fanny, and giving her the most important opportunities of improvement in pressing her frequent calls.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81622,\n            \"Fanny, having been sent into the village on some errand by her aunt Norris, was overtaken by a heavy shower close to the Parsonage;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81649,\n            \"and being descried from one of the windows endeavouring to find shelter under the branches and lingering leaves of an oak just beyond their premises, was forced, though not without some modest reluctance on her part, to come in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81692,\n            \"A civil servant she had withstood;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81836,\n            \"She was all alive again directly, and among the most active in being useful to Fanny, in detecting her to be wetter than she would at first allow, and providing her with dry clothes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81874,\n            \"and Fanny, after being obliged to submit to all this attention, and to being assisted and waited on by mistresses and maids, being also obliged, on returning downstairs, to be fixed in their drawing-room for an hour while the rain continued, the blessing of something fresh to see and think of was thus extended to Miss Crawford, and might carry on her spirits to the period of dressing and dinner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81954,\n            \"The two sisters were so kind to her, and so pleasant, that Fanny might have enjoyed her visit could she have believed herself not in the way, and could she have foreseen that the weather would certainly clear at the end of the hour, and save her from the shame of having Dr. Grant\\u2019s carriage and horses out to take her home, with which she was threatened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82056,\n            \"for as her being out was known only to her two aunts, she was perfectly aware that none would be felt, and that in whatever cottage aunt Norris might chuse to establish her during the rain, her being in such cottage would be indubitable to aunt Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82226,\n            \"and \\u201cShall I play to you now?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82292,\n            \"She played till Fanny\\u2019s eyes, straying to the window on the weather\\u2019s being evidently fair, spoke what she felt must be done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82415,\n            \"And besides, I want to play something more to you \\u2014 a very pretty piece \\u2014 and your cousin Edmund\\u2019s prime favourite.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82459,\n            \"and though she had not waited for that sentence to be thinking of Edmund, such a memento made her particularly awake to his idea, and she fancied him sitting in that room again and again, perhaps in the very spot where she sat now, listening with constant delight to the favourite air, played, as it appeared to her, with superior tone and expression;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82530,\n            \"and though pleased with it herself, and glad to like whatever was liked by him, she was more sincerely impatient to go away at the conclusion of it than she had been before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82566,\n            \"and on this being evident, she was so kindly asked to call again, to take them in her walk whenever she could, to come and hear more of the harp, that she felt it necessary to be done, if no objection arose at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82616,\n            \"Such was the origin of the sort of intimacy which took place between them within the first fortnight after the Miss Bertrams\\u2019 going away \\u2014 an intimacy resulting principally from Miss Crawford\\u2019s desire of something new, and which had little reality in Fanny\\u2019s feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82667,\n            \"Fanny went to her every two or three days: it seemed a kind of fascination: she could not be easy without going, and yet it was without loving her, without ever thinking like her, without any sense of obligation for being sought after now when nobody else was to be had;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82765,\n            \"She went, however, and they sauntered about together many an half-hour in Mrs. Grant\\u2019s shrubbery, the weather being unusually mild for the time of year, and venturing sometimes even to sit down on one of the benches now comparatively unsheltered, remaining there perhaps till, in the midst of some tender ejaculation of Fanny\\u2019s on the sweets of so protracted an autumn, they were forced, by the sudden swell of a cold gust shaking down the last few yellow leaves about them, to jump up and walk for warmth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82870,\n            \"\\u201cThis is pretty, very pretty,\\u201dsaid Fanny, looking around her as they were thus sitting together one day;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83148,\n            \"and Fanny, perceiving it, brought back her own mind to what she thought must interest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83631,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny\\u2019s heart beat quick, and she felt quite unequal to surmising or soliciting anything more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83927,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny was silent, and Miss Crawford relapsed into thoughtfulness, till suddenly looking up at the end of a few minutes, she exclaimed, \\u201cAh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84255,\n            \"A friendship between two so very dear to him was exactly what he could have wished: and to the credit of the lover\\u2019s understanding, be it stated, that he did not by any means consider Fanny as the only, or even as the greater gainer by such a friendship.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85422,\n            \"\\u201d of some length from the fair lady before she could add, \\u201cYou ought to be in parliament, or you should have gone into the army ten years ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85550,\n            \"\\u201d A look of consciousness as he spoke, and what seemed a consciousness of manner on Miss Crawford\\u2019s side as she made some laughing answer, was sorrowfull food for Fanny\\u2019s observation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85588,\n            \"and finding herself quite unable to attend as she ought to Mrs. Grant, by whose side she was now following the others, she had nearly resolved on going home immediately, and only waited for courage to say so, when the sound of the great clock at Mansfield Park, striking three, made her feel that she had really been much longer absent than usual, and brought the previous self-inquiry of whether she should take leave or not just then, and how, to a very speedy issue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85695,\n            \"and Edmund began at the same time to recollect that his mother had been inquiring for her, and that he had walked down to the Parsonage on purpose to bring her back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85777,\n            \"Dr. Grant was in the vestibule, and as they stopt to speak to him she found, from Edmund\\u2019s manner, that he _ did _ mean to go with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85947,\n            \"But Edmund, delighted with her having such an happiness offered, and ascertaining with half a look, and half a sentence, that she had no objection but on her aunt\\u2019s account, could not imagine that his mother would make any difficulty of sparing her, and therefore gave his decided open advice that the invitation should be accepted;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86297,\n            \"\\u201cHow came she to think of asking Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86307,\n            \"Fanny never dines there, you know, in this sort of way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86321,\n            \"I cannot spare her, and I am sure she does not want to go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86349,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf you put such a question to her,\\u201dcried Edmund, preventing his cousin\\u2019s speaking, \\u201cFanny will immediately say No;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86378,\n            \"but I am sure, my dear mother, she would like to go;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86404,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI cannot imagine why Mrs. Grant should think of asking her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86424,\n            \"She used to ask your sisters now and then, but she never asked Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86440,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf you cannot do without me, ma\\u2019am \\u2014\\u201dsaid Fanny, in a self-denying tone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86518,\n            \"I will ask Sir Thomas, as soon as he comes in, whether I can do without her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86576,\n            \"and I think he will consider it a right thing by Mrs. Grant, as well as by Fanny, that being the _ first _ invitation it should be accepted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86621,\n            \"But he will be very much surprised that Mrs. Grant should ask Fanny at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86792,\n            \"for to hear herself the subject of any discussion with her uncle was more than her nerves could bear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86840,\n            \"but if her uncle were to be a great while considering and deciding, and with very grave looks, and those grave looks directed to her, and at last decide against her, she might not be able to appear properly submissive and indifferent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86954,\n            \"But how can I spare her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87327,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThank you, I am _ so _ glad,\\u201dwas Fanny\\u2019s instinctive reply;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87554,\n            \"\\u201cUpon my word, Fanny, you are in high luck to meet with such attention and indulgence!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88062,\n            \"\\u201cThe nonsense and folly of people\\u2019s stepping out of their rank and trying to appear above themselves, makes me think it right to give _ you _ a hint, Fanny, now that you are going into company without any of us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88357,\n            \"and when Sir Thomas soon afterwards, just opening the door, said, \\u201cFanny, at what time would you have the carriage come round?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88678,\n            \"\\u201cNow I must look at you, Fanny,\\u201dsaid Edmund, with the kind smile of an affectionate brother, \\u201cand tell you how I like you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89139,\n            \"for though she must submit, as her own propriety of mind directed, in spite of her aunt Norris\\u2019 s opinion, to being the principal lady in company, and to all the little distinctions consequent thereon, she found, while they were at table, such a happy flow of conversation prevailing, in which she was not required to take any part \\u2014 there was so much to be said between the brother and sister about Bath, so much between the two young men about hunting, so much of politics between Mr. Crawford and Dr. Grant, and of everything and all together between Mr. Crawford and Mrs. Grant, as to leave her the fairest prospect of having only to listen in quiet, and of passing a very agreeable day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89284,\n            \"She could not compliment the newly arrived gentleman, however, with any appearance of interest, in a scheme for extending his stay at Mansfield, and sending for his hunters from Norfolk, which, suggested by Dr. Grant, advised by Edmund, and warmly urged by the two sisters, was soon in possession of his mind, and which he seemed to want to be encouraged even by her to resolve on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89408,\n            \"Her two absent cousins, especially Maria, were much in her thoughts on seeing him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89475,\n            \"She heard them spoken of by him only in a general way, till they were all re-assembled in the drawing-room, when Edmund, being engaged apart in some matter of business with Dr. Grant, which seemed entirely to engross them, and Mrs. Grant occupied at the tea-table, he began talking of them with more particularity to his other sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89548,\n            \"With a significant smile, which made Fanny quite hate him, he said, \\u201cSo!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89581,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, they have been there about a fortnight, Miss Price, have they not?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89757,\n            \"\\u201d And then changing his tone again to one of gentle gallantry, and addressing Fanny, he said, \\u201cYou were Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s best friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89788,\n            \"Your kindness and patience can never be forgotten, your indefatigable patience in trying to make it possible for him to learn his part \\u2014 in trying to give him a brain which nature had denied \\u2014 to mix up an understanding for him out of the superfluity of your own!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89840,\n            \"_ He _ might not have sense enough himself to estimate your kindness, but I may venture to say that it had honour from all the rest of the party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90027,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWe were unlucky, Miss Price,\\u201dhe continued, in a lower tone, to avoid the possibility of being heard by Edmund, and not at all aware of her feelings, \\u201cwe certainly were very unlucky.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90150,\n            \"I think, Miss Price, we would have indulged ourselves with a week\\u2019s calm in the Atlantic at that season.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90182,\n            \"and Fanny, averting her face, said, with a firmer tone than usual, \\u201cAs far as _ I _ am concerned, sir, I would not have delayed his return for a day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90244,\n            \"\\u201d She had never spoken so much at once to him in her life before, and never so angrily to any one;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91464,\n            \"No, my plan is to make Fanny Price in love with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91499,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut I cannot be satisfied without Fanny Price, without making a small hole in Fanny Price\\u2019s heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91522,\n            \"You do not seem properly aware of her claims to notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91534,\n            \"When we talked of her last night, you none of you seemed sensible of the wonderful improvement that has taken place in her looks within the last six weeks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91565,\n            \"You see her every day, and therefore do not notice it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91578,\n            \"but I assure you she is quite a different creature from what she was in the autumn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91618,\n            \"I used to think she had neither complexion nor countenance;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91653,\n            \"and from what I observed of her eyes and mouth, I do not despair of their being capable of expression enough when she has anything to express.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91723,\n            \"This is only because there were no tall women to compare her with, and because she has got a new gown, and you never saw her so well dressed before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91756,\n            \"She is just what she was in October, believe me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91768,\n            \"The truth is, that she was the only girl in company for you to notice, and you must have a somebody.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91792,\n            \"I have always thought her pretty \\u2014 not strikingly pretty \\u2014 but \\u2018 pretty enough,\\u2019as people say;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92339,\n            \"\\u201d And without attempting any farther remonstrance, she left Fanny to her fate, a fate which, had not Fanny\\u2019s heart been guarded in a way unsuspected by Miss Crawford, might have been a little harder than she deserved;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92384,\n            \"for although there doubtless are such unconquerable young ladies of eighteen (or one should not read about them) as are never to be persuaded into love against their judgment by all that talent, manner, attention, and flattery can do, I have no inclination to believe Fanny one of them, or to think that with so much tenderness of disposition, and so much taste as belonged to her, she could have escaped heart-whole from the courtship (though the courtship only of a fortnight) of such a man as Crawford, in spite of there being some previous ill opinion of him to be overcome, had not her affection been engaged elsewhere.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92636,\n            \"and at the end of those few days, circumstances arose which had a tendency rather to forward his views of pleasing her, inasmuch as they gave her a degree of happiness which must dispose her to be pleased with everybody.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92737,\n            \"and when Crawford walked up with the newspaper in his hand, which he had hoped would bring the first tidings, he found her trembling with joy over this letter, and listening with a glowing, grateful countenance to the kind invitation which her uncle was most collectedly dictating in reply.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92871,\n            \"and the good luck which attended his early examination of ship news the next morning seemed the reward of his ingenuity in finding out such a method of pleasing her, as well as of his dutiful attention to the Admiral, in having for many years taken in the paper esteemed to have the earliest naval intelligence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93029,\n            \"and as his parents, from living on the spot, must already have seen him, and be seeing him perhaps daily, his direct holidays might with justice be instantly given to the sister, who had been his best correspondent through a period of seven years, and the uncle who had done most for his support and advancement;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93184,\n            \"and there being neither ceremony nor fearfulness to delay the moment of meeting, she was with him as he entered the house, and the first minutes of exquisite feeling had no interruption and no witnesses, unless the servants chiefly intent upon opening the proper doors could be called such.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93294,\n            \"William and Fanny soon shewed themselves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93655,\n            \"who could give her direct and minute information of the father and mother, brothers and sisters, of whom she very seldom heard;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94057,\n            \"and saw, with lively admiration, the glow of Fanny\\u2019s cheek, the brightness of her eye, the deep interest, the absorbed attention, while her brother was describing any of the imminent hazards, or terrific scenes, which such a period at sea must supply.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94699,\n            \"and Crawford could mount him without the slightest inconvenience to himself, and with only some scruples to obviate in Sir Thomas, who knew better than his nephew the value of such a loan, and some alarms to reason away in Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94818,\n            \"nor till he returned safe and well, without accident or discredit, could she be reconciled to the risk, or feel any of that obligation to Mr. Crawford for lending the horse which he had fully intended it should produce.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94862,\n            \"When it was proved, however, to have done William no harm, she could allow it to be a kindness, and even reward the owner with a smile when the animal was one minute tendered to his use again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95689,\n            \"and Sir Thomas, Mrs. Norris, and Dr. and Mrs. Grant being seated at the table of prime intellectual state and dignity, the remaining six, under Miss Crawford\\u2019s direction, were arranged round the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95733,\n            \"It was a fine arrangement for Henry Crawford, who was close to Fanny, and with his hands full of business, having two persons\\u2019 cards to manage as well as his own;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95769,\n            \"for though it was impossible for Fanny not to feel herself mistress of the rules of the game in three minutes, he had yet to inspirit her play, sharpen her avarice, and harden her heart, which, especially in any competition with William, was a work of some difficulty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97584,\n            \"_ You _ think with me, I hope\\u201d(turning with a softened voice to Fanny).\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98747,\n            \"and Fanny\\u2019s reception of it was so proper and modest, so calm and uninviting, that he had nothing to censure in her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99364,\n            \"\\u201d Whatever effect Sir Thomas\\u2019 s little harangue might really produce on Mr. Crawford, it raised some awkward sensations in two of the others, two of his most attentive listeners \\u2014 Miss Crawford and Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99444,\n            \"and the other, startled from the agreeable fancies she had been previously indulging on the strength of her brother\\u2019s description, no longer able, in the picture she had been forming of a future Thornton, to shut out the church, sink the clergyman, and see only the respectable, elegant, modernised, and occasional residence of a man of independent fortune, was considering Sir Thomas, with decided ill-will, as the destroyer of all this, and suffering the more from that involuntary forbearance which his character and manner commanded, and from not daring to relieve herself by a single attempt at throwing ridicule on his cause.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99592,\n            \"and she was glad to find it necessary to come to a conclusion, and be able to refresh her spirits by a change of place and neighbour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99642,\n            \"William and Fanny were the most detached.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99769,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo, Fanny, that I do not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99780,\n            \"I shall have enough of Portsmouth and of dancing too, when I cannot have you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99855,\n            \"You remember the Gregorys;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100049,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI begin to think I shall never be a lieutenant, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100089,\n            \"My uncle says nothing, but I am sure he will do everything in his power to get you made.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100125,\n            \"\\u201d She was checked by the sight of her uncle much nearer to them than she had any suspicion of, and each found it necessary to talk of something else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100178,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI should like to go to a ball with you and see you dance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100203,\n            \"I should like to see you dance, and I\\u2019d dance with you if you _ would _, for nobody would know who I was here, and I should like to be your partner once more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100287,\n            \"\\u201d And turning to his uncle, who was now close to them, \\u201cIs not Fanny a very good dancer, sir?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100396,\n            \"I have never seen Fanny dance since she was a little girl;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100488,\n            \"But I believe\\u201d(seeing Fanny looked distressed) \\u201cit must be at some other time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100526,\n            \"\\u201d True enough, he had once seen Fanny dance;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100688,\n            \"\\u201cCome, Fanny, Fanny, what are you about?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100803,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s last feeling in the visit was disappointment: for the shawl which Edmund was quietly taking from the servant to bring and put round her shoulders was seized by Mr. Crawford\\u2019s quicker hand, and she was obliged to be indebted to his more prominent attention.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100910,\n            \"to gratify anybody else who might wish to see Fanny dance, and to give pleasure to the young people in general;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101371,\n            \"Edmund, William, and Fanny did, in their different ways, look and speak as much grateful pleasure in the promised ball as Sir Thomas could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101710,\n            \"Invitations were sent with despatch, and many a young lady went to bed that night with her head full of happy cares as well as Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102869,\n            \"and on Wednesday morning Fanny, still unable to satisfy herself as to what she ought to wear, determined to seek the counsel of the more enlightened, and apply to Mrs. Grant and her sister, whose acknowledged taste would certainly bear her blameless;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102956,\n            \"and the privacy of such a discussion was a most important part of it to Fanny, being more than half-ashamed of her own solicitude.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103245,\n            \"\\u201d And as she spoke she was undoing a small parcel, which Fanny had observed in her hand when they met.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103268,\n            \"Fanny acknowledged her wishes and doubts on this point: she did not know how either to wear the cross, or to refrain from wearing it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103323,\n            \"Such had been the parcel with which Miss Crawford was provided, and such the object of her intended visit: and in the kindest manner she now urged Fanny\\u2019s taking one for the cross and to keep for her sake, saying everything she could think of to obviate the scruples which were making Fanny start back at first with a look of horror at the proposal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103498,\n            \"Fanny found herself obliged to yield, that she might not be accused of pride or indifference, or some other littleness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103583,\n            \"and though Fanny would have preferred a longer and a plainer chain as more adapted for her purpose, she hoped, in fixing on this, to be chusing what Miss Crawford least wished to keep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103650,\n            \"Fanny had not a word to say against its becomingness, and, excepting what remained of her scruples, was exceedingly pleased with an acquisition so very apropos.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104443,\n            \"CHAPTER XXVII On reaching home Fanny went immediately upstairs to deposit this unexpected acquisition, this doubtful good of a necklace, in some favourite box in the East room, which held all her smaller treasures;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104519,\n            \"\\u201cFanny,\\u201dsaid he directly, leaving his seat and his pen, and meeting her with something in his hand, \\u201cI beg your pardon for being here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104667,\n            \"I hope you will like the chain itself, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104818,\n            \"Your goodness in thinking of me in such a way is beyond \\u2014\\u201d\\u201cIf that is all you have to say, Fanny\\u201dsmiling and turning away again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105173,\n            \"for Edmund was so struck with the circumstance, so delighted with what Miss Crawford had done, so gratified by such a coincidence of conduct between them, that Fanny could not but admit the superior power of one pleasure over his own mind, though it might have its drawback.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105361,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf it had been given to me in the first instance,\\u201dsaid Fanny, \\u201cI should not have thought of returning it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105448,\n            \"for as she was not prevented from offering, nor you from taking it on that account, it ought not to prevent you from keeping it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105805,\n            \"and Fanny remained to tranquillise herself as she could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105983,\n            \"Till she had shed many tears over this deception, Fanny could not subdue her agitation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106529,\n            \"and opened with more kindness to Fanny than such self-willed, unmanageable days often volunteer, for soon after breakfast a very friendly note was brought from Mr. Crawford to William, stating that as he found himself obliged to go to London on the morrow for a few days, he could not help trying to procure a companion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107206,\n            \"and left alone to bear the worrying of Mrs. Norris, who was cross because the housekeeper would have her own way with the supper, and whom _ she _ could not avoid though the housekeeper might, Fanny was worn down at last to think everything an evil belonging to the ball, and when sent off with a parting worry to dress, moved as languidly towards her own room, and felt as incapable of happiness as if she had been allowed no share in it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107357,\n            \"\\u201cFanny,\\u201dsaid a voice at that moment near her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107403,\n            \"\\u201cYou look tired and fagged, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107535,\n            \"\\u201cYou may guess my errand there, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107545,\n            \"\\u201d And he looked so conscious, that Fanny could think but of one errand, which turned her too sick for speech.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107569,\n            \"\\u201cI wished to engage Miss Crawford for the two first dances,\\u201dwas the explanation that followed, and brought Fanny to life again, enabling her, as she found she was expected to speak, to utter something like an inquiry as to the result.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107742,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny struggled for speech, and said, \\u201cI am very sorry that anything has occurred to distress you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107830,\n            \"But, Fanny,\\u201dstopping her, by taking her hand, and speaking low and seriously, \\u201cyou know what all this means.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108027,\n            \"for sometimes, Fanny, I own to you, it does appear more than manner: it appears as if the mind itself was tainted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108054,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny imagined this to be an appeal to her judgment, and therefore, after a moment\\u2019s consideration, said, \\u201cIf you only want me as a listener, cousin, I will be as useful as I can;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108122,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou are right, Fanny, to protest against such an office, but you need not be afraid.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108418,\n            \"you can bear me witness, Fanny, that I have never been blinded.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108501,\n            \"He had said enough to give Fanny some happier feelings than she had lately known, and with a brighter look, she answered, \\u201cYes, cousin, I am convinced that _ you _ would be incapable of anything else, though perhaps some might not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108990,\n            \"and Fanny left her room at last, comfortably satisfied with herself and all about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109023,\n            \"It had really occurred to her, unprompted, that Fanny, preparing for a ball, might be glad of better help than the upper housemaid\\u2019s, and when dressed herself, she actually sent her own maid to assist her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109129,\n            \"CHAPTER XXVIII Her uncle and both her aunts were in the drawing-room when Fanny went down.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109148,\n            \"To the former she was an interesting object, and he saw with pleasure the general elegance of her appearance, and her being in remarkably good looks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109231,\n            \"I sent Chapman to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109246,\n            \"\\u201d cried Mrs. Norris, \\u201cshe has good reason to look well with all her advantages: brought up in this family as she has been, with all the benefit of her cousins\\u2019 manners before her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109309,\n            \"The very gown you have been taking notice of is your own generous present to her when dear Mrs. Rushworth married.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109332,\n            \"What would she have been if we had not taken her by the hand?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109424,\n            \"for in following her aunts out of the room, Edmund, who was holding open the door, said, as she passed him, \\u201cYou must dance with me, Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109503,\n            \"Her cousins\\u2019 former gaiety on the day of a ball was no longer surprising to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109521,\n            \"she felt it to be indeed very charming, and was actually practising her steps about the drawing-room as long as she could be safe from the notice of her aunt Norris, who was entirely taken up at first in fresh arranging and injuring the noble fire which the butler had prepared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109703,\n            \"When the carriages were really heard, when the guests began really to assemble, her own gaiety of heart was much subdued: the sight of so many strangers threw her back into herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109780,\n            \"She was introduced here and there by her uncle, and forced to be spoken to, and to curtsey, and speak again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110014,\n            \"and she so little understood her own claims as to think that if Mr. Crawford had not asked her, she must have been the last to be sought after, and should have received a partner only through a series of inquiry, and bustle, and interference, which would have been terrible;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110124,\n            \"And though there was no second glance to disturb her, though his object seemed then to be only quietly agreeable, she could not get the better of her embarrassment, heightened as it was by the idea of his perceiving it, and had no composure till he turned away to some one else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110514,\n            \"Sir Thomas brought him to her, saying something which discovered to Fanny, that _ she _ was to lead the way and open the ball;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110712,\n            \"and she found herself the next moment conducted by Mr. Crawford to the top of the room, and standing there to be joined by the rest of the dancers, couple after couple, as they were formed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110775,\n            \"It was treating her like her cousins!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110783,\n            \"And her thoughts flew to those absent cousins with most unfeigned and truly tender regret, that they were not at home to take their own place in the room, and have their share of a pleasure which would have been so very delightful to them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110831,\n            \"So often as she had heard them wish for a ball at home as the greatest of all felicities!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110851,\n            \"And to have them away when it was given \\u2014 and for _ her _ to be opening the ball \\u2014 and with Mr. Crawford too!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110879,\n            \"She hoped they would not envy her that distinction _ now _;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110892,\n            \"but when she looked back to the state of things in the autumn, to what they had all been to each other when once dancing in that house before, the present arrangement was almost more than she could understand herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110939,\n            \"It was rather honour than happiness to Fanny, for the first dance at least: her partner was in excellent spirits, and tried to impart them to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111028,\n            \"She was attractive, she was modest, she was Sir Thomas\\u2019 s niece, and she was soon said to be admired by Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111177,\n            \"Her praise was warm, and he received it as she could wish, joining in it as far as discretion, and politeness, and slowness of speech would allow, and certainly appearing to greater advantage on the subject than his lady did soon afterwards, when Mary, perceiving her on a sofa very near, turned round before she began to dance, to compliment her on Miss Price\\u2019s looks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111285,\n            \"\\u201d Not but that she was really pleased to have Fanny admired;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111326,\n            \"Miss Crawford knew Mrs. Norris too well to think of gratifying _ her _ by commendation of Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111434,\n            \"Miss Crawford blundered most towards Fanny herself in her intentions to please.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111447,\n            \"She meant to be giving her little heart a happy flutter, and filling her with sensations of delightful self-consequence;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111470,\n            \"and, misinterpreting Fanny\\u2019s blushes, still thought she must be doing so when she went to her after the two first dances, and said, with a significant look, \\u201cPerhaps _ you _ can tell me why my brother goes to town to-morrow?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111580,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny protested her ignorance as steadily as her embarrassment allowed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112041,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny would hardly even speak her agreement.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112218,\n            \"Fanny, not able to refrain entirely from observing them, had seen enough to be tolerably satisfied.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112286,\n            \"and Sir Thomas, having seen her walk rather than dance down the shortening set, breathless, and with her hand at her side, gave his orders for her sitting down entirely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112438,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, then, Fanny, you shall not get up to-morrow before I go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112495,\n            \"yes, sir,\\u201dcried Fanny, rising eagerly from her seat to be nearer her uncle;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112575,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny was too urgent, however, and had too many tears in her eyes for denial;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112756,\n            \"Mr. Crawford was in love with Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113289,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s disposition was such that she could never even think of her aunt Norris in the meagreness and cheerlessness of her own small house, without reproaching herself for some little want of attention to her when they had been last together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113475,\n            \"\\u201cShe could not recollect what it was that she had heard about one of the Miss Maddoxes, or what it was that Lady Prescott had noticed in Fanny: she was not sure whether Colonel Harrison had been talking of Mr. Crawford or of William when he said he was the finest young man in the room \\u2014 somebody had whispered something to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113709,\n            \"Fanny, you must do something to keep me awake.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113797,\n            \"You are to deal, ma\\u2019am;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114112,\n            \"and in consideration of Fanny\\u2019s swimming eyes, nothing more was said on the first day than to drink their good health;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114405,\n            \"and at the end of a quarter of an hour\\u2019s silent consideration spontaneously observed, \\u201cSir Thomas, I have been thinking \\u2014 and I am very glad we took Fanny as we did, for now the others are away we feel the good of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114470,\n            \"We shew Fanny what a good girl we think her by praising her to her face, she is now a very valuable companion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114495,\n            \"If we have been kind to _ her _, she is now quite as necessary to _ us _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114526,\n            \"\\u201cand it is a comfort to think that we shall always have _ her _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114543,\n            \"\\u201d Sir Thomas paused, half smiled, glanced at his niece, and then gravely replied, \\u201cShe will never leave us, I hope, till invited to some other home that may reasonably promise her greater happiness than she knows here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115396,\n            \"But at last Lady Bertram left the room, and then almost immediately Miss Crawford thus began, with a voice as well regulated as she could \\u2014 \\u201cAnd how do _ you _ like your cousin Edmund\\u2019s staying away so long?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115442,\n            \"Being the only young person at home, I consider _ you _ as the greatest sufferer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115622,\n            \"But you must give my compliments to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115640,\n            \"Is not there a something wanted, Miss Price, in our language \\u2014 a something between compliments and \\u2014 and love \\u2014 to suit the sort of friendly acquaintance we have had together?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115911,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat is the first question, you know,\\u201dsaid Miss Crawford, trying to appear gay and unconcerned, \\u201cwhich every woman who plays herself is sure to ask about another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116046,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI know nothing of the Miss Owens,\\u201dsaid Fanny calmly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116275,\n            \"\\u201d Now Fanny could not bring herself to speak, and Miss Crawford was disappointed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116461,\n            \"You don\\u2019t speak, Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116491,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo,\\u201dsaid Fanny stoutly, \\u201cI do not expect it at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116559,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo, I do not,\\u201dsaid Fanny softly, hoping she did not err either in the belief or the acknowledgment of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116843,\n            \"\\u201d he had only to say that he had been sitting with Lady Bertram and Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116944,\n            \"No: you must be aware that I am quite determined to marry Fanny Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117113,\n            \"I have, I flatter myself, made no inconsiderable progress in her affections;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117235,\n            \"Mrs. Norris often talks of her luck;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117259,\n            \"And she has some _ true _ friends in it!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117290,\n            \"When did you begin to think seriously about her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117438,\n            \"\\u201cWhen Fanny is known to him,\\u201dcontinued Henry, \\u201che will doat on her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117457,\n            \"She is exactly the woman to do away every prejudice of such a man as the Admiral, for she is exactly such a woman as he thinks does not exist in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117492,\n            \"She is the very impossibility he would describe, if indeed he has now delicacy of language enough to embody his own ideas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117666,\n            \"She is niece to Sir Thomas Bertram;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117728,\n            \"Mary, she is not like her cousins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117755,\n            \"Were you even less pleasing \\u2014 supposing her not to love you already (of which, however, I can have little doubt) \\u2014 you would be safe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117786,\n            \"The gentleness and gratitude of her disposition would secure her all your own immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117801,\n            \"From my soul I do not think she would marry you _ without _ love;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117817,\n            \"that is, if there is a girl in the world capable of being uninfluenced by ambition, I can suppose it her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117841,\n            \"but ask her to love you, and she will never have the heart to refuse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117882,\n            \"and a conversation followed almost as deeply interesting to her as to himself, though he had in fact nothing to relate but his own sensations, nothing to dwell on but Fanny\\u2019s charms.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117959,\n            \"that sweetness which makes so essential a part of every woman\\u2019s worth in the judgment of man, that though he sometimes loves where it is not, he can never believe it absent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118237,\n            \"\\u201d Well might his sister, believing as she really did that his opinion of Fanny Price was scarcely beyond her merits, rejoice in her prospects.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118576,\n            \"\\u201cI cannot admit Mrs. Grant to have an equal claim with Fanny and myself, for we shall both have a right in you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118846,\n            \"You must not prejudice Fanny against him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119003,\n            \"\\u201d The impossibility of not doing everything in the world to make Fanny Price happy, or of ceasing to love Fanny Price, was of course the groundwork of his eloquent answer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119474,\n            \"and it will be the completion of my happiness to know that I am the doer of it, that I am the person to give the consequence so justly her due.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119551,\n            \"True, I believe he is, generally speaking, kind to her, and so is Sir Thomas in his way;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119592,\n            \"What can Sir Thomas and Edmund together do, what _ do _ they do for her happiness, comfort, honour, and dignity in the world, to what I _ shall _ do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119735,\n            \"Henry, overjoyed to have her go, bowed and watched her off, and without losing another moment, turned instantly to Fanny, and, taking out some letters, said, with a most animated look, \\u201cI must acknowledge myself infinitely obliged to any creature who gives me such an opportunity of seeing you alone: I have been wishing it more than you can have any idea.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119809,\n            \"Knowing as I do what your feelings as a sister are, I could hardly have borne that any one in the house should share with you in the first knowledge of the news I now bring.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119857,\n            \"I have the infinite satisfaction of congratulating you on your brother\\u2019s promotion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119896,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny could not speak, but he did not want her to speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119942,\n            \"She took the letters as he gave them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120097,\n            \"While her hand was trembling under these letters, her eye running from one to the other, and her heart swelling with emotion, Crawford thus continued, with unfeigned eagerness, to express his interest in the event \\u2014 \\u201cI will not talk of my own happiness,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cgreat as it is, for I think only of yours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120177,\n            \"I have almost grudged myself my own prior knowledge of what you ought to have known before all the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120555,\n            \"I beg your pardon, but I am bewildered.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120694,\n            \"and he spoke with such a glow of what his solicitude had been, and used such strong expressions, was so abounding in the _ deepest _ _ interest _, in _ twofold _ _ motives _, in _ views _ _ and _ _ wishes _ _ more _ _ than _ _ could _ _ be _ _ told _, that Fanny could not have remained insensible of his drift, had she been able to attend;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120778,\n            \"but her heart was so full and her senses still so astonished, that she could listen but imperfectly even to what he told her of William, and saying only when he paused, \\u201cHow kind!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120839,\n            \"\\u201d She jumped up and moved in haste towards the door, crying out, \\u201cI will go to my uncle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120947,\n            \"When she did understand it, however, and found herself expected to believe that she had created sensations which his heart had never known before, and that everything he had done for William was to be placed to the account of his excessive and unequalled attachment to her, she was exceedingly distressed, and for some moments unable to speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121033,\n            \"she could not but feel that it was treating her improperly and unworthily, and in such a way as she had not deserved;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121058,\n            \"but it was like himself, and entirely of a piece with what she had seen before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121076,\n            \"and she would not allow herself to shew half the displeasure she felt, because he had been conferring an obligation, which no want of delicacy on his part could make a trifle to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121142,\n            \"and after having twice drawn back her hand, and twice attempted in vain to turn away from him, she got up, and said only, with much agitation, \\u201cDon\\u2019t, Mr. Crawford, pray don\\u2019t!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121188,\n            \"I beg you would not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121217,\n            \"\\u201d But he was still talking on, describing his affection, soliciting a return, and, finally, in words so plain as to bear but one meaning even to her, offering himself, hand, fortune, everything, to her acceptance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121279,\n            \"and though still not knowing how to suppose him serious, she could hardly stand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121335,\n            \"Your kindness to William makes me more obliged to you than words can express;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121378,\n            \"But you are _ not _ thinking of me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121395,\n            \"\\u201d She had burst away from him, and at that moment Sir Thomas was heard speaking to a servant in his way towards the room they were in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121425,\n            \"It was no time for farther assurances or entreaty, though to part with her at a moment when her modesty alone seemed, to his sanguine and preassured mind, to stand in the way of the happiness he sought, was a cruel necessity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121472,\n            \"She rushed out at an opposite door from the one her uncle was approaching, and was walking up and down the East room in the utmost confusion of contrary feeling, before Sir Thomas\\u2019 s politeness or apologies were over, or he had reached the beginning of the joyful intelligence which his visitor came to communicate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121582,\n            \"He had previously made her the happiest of human beings, and now he had insulted \\u2014 she knew not what to say, how to class, or how to regard it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121616,\n            \"She would not have him be serious, and yet what could excuse the use of such words and offers, if they meant but to trifle?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121678,\n            \"Mr. Crawford would certainly never address her so again: he must have seen how unwelcome it was to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121700,\n            \"and in that case, how gratefully she could esteem him for his friendship to William!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121717,\n            \"She would not stir farther from the East room than the head of the great staircase, till she had satisfied herself of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s having left the house;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121750,\n            \"but when convinced of his being gone, she was eager to go down and be with her uncle, and have all the happiness of his joy as well as her own, and all the benefit of his information or his conjectures as to what would now be William\\u2019s destination.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121805,\n            \"Sir Thomas was as joyful as she could desire, and very kind and communicative;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121821,\n            \"and she had so comfortable a talk with him about William as to make her feel as if nothing had occurred to vex her, till she found, towards the close, that Mr. Crawford was engaged to return and dine there that very day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121927,\n            \"but it was quite impossible for her not to look most shy and uncomfortable when their visitor entered the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121981,\n            \"Mr. Crawford was not only in the room \\u2014 he was soon close to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122008,\n            \"Fanny could not look at him, but there was no consciousness of past folly in his voice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122027,\n            \"She opened her note immediately, glad to have anything to do, and happy, as she read it, to feel that the fidgetings of her aunt Norris, who was also to dine there, screened her a little from view.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122171,\n            \"so you may smile upon him with your sweetest smiles this afternoon, and send him back to me even happier than he goes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123024,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny, meanwhile, speaking only when she could not help it, was very earnestly trying to understand what Mr. and Miss Crawford were at.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123224,\n            \"Fanny was ashamed of her own doubts.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123961,\n            \"Fanny thought she had never known a day of greater agitation, both of pain and pleasure;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124073,\n            \"CHAPTER XXXII Fanny had by no means forgotten Mr. Crawford when she awoke the next morning;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124938,\n            \"but I think too well of you, Fanny, to suppose you will ever harbour resentment on that account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125459,\n            \"For a moment he ceased, but she had barely become conscious of it, when, rising from his chair, he said, \\u201cAnd now, Fanny, having performed one part of my commission, and shewn you everything placed on a basis the most assured and satisfactory, I may execute the remainder by prevailing on you to accompany me downstairs, where, though I cannot but presume on having been no unacceptable companion myself, I must submit to your finding one still better worth listening to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125808,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou are mistaken, sir,\\u201dcried Fanny, forced by the anxiety of the moment even to tell her uncle that he was wrong;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126356,\n            \"I am half inclined to think, Fanny, that you do not quite know your own feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126864,\n            \"and getting up and walking about the room with a frown, which Fanny could picture to herself, though she dared not lift up her eyes, he shortly afterwards, and in a voice of authority, said, \\u201cHave you any reason, child, to think ill of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s temper?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127077,\n            \"Sir Thomas came towards the table where she sat in trembling wretchedness, and with a good deal of cold sternness, said, \\u201cIt is of no use, I perceive, to talk to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127217,\n            \"I had thought you peculiarly free from wilfulness of temper, self-conceit, and every tendency to that independence of spirit which prevails so much in modern days, even in young women, and which in young women is offensive and disgusting beyond all common offence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127281,\n            \"that you can and will decide for yourself, without any consideration or deference for those who have surely some right to guide you, without even asking their advice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127327,\n            \"The advantage or disadvantage of your family, of your parents, your brothers and sisters, never seems to have had a moment\\u2019s share in your thoughts on this occasion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127361,\n            \"How _ they _ might be benefited, how _ they _ must rejoice in such an establishment for you, is nothing to _ you _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127741,\n            \"You do not owe me the duty of a child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127752,\n            \"But, Fanny, if your heart can acquit you of _ ingratitude _ \\u2014\\u201dHe ceased.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128920,\n            \"this was an act of kindness which Fanny felt at her heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129533,\n            \"Fanny would have had quite as good a walk there, I assure you, with the advantage of being of some use, and obliging her aunt: it is all her fault.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129568,\n            \"If she would but have let us know she was going out but there is a something about Fanny, I have often observed it before \\u2014 she likes to go her own way to work;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129624,\n            \"she certainly has a little spirit of secrecy, and independence, and nonsense, about her, which I would advise her to get the better of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129778,\n            \"and the evening set in with more composure to Fanny, and more cheerfulness of spirits than she could have hoped for after so stormy a morning;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130017,\n            \"While Fanny\\u2019s mind was engaged in these sort of hopes, her uncle was, soon after tea, called out of the room;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130118,\n            \"but instantly rising, she was preparing to obey, when Mrs. Norris called out, \\u201cStay, stay, Fanny!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130314,\n            \"and Fanny, walking off in agitating consciousness, found herself, as she anticipated, in another minute alone with Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130802,\n            \"To Fanny, however, who had known too much opposition all her life to find any charm in it, all this was unintelligible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131024,\n            \"Fanny knew her own meaning, but was no judge of her own manner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131611,\n            \"So thought Fanny, in good truth and sober sadness, as she sat musing over that too great indulgence and luxury of a fire upstairs: wondering at the past and present;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132043,\n            \"Accordingly, on this principle, Sir Thomas took the first opportunity of saying to her, with a mild gravity, intended to be overcoming, \\u201cWell, Fanny, I have seen Mr. Crawford again, and learn from him exactly how matters stand between you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132220,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed, sir,\\u201dsaid Fanny, \\u201cI am very sorry that Mr. Crawford should continue to \\u2014 I know that it is paying me a very great compliment, and I feel most undeservedly honoured;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133003,\n            \"and, independently of that, she disliked Fanny, because she had neglected her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133106,\n            \"To know Fanny to be sought in marriage by a man of fortune, raised her, therefore, very much in her opinion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133131,\n            \"By convincing her that Fanny _ was _ very pretty, which she had been doubting about before, and that she would be advantageously married, it made her feel a sort of credit in calling her niece.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133171,\n            \"\\u201cWell, Fanny,\\u201dsaid she, as soon as they were alone together afterwards, and she really had known something like impatience to be alone with her, and her countenance, as she spoke, had extraordinary animation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133215,\n            \"\\u201cWell, Fanny, I have had a very agreeable surprise this morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133420,\n            \"And you must be aware, Fanny, that it is every young woman\\u2019s duty to accept such a very unexceptionable offer as this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133447,\n            \"\\u201d This was almost the only rule of conduct, the only piece of advice, which Fanny had ever received from her aunt in the course of eight years and a half.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133518,\n            \"\\u201cI will tell you what, Fanny,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cI am sure he fell in love with you at the ball;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133607,\n            \"\\u201d And still pursuing the same cheerful thoughts, she soon afterwards added, \\u201cAnd I will tell you what, Fanny, which is more than I did for Maria: the next time Pug has a litter you shall have a puppy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133952,\n            \"After dinner, when he and his father were alone, he had Fanny\\u2019s history;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134388,\n            \"Meanwhile, he saw enough of Fanny\\u2019s embarrassment to make him scrupulously guard against exciting it a second time, by any word, or look, or movement.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134457,\n            \"He staid of course, and Edmund had then ample opportunity for observing how he sped with Fanny, and what degree of immediate encouragement for him might be extracted from her manners;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134655,\n            \"When he and Crawford walked into the drawing-room, his mother and Fanny were sitting as intently and silently at work as if there were nothing else to care for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134714,\n            \"\\u201cFanny has been reading to me, and only put the book down upon hearing you coming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134759,\n            \"\\u201cShe often reads to me out of those books;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134770,\n            \"and she was in the middle of a very fine speech of that man\\u2019s \\u2014 what\\u2019s his name, Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134949,\n            \"his reading was capital, and her pleasure in good reading extreme.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134962,\n            \"To _ good _ reading, however, she had been long used: her uncle read well, her cousins all, Edmund very well, but in Mr. Crawford\\u2019s reading there was a variety of excellence beyond what she had ever met with.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135096,\n            \"His acting had first taught Fanny what pleasure a play might give, and his reading brought all his acting before her again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135120,\n            \"nay, perhaps with greater enjoyment, for it came unexpectedly, and with no such drawback as she had been used to suffer in seeing him on the stage with Miss Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135154,\n            \"Edmund watched the progress of her attention, and was amused and gratified by seeing how she gradually slackened in the needlework, which at the beginning seemed to occupy her totally: how it fell from her hand while she sat motionless over it, and at last, how the eyes which had appeared so studiously to avoid him throughout the day were turned and fixed on Crawford \\u2014 fixed on him for minutes, fixed on him, in short, till the attraction drew Crawford\\u2019s upon her, and the book was closed, and the charm was broken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135277,\n            \"but it had been enough to give Edmund encouragement for his friend, and as he cordially thanked him, he hoped to be expressing Fanny\\u2019s secret feelings too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135597,\n            \"Both gentlemen had a glance at Fanny, to see if a word of accordant praise could be extorted from her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136277,\n            \"questions, which being made, though with the vivacity of friendly interest and quick taste, without any touch of that spirit of banter or air of levity which Edmund knew to be most offensive to Fanny, he had true pleasure in satisfying;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136479,\n            \"For myself, at least, I must confess being not always so attentive as I ought to be\\u201d(here was a glance at Fanny);\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136554,\n            \"and upon her saying \\u201cNo,\\u201dhe added, \\u201cAre you sure you did not speak?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136574,\n            \"I saw your lips move.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136580,\n            \"I fancied you might be going to tell me I ought to be more attentive, and not _ allow _ my thoughts to wander.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136606,\n            \"Are not you going to tell me so?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136995,\n            \"\\u201d Here Fanny, who could not but listen, involuntarily shook her head, and Crawford was instantly by her side again, entreating to know her meaning;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137025,\n            \"and as Edmund perceived, by his drawing in a chair, and sitting down close by her, that it was to be a very thorough attack, that looks and undertones were to be well tried, he sank as quietly as possible into a corner, turned his back, and took up a newspaper, very sincerely wishing that dear little Fanny might be persuaded into explaining away that shake of the head to the satisfaction of her ardent lover;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137160,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny, meanwhile, vexed with herself for not having been as motionless as she was speechless, and grieved to the heart to see Edmund\\u2019s arrangements, was trying by everything in the power of her modest, gentle nature, to repulse Mr. Crawford, and avoid both his looks and inquiries;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137577,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cPerhaps, sir,\\u201dsaid Fanny, wearied at last into speaking \\u2014 \\u201cperhaps, sir, I thought it was a pity you did not always know yourself as well as you seemed to do at that moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137641,\n            \"and poor Fanny, who had hoped to silence him by such an extremity of reproof, found herself sadly mistaken, and that it was only a change from one object of curiosity and one set of words to another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137782,\n            \"\\u201cI am happier than I was, because I now understand more clearly your opinion of me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137801,\n            \"You think me unsteady: easily swayed by the whim of the moment, easily tempted, easily put aside.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137836,\n            \"\\u2014 It is not by protestations that I shall endeavour to convince you I am wronged;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137853,\n            \"it is not by telling you that my affections are steady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137882,\n            \"_ They _ shall prove that, as far as you can be deserved by anybody, I do deserve you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137904,\n            \"You are infinitely my superior in merit;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137919,\n            \"You have qualities which I had not before supposed to exist in such a degree in any human creature.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138001,\n            \"It is he who sees and worships your merit the strongest, who loves you most devotedly, that has the best right to a return.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138034,\n            \"By that right I do and will deserve you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138044,\n            \"and when once convinced that my attachment is what I declare it, I know you too well not to entertain the warmest hopes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138076,\n            \"Nay\\u201d(seeing her draw back displeased), \\u201cforgive me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138098,\n            \"but by what other name can I call you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138108,\n            \"Do you suppose you are ever present to my imagination under any other?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138224,\n            \"The solemn procession, headed by Baddeley, of tea-board, urn, and cake-bearers, made its appearance, and delivered her from a grievous imprisonment of body and mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138300,\n            \"But though the conference had seemed full long to him, and though on looking at Fanny he saw rather a flush of vexation, he inclined to hope that so much could not have been said and listened to without some profit to the speaker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138347,\n            \"CHAPTER XXXV Edmund had determined that it belonged entirely to Fanny to chuse whether her situation with regard to Crawford should be mentioned between them or not;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138722,\n            \"\\u201cI am come to walk with you, Fanny,\\u201dsaid he.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138839,\n            \"Am I to hear of it from everybody but Fanny herself?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138851,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny, at once agitated and dejected, replied, \\u201cIf you hear of it from everybody, cousin, there can be nothing for me to tell.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139095,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThis comfort you might have had sooner, Fanny, had you sought it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139175,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAs far as you have gone, Fanny, I think you perfectly right.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139650,\n            \"I wish he had known you as well as I do, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139767,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWe are so totally unlike,\\u201dsaid Fanny, avoiding a direct answer, \\u201cwe are so very, very different in all our inclinations and ways, that I consider it as quite impossible we should ever be tolerably happy together, even if I _ could _ like him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139844,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou are mistaken, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139891,\n            \"and, Fanny, who that heard him read, and saw you listen to Shakespeare the other night, will think you unfitted as companions?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139918,\n            \"You forget yourself: there is a decided difference in your tempers, I allow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139995,\n            \"Your being so far unlike, Fanny, does not in the smallest degree make against the probability of your happiness together: do not imagine it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140145,\n            \"\\u201d Full well could Fanny guess where his thoughts were now: Miss Crawford\\u2019s power was all returning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140201,\n            \"After leaving him to his happier thoughts for some minutes, Fanny, feeling it due to herself, returned to Mr. Crawford, and said, \\u201cIt is not merely in _ temper _ that I consider him as totally unsuited to myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140489,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAs a bystander,\\u201dsaid Fanny, \\u201cperhaps I saw more than you did;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140622,\n            \"And, Fanny, though I hope I do justice to my sisters\\u2019 good qualities, I think it very possible that they might, one or both, be more desirous of being admired by Crawford, and might shew that desire rather more unguardedly than was perfectly prudent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141005,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI would not engage in such a charge,\\u201dcried Fanny, in a shrinking accent;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141201,\n            \"but yet I was afraid of her not estimating your worth to her brother quite as it deserved, and of her regretting that he had not rather fixed on some woman of distinction or fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141394,\n            \"and when once we had begun, we had not done with you, Fanny, till Crawford and Dr. Grant came in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141551,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy dearest Fanny,\\u201dcried Edmund, pressing her arm closer to him, \\u201cdo not let the idea of her anger distress you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141638,\n            \"And I observed that she always spoke of you as \\u2018 Fanny,\\u2019which she was never used to do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141704,\n            \"The surprise of your refusal, Fanny, seems to have been unbounded.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141796,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI _ should _ have thought,\\u201dsaid Fanny, after a pause of recollection and exertion, \\u201cthat every woman must have felt the possibility of a man\\u2019s not being approved, not being loved by some one of her sex at least, let him be ever so generally agreeable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142834,\n            \"CHAPTER XXXVI Edmund now believed himself perfectly acquainted with all that Fanny could tell, or could leave to be conjectured of her sentiments, and he was satisfied.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142990,\n            \"Edmund\\u2019s account of Fanny\\u2019s disposition he could believe to be just;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143103,\n            \"The promised visit from \\u201cher friend,\\u201das Edmund called Miss Crawford, was a formidable threat to Fanny, and she lived in continual terror of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143188,\n            \"and the dependence of having others present when they met was Fanny\\u2019s only support in looking forward to it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143268,\n            \"and the first misery over, and Miss Crawford looking and speaking with much less particularity of expression than she had anticipated, Fanny began to hope there would be nothing worse to be endured than a half-hour of moderate agitation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143362,\n            \"words that Fanny felt all over her, in all her pulses and all her nerves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143440,\n            \"She immediately shook her head at Fanny with arch, yet affectionate reproach, and taking her hand, seemed hardly able to help beginning directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143982,\n            \"Yet, Fanny, do not imagine I would now speak disrespectfully of Sir Thomas, though I certainly did hate him for many a week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144128,\n            \"for as to scolding you, Fanny, which I came fully intending to do, I have not the heart for it when it comes to the point.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144158,\n            \"\\u201d And embracing her very affectionately, \\u201cGood, gentle Fanny!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144704,\n            \"\\u201cWhy, Fanny, you are absolutely in a reverie.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145208,\n            \"I shall be at Mansfield for ever, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145357,\n            \"I have not so much to say for my friend Flora, who jilted a very nice young man in the Blues for the sake of that horrid Lord Stornaway, who has about as much sense, Fanny, as Mr. Rushworth, but much worse-looking, and with a blackguard character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145465,\n            \"But were I to attempt to tell you of all the women whom I have known to be in love with him, I should never have done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145494,\n            \"It is you, only you, insensible Fanny, who can think of him with anything like indifference.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145524,\n            \"No, no, I see you are not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145566,\n            \"I will not tease you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145578,\n            \"But, dear Fanny, you must allow that you were not so absolutely unprepared to have the question asked as your cousin fancies.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145627,\n            \"You must have seen that he was trying to please you by every attention in his power.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145645,\n            \"Was not he devoted to you at the ball?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145689,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo you mean, then, that your brother knew of the necklace beforehand?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145762,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI will not say,\\u201dreplied Fanny, \\u201cthat I was not half afraid at the time of its being so, for there was something in your look that frightened me, but not at first;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146152,\n            \"I leave him entirely to your mercy, and when he has got you at Everingham, I do not care how much you lecture him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146229,\n            \"And I do seriously and truly believe that he is attached to you in a way that he never was to any woman before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146254,\n            \"that he loves you with all his heart, and will love you as nearly for ever as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146274,\n            \"If any man ever loved a woman for ever, I think Henry will do as much for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146487,\n            \"and she sat thinking deeply of it till Mary, who had been first watching her complacently, and then musing on something else, suddenly called her attention by saying: \\u201cI should like to sit talking with you here all day, but we must not forget the ladies below, and so good-bye, my dear, my amiable, my excellent Fanny, for though we shall nominally part in the breakfast-parlour, I must take leave of you here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146695,\n            \"I have two favours to ask, Fanny: one is your correspondence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146951,\n            \"He was evidently oppressed, and Fanny must grieve for him, though hoping she might never see him again till he were the husband of some other woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147064,\n            \"and he entertained great hope that his niece would find a blank in the loss of those attentions which at the time she had felt, or fancied, an evil.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147248,\n            \"What chiefly surprised Edmund was, that Crawford\\u2019s sister, the friend and companion who had been so much to her, should not be more visibly regretted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147279,\n            \"He wondered that Fanny spoke so seldom of _ her _, and had so little voluntarily to say of her concern at this separation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147650,\n            \"Fanny believed there was scarcely a second feeling in common between them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147780,\n            \"But as such were Fanny\\u2019s persuasions, she suffered very much from them, and could never speak of Miss Crawford without pain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148064,\n            \"So reasoned Edmund, till his father made him the confidant of a scheme which placed Fanny\\u2019s chance of seeing the second lieutenant of H.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148194,\n            \"and he had no doubt of it being highly agreeable to Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148458,\n            \"Had Fanny been at all addicted to raptures, she must have had a strong attack of them when she first understood what was intended, when her uncle first made her the offer of visiting the parents, and brothers, and sisters, from whom she had been divided almost half her life;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149013,\n            \"and now by dint of long talking on the subject, explaining and dwelling on the duty of Fanny\\u2019s sometimes seeing her family, he did induce his wife to let her go;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149049,\n            \"obtaining it rather from submission, however, than conviction, for Lady Bertram was convinced of very little more than that Sir Thomas thought Fanny ought to go, and therefore that she must.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149085,\n            \"In the calmness of her own dressing-room, in the impartial flow of her own meditations, unbiassed by his bewildering statements, she could not acknowledge any necessity for Fanny\\u2019s ever going near a father and mother who had done without her so long, while she was so useful to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149741,\n            \"and for part of one of those days the young travellers were in a good deal of alarm on the subject of their journey, for when the mode of it came to be talked of, and Mrs. Norris found that all her anxiety to save her brother-in-law\\u2019s money was vain, and that in spite of her wishes and hints for a less expensive conveyance of Fanny, they were to travel post;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150315,\n            \"and Fanny was the more affected from feeling it to be the last time in which Miss Crawford\\u2019s name would ever be mentioned between them with any remains of liberty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150384,\n            \"and Edmund, at a convenient moment, then added in a whisper, \\u201cAnd _ I _ shall write to you, Fanny, when I have anything worth writing about, anything to say that I think you will like to hear, and that you will not hear so soon from any other quarter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150683,\n            \"and when the small, diminished party met at breakfast, William and Fanny were talked of as already advanced one stage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150795,\n            \"Everything supplied an amusement to the high glee of William\\u2019s mind, and he was full of frolic and joke in the intervals of their higher-toned subjects, all of which ended, if they did not begin, in praise of the Thrush, conjectures how she would be employed, schemes for an action with some superior force, which (supposing the first lieutenant out of the way, and William was not very merciful to the first lieutenant) was to give himself the next step as soon as possible, or speculations upon prize-money, which was to be generously distributed at home, with only the reservation of enough to make the little cottage comfortable, in which he and Fanny were to pass all their middle and later life together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150939,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s immediate concerns, as far as they involved Mr. Crawford, made no part of their conversation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151085,\n            \"It was a correspondence which Fanny found quite as unpleasant as she had feared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151170,\n            \"There had, in fact, been so much of message, of allusion, of recollection, so much of Mansfield in every letter, that Fanny could not but suppose it meant for him to hear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151307,\n            \"With such thoughts as these, among ten hundred others, Fanny proceeded in her journey safely and cheerfully, and as expeditiously as could rationally be hoped in the dirty month of February.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151406,\n            \"and with no events, and no delays, they regularly advanced, and were in the environs of Portsmouth while there was yet daylight for Fanny to look around her, and wonder at the new buildings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151719,\n            \"\\u201d A stare or two at Fanny, as William helped her out of the carriage, was all the voluntary notice which this brother bestowed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151798,\n            \"Another moment and Fanny was in the narrow entrance-passage of the house, and in her mother\\u2019s arms, who met her there with looks of true kindness, and with features which Fanny loved the more, because they brought her aunt Bertram\\u2019s before her, and there were her two sisters: Susan, a well-grown fine girl of fourteen, and Betsey, the youngest of the family, about five \\u2014 both glad to see her in their way, though with no advantage of manner in receiving her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152256,\n            \"here\\u2019s Fanny in the parlour, and why should we stay in the passage?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152273,\n            \"Come, mother, you have hardly looked at your own dear Fanny yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153252,\n            \"\\u201d With an acknowledgment that he had quite forgot her, Mr. Price now received his daughter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153271,\n            \"and having given her a cordial hug, and observed that she was grown into a woman, and he supposed would be wanting a husband soon, seemed very much inclined to forget her again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153328,\n            \"and he talked on only to his son, and only of the Thrush, though William, warmly interested as he was in that subject, more than once tried to make his father think of Fanny, and her long absence and long journey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153501,\n            \"Charles had been born since Fanny\\u2019s going away, but Tom she had often helped to nurse, and now felt a particular pleasure in seeing again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154361,\n            \"\\u201d This threat was so palpably disregarded, that though within five minutes afterwards the three boys all burst into the room together and sat down, Fanny could not consider it as a proof of anything more than their being for the time thoroughly fagged, which their hot faces and panting breaths seemed to prove, especially as they were still kicking each other\\u2019s shins, and hallooing out at sudden starts immediately under their father\\u2019s eye.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154476,\n            \"Susan and an attendant girl, whose inferior appearance informed Fanny, to her great surprise, that she had previously seen the upper servant, brought in everything necessary for the meal;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154679,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s spirit was as much refreshed as her body;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154714,\n            \"she was like William, and Fanny hoped to find her like him in disposition and goodwill towards herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154754,\n            \"He, complete in his lieutenant\\u2019s uniform, looking and moving all the taller, firmer, and more graceful for it, and with the happiest smile over his face, walked up directly to Fanny, who, rising from her seat, looked at him for a moment in speechless admiration, and then threw her arms round his neck to sob out her various emotions of pain and pleasure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155240,\n            \"The Bertrams were all forgotten in detailing the faults of Rebecca, against whom Susan had also much to depose, and little Betsey a great deal more, and who did seem so thoroughly without a single recommendation, that Fanny could not help modestly presuming that her mother meant to part with her when her year was up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155660,\n            \"but the child ran to her mother\\u2019s protection, and Susan could only reproach, which she did very warmly, and evidently hoping to interest Fanny on her side.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155995,\n            \"she was so fond of it, Fanny, that she would have it lay by her in bed, all through her illness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156099,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny had indeed nothing to convey from aunt Norris, but a message to say she hoped that her god-daughter was a good girl, and learnt her book.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156709,\n            \"\\u201d William was gone: and the home he had left her in was, Fanny could not conceal it from herself, in almost every respect the very reverse of what she could have wished.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157455,\n            \"Fanny was very anxious to be useful, and not to appear above her home, or in any way disqualified or disinclined, by her foreign education, from contributing her help to its comforts, and therefore set about working for Sam immediately;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157816,\n            \"Her continual disagreements with her mother, her rash squabbles with Tom and Charles, and petulance with Betsey, were at least so distressing to Fanny that, though admitting they were by no means without provocation, she feared the disposition that could push them to such length must be far from amiable, and from affording any repose to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158219,\n            \"In a review of the two houses, as they appeared to her before the end of a week, Fanny was tempted to apply to them Dr. Johnson\\u2019s celebrated judgment as to matrimony and celibacy, and say, that though Mansfield Park might have some pains, Portsmouth could have no pleasures.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158277,\n            \"CHAPTER XL Fanny was right enough in not expecting to hear from Miss Crawford now at the rapid rate in which their correspondence had begun;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158516,\n            \"But there he is, and, by the bye, his absence may sufficiently account for any remissness of his sister\\u2019s in writing, for there has been no \\u2018 Well, Mary, when do you write to Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158712,\n            \"There was no recovering the complexion from the moment that I spoke of \\u2018 Fanny,\\u2019and spoke of her as a sister should.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159031,\n            \"my dear sweet Fanny, this is a long letter from London: write me a pretty one in reply to gladden Henry\\u2019s eyes, when he comes back, and send me an account of all the dashing young captains whom you disdain for his sake.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159319,\n            \"The first solid consolation which Fanny received for the evils of home, the first which her judgment could entirely approve, and which gave any promise of durability, was in a better knowledge of Susan, and a hope of being of service to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159737,\n            \"and new as anything like an office of authority was to Fanny, new as it was to imagine herself capable of guiding or informing any one, she did resolve to give occasional hints to Susan, and endeavour to exercise for her advantage the juster notions of what was due to everybody, and what would be wisest for herself, which her own more favoured education had fixed in her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160054,\n            \"and no reproach seemed conveyed to the equally satisfied mother, which Fanny had almost feared to be impossible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160198,\n            \"and from that hour Fanny, understanding the worth of her disposition and perceiving how fully she was inclined to seek her good opinion and refer to her judgment, began to feel again the blessing of affection, and to entertain the hope of being useful to a mind so much in need of help, and so much deserving it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160553,\n            \"By degrees the girls came to spend the chief of the morning upstairs, at first only in working and talking, but after a few days, the remembrance of the said books grew so potent and stimulative that Fanny found it impossible not to try for books again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160687,\n            \"Susan had read nothing, and Fanny longed to give her a share in her own first pleasures, and inspire a taste for the biography and poetry which she delighted in herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160930,\n            \"One morning, about this time, Fanny having now been nearly four weeks from Mansfield, a point which she never failed to think over and calculate every day, as she and Susan were preparing to remove, as usual, upstairs, they were stopped by the knock of a visitor, whom they felt they could not avoid, from Rebecca\\u2019s alertness in going to the door, a duty which always interested her beyond any other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161022,\n            \"it was a voice that Fanny was just turning pale about, when Mr. Crawford walked into the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161311,\n            \"Fanny was just recovered enough to feel that _ she _ could not regret it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161351,\n            \"She might scold herself for the weakness, but there was no scolding it away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161570,\n            \"By the time he had given all this information, it was not unreasonable to suppose that Fanny might be looked at and spoken to;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162248,\n            \"but (as Fanny instantly, and to her great relief, discerned) her father was a very different man, a very different Mr. Price in his behaviour to this most highly respected stranger, from what he was in his own family at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162386,\n            \"The conclusion of the two gentlemen\\u2019s civilities was an offer of Mr. Price\\u2019s to take Mr. Crawford into the dockyard, which Mr. Crawford, desirous of accepting as a favour what was intended as such, though he had seen the dockyard again and again, and hoping to be so much the longer with Fanny, was very gratefully disposed to avail himself of, if the Miss Prices were not afraid of the fatigue;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162559,\n            \"and it did not delay them long, for Fanny could so little bear to excite impatience, or be waited for, that before the gentlemen, as they stood at the door, could do more than begin upon the last naval regulations, or settle the number of three-deckers now in commission, their companions were ready to proceed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162785,\n            \"Once fairly in the dockyard, he began to reckon upon some happy intercourse with Fanny, as they were very soon joined by a brother lounger of Mr. Price\\u2019s, who was come to take his daily survey of how things went on, and who must prove a far more worthy companion than himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162977,\n            \"He must content himself with being only generally agreeable, and letting Susan have her share of entertainment, with the indulgence, now and then, of a look or hint for the better-informed and conscious Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163087,\n            \"For Fanny, somewhat more was related than the accidental agreeableness of the parties he had been in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163342,\n            \"and she was on the point of giving him an approving look, when it was all frightened off by his adding a something too pointed of his hoping soon to have an assistant, a friend, a guide in every plan of utility or charity for Everingham: a somebody that would make Everingham and all about it a dearer object than it had ever been yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163412,\n            \"She turned away, and wished he would not say such things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163425,\n            \"She was willing to allow he might have more good qualities than she had been wont to suppose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163444,\n            \"She began to feel the possibility of his turning out well at last;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163458,\n            \"but he was and must ever be completely unsuited to her, and ought not to think of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163543,\n            \"Now so long divided from everybody who knew the place, she felt it quite the voice of a friend when he mentioned it, and led the way to her fond exclamations in praise of its beauties and comforts, and by his honourable tribute to its inhabitants allowed her to gratify her own heart in the warmest eulogium, in speaking of her uncle as all that was clever and good, and her aunt as having the sweetest of all sweet tempers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163812,\n            \"though when the moment was passed, could regret that she had not forced herself into the acknowledged comprehension of one half of his meaning, and encouraged him to say something more of his sister and Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163902,\n            \"and in the course of their walk back, Mr. Crawford contrived a minute\\u2019s privacy for telling Fanny that his only business in Portsmouth was to see her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163970,\n            \"and yet in spite of this and the two or three other things which she wished he had not said, she thought him altogether improved since she had seen him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164026,\n            \"she had never seen him so agreeable \\u2014 so _ near _ being agreeable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164071,\n            \"She wished the next day over, she wished he had come only for one day;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164112,\n            \"Before they parted, she had to thank him for another pleasure, and one of no trivial kind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164132,\n            \"Her father asked him to do them the honour of taking his mutton with them, and Fanny had time for only one thrill of horror, before he declared himself prevented by a prior engagement.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164217,\n            \", and so they parted \\u2014 Fanny in a state of actual felicity from escaping so horrible an evil!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164259,\n            \"Rebecca\\u2019s cookery and Rebecca\\u2019s waiting, and Betsey\\u2019s eating at table without restraint, and pulling everything about as she chose, were what Fanny herself was not yet enough inured to for her often to make a tolerable meal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164482,\n            \"to think that where nature had made so little difference, circumstances should have made so much, and that her mother, as handsome as Lady Bertram, and some years her junior, should have an appearance so much more worn and faded, so comfortless, so slatternly, so shabby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164724,\n            \"and before they had been there long, somehow or other, there was no saying how, Fanny could not have believed it, but he was walking between them with an arm of each under his, and she did not know how to prevent or put an end to it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164923,\n            \"Nay, had she been without his arm, she would soon have known that she needed it, for she wanted strength for a two hours\\u2019 saunter of this kind, coming, as it generally did, upon a week\\u2019s previous inactivity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165020,\n            \"The loveliness of the day, and of the view, he felt like herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165059,\n            \"and considering he was not Edmund, Fanny could not but allow that he was sufficiently open to the charms of nature, and very well able to express his admiration.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165091,\n            \"She had a few tender reveries now and then, which he could sometimes take advantage of to look in her face without detection;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165160,\n            \"but take it all in all, he was convinced that her present residence could not be comfortable, and therefore could not be salutary for her, and he was growing anxious for her being again at Mansfield, where her own happiness, and his in seeing her, must be so much greater.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165590,\n            \"If, therefore\\u201d(turning again to Fanny), \\u201cyou find yourself growing unwell, and any difficulties arise about your returning to Mansfield, without waiting for the two months to be ended, _ that _ must not be regarded as of any consequence, if you feel yourself at all less strong or comfortable than usual, and will only let my sister know it, give her only the slightest hint, she and I will immediately come down, and take you back to Mansfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165709,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny thanked him, but tried to laugh it off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165721,\n            \"\\u201cI am perfectly serious,\\u201dhe replied, \\u201cas you perfectly know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165737,\n            \"And I hope you will not be cruelly concealing any tendency to indisposition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165767,\n            \"for so long only as you positively say, in every letter to Mary, \\u2018 I am well,\\u2019and I know you cannot speak or write a falsehood, so long only shall you be considered as well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165809,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny thanked him again, but was affected and distressed to a degree that made it impossible for her to say much, or even to be certain of what she ought to say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165892,\n            \"\\u201cI wish you were not so tired,\\u201dsaid he, still detaining Fanny after all the others were in the house \\u2014 \\u201cI wish I left you in stronger health.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166379,\n            \"\\u201d He could say no more, for Fanny would be no longer detained.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166407,\n            \"_ He _ went to while away the next three hours as he could, with his other acquaintance, till the best dinner that a capital inn afforded was ready for their enjoyment, and _ she _ turned in to her more simple one immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166990,\n            \"and two days afterwards, it was a fact ascertained to Fanny by the following letter from his sister, opened and read by her, on another account, with the most anxious curiosity: \\u2014 \\u201cI have to inform you, my dearest Fanny, that Henry has been down to Portsmouth to see you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168716,\n            \"What Fanny told her of former times dwelt more on her mind than the pages of Goldsmith;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168821,\n            \"Susan, who had an innate taste for the genteel and well-appointed, was eager to hear, and Fanny could not but indulge herself in dwelling on so beloved a theme.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168923,\n            \"and as Fanny grew thoroughly to understand this, she began to feel that when her own release from Portsmouth came, her happiness would have a material drawback in leaving Susan behind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169770,\n            \"I cannot give her up, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170087,\n            \"The loss of Mary I must consider as comprehending the loss of Crawford and of Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170416,\n            \"This long letter, full of my own concerns alone, will be enough to tire even the friendship of a Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170656,\n            \"I miss you more than I can express.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170665,\n            \"My mother desires her best love, and hopes to hear from you soon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170680,\n            \"She talks of you almost every hour, and I am sorry to find how many weeks more she is likely to be without you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170706,\n            \"My father means to fetch you himself, but it will not be till after Easter, when he has business in town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170730,\n            \"You are happy at Portsmouth, I hope, but this must not be a yearly visit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170748,\n            \"I want you at home, that I may have your opinion about Thornton Lacey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170917,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny checked the tendency of these thoughts as well as she could, but she was within half a minute of starting the idea that Sir Thomas was quite unkind, both to her aunt and to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171637,\n            \"Within a few days from the receipt of Edmund\\u2019s letter, Fanny had one from her aunt, beginning thus \\u2014 \\u201cMy Dear Fanny, \\u2014 I take up my pen to communicate some very alarming intelligence, which I make no doubt will give you much concern \\u201d.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171884,\n            \"\\u201cThis distressing intelligence, as you may suppose,\\u201dobserved her ladyship, after giving the substance of it, \\u201chas agitated us exceedingly, and we cannot prevent ourselves from being greatly alarmed and apprehensive for the poor invalid, whose state Sir Thomas fears may be very critical;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172054,\n            \"As I have little doubt of your feeling for us, my dear Fanny, under these distressing circumstances, I will write again very soon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172081,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny\\u2019s feelings on the occasion were indeed considerably more warm and genuine than her aunt\\u2019s style of writing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172196,\n            \"they were receiving frequent accounts from Edmund, and these accounts were as regularly transmitted to Fanny, in the same diffuse style, and the same medley of trusts, hopes, and fears, all following and producing each other at haphazard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172398,\n            \"and how glad I should be if you were here to comfort me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172948,\n            \"Lady Bertram could think nothing less, and Fanny shared her aunt\\u2019s security, till she received a few lines from Edmund, written purposely to give her a clearer idea of his brother\\u2019s situation, and acquaint her with the apprehensions which he and his father had imbibed from the physician with respect to some strong hectic symptoms, which seemed to seize the frame on the departure of the fever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173206,\n            \"Fanny would certainly believe him so at least, and must find that her estimation of him was higher than ever when he appeared as the attendant, supporter, cheerer of a suffering brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173441,\n            \"A line occasionally added by Edmund to his mother\\u2019s letter was enough for Fanny\\u2019s information.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173526,\n            \"Her aunt often expressed a wish for her, but there was no notice, no message from the uncle on whom all depended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173551,\n            \"She supposed he could not yet leave his son, but it was a cruel, a terrible delay to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173581,\n            \"it would soon be almost three months, instead of two, that she had been absent from them all, and that her days had been passing in a state of penance, which she loved them too well to hope they would thoroughly understand;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173645,\n            \"Her eagerness, her impatience, her longings to be with them, were such as to bring a line or two of Cowper\\u2019s Tirocinium for ever before her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173783,\n            \"They had been long so arranged in the indulgence of her secret meditations, and nothing was more consolatory to her than to find her aunt using the same language: \\u201cI cannot but say I much regret your being from home at this distressing time, so very trying to my spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173838,\n            \"I trust and hope, and sincerely wish you may never be absent from home so long again,\\u201dwere most delightful sentences to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173875,\n            \"Delicacy to her parents made her careful not to betray such a preference of her uncle\\u2019s house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173961,\n            \"She reproached herself, coloured, and looked fearfully towards her father and mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174071,\n            \"What animation, both of body and mind, she had derived from watching the advance of that season which cannot, in spite of its capriciousness, be unlovely, and seeing its increasing beauties from the earliest flowers in the warmest divisions of her aunt\\u2019s garden, to the opening of leaves of her uncle\\u2019s plantations, and the glory of his woods.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174150,\n            \"to be losing them, because she was in the midst of closeness and noise, to have confinement, bad air, bad smells, substituted for liberty, freshness, fragrance, and verdure, was infinitely worse: but even these incitements to regret were feeble, compared with what arose from the conviction of being missed by her best friends, and the longing to be useful to those who were wanting her!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174593,\n            \"It was so long since Fanny had had any letter from her, that she had some reason to think lightly of the friendship which had been so dwelt on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175009,\n            \"Fanny, Fanny, I see you smile and look cunning, but, upon my honour, I never bribed a physician in my life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175131,\n            \"With real affection, Fanny, like mine, more might be overlooked.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175833,\n            \"To be finding herself, perhaps within three days, transported to Mansfield, was an image of the greatest felicity, but it would have been a material drawback to be owing such felicity to persons in whose feelings and conduct, at the present moment, she saw so much to condemn: the sister\\u2019s feelings, the brother\\u2019s conduct, _ her _ cold-hearted ambition, _ his _ thoughtless vanity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175992,\n            \"Her awe of her uncle, and her dread of taking a liberty with him, made it instantly plain to her what she had to do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176027,\n            \"If he wanted, he would send for her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176067,\n            \"\\u201cHer uncle, she understood, meant to fetch her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176079,\n            \"and as her cousin\\u2019s illness had continued so many weeks without her being thought at all necessary, she must suppose her return would be unwelcome at present, and that she should be felt an encumbrance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176119,\n            \"\\u201d Her representation of her cousin\\u2019s state at this time was exactly according to her own belief of it, and such as she supposed would convey to the sanguine mind of her correspondent the hope of everything she was wishing for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176182,\n            \"and this, she suspected, was all the conquest of prejudice which he was so ready to congratulate himself upon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176312,\n            \"and two moments were enough to start the probability of its being merely to give her notice that they should be in Portsmouth that very day, and to throw her into all the agitation of doubting what she ought to do in such a case.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176376,\n            \"and before she had opened the letter, the possibility of Mr. and Miss Crawford\\u2019s having applied to her uncle and obtained his permission was giving her ease.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177270,\n            \"and Fanny was first roused by his calling out to her, after humphing and considering over a particular paragraph: \\u201cWhat\\u2019s the name of your great cousins in town, Fan?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177584,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt is a mistake, sir,\\u201dsaid Fanny instantly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178038,\n            \"Fanny seemed to herself never to have been shocked before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178605,\n            \"\\u201cDear Fanny, \\u2014 You know our present wretchedness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179462,\n            \"The girls heard his entrance from above, and Fanny went down.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179529,\n            \"and she found herself pressed to his heart with only these words, just articulate, \\u201cMy Fanny, my only sister;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179687,\n            \"Fanny answered for their having breakfasted and being quite ready in half an hour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179860,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s last meal in her father\\u2019s house was in character with her first: she was dismissed from it as hospitably as she had been welcomed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180001,\n            \"Fanny watched him with never-failing solicitude, and sometimes catching his eye, revived an affectionate smile, which comforted her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180182,\n            \"But _ yours _ \\u2014 your regard was new compared with \\u2014 \\u2014 Fanny, think of _ me _!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180269,\n            \"Fanny began to dread the meeting with her aunts and Tom, under so dreadful a humiliation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180583,\n            \"Fanny had scarcely passed the solemn-looking servants, when Lady Bertram came from the drawing-room to meet her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180911,\n            \"Had Fanny accepted Mr. Crawford this could not have happened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181293,\n            \"and she saw, therefore, in all its enormity, what had happened, and neither endeavoured herself, nor required Fanny to advise her, to think little of guilt and infamy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181404,\n            \"Fanny learnt from her all the particulars which had yet transpired.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181416,\n            \"Her aunt was no very methodical narrator, but with the help of some letters to and from Sir Thomas, and what she already knew herself, and could reasonably combine, she was soon able to understand quite as much as she wished of the circumstances attending the story.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181537,\n            \"Mr. Rushworth had been gone at this time to Bath, to pass a few days with his mother, and bring her back to town, and Maria was with these friends without any restraint, without even Julia;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182414,\n            \"Fanny felt for him most acutely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182439,\n            \"His displeasure against herself she trusted, reasoning differently from Mrs. Norris, would now be done away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182466,\n            \"Mr. Crawford would have fully acquitted her conduct in refusing him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182496,\n            \"Her uncle\\u2019s displeasure was terrible to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182506,\n            \"but what could her justification or her gratitude and attachment do for him?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182528,\n            \"She was mistaken, however, in supposing that Edmund gave his father no present pain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182659,\n            \"and, having reason to think that one interview with Miss Crawford had taken place, from which Edmund derived only increased distress, had been as anxious on that account as on others to get him out of town, and had engaged him in taking Fanny home to her aunt, with a view to his relief and benefit, no less than theirs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182726,\n            \"Fanny was not in the secret of her uncle\\u2019s feelings, Sir Thomas not in the secret of Miss Crawford\\u2019s character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182752,\n            \"Had he been privy to her conversation with his son, he would not have wished her to belong to him, though her twenty thousand pounds had been forty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182802,\n            \"and yet, till she knew that he felt the same, her own conviction was insufficient.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182820,\n            \"She thought he did, but she wanted to be assured of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182834,\n            \"If he would now speak to her with the unreserve which had sometimes been too much for her before, it would be most consoling;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182871,\n            \"She seldom saw him: never alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182879,\n            \"He probably avoided being alone with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182947,\n            \"Long, long would it be ere Miss Crawford\\u2019s name passed his lips again, or she could hope for a renewal of such confidential intercourse as had been.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182985,\n            \"They reached Mansfield on Thursday, and it was not till Sunday evening that Edmund began to talk to her on the subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183009,\n            \"Sitting with her on Sunday evening \\u2014 a wet Sunday evening \\u2014 the very time of all others when, if a friend is at hand, the heart must be opened, and everything told;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183078,\n            \"and so, with the usual beginnings, hardly to be traced as to what came first, and the usual declaration that if she would listen to him for a few minutes, he should be very brief, and certainly never tax her kindness in the same way again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183173,\n            \"How Fanny listened, with what curiosity and concern, what pain and what delight, how the agitation of his voice was watched, and how carefully her own eyes were fixed on any object but himself, may be imagined.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183249,\n            \"and regarding it as what was meant to be the last, last interview of friendship, and investing her with all the feelings of shame and wretchedness which Crawford\\u2019s sister ought to have known, he had gone to her in such a state of mind, so softened, so devoted, as made it for a few moments impossible to Fanny\\u2019s fears that it should be the last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183325,\n            \"But as he proceeded in his story, these fears were over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183472,\n            \"\\u2019 So she began, but how she went on, Fanny, is not fit, is hardly fit to be repeated to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183655,\n            \"For where, Fanny, shall we find a woman whom nature had so richly endowed?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183812,\n            \"\\u201cAnd what,\\u201dsaid Fanny (believing herself required to speak), \\u201cwhat could you say?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184355,\n            \"Hers are faults of principle, Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184481,\n            \"She spoke of it, Fanny, with a steadier voice than I can.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184555,\n            \"I do not think that even _ he _ could now hope to succeed with one of her stamp, and therefore I hope we may find no insuperable difficulty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184599,\n            \"and when once married, and properly supported by her own family, people of respectability as they are, she may recover her footing in society to a certain degree.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184631,\n            \"In some circles, we know, she would never be admitted, but with good dinners, and large parties, there will always be those who will be glad of her acquaintance;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184713,\n            \"If by any officious exertions of his, she is induced to leave Henry\\u2019s protection, there will be much less chance of his marrying her than if she remain with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184775,\n            \"but if he get his daughter away, it will be destroying the chief hold.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185673,\n            \"\\u201d And such was Fanny\\u2019s dependence on his words, that for five minutes she thought they _ had _ done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185775,\n            \"Fanny, now at liberty to speak openly, felt more than justified in adding to his knowledge of her real character, by some hint of what share his brother\\u2019s state of health might be supposed to have in her wish for a complete reconciliation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186070,\n            \"My Fanny, indeed, at this very time, I have the satisfaction of knowing, must have been happy in spite of everything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186752,\n            \"After wandering about and sitting under trees with Fanny all the summer evenings, he had so well talked his mind into submission as to be very tolerably cheerful again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187328,\n            \"She had lived with him to be reproached as the ruin of all his happiness in Fanny, and carried away no better consolation in leaving him than that she _ had _ divided them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188123,\n            \"Not even Fanny had tears for aunt Norris, not even when she was gone for ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188663,\n            \"Would he have persevered, and uprightly, Fanny must have been his reward, and a reward very voluntarily bestowed, within a reasonable period from Edmund\\u2019s marrying Mary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189032,\n            \"To keep Fanny and the Bertrams from a knowledge of what was passing became his first object.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189101,\n            \"and he went off with her at last, because he could not help it, regretting Fanny even at the moment, but regretting her infinitely more when all the bustle of the intrigue was over, and a very few months had taught him, by the force of contrast, to place a yet higher value on the sweetness of her temper, the purity of her mind, and the excellence of her principles.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189714,\n            \"Scarcely had he done regretting Mary Crawford, and observing to Fanny how impossible it was that he should ever meet with such another woman, before it began to strike him whether a very different kind of woman might not do just as well, or a great deal better: whether Fanny herself were not growing as dear, as important to him in all her smiles and all her ways, as Mary Crawford had ever been;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189872,\n            \"I only entreat everybody to believe that exactly at the time when it was quite natural that it should be so, and not a week earlier, Edmund did cease to care about Miss Crawford, and became as anxious to marry Fanny as Fanny herself could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190505,\n            \"and the joyful consent which met Edmund\\u2019s application, the high sense of having realised a great acquisition in the promise of Fanny for a daughter, formed just such a contrast with his early opinion on the subject when the poor little girl\\u2019s coming had been first agitated, as time is for ever producing between the plans and decisions of mortals, for their own instruction, and their neighbours\\u2019 entertainment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190584,\n            \"Fanny was indeed the daughter that he wanted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190811,\n            \"First as a comfort to Fanny, then as an auxiliary, and last as her substitute, she was established at Mansfield, with every appearance of equal permanency.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190889,\n            \"and after Fanny\\u2019s removal succeeded so naturally to her influence over the hourly comfort of her aunt, as gradually to become, perhaps, the most beloved of the two.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191136,\n            \"and the Parsonage there, which, under each of its two former owners, Fanny had never been able to approach but with some painful sensation of restraint or alarm, soon grew as dear to her heart, and as thoroughly perfect in her eyes, as everything else within the view and patronage of Mansfield Park had long been.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 10]\": [\n        [\n            15676,\n            \"She was delighted with each, but Mary was her dearest object;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15771,\n            \"and being a warm-hearted, unreserved woman, Mary had not been three hours in the house before she told her what she had planned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15976,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear sister,\\u201dsaid Mary, \\u201cif you can persuade him into anything of the sort, it will be a fresh matter of delight to me to find myself allied to anybody so clever, and I shall only regret that you have not half a dozen daughters to dispose of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16172,\n            \"You will be kinder than Mary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16852,\n            \"\\u201cI like your Miss Bertrams exceedingly, sister,\\u201dsaid he, as he returned from attending them to their carriage after the said dinner visit;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16890,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cSo they are indeed, and I am delighted to hear you say it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16967,\n            \"Miss Bertram is certainly the handsomest, and I have found her the most agreeable, but I shall always like Julia best, because you order me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16996,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI shall not talk to you, Henry, but I know you _ will _ like her best at last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17233,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMary, how shall we manage him?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17268,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut I would not have him _ taken _ _ in _;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17283,\n            \"I would not have him duped;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17347,\n            \"With all due respect to such of the present company as chance to be married, my dear Mrs. Grant, there is not one in a hundred of either sex who is not taken in when they marry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17629,\n            \"if the first calculation is wrong, we make a second better: we find comfort somewhere \\u2014 and those evil-minded observers, dearest Mary, who make much of a little, are more taken in and deceived than the parties themselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17730,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou are as bad as your brother, Mary;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17787,\n            \"Mary was satisfied with the Parsonage as a present home, and Henry equally ready to lengthen his visit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64745,\n            \"\\u201cI rather wonder Julia is not in love with Henry,\\u201dwas her observation to Mary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64764,\n            \"\\u201cI dare say she is,\\u201dreplied Mary coldly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64930,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cSir Thomas is to achieve many mighty things when he comes home,\\u201dsaid Mary, after a pause.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65028,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou will find his consequence very just and reasonable when you see him in his family, I assure you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65111,\n            \"But, Mary, do not fancy that Maria Bertram cares for Henry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91028,\n            \"and her tranquillity remained undisturbed the rest of the evening, except when Mr. Crawford now and then addressed to her a question or observation, which she could not avoid answering.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91082,\n            \"With that she soothed herself and amused her friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91256,\n            \"CHAPTER XXIV Henry Crawford had quite made up his mind by the next morning to give another fortnight to Mansfield, and having sent for his hunters, and written a few lines of explanation to the Admiral, he looked round at his sister as he sealed and threw the letter from him, and seeing the coast clear of the rest of the family, said, with a smile, \\u201cAnd how do you think I mean to amuse myself, Mary, on the days that I do not hunt?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91367,\n            \"but I have a plan for the intermediate days, and what do you think it is?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92077,\n            \"This it is, her not caring about you, which gives her such a soft skin, and makes her so much taller, and produces all these charms and graces!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92339,\n            \"\\u201d And without attempting any farther remonstrance, she left Fanny to her fate, a fate which, had not Fanny\\u2019s heart been guarded in a way unsuspected by Miss Crawford, might have been a little harder than she deserved;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97368,\n            \"(Let me see, Mary;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116796,\n            \"and when his sister, who had been waiting for him to walk with her in the garden, met him at last most impatiently in the sweep, and cried out, \\u201cMy dear Henry, where can you have been all this time?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116884,\n            \"\\u201cYes, Mary,\\u201dsaid he, drawing her arm within his, and walking along the sweep as if not knowing where he was: \\u201cI could not get away sooner;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116925,\n            \"I am quite determined, Mary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116944,\n            \"No: you must be aware that I am quite determined to marry Fanny Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116967,\n            \"for, in spite of whatever his consciousness might suggest, a suspicion of his having any such views had never entered his sister\\u2019s imagination;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116995,\n            \"and she looked so truly the astonishment she felt, that he was obliged to repeat what he had said, and more fully and more solemnly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117044,\n            \"Mary was in a state of mind to rejoice in a connexion with the Bertram family, and to be not displeased with her brother\\u2019s marrying a little beneath him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117077,\n            \"\\u201cYes, Mary,\\u201dwas Henry\\u2019s concluding assurance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117096,\n            \"You know with what idle designs I began;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117160,\n            \"My dearest Henry, this must be my _ first _ feeling;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117173,\n            \"but my _ second _, which you shall have as sincerely, is, that I approve your choice from my soul, and foresee your happiness as heartily as I wish and desire it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117340,\n            \"and before he had expressed the same sentiment with a little variation of words three times over, his sister eagerly interrupted him with, \\u201cAh, my dear Henry, and this is what took you to London!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117536,\n            \"No, Mary, you are quite mistaken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117728,\n            \"Mary, she is not like her cousins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118237,\n            \"\\u201d Well might his sister, believing as she really did that his opinion of Fanny Price was scarcely beyond her merits, rejoice in her prospects.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118265,\n            \"\\u201cThe more I think of it,\\u201dshe cried, \\u201cthe more am I convinced that you are doing quite right;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118290,\n            \"and though I should never have selected Fanny Price as the girl most likely to attach you, I am now persuaded she is the very one to make you happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118385,\n            \"I will make her very happy, Mary;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118523,\n            \"for her brother saw her only as the supposed inmate of Mansfield parsonage, and replied but to invite her in the kindest manner to his own house, and to claim the best right in her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118561,\n            \"\\u201cYou must give us more than half your time,\\u201dsaid he.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118576,\n            \"\\u201cI cannot admit Mrs. Grant to have an equal claim with Fanny and myself, for we shall both have a right in you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118755,\n            \"but, in my estimation, your marrying early may be the saving of you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118771,\n            \"To have seen you grow like the Admiral in word or deed, look or gesture, would have broken my heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118846,\n            \"You must not prejudice Fanny against him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118862,\n            \"\\u201d Mary refrained from saying what she felt, that there could not be two persons in existence whose characters and manners were less accordant: time would discover it to him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118895,\n            \"but she could not help _ this _ reflection on the Admiral.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118908,\n            \"\\u201cHenry, I think so highly of Fanny Price, that if I could suppose the next Mrs. Crawford would have half the reason which my poor ill-used aunt had to abhor the very name, I would prevent the marriage, if possible;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118957,\n            \"but I know you: I know that a wife you _ loved _ would be the happiest of women, and that even when you ceased to love, she would yet find in you the liberality and good-breeding of a gentleman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119037,\n            \"\\u201cHad you seen her this morning, Mary,\\u201dhe continued, \\u201cattending with such ineffable sweetness and patience to all the demands of her aunt\\u2019s stupidity, working with her, and for her, her colour beautifully heightened as she leant over the work, then returning to her seat to finish a note which she was previously engaged in writing for that stupid woman\\u2019s service, and all this with such unpretending gentleness, so much as if it were a matter of course that she was not to have a moment at her own command, her hair arranged as neatly as it always is, and one little curl falling forward as she wrote, which she now and then shook back, and in the midst of all this, still speaking at intervals to _ me _, or listening, and as if she liked to listen, to what I said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119205,\n            \"Had you seen her so, Mary, you would not have implied the possibility of her power over my heart ever ceasing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119229,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy dearest Henry,\\u201dcried Mary, stopping short, and smiling in his face, \\u201chow glad I am to see you so much in love!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120650,\n            \"He had communicated it to no creature: he had not breathed a syllable of it even to Mary;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123434,\n            \"but the comfort of the sound was impaired by his turning to her the next moment, and saying, \\u201cHave you nothing to send to Mary?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123469,\n            \"She will be disappointed if she receives nothing from you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143982,\n            \"Yet, Fanny, do not imagine I would now speak disrespectfully of Sir Thomas, though I certainly did hate him for many a week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144009,\n            \"No, I do him justice now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144128,\n            \"for as to scolding you, Fanny, which I came fully intending to do, I have not the heart for it when it comes to the point.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144171,\n            \"when I think of this being the last time of seeing you for I do not know how long, I feel it quite impossible to do anything but love you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144370,\n            \"Mrs. Fraser has been my intimate friend for years.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144381,\n            \"But I have not the least inclination to go near her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144393,\n            \"I can think only of the friends I am leaving: my excellent sister, yourself, and the Bertrams in general.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144436,\n            \"You all give me a feeling of being able to trust and confide in you, which in common intercourse one knows nothing of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144461,\n            \"I wish I had settled with Mrs. Fraser not to go to her till after Easter, a much better time for the visit, but now I cannot put her off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144495,\n            \"And when I have done with her I must go to her sister, Lady Stornaway, because _ she _ was rather my most particular friend of the two, but I have not cared much for _ her _ these three years.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146085,\n            \"I am sure it is not in woman\\u2019s nature to refuse such a triumph.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146144,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI do not defend him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146152,\n            \"I leave him entirely to your mercy, and when he has got you at Everingham, I do not care how much you lecture him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146179,\n            \"But this I will say, that his fault, the liking to make girls a little in love with him, is not half so dangerous to a wife\\u2019s happiness as a tendency to fall in love himself, which he has never been addicted to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146229,\n            \"And I do seriously and truly believe that he is attached to you in a way that he never was to any woman before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146274,\n            \"If any man ever loved a woman for ever, I think Henry will do as much for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146309,\n            \"\\u201cI cannot imagine Henry ever to have been happier,\\u201dcontinued Mary presently, \\u201cthan when he had succeeded in getting your brother\\u2019s commission.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146366,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI know he must have exerted himself very much, for I know the parties he had to move.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146440,\n            \"I wish we could see him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146487,\n            \"and she sat thinking deeply of it till Mary, who had been first watching her complacently, and then musing on something else, suddenly called her attention by saying: \\u201cI should like to sit talking with you here all day, but we must not forget the ladies below, and so good-bye, my dear, my amiable, my excellent Fanny, for though we shall nominally part in the breakfast-parlour, I must take leave of you here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146577,\n            \"And I do take leave, longing for a happy reunion, and trusting that when we meet again, it will be under circumstances which may open our hearts to each other without any remnant or shadow of reserve.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146636,\n            \"\\u201cI shall see your cousin in town soon: he talks of being there tolerably soon;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146654,\n            \"and Sir Thomas, I dare say, in the course of the spring;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146669,\n            \"and your eldest cousin, and the Rushworths, and Julia, I am sure of meeting again and again, and all but you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146695,\n            \"I have two favours to ask, Fanny: one is your correspondence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146709,\n            \"You must write to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146715,\n            \"And the other, that you will often call on Mrs. Grant, and make her amends for my being gone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147329,\n            \"If she could have believed Mary\\u2019s future fate as unconnected with Mansfield as she was determined the brother\\u2019s should be, if she could have hoped her return thither to be as distant as she was much inclined to think his, she would have been light of heart indeed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155716,\n            \"little sister Mary had left it to her upon her deathbed, and she ought to have had it to keep herself long ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155927,\n            \"Poor Mary little thought it would be such a bone of contention when she gave it me to keep, only two hours before she died.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155958,\n            \"she could but just speak to be heard, and she said so prettily, \\u2018 Let sister Susan have my knife, mama, when I am dead and buried.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155995,\n            \"she was so fond of it, Fanny, that she would have it lay by her in bed, all through her illness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156099,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny had indeed nothing to convey from aunt Norris, but a message to say she hoped that her god-daughter was a good girl, and learnt her book.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158359,\n            \"In her present exile from good society, and distance from everything that had been wont to interest her, a letter from one belonging to the set where her heart lived, written with affection, and some degree of elegance, was thoroughly acceptable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158424,\n            \"\\u201cAnd now that I have begun,\\u201dshe continued, \\u201cmy letter will not be worth your reading, for there will be no little offering of love at the end, no three or four lines _ passionn\\u00e9es _ from the most devoted H.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158516,\n            \"But there he is, and, by the bye, his absence may sufficiently account for any remissness of his sister\\u2019s in writing, for there has been no \\u2018 Well, Mary, when do you write to Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158690,\n            \"Upon the whole, Julia was in the best looks of the two, at least after you were spoken of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158906,\n            \"From all that I hear and guess, Baron Wildenheim\\u2019s attentions to Julia continue, but I do not know that he has any serious encouragement.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161596,\n            \"and she was tolerably able to bear his eye, and hear that he had spent half an hour with his sister the evening before his leaving London;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161643,\n            \"that he thought himself lucky in seeing Mary for even half an hour, having spent scarcely twenty-four hours in London, after his return from Norfolk, before he set off again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165440,\n            \"I am aware that you may be left here week after week, if Sir Thomas cannot settle everything for coming himself, or sending your aunt\\u2019s maid for you, without involving the slightest alteration of the arrangements which he may have laid down for the next quarter of a year.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165515,\n            \"I am considering your sister\\u2019s health,\\u201dsaid he, addressing himself to Susan, \\u201cwhich I think the confinement of Portsmouth unfavourable to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165551,\n            \"When you know her as well as I do, I am sure you will agree that she does, and that she ought never to be long banished from the free air and liberty of the country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165590,\n            \"If, therefore\\u201d(turning again to Fanny), \\u201cyou find yourself growing unwell, and any difficulties arise about your returning to Mansfield, without waiting for the two months to be ended, _ that _ must not be regarded as of any consequence, if you feel yourself at all less strong or comfortable than usual, and will only let my sister know it, give her only the slightest hint, she and I will immediately come down, and take you back to Mansfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165767,\n            \"for so long only as you positively say, in every letter to Mary, \\u2018 I am well,\\u2019and I know you cannot speak or write a falsehood, so long only shall you be considered as well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166317,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy love to your sister, if you please;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166733,\n            \"and she could not think of his returning to town, and being frequently with Mary and Edmund, without feelings so near akin to envy as made her hate herself for having them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188663,\n            \"Would he have persevered, and uprightly, Fanny must have been his reward, and a reward very voluntarily bestowed, within a reasonable period from Edmund\\u2019s marrying Mary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189004,\n            \"He was entangled by his own vanity, with as little excuse of love as possible, and without the smallest inconstancy of mind towards her cousin.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189511,\n            \"and Mary had had enough of her own friends, enough of vanity, ambition, love, and disappointment in the course of the last half-year, to be in need of the true kindness of her sister\\u2019s heart, and the rational tranquillity of her ways.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189594,\n            \"for Mary, though perfectly resolved against ever attaching herself to a younger brother again, was long in finding among the dashing representatives, or idle heir-apparents, who were at the command of her beauty, and her \\u00a320, 000, any one who could satisfy the better taste she had acquired at Mansfield, whose character and manners could authorise a hope of the domestic happiness she had there learned to estimate, or put Edmund Bertram sufficiently out of her head.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190505,\n            \"and the joyful consent which met Edmund\\u2019s application, the high sense of having realised a great acquisition in the promise of Fanny for a daughter, formed just such a contrast with his early opinion on the subject when the poor little girl\\u2019s coming had been first agitated, as time is for ever producing between the plans and decisions of mortals, for their own instruction, and their neighbours\\u2019 entertainment.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 11]\": [\n        [\n            5243,\n            \"It was William whom she talked of most, and wanted most to see.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5258,\n            \"William, the eldest, a year older than herself, her constant companion and friend;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5292,\n            \"\\u201cWilliam did not like she should come away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5302,\n            \"he had told her he should miss her very much indeed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5314,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut William will write to you, I dare say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5327,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, he had promised he would, but he had told _ her _ to write first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5408,\n            \"Would it make you happy to write to William?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5489,\n            \"and, as your uncle will frank it, it will cost William nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7547,\n            \"Once, and once only, in the course of many years, had she the happiness of being with William.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7601,\n            \"but William determining, soon after her removal, to be a sailor, was invited to spend a week with his sister in Northamptonshire before he went to sea.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7661,\n            \"as well as the sanguine views and spirits of the boy even to the last, and the misery of the girl when he left her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7709,\n            \"and he told her such charming things of what William was to do, and be hereafter, in consequence of his profession, as made her gradually admit that the separation might have some use.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7972,\n            \"In return for such services she loved him better than anybody in the world except William: her heart was divided between the two.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8132,\n            \"But Tom\\u2019s extravagance had, previous to that event, been so great as to render a different disposal of the next presentation necessary, and the younger brother must help to pay for the pleasures of the elder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12167,\n            \"\\u201d He had said to her, moreover, on the very last morning, that he hoped she might see William again in the course of the ensuing winter, and had charged her to write and invite him to Mansfield as soon as the squadron to which he belonged should be known to be in England.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12269,\n            \"But he had ended his speech in a way to sink her in sad mortification, by adding, \\u201cIf William does come to Mansfield, I hope you may be able to convince him that the many years which have passed since you parted have not been spent on your side entirely without improvement;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12326,\n            \"though, I fear, he must find his sister at sixteen in some respects too much like his sister at ten.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22845,\n            \"and my brother-in-law himself, who is all kindness in general, looked rather black upon me when he found what I had been at.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23144,\n            \"Now, Mr. Bertram, if you write to your brother, I entreat you to tell him that my harp is come: he heard so much of my misery about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23179,\n            \"And you may say, if you please, that I shall prepare my most plaintive airs against his return, in compassion to his feelings, as I know his horse will lose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23242,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo, I dare say, nor if he were to be gone a twelvemonth, would you ever write to him, nor he to you, if it could be helped.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23446,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWhen they are at a distance from all their family,\\u201dsaid Fanny, colouring for William\\u2019s sake, \\u201cthey can write long letters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24808,\n            \"An uncle with whom she has been living so many years, and who, whatever his faults may be, is so very fond of her brother, treating him, they say, quite like a son.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25152,\n            \"She speaks of her brother with a very pleasing affection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25163,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, except as to his writing her such short letters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25220,\n            \"I am sure William would never have used _ me _ so, under any circumstances.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44458,\n            \"He has met with great kindness from the chaplain of the Antwerp,\\u201dwas a tender apostrophe of Fanny\\u2019s, very much to the purpose of her own feelings if not of the conversation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93029,\n            \"and as his parents, from living on the spot, must already have seen him, and be seeing him perhaps daily, his direct holidays might with justice be instantly given to the sister, who had been his best correspondent through a period of seven years, and the uncle who had done most for his support and advancement;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93184,\n            \"and there being neither ceremony nor fearfulness to delay the moment of meeting, she was with him as he entered the house, and the first minutes of exquisite feeling had no interruption and no witnesses, unless the servants chiefly intent upon opening the proper doors could be called such.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93294,\n            \"William and Fanny soon shewed themselves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93301,\n            \"and Sir Thomas had the pleasure of receiving, in his prot\\u00e9g\\u00e9, certainly a very different person from the one he had equipped seven years ago, but a young man of an open, pleasant countenance, and frank, unstudied, but feeling and respectful manners, and such as confirmed him his friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93518,\n            \"On the morrow they were walking about together with true enjoyment, and every succeeding morrow renewed a _ t\\u00eate-\\u00e0-t\\u00eate _ which Sir Thomas could not but observe with complacency, even before Edmund had pointed it out to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93880,\n            \"But with William and Fanny Price it was still a sentiment in all its prime and freshness, wounded by no opposition of interest, cooled by no separate attachment, and feeling the influence of time and absence only in its increase.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94213,\n            \"William was often called on by his uncle to be the talker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94699,\n            \"and Crawford could mount him without the slightest inconvenience to himself, and with only some scruples to obviate in Sir Thomas, who knew better than his nephew the value of such a loan, and some alarms to reason away in Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94862,\n            \"When it was proved, however, to have done William no harm, she could allow it to be a kindness, and even reward the owner with a smile when the animal was one minute tendered to his use again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95769,\n            \"for though it was impossible for Fanny not to feel herself mistress of the rules of the game in three minutes, he had yet to inspirit her play, sharpen her avarice, and harden her heart, which, especially in any competition with William, was a work of some difficulty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96470,\n            \"and her interest in a negotiation for William Price\\u2019s knave increased.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96953,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Crawford, a little suspicious and resentful of a certain tone of voice, and a certain half-look attending the last expression of his hope, made a hasty finish of her dealings with William Price;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97654,\n            \"but Crawford pursued with \\u201cNo, no, you must not part with the queen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97671,\n            \"You have bought her too dearly, and your brother does not offer half her value.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98100,\n            \"but the next time you come, I hope dear Mr. and Mrs. Rushworth will be at home, and I am sure I can answer for your being kindly received by both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98158,\n            \"They are at Brighton now, you know;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98190,\n            \"I do not exactly know the distance, but when you get back to Portsmouth, if it is not very far off, you ought to go over and pay your respects to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98226,\n            \"and I could send a little parcel by you that I want to get conveyed to your cousins.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98245,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI should be very happy, aunt;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98360,\n            \"and you will find Mr. Rushworth most sincerely disposed to regard all the connexions of our family as his own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98382,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI would rather find him private secretary to the First Lord than anything else,\\u201dwas William\\u2019s only answer, in an undervoice, not meant to reach far, and the subject dropped.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99756,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut you do not wish yourself at Portsmouth, William?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100026,\n            \"only think, William, when you are a lieutenant, how little you will care for any nonsense of this kind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100369,\n            \"But, on the contrary, it was no worse than, \\u201cI am sorry to say that I am unable to answer your question.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100442,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have had the pleasure of seeing your sister dance, Mr. Price,\\u201dsaid Henry Crawford, leaning forward, \\u201cand will engage to answer every inquiry which you can make on the subject, to your entire satisfaction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100612,\n            \"and Sir Thomas, by no means displeased, prolonged the conversation on dancing in general, and was so well engaged in describing the balls of Antigua, and listening to what his nephew could relate of the different modes of dancing which had fallen within his observation, that he had not heard his carriage announced, and was first called to the knowledge of it by the bustle of Mrs. Norris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100736,\n            \"My dear Sir Thomas, we have settled it that the carriage should come back for you, and Edmund and William.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101157,\n            \"Thank your uncle, William, thank your uncle!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101371,\n            \"Edmund, William, and Fanny did, in their different ways, look and speak as much grateful pleasure in the promised ball as Sir Thomas could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101782,\n            \"and the almost solitary ornament in her possession, a very pretty amber cross which William had brought her from Sicily, was the greatest distress of all, for she had nothing but a bit of ribbon to fasten it to;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101871,\n            \"William had wanted to buy her a gold chain too, but the purchase had been beyond his means, and therefore not to wear the cross might be mortifying him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102917,\n            \"and as Edmund and William were gone to Northampton, and she had reason to think Mr. Crawford likewise out, she walked down to the Parsonage without much fear of wanting an opportunity for private discussion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103234,\n            \"\\u201cShall not you wear your brother\\u2019s cross?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103461,\n            \"But Miss Crawford persevered, and argued the case with so much affectionate earnestness through all the heads of William and the cross, and the ball, and herself, as to be finally successful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104594,\n            \"but I can now speak my business, which is merely to beg your acceptance of this little trifle \\u2014 a chain for William\\u2019s cross.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107056,\n            \"To dance without much observation or any extraordinary fatigue, to have strength and partners for about half the evening, to dance a little with Edmund, and not a great deal with Mr. Crawford, to see William enjoy himself, and be able to keep away from her aunt Norris, was the height of her ambition, and seemed to comprehend her greatest possibility of happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111802,\n            \"and sometimes, when he talked of William, he was really not unagreeable, and shewed even a warmth of heart which did him credit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111840,\n            \"She was happy whenever she looked at William, and saw how perfectly he was enjoying himself, in every five minutes that she could walk about with him and hear his account of his partners;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111964,\n            \"His mind was fagged, and her happiness sprung from being the friend with whom it could find repose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112050,\n            \"A weariness, arising probably, in great measure, from the same feelings which he had acknowledged in the morning, was peculiarly to be respected, and they went down their two dances together with such sober tranquillity as might satisfy any looker-on that Sir Thomas had been bringing up no wife for his younger son.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112335,\n            \"\\u201d cried William, coming for a moment to visit her, and working away his partner\\u2019s fan as if for life, \\u201chow soon she is knocked up!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112377,\n            \"I hope we shall keep it up these two hours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112401,\n            \"my good friend,\\u201dsaid Sir Thomas, producing his watch with all necessary caution;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112438,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, then, Fanny, you shall not get up to-morrow before I go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112458,\n            \"Sleep as long as you can, and never mind me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112480,\n            \"Did she think of being up before you set off?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112495,\n            \"yes, sir,\\u201dcried Fanny, rising eagerly from her seat to be nearer her uncle;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112514,\n            \"\\u201cI must get up and breakfast with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112559,\n            \"Mr. Crawford, I think you call for him at half-past nine?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112610,\n            \"\\u201cYes, half-past nine,\\u201dsaid Crawford to William as the latter was leaving them, \\u201cand I shall be punctual, for there will be no kind sister to get up for _ me _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112791,\n            \"She had hoped to have William all to herself the last morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113172,\n            \"and there her uncle kindly left her to cry in peace, conceiving, perhaps, that the deserted chair of each young man might exercise her tender enthusiasm, and that the remaining cold pork bones and mustard in William\\u2019s plate might but divide her feelings with the broken egg-shells in Mr. Crawford\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113234,\n            \"She sat and cried _ con _ _ amore _ as her uncle intended, but it was _ con _ _ amore _ fraternal and no other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113263,\n            \"William was gone, and she now felt as if she had wasted half his visit in idle cares and selfish solicitudes unconnected with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113334,\n            \"much less could her feelings acquit her of having done and said and thought everything by William that was due to him for a whole fortnight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113369,\n            \"Soon after the second breakfast, Edmund bade them good-bye for a week, and mounted his horse for Peterborough, and then all were gone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113475,\n            \"\\u201cShe could not recollect what it was that she had heard about one of the Miss Maddoxes, or what it was that Lady Prescott had noticed in Fanny: she was not sure whether Colonel Harrison had been talking of Mr. Crawford or of William when he said he was the finest young man in the room \\u2014 somebody had whispered something to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113894,\n            \"She could think of William the next day more cheerfully;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113983,\n            \"They were indeed a smaller party than she had ever known there for a whole day together, and _ he _ was gone on whom the comfort and cheerfulness of every family meeting and every meal chiefly depended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114039,\n            \"and she was thankful that she could now sit in the same room with her uncle, hear his voice, receive his questions, and even answer them, without such wretched feelings as she had formerly known.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114157,\n            \"\\u201cAnd there is no reason to suppose,\\u201dadded Sir Thomas, \\u201cbut that his visits to us may now be tolerably frequent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120388,\n            \"My uncle, who is the very best man in the world, has exerted himself, as I knew he would, after seeing your brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120416,\n            \"He was delighted with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120470,\n            \"_ Now _ I may say that even I could not require William Price to excite a greater interest, or be followed by warmer wishes and higher commendation, than were most voluntarily bestowed by my uncle after the evening they had passed together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120605,\n            \"His last journey to London had been undertaken with no other view than that of introducing her brother in Hill Street, and prevailing on the Admiral to exert whatever interest he might have for getting him on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120778,\n            \"but her heart was so full and her senses still so astonished, that she could listen but imperfectly even to what he told her of William, and saying only when he paused, \\u201cHow kind!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120947,\n            \"When she did understand it, however, and found herself expected to believe that she had created sensations which his heart had never known before, and that everything he had done for William was to be placed to the account of his excessive and unequalled attachment to her, she was exceedingly distressed, and for some moments unable to speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121335,\n            \"Your kindness to William makes me more obliged to you than words can express;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121616,\n            \"She would not have him be serious, and yet what could excuse the use of such words and offers, if they meant but to trifle?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121644,\n            \"But William was a lieutenant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121700,\n            \"and in that case, how gratefully she could esteem him for his friendship to William!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121750,\n            \"but when convinced of his being gone, she was eager to go down and be with her uncle, and have all the happiness of his joy as well as her own, and all the benefit of his information or his conjectures as to what would now be William\\u2019s destination.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121821,\n            \"and she had so comfortable a talk with him about William as to make her feel as if nothing had occurred to vex her, till she found, towards the close, that Mr. Crawford was engaged to return and dine there that very day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122171,\n            \"so you may smile upon him with your sweetest smiles this afternoon, and send him back to me even happier than he goes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122214,\n            \"for though she read in too much haste and confusion to form the clearest judgment of Miss Crawford\\u2019s meaning, it was evident that she meant to compliment her on her brother\\u2019s attachment, and even to _ appear _ to believe it serious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122397,\n            \"for though nothing could have tempted her to turn her eyes to the right hand, where he sat, she felt that _ his _ were immediately directed towards her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122436,\n            \"She would hardly join even when William was the subject, for his commission came all from the right hand too, and there was pain in the connexion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122486,\n            \"but at last they were in the drawing-room, and she was able to think as she would, while her aunts finished the subject of William\\u2019s appointment in their own style.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122546,\n            \"\\u201c_ Now _ William would be able to keep himself, which would make a vast difference to his uncle, for it was unknown how much he had cost his uncle;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122596,\n            \"She was very glad that she had given William what she did at parting, very glad, indeed, that it had been in her power, without material inconvenience, just at that time to give him something rather considerable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122639,\n            \"that is, for _ her _, with _ her _ limited means, for now it would all be useful in helping to fit up his cabin.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122669,\n            \"She knew he must be at some expense, that he would have many things to buy, though to be sure his father and mother would be able to put him in the way of getting everything very cheap;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123617,\n            \"and with only one decided feeling, that of wishing not to appear to think anything really intended, she wrote thus, in great trembling both of spirits and hand \\u2014 \\u201cI am very much obliged to you, my dear Miss Crawford, for your kind congratulations, as far as they relate to my dearest William.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123994,\n            \"for every day would restore the knowledge of William\\u2019s advancement, whereas the pain, she hoped, would return no more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131344,\n            \"She must have a sensation of being honoured, and whether thinking of herself or her brother, she must have a strong feeling of gratitude.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147912,\n            \"William had obtained a ten days\\u2019 leave of absence, to be given to Northamptonshire, and was coming, the happiest of lieutenants, because the latest made, to shew his happiness and describe his uniform.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148105,\n            \"This scheme was that she should accompany her brother back to Portsmouth, and spend a little time with her own family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148514,\n            \"of returning for a couple of months to the scenes of her infancy, with William for the protector and companion of her journey, and the certainty of continuing to see William to the last hour of his remaining on land.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148622,\n            \"Afterwards, when familiarised with the visions of enjoyment so suddenly opened, she could speak more largely to William and Edmund of what she felt;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149498,\n            \"William was almost as happy in the plan as his sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149510,\n            \"It would be the greatest pleasure to him to have her there to the last moment before he sailed, and perhaps find her there still when he came in from his first cruise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149545,\n            \"And besides, he wanted her so very much to see the Thrush before she went out of harbour \\u2014 the Thrush was certainly the finest sloop in the service \\u2014 and there were several improvements in the dockyard, too, which he quite longed to shew her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149595,\n            \"He did not scruple to add that her being at home for a while would be a great advantage to everybody.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149656,\n            \"You will set things going in a better way, I am sure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149824,\n            \"when she saw Sir Thomas actually give William notes for the purpose, she was struck with the idea of there being room for a third in the carriage, and suddenly seized with a strong inclination to go with them, to go and see her poor dear sister Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150193,\n            \"He too had a sacrifice to make to Mansfield Park as well as his aunt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150223,\n            \"but he could not leave his father and mother just when everybody else of most importance to their comfort was leaving them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150348,\n            \"Once afterwards she was alluded to by him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150384,\n            \"and Edmund, at a convenient moment, then added in a whisper, \\u201cAnd _ I _ shall write to you, Fanny, when I have anything worth writing about, anything to say that I think you will like to hear, and that you will not hear so soon from any other quarter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150443,\n            \"\\u201d Had she doubted his meaning while she listened, the glow in his face, when she looked up at him, would have been decisive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150618,\n            \"and as for Edmund, she could neither speak, nor look, nor think, when the last moment came with _ him _;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150644,\n            \"and it was not till it was over that she knew he was giving her the affectionate farewell of a brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150683,\n            \"and when the small, diminished party met at breakfast, William and Fanny were talked of as already advanced one stage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150795,\n            \"Everything supplied an amusement to the high glee of William\\u2019s mind, and he was full of frolic and joke in the intervals of their higher-toned subjects, all of which ended, if they did not begin, in praise of the Thrush, conjectures how she would be employed, schemes for an action with some superior force, which (supposing the first lieutenant out of the way, and William was not very merciful to the first lieutenant) was to give himself the next step as soon as possible, or speculations upon prize-money, which was to be generously distributed at home, with only the reservation of enough to make the little cottage comfortable, in which he and Fanny were to pass all their middle and later life together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150961,\n            \"William knew what had passed, and from his heart lamented that his sister\\u2019s feelings should be so cold towards a man whom he must consider as the first of human characters;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151455,\n            \"and the light was only beginning to fail as, guided by William\\u2019s powerful voice, they were rattled into a narrow street, leading from the High Street, and drawn up before the door of a small house now inhabited by Mr. Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151516,\n            \"The moment they stopped, a trollopy-looking maidservant, seemingly in waiting for them at the door, stepped forward, and more intent on telling the news than giving them any help, immediately began with, \\u201cThe Thrush is gone out of harbour, please sir, and one of the officers has been here to \\u2014\\u201dShe was interrupted by a fine tall boy of eleven years old, who, rushing out of the house, pushed the maid aside, and while William was opening the chaise-door himself, called out, \\u201cYou are just in time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151719,\n            \"\\u201d A stare or two at Fanny, as William helped her out of the carriage, was all the voluntary notice which this brother bestowed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152009,\n            \"She was gone again to the street-door, to welcome William.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152745,\n            \"and lastly, in walked Mr. Price himself, his own loud voice preceding him, as with something of the oath kind he kicked away his son\\u2019s portmanteau and his daughter\\u2019s bandbox in the passage, and called out for a candle;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152901,\n            \"The doctor has been here inquiring for you: he has got one of the boats, and is to be off for Spithead by six, so you had better go with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152936,\n            \"I have been to Turner\\u2019s about your mess;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152987,\n            \"and Captain Walsh thinks you will certainly have a cruise to the westward, with the Elephant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153014,\n            \"But old Scholey was saying, just now, that he thought you would be sent first to the Texel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153086,\n            \"Old Scholey ran in at breakfast-time, to say she had slipped her moorings and was coming out, I jumped up, and made but two steps to the platform.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153222,\n            \"But here is my sister, sir;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153252,\n            \"\\u201d With an acknowledgment that he had quite forgot her, Mr. Price now received his daughter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153271,\n            \"and having given her a cordial hug, and observed that she was grown into a woman, and he supposed would be wanting a husband soon, seemed very much inclined to forget her again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153328,\n            \"and he talked on only to his son, and only of the Thrush, though William, warmly interested as he was in that subject, more than once tried to make his father think of Fanny, and her long absence and long journey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153386,\n            \"but as there was still no appearance of tea, nor, from Betsey\\u2019s reports from the kitchen, much hope of any under a considerable period, William determined to go and change his dress, and make the necessary preparations for his removal on board directly, that he might have his tea in comfort afterwards.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153703,\n            \"William was soon calling out from the landing-place of the second story for his mother and for Rebecca.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153742,\n            \"A key was mislaid, Betsey accused of having got at his new hat, and some slight, but essential alteration of his uniform waistcoat, which he had been promised to have done for him, entirely neglected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153783,\n            \"Mrs. Price, Rebecca, and Betsey all went up to defend themselves, all talking together, but Rebecca loudest, and the job was to be done as well as it could in a great hurry;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153823,\n            \"William trying in vain to send Betsey down again, or keep her from being troublesome where she was;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153970,\n            \"and he, taking out a newspaper, the accustomary loan of a neighbour, applied himself to studying it, without seeming to recollect her existence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153998,\n            \"The solitary candle was held between himself and the paper, without any reference to her possible convenience;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154347,\n            \"Sam, stop your confounded pipe, or I shall be after you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154361,\n            \"\\u201d This threat was so palpably disregarded, that though within five minutes afterwards the three boys all burst into the room together and sat down, Fanny could not consider it as a proof of anything more than their being for the time thoroughly fagged, which their hot faces and panting breaths seemed to prove, especially as they were still kicking each other\\u2019s shins, and hallooing out at sudden starts immediately under their father\\u2019s eye.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154714,\n            \"she was like William, and Fanny hoped to find her like him in disposition and goodwill towards herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154734,\n            \"In this more placid state of things William reentered, followed not far behind by his mother and Betsey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154754,\n            \"He, complete in his lieutenant\\u2019s uniform, looking and moving all the taller, firmer, and more graceful for it, and with the happiest smile over his face, walked up directly to Fanny, who, rising from her seat, looked at him for a moment in speechless admiration, and then threw her arms round his neck to sob out her various emotions of pain and pleasure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154841,\n            \"and wiping away her tears, was able to notice and admire all the striking parts of his dress;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154861,\n            \"listening with reviving spirits to his cheerful hopes of being on shore some part of every day before they sailed, and even of getting her to Spithead to see the sloop.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155012,\n            \"for the three boys, in spite of their mother\\u2019s entreaty, determined to see their brother and Mr. Campbell to the sally-port;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155041,\n            \"and Mr. Price walked off at the same time to carry back his neighbour\\u2019s newspaper.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155069,\n            \"and accordingly, when Rebecca had been prevailed on to carry away the tea-things, and Mrs. Price had walked about the room some time looking for a shirt-sleeve, which Betsey at last hunted out from a drawer in the kitchen, the small party of females were pretty well composed, and the mother having lamented again over the impossibility of getting Sam ready in time, was at leisure to think of her eldest daughter and the friends she had come from.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156422,\n            \"for though a good night\\u2019s rest, a pleasant morning, the hope of soon seeing William again, and the comparatively quiet state of the house, from Tom and Charles being gone to school, Sam on some project of his own, and her father on his usual lounges, enabled her to express herself cheerfully on the subject of home, there were still, to her own perfect consciousness, many drawbacks suppressed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156557,\n            \"The Thrush had had her orders, the wind had changed, and he was sailed within four days from their reaching Portsmouth;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156581,\n            \"and during those days she had seen him only twice, in a short and hurried way, when he had come ashore on duty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156643,\n            \"Everything in that quarter failed her, except William\\u2019s affection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156656,\n            \"His last thought on leaving home was for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156709,\n            \"\\u201d William was gone: and the home he had left her in was, Fanny could not conceal it from herself, in almost every respect the very reverse of what she could have wished.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156785,\n            \"On her father, her confidence had not been sanguine, but he was more negligent of his family, his habits were worse, and his manners coarser, than she had been prepared for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156879,\n            \"She had never been able to recall anything approaching to tenderness in his former treatment of herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156909,\n            \"and now he scarcely ever noticed her, but to make her the object of a coarse joke.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157057,\n            \"She was fond of her sons, especially of William, but Betsey was the first of her girls whom she had ever much regarded.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161057,\n            \"and she found that she had been able to name him to her mother, and recall her remembrance of the name, as that of \\u201cWilliam\\u2019s friend,\\u201dthough she could not previously have believed herself capable of uttering a syllable at such a moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161108,\n            \"The consciousness of his being known there only as William\\u2019s friend was some support.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161258,\n            \"Warmed by the sight of such a friend to her son, and regulated by the wish of appearing to advantage before him, she was overflowing with gratitude \\u2014 artless, maternal gratitude \\u2014 which could not be unpleasing.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 12]\": [\n        [\n            68,\n            \"All Huntingdon exclaimed on the greatness of the match, and her uncle, the lawyer, himself, allowed her to be at least three thousand pounds short of any equitable claim to it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104,\n            \"She had two sisters to be benefited by her elevation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115,\n            \"and such of their acquaintance as thought Miss Ward and Miss Frances quite as handsome as Miss Maria, did not scruple to predict their marrying with almost equal advantage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169,\n            \"Miss Ward, at the end of half a dozen years, found herself obliged to be attached to the Rev.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            441,\n            \"To save herself from useless remonstrance, Mrs. Price never wrote to her family on the subject till actually married.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13601,\n            \"Though Edmund was much more displeased with his aunt than with his mother, as evincing least regard for her niece, he could not help paying more attention to what she said;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14566,\n            \"Maria was indeed the pride and delight of them all \\u2014 perfectly faultless \\u2014 an angel;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27532,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes,\\u201dadded Maria, \\u201cand her spirits are as good, and she has the same energy of character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40309,\n            \"\\u201cBut they cannot be very far off, and I think I am equal to as much as Maria, even without help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40577,\n            \"The mother I could not avoid, as long as my tiresome aunt was dancing about with the housekeeper, but the son I _ can _ get away from.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40764,\n            \"\\u201cThey desired me to stay \\u2014 my cousin Maria charged me to say that you would find them at that knoll, or thereabouts.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42744,\n            \"And if I have good luck, your mother shall have some.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42981,\n            \"for to her the father brought a husband, and the return of the friend most solicitous for her happiness would unite her to the lover, on whom she had chosen that happiness should depend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46223,\n            \"Maria, with only Mr. Rushworth to attend to her, and doomed to the repeated details of his day\\u2019s sport, good or bad, his boast of his dogs, his jealousy of his neighbours, his doubts of their qualifications, and his zeal after poachers, subjects which will not find their way to female feelings without some talent on one side or some attachment on the other, had missed Mr. Crawford grievously;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46330,\n            \"Julia might be justified in so doing by the hints of Mrs. Grant, inclined to credit what she wished, and Maria by the hints of Mr. Crawford himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47127,\n            \"While waiting and wishing, looking now at the dancers and now at the door, this dialogue between the two above-mentioned ladies was forced on her \\u2014 \\u201cI think, ma\\u2019am,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris, her eyes directed towards Mr. Rushworth and Maria, who were partners for the second time, \\u201cwe shall see some happy faces again now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47290,\n            \"But dear Maria has such a strict sense of propriety, so much of that true delicacy which one seldom meets with nowadays, Mrs. Rushworth \\u2014 that wish of avoiding particularity!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47349,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Bertram did indeed look happy, her eyes were sparkling with pleasure, and she was speaking with great animation, for Julia and her partner, Mr. Crawford, were close to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47395,\n            \"How she had looked before, Fanny could not recollect, for she had been dancing with Edmund herself, and had not thought about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49776,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI believe we must be satisfied with _ less _,\\u201dsaid Maria.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50190,\n            \"Maria, Julia, Henry Crawford, and Mr. Yates were in the billiard-room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50538,\n            \"and it would be imprudent, I think, with regard to Maria, whose situation is a very delicate one, considering everything, extremely delicate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52140,\n            \"\\u201d Maria gave Edmund a glance, which meant, \\u201cWhat say you now?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53629,\n            \"when Julia, meaning, like her sister, to be Agatha, began to be scrupulous on Miss Crawford\\u2019s account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53674,\n            \"Amelia and Agatha may do for Maria and me, but here is nothing for your sister, Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54061,\n            \"Maria must be Agatha.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54066,\n            \"Maria will be the best Agatha.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55222,\n            \"but her brother soon returned to business and Lovers\\u2019 Vows, and was eagerly looking over the play, with Mr. Yates\\u2019 s help, to ascertain what scenery would be necessary \\u2014 while Maria and Henry Crawford conversed together in an under-voice, and the declaration with which she began of, \\u201cI am sure I would give up the part to Julia most willingly, but that though I shall probably do it very ill, I feel persuaded _ she _ would do it worse,\\u201dwas doubtless receiving all the compliments it called for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55775,\n            \"and was too much engaged with what his own appearance would be to think of the others, or draw any of those conclusions, or feel any of that displeasure which Maria had been half prepared for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55835,\n            \"but when he entered the drawing-room before dinner, the buzz of discussion was high between Tom, Maria, and Mr. Yates;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56111,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut what do you do for women?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56131,\n            \"Maria blushed in spite of herself as she answered, \\u201cI take the part which Lady Ravenshaw was to have done, and\\u201d(with a bolder eye) \\u201cMiss Crawford is to be Amelia.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56415,\n            \"Read only the first act aloud to either your mother or aunt, and see how you can approve it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56436,\n            \"It will not be necessary to send you to your _ father\\u2019s _ judgment, I am convinced.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56457,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWe see things very differently,\\u201dcried Maria.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56568,\n            \"If others have blundered, it is your place to put them right, and shew them what true delicacy is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56590,\n            \"In all points of decorum _ your _ conduct must be law to the rest of the party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56609,\n            \"\\u201d This picture of her consequence had some effect, for no one loved better to lead than Maria;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56767,\n            \"All who can distinguish will understand your motive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56864,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere, my dear, do you hear what Edmund says?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57602,\n            \"Maria, wanting Henry Crawford\\u2019s animating support, thought the subject better avoided.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57707,\n            \"and the spirits of evening giving fresh courage, Tom, Maria, and Mr. Yates, soon after their being reassembled in the drawing-room, seated themselves in committee at a separate table, with the play open before them, and were just getting deep in the subject when a most welcome interruption was given by the entrance of Mr. and Miss Crawford, who, late and dark and dirty as it was, could not help coming, and were received with the most grateful joy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59338,\n            \"and it was not merely Tom, for the requisition was now backed by Maria, and Mr. Crawford, and Mr. Yates, with an urgency which differed from his but in being more gentle or more ceremonious, and which altogether was quite overpowering to Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59608,\n            \"but Miss Crawford, looking for a moment with astonished eyes at Mrs. Norris, and then at Fanny, whose tears were beginning to shew themselves, immediately said, with some keenness, \\u201cI do not like my situation: this _ place _ is too hot for me,\\u201dand moved away her chair to the opposite side of the table, close to Fanny, saying to her, in a kind, low whisper, as she placed herself, \\u201cNever mind, my dear Miss Price, this is a cross evening: everybody is cross and teasing, but do not let us mind them \\u201d;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60157,\n            \"\\u201d While he spoke, Maria was looking apprehensively round at Edmund in full expectation that he must oppose such an enlargement of the plan as this: so contrary to all their first protestations;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60321,\n            \"and though Julia, who had scarcely opened her lips before, observed, in a sarcastic manner, and with a glance first at Maria and then at Edmund, that \\u201cthe Mansfield theatricals would enliven the whole neighbourhood exceedingly,\\u201dEdmund still held his peace, and shewed his feelings only by a determined gravity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60642,\n            \"and if she were applied to again among themselves with all the authoritative urgency that Tom and Maria were capable of, and Edmund perhaps away, what should she do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60940,\n            \"The East room, as it had been called ever since Maria Bertram was sixteen, was now considered Fanny\\u2019s, almost as decidedly as the white attic: the smallness of the one making the use of the other so evidently reasonable that the Miss Bertrams, with every superiority in their own apartments which their own sense of superiority could demand, were entirely approving it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65150,\n            \"and though he and Maria are very good friends, I think she likes Sotherton too well to be inconstant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65348,\n            \"The sister with whom she was used to be on easy terms was now become her greatest enemy: they were alienated from each other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65374,\n            \"and Julia was not superior to the hope of some distressing end to the attentions which were still carrying on there, some punishment to Maria for conduct so shameful towards herself as well as towards Mr. Rushworth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65484,\n            \"and Julia could never see Maria distinguished by Henry Crawford without trusting that it would create jealousy, and bring a public disturbance at last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69302,\n            \"\\u201cAnd I do believe she can say every word of it,\\u201dadded Maria, \\u201cfor she could put Mrs. Grant right the other day in twenty places.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69335,\n            \"Fanny, I am sure you know the part.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69870,\n            \"Maria joined them with the same intent, just then the stoutest of the three;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72344,\n            \"\\u201cIt is time to think of our visitors,\\u201dsaid Maria, still feeling her hand pressed to Henry Crawford\\u2019s heart, and caring little for anything else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75120,\n            \"She took to herself all the credit of bringing Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s admiration of Maria to any effect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76576,\n            \"and she had fondly hoped for such an immediate _ eclaircissement _ as might save him the trouble of ever coming back again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76770,\n            \"Sir Thomas soon appeared, and Maria saw with delight and agitation the introduction of the man she loved to her father.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76793,\n            \"Her sensations were indefinable, and so were they a few minutes afterwards upon hearing Henry Crawford, who had a chair between herself and Tom, ask the latter in an undervoice whether there were any plans for resuming the play after the present happy interruption (with a courteous glance at Sir Thomas), because, in that case, he should make a point of returning to Mansfield at any time required by the party: he was going away immediately, being to meet his uncle at Bath without delay;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77172,\n            \"To her he soon turned, repeating much of what he had already said, with only a softened air and stronger expressions of regret.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77243,\n            \"He might talk of necessity, but she knew his independence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77255,\n            \"The hand which had so pressed hers to his heart!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77292,\n            \"She had not long to endure what arose from listening to language which his actions contradicted, or to bury the tumult of her feelings under the restraint of society;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77323,\n            \"for general civilities soon called his notice from her, and the farewell visit, as it then became openly acknowledged, was a very short one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77351,\n            \"He was gone \\u2014 he had touched her hand for the last time, he had made his parting bow, and she might seek directly all that solitude could do for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77404,\n            \"and so ended all the hopes his selfish vanity had raised in Maria and Julia Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77439,\n            \"and if Maria gained him not, she was now cool enough to dispense with any other revenge.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78187,\n            \"\\u201d said Fanny: \\u201cin my opinion, my uncle would not like _ any _ addition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79583,\n            \"I am sorry for them all, and would give something that Rushworth and Maria had never met.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79869,\n            \"He would act for her and release her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79918,\n            \"She thanked him for his great attention, his paternal kindness, but he was quite mistaken in supposing she had the smallest desire of breaking through her engagement, or was sensible of any change of opinion or inclination since her forming it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80097,\n            \"he had never supposed them to be so;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80237,\n            \"happy to secure a marriage which would bring him such an addition of respectability and influence, and very happy to think anything of his daughter\\u2019s disposition that was most favourable for the purpose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80274,\n            \"To her the conference closed as satisfactorily as to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80285,\n            \"She was in a state of mind to be glad that she had secured her fate beyond recall: that she had pledged herself anew to Sotherton;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80335,\n            \"and retired in proud resolve, determined only to behave more cautiously to Mr. Rushworth in future, that her father might not be again suspecting her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80364,\n            \"Had Sir Thomas applied to his daughter within the first three or four days after Henry Crawford\\u2019s leaving Mansfield, before her feelings were at all tranquillised, before she had given up every hope of him, or absolutely resolved on enduring his rival, her answer might have been different;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80471,\n            \"Henry Crawford had destroyed her happiness, but he should not know that he had done it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80489,\n            \"he should not destroy her credit, her appearance, her prosperity, too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80504,\n            \"He should not have to think of her as pining in the retirement of Mansfield for _ him _, rejecting Sotherton and London, independence and splendour, for _ his _ sake.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80556,\n            \"She was less and less able to endure the restraint which her father imposed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80584,\n            \"She must escape from him and Mansfield as soon as possible, and find consolation in fortune and consequence, bustle and the world, for a wounded spirit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89408,\n            \"Her two absent cousins, especially Maria, were much in her thoughts on seeing him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127592,\n            \"but had Mr. Crawford sought Julia\\u2019s hand, I should have given it to him with superior and more heartfelt satisfaction than I gave Maria\\u2019s to Mr. Rushworth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133607,\n            \"\\u201d And still pursuing the same cheerful thoughts, she soon afterwards added, \\u201cAnd I will tell you what, Fanny, which is more than I did for Maria: the next time Pug has a litter you shall have a puppy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140315,\n            \"I then saw him behaving, as it appeared to me, so very improperly and unfeelingly \\u2014 I may speak of it now because it is all over \\u2014 so improperly by poor Mr. Rushworth, not seeming to care how he exposed or hurt him, and paying attentions to my cousin Maria, which \\u2014 in short, at the time of the play, I received an impression which will never be got over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140448,\n            \"Maria was wrong, Crawford was wrong, we were all wrong together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140553,\n            \"but, if she could undertake the part, we must not be surprised at the rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140571,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBefore the play, I am much mistaken if _ Julia _ did not think he was paying her attentions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140598,\n            \"I have heard before from some one of his being in love with Julia;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141201,\n            \"but yet I was afraid of her not estimating your worth to her brother quite as it deserved, and of her regretting that he had not rather fixed on some woman of distinction or fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141277,\n            \"She desires the connexion as warmly as your uncle or myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141394,\n            \"and when once we had begun, we had not done with you, Fanny, till Crawford and Dr. Grant came in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141419,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt is above a week since I saw Miss Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141539,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI knew she would be very angry with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170540,\n            \"I saw him draw back surprised, and I was sorry that Mrs. Rushworth should resent any former supposed slight to Miss Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170565,\n            \"You will wish to hear my opinion of Maria\\u2019s degree of comfort as a wife.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180649,\n            \"Mrs. Norris, however, as most attached to Maria, was really the greatest sufferer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183560,\n            \"but still more the folly of poor Maria, in sacrificing such a situation, plunging into such difficulties, under the idea of being really loved by a man who had long ago made his indifference clear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184133,\n            \"He would have taken no pains to be on terms with Mrs. Rushworth again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187638,\n            \"She persisted in placing his scruples to _ her _ account, though Sir Thomas very solemnly assured her that, had there been no young woman in question, had there been no young person of either sex belonging to him, to be endangered by the society or hurt by the character of Mrs. Rushworth, he would never have offered so great an insult to the neighbourhood as to expect it to notice her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187717,\n            \"As a daughter, he hoped a penitent one, she should be protected by him, and secured in every comfort, and supported by every encouragement to do right, which their relative situations admitted;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187766,\n            \"Maria had destroyed her own character, and he would not, by a vain attempt to restore what never could be restored, by affording his sanction to vice, or in seeking to lessen its disgrace, be anywise accessory to introducing such misery in another man\\u2019s family as he had known himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187824,\n            \"It ended in Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s resolving to quit Mansfield and devote herself to her unfortunate Maria, and in an establishment being formed for them in another country, remote and private, where, shut up together with little society, on one side no affection, on the other no judgment, it may be reasonably supposed that their tempers became their mutual punishment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188141,\n            \"That Julia escaped better than Maria was owing, in some measure, to a favourable difference of disposition and circumstance, but in a greater to her having been less the darling of that very aunt, less flattered and less spoilt.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 13]\": [\n        [\n            115,\n            \"and such of their acquaintance as thought Miss Ward and Miss Frances quite as handsome as Miss Maria, did not scruple to predict their marrying with almost equal advantage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            254,\n            \"and Mr. and Mrs. Norris began their career of conjugal felicity with very little less than a thousand a year.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            277,\n            \"But Miss Frances married, in the common phrase, to disoblige her family, and by fixing on a lieutenant of marines, without education, fortune, or connexions, did it very thoroughly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            502,\n            \"but Mrs. Norris had a spirit of activity, which could not be satisfied till she had written a long and angry letter to Fanny, to point out the folly of her conduct, and threaten her with all its possible ill consequences.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            561,\n            \"and an answer, which comprehended each sister in its bitterness, and bestowed such very disrespectful reflections on the pride of Sir Thomas as Mrs. Norris could not possibly keep to herself, put an end to all intercourse between them for a considerable period.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            609,\n            \"Their homes were so distant, and the circles in which they moved so distinct, as almost to preclude the means of ever hearing of each other\\u2019s existence during the eleven following years, or, at least, to make it very wonderful to Sir Thomas that Mrs. Norris should ever have it in her power to tell them, as she now and then did, in an angry voice, that Fanny had got another child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1005,\n            \"Mrs. Norris was often observing to the others that she could not get her poor sister and her family out of her head, and that, much as they had all done for her, she seemed to be wanting to do more;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1856,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI thoroughly understand you,\\u201dcried Mrs. Norris, \\u201cyou are everything that is generous and considerate, and I am sure we shall never disagree on this point.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2238,\n            \"for Sir Thomas was fully resolved to be the real and consistent patron of the selected child, and Mrs. Norris had not the least intention of being at any expense whatever in her maintenance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2275,\n            \"As far as walking, talking, and contriving reached, she was thoroughly benevolent, and nobody knew better how to dictate liberality to others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2399,\n            \"Had there been a family to provide for, Mrs. Norris might never have saved her money;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2638,\n            \"Mrs. Norris was sorry to say that the little girl\\u2019s staying with them, at least as things then were, was quite out of the question.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2897,\n            \"but you see I do all in my power.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2919,\n            \"and Nanny shall fetch her, however it may put me to inconvenience to have my chief counsellor away for three days.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2963,\n            \"It will be much the best place for her, so near Miss Lee, and not far from the girls, and close by the housemaids, who could either of them help to dress her, you know, and take care of her clothes, for I suppose you would not think it fair to expect Ellis to wait on her as well as the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3055,\n            \"\\u201cI hope she will prove a well-disposed girl,\\u201dcontinued Mrs. Norris, \\u201cand be sensible of her uncommon good fortune in having such friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3243,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat is exactly what I think,\\u201dcried Mrs. Norris, \\u201cand what I was saying to my husband this morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3270,\n            \"It will be an education for the child, said I, only being with her cousins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3337,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere will be some difficulty in our way, Mrs. Norris,\\u201dobserved Sir Thomas, \\u201cas to the distinction proper to be made between the girls as they grow up: how to preserve in the minds of my _ daughters _ the consciousness of what they are, without making them think too lowly of their cousin;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3502,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Norris was quite at his service;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3512,\n            \"and though she perfectly agreed with him as to its being a most difficult thing, encouraged him to hope that between them it would be easily managed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3675,\n            \"and at Northampton was met by Mrs. Norris, who thus regaled in the credit of being foremost to welcome her, and in the importance of leading her in to the others, and recommending her to their kindness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4178,\n            \"Mrs. Norris had been talking to her the whole way from Northampton of her wonderful good fortune, and the extraordinary degree of gratitude and good behaviour which it ought to produce, and her consciousness of misery was therefore increased by the idea of its being a wicked thing for her not to be happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4253,\n            \"In vain were the well-meant condescensions of Sir Thomas, and all the officious prognostications of Mrs. Norris that she would be a good girl;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4367,\n            \"\\u201cAfter all that I said to her as we came along, I thought she would have behaved better;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4388,\n            \"I told her how much might depend upon her acquitting herself well at first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4403,\n            \"I wish there may not be a little sulkiness of temper \\u2014 her poor mother had a good deal;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4423,\n            \"but we must make allowances for such a child \\u2014 and I do not know that her being sorry to leave her home is really against her, for, with all its faults, it _ was _ her home, and she cannot as yet understand how much she has changed for the better;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4721,\n            \"She was disheartened by Lady Bertram\\u2019s silence, awed by Sir Thomas\\u2019 s grave looks, and quite overcome by Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s admonitions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7914,\n            \"Miss Lee taught her French, and heard her read the daily portion of history;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8031,\n            \"Mrs. Norris, on quitting the Parsonage, removed first to the Park, and afterwards to a small house of Sir Thomas\\u2019 s in the village, and consoled herself for the loss of her husband by considering that she could do very well without him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8479,\n            \"On Mr. Norris\\u2019 s death the presentation became the right of a Dr. Grant, who came consequently to reside at Mansfield;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8591,\n            \"The time was now come when Sir Thomas expected his sister-in-law to claim her share in their niece, the change in Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s situation, and the improvement in Fanny\\u2019s age, seeming not merely to do away any former objection to their living together, but even to give it the most decided eligibility;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8821,\n            \"You have been five years with us, and my sister always meant to take you when Mr. Norris died.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8871,\n            \"She had never received kindness from her aunt Norris, and could not love her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9039,\n            \"she could not feel the difference to be so small, she could not think of living with her aunt with anything like satisfaction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9126,\n            \"I am going to live entirely with my aunt Norris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9145,\n            \"my aunt Bertram has just told me so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9159,\n            \"I am to leave Mansfield Park, and go to the White House, I suppose, as soon as she is removed there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9224,\n            \"My aunt is acting like a sensible woman in wishing for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9261,\n            \"You will be what you ought to be to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9310,\n            \"You know how uncomfortable I feel with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9642,\n            \"The only difference will be that, living with your aunt, you will necessarily be brought forward as you ought to be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9679,\n            \"but with _ her _ you will be forced to speak for yourself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9715,\n            \"Mrs. Norris is much better fitted than my mother for having the charge of you now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9733,\n            \"She is of a temper to do a great deal for anybody she really interests herself about, and she will force you to do justice to your natural powers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9811,\n            \"If I could suppose my aunt really to care for me, it would be delightful to feel myself of consequence to anybody.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10055,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd I am quite convinced that your being with Mrs. Norris will be as good for your mind as riding has been for your health, and as much for your ultimate happiness too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10152,\n            \"To prevent its being expected, she had fixed on the smallest habitation which could rank as genteel among the buildings of Mansfield parish, the White House being only just large enough to receive herself and her servants, and allow a spare room for a friend, of which she made a very particular point.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10281,\n            \"Lady Bertram soon brought the matter to a certainty by carelessly observing to Mrs. Norris \\u2014 \\u201cI think, sister, we need not keep Miss Lee any longer, when Fanny goes to live with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11123,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, Lady Bertram,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris, moving to go, \\u201cI can only say that my sole desire is to be of use to your family: and so, if Sir Thomas should ever speak again about my taking Fanny, you will be able to say that my health and spirits put it quite out of the question;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11192,\n            \"besides that, I really should not have a bed to give her, for I must keep a spare room for a friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11217,\n            \"\\u201d Lady Bertram repeated enough of this conversation to her husband to convince him how much he had mistaken his sister-in-law\\u2019s views;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11246,\n            \"and she was from that moment perfectly safe from all expectation, or the slightest allusion to it from him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11267,\n            \"He could not but wonder at her refusing to do anything for a niece whom she had been so forward to adopt;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11290,\n            \"but, as she took early care to make him, as well as Lady Bertram, understand that whatever she possessed was designed for their family, he soon grew reconciled to a distinction which, at the same time that it was advantageous and complimentary to them, would enable him better to provide for Fanny himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11394,\n            \"Mrs. Norris took possession of the White House, the Grants arrived at the Parsonage, and these events over, everything at Mansfield went on for some time as usual.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11449,\n            \"They had their faults, and Mrs. Norris soon found them out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11546,\n            \"\\u201cNobody loved plenty and hospitality more than herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11562,\n            \"the Parsonage, she believed, had never been wanting in comforts of any sort, had never borne a bad character in _ her _ _ time _, but this was a way of going on that she could not understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11678,\n            \"She could not enter into the wrongs of an economist, but she felt all the injuries of beauty in Mrs. Grant\\u2019s being so well settled in life without being handsome, and expressed her astonishment on that point almost as often, though not so diffusely, as Mrs. Norris discussed the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11905,\n            \"but, in Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s watchful attention, and in Edmund\\u2019s judgment, he had sufficient confidence to make him go without fears for their conduct.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12403,\n            \"and Lady Bertram was soon astonished to find how very well they did even without his father, how well Edmund could supply his place in carving, talking to the steward, writing to the attorney, settling with the servants, and equally saving her from all possible fatigue or exertion in every particular but that of directing her letters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12486,\n            \"though not before Mrs. Norris had been indulging in very dreadful fears, and trying to make Edmund participate them whenever she could get him alone;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12590,\n            \"and Mrs. Norris, in promoting gaieties for her nieces, assisting their toilets, displaying their accomplishments, and looking about for their future husbands, had so much to do as, in addition to all her own household cares, some interference in those of her sister, and Mrs. Grant\\u2019s wasteful doings to overlook, left her very little occasion to be occupied in fears for the absent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12737,\n            \"while the praises attending such behaviour, secured and brought round by their aunt, served to strengthen them in believing they had no faults.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12852,\n            \"but she enjoyed being avowedly useful as her aunt\\u2019s companion when they called away the rest of the family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13242,\n            \"and Mrs. Norris, who was walking all day, thinking everybody ought to walk as much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13404,\n            \"She could not but consider it as absolutely unnecessary, and even improper, that Fanny should have a regular lady\\u2019s horse of her own, in the style of her cousins.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13944,\n            \"and had Lady Bertram ever thought about her own objection again, he might have been excused in her eyes for not waiting till Sir Thomas\\u2019 s return in September, for when September came Sir Thomas was still abroad, and without any near prospect of finishing his business.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14073,\n            \"Sir Thomas\\u2019 s sending away his son seemed to her so like a parent\\u2019s care, under the influence of a foreboding of evil to himself, that she could not help feeling dreadful presentiments;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14438,\n            \"and, among other means, by seeking an intimacy with the gentleman\\u2019s mother, who at present lived with him, and to whom she even forced Lady Bertram to go through ten miles of indifferent road to pay a morning visit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14726,\n            \"but, in the meanwhile, as no one felt a doubt of his most cordial pleasure in the connexion, the intercourse of the two families was carried on without restraint, and no other attempt made at secrecy than Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s talking of it everywhere as a matter not to be talked of at present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14804,\n            \"but no representation of his aunt\\u2019s could induce him to find Mr. Rushworth a desirable companion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19974,\n            \"and on their all dining together at the Park soon after his going, she retook her chosen place near the bottom of the table, fully expecting to feel a most melancholy difference in the change of masters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20089,\n            \"\\u201d She must try to find amusement in what was passing at the upper end of the table, and in observing Mr. Rushworth, who was now making his appearance at Mansfield for the first time since the Crawfords\\u2019 arrival.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20221,\n            \"Miss Bertram\\u2019s attention and opinion was evidently his chief aim;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20234,\n            \"and though her deportment showed rather conscious superiority than any solicitude to oblige him, the mention of Sotherton Court, and the ideas attached to it, gave her a feeling of complacency, which prevented her from being very ungracious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20277,\n            \"\\u201cI wish you could see Compton,\\u201dsaid he;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20441,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo wonder that Mr. Rushworth should think so at present,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Grant to Mrs. Norris, with a smile;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20527,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYour best friend upon such an occasion,\\u201dsaid Miss Bertram calmly, \\u201cwould be Mr. Repton, I imagine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20628,\n            \"If I were you, I should not think of the expense.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20852,\n            \"He could hardly ever get out, poor man, to enjoy anything, and _ that _ disheartened me from doing several things that Sir Thomas and I used to talk of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20932,\n            \"It was only the spring twelvemonth before Mr. Norris\\u2019 s death that we put in the apricot against the stable wall, which is now grown such a noble tree, and getting to such perfection, sir,\\u201daddressing herself then to Dr. Grant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21142,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThe truth is, ma\\u2019am,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Grant, pretending to whisper across the table to Mrs. Norris, \\u201cthat Dr. Grant hardly knows what the natural taste of our apricot is: he is scarcely ever indulged with one, for it is so valuable a fruit;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21333,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMr. Rushworth,\\u201dsaid Lady Bertram, \\u201cif I were you, I would have a very pretty shrubbery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21370,\n            \"\\u201d Mr. Rushworth was eager to assure her ladyship of his acquiescence, and tried to make out something complimentary;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21392,\n            \"but, between his submission to _ her _ taste, and his having always intended the same himself, with the superadded objects of professing attention to the comfort of ladies in general, and of insinuating that there was one only whom he was anxious to please, he grew puzzled, and Edmund was glad to put an end to his speech by a proposal of wine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21557,\n            \"There have been two or three fine old trees cut down, that grew too near the house, and it opens the prospect amazingly, which makes me think that Repton, or anybody of that sort, would certainly have the avenue at Sotherton down: the avenue that leads from the west front to the top of the hill, you know,\\u201dturning to Miss Bertram particularly as he spoke.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21848,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI collect,\\u201dsaid Miss Crawford, \\u201cthat Sotherton is an old place, and a place of some grandeur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28170,\n            \"and even Mrs. Norris, discomposed by her niece\\u2019s ill-humour, and having asked one or two questions about the dinner, which were not immediately attended to, seemed almost determined to say no more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28291,\n            \"\\u201d Her own gentle voice speaking from the other end of the room, which was a very long one, told them that she was on the sofa.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28365,\n            \"If you have no work of your own, I can supply you from the poor basket.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28422,\n            \"and, take my word for it, it is a shocking trick for a young person to be always lolling upon a sofa.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28614,\n            \"to be sure she did,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris: \\u201cwould you have her stay within such a fine day as this?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28825,\n            \"\\u201cbut I question whether her headache might not be caught _ then _, sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28871,\n            \"Suppose you let her have your aromatic vinegar;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28888,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cShe has got it,\\u201dsaid Lady Bertram;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28900,\n            \"\\u201cshe has had it ever since she came back from your house the second time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28974,\n            \"\\u201cI was afraid it would be too much for her,\\u201dsaid Lady Bertram;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29166,\n            \"and I was talking to Mr. Green at that very time about your mother\\u2019s dairymaid, by _ her _ desire, and had promised John Groom to write to Mrs. Jefferies about his son, and the poor fellow was waiting for me half an hour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29218,\n            \"I think nobody can justly accuse me of sparing myself upon any occasion, but really I cannot do everything at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29341,\n            \"She has not been out on horseback now this long while, and I am persuaded that, when she does not ride, she ought to walk.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29370,\n            \"If she had been riding before, I should not have asked it of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29386,\n            \"But I thought it would rather do her good after being stooping among the roses;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29432,\n            \"Between ourselves, Edmund,\\u201dnodding significantly at his mother, \\u201cit was cutting the roses, and dawdling about in the flower-garden, that did the mischief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29488,\n            \"\\u201cI am very much afraid she caught the headache there, for the heat was enough to kill anybody.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29519,\n            \"Sitting and calling to Pug, and trying to keep him from the flower-beds, was almost too much for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29892,\n            \"While she was gone Mr. Rushworth arrived, escorting his mother, who came to be civil and to shew her civility especially, in urging the execution of the plan for visiting Sotherton, which had been started a fortnight before, and which, in consequence of her subsequent absence from home, had since lain dormant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29953,\n            \"Mrs. Norris and her nieces were all well pleased with its revival, and an early day was named and agreed to, provided Mr. Crawford should be disengaged: the young ladies did not forget that stipulation, and though Mrs. Norris would willingly have answered for his being so, they would neither authorise the liberty nor run the risk;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30153,\n            \"and Mrs. Rushworth, a well-meaning, civil, prosing, pompous woman, who thought nothing of consequence, but as it related to her own and her son\\u2019s concerns, had not yet given over pressing Lady Bertram to be of the party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30210,\n            \"but her placid manner of refusal made Mrs. Rushworth still think she wished to come, till Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s more numerous words and louder tone convinced her of the truth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30245,\n            \"\\u201cThe fatigue would be too much for my sister, a great deal too much, I assure you, my dear Mrs. Rushworth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30283,\n            \"You must excuse my sister on this occasion, and accept of our two dear girls and myself without her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30461,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou are very kind, you are all kindness, my dear madam,\\u201dcried Mrs. Norris;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30727,\n            \"The Miss Bertrams laughed at the idea, assuring her that the barouche would hold four perfectly well, independent of the box, on which _ one _ might go with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31196,\n            \"I told Mrs. Rushworth so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31208,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou can have no reason, I imagine, madam,\\u201dsaid he, addressing his mother, \\u201cfor wishing Fanny _ not _ to be of the party, but as it relates to yourself, to your own comfort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31357,\n            \"She has not often a gratification of the kind, and I am sure, ma\\u2019am, you would be glad to give her the pleasure now?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31402,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Norris was very ready with the only objection which could remain \\u2014 their having positively assured Mrs. Rushworth that Fanny could not go, and the very strange appearance there would consequently be in taking her, which seemed to her a difficulty quite impossible to be got over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31575,\n            \"When Edmund, therefore, told her in reply, as he did when she would give him the hearing, that she need not distress herself on Mrs. Rushworth\\u2019s account, because he had taken the opportunity, as he walked with her through the hall, of mentioning Miss Price as one who would probably be of the party, and had directly received a very sufficient invitation for his cousin, Mrs. Norris was too much vexed to submit with a very good grace, and would only say, \\u201cVery well, very well, just as you chuse, settle it your own way, I am sure I do not care about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41625,\n            \"On reaching the bottom of the steps to the terrace, Mrs. Rushworth and Mrs. Norris presented themselves at the top, just ready for the wilderness, at the end of an hour and a half from their leaving the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41682,\n            \"Whatever cross-accidents had occurred to intercept the pleasures of her nieces, she had found a morning of complete enjoyment;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41745,\n            \"and since Julia\\u2019s leaving them they had been met by the gardener, with whom she had made a most satisfactory acquaintance, for she had set him right as to his grandson\\u2019s illness, convinced him that it was an ague, and promised him a charm for it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42069,\n            \"and from the time of their sitting down to table, it was a quick succession of busy nothings till the carriage came to the door, and Mrs. Norris, having fidgeted about, and obtained a few pheasants\\u2019 eggs and a cream cheese from the housekeeper, and made abundance of civil speeches to Mrs. Rushworth, was ready to lead the way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42282,\n            \"\\u201cWell, Fanny, this has been a fine day for you, upon my word,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris, as they drove through the park.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42382,\n            \"Your lap seems full of good things, and here is a basket of something between us which has been knocking my elbow unmercifully.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52224,\n            \"and as to Mrs. Norris, he was mistaken in supposing she would wish to make any.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52243,\n            \"She started no difficulties that were not talked down in five minutes by her eldest nephew and niece, who were all-powerful with her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52270,\n            \"and as the whole arrangement was to bring very little expense to anybody, and none at all to herself, as she foresaw in it all the comforts of hurry, bustle, and importance, and derived the immediate advantage of fancying herself obliged to leave her own house, where she had been living a month at her own cost, and take up her abode in theirs, that every hour might be spent in their service, she was, in fact, exceedingly delighted with the project.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52450,\n            \"An enormous roll of green baize had arrived from Northampton, and been cut out by Mrs. Norris (with a saving by her good management of full three-quarters of a yard), and was actually forming into a curtain by the housemaids, and still the play was wanting;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59389,\n            \"and before she could breathe after it, Mrs. Norris completed the whole by thus addressing her in a whisper at once angry and audible \\u2014 \\u201cWhat a piece of work here is about nothing: I am quite ashamed of you, Fanny, to make such a difficulty of obliging your cousins in a trifle of this sort \\u2014 so kind as they are to you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59460,\n            \"Take the part with a good grace, and let us hear no more of the matter, I entreat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59545,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am not going to urge her,\\u201dreplied Mrs. Norris sharply;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59562,\n            \"\\u201cbut I shall think her a very obstinate, ungrateful girl, if she does not do what her aunt and cousins wish her \\u2014 very ungrateful, indeed, considering who and what she is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59608,\n            \"but Miss Crawford, looking for a moment with astonished eyes at Mrs. Norris, and then at Fanny, whose tears were beginning to shew themselves, immediately said, with some keenness, \\u201cI do not like my situation: this _ place _ is too hot for me,\\u201dand moved away her chair to the opposite side of the table, close to Fanny, saying to her, in a kind, low whisper, as she placed herself, \\u201cNever mind, my dear Miss Price, this is a cross evening: everybody is cross and teasing, but do not let us mind them \\u201d;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60481,\n            \"When the evening was over, she went to bed full of it, her nerves still agitated by the shock of such an attack from her cousin Tom, so public and so persevered in, and her spirits sinking under her aunt\\u2019s unkind reflection and reproach.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61011,\n            \"and Mrs. Norris, having stipulated for there never being a fire in it on Fanny\\u2019s account, was tolerably resigned to her having the use of what nobody else wanted, though the terms in which she sometimes spoke of the indulgence seemed to imply that it was the best room in the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71251,\n            \"She had been _ almost _ fluttered for a few minutes, and still remained so sensibly animated as to put away her work, move Pug from her side, and give all her attention and all the rest of her sofa to her husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71298,\n            \"She had no anxieties for anybody to cloud _ her _ pleasure: her own time had been irreproachably spent during his absence: she had done a great deal of carpet-work, and made many yards of fringe;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71340,\n            \"and she would have answered as freely for the good conduct and useful pursuits of all the young people as for her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71364,\n            \"It was so agreeable to her to see him again, and hear him talk, to have her ear amused and her whole comprehension filled by his narratives, that she began particularly to feel how dreadfully she must have missed him, and how impossible it would have been for her to bear a lengthened absence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71423,\n            \"Mrs. Norris was by no means to be compared in happiness to her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71439,\n            \"Not that _ she _ was incommoded by many fears of Sir Thomas\\u2019 s disapprobation when the present state of his house should be known, for her judgment had been so blinded that, except by the instinctive caution with which she had whisked away Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s pink satin cloak as her brother-in-law entered, she could hardly be said to shew any sign of alarm;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71515,\n            \"but she was vexed by the _ manner _ of his return.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71603,\n            \"Mrs. Norris felt herself defrauded of an office on which she had always depended, whether his arrival or his death were to be the thing unfolded;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71662,\n            \"Would Sir Thomas have consented to eat, she might have gone to the housekeeper with troublesome directions, and insulted the footmen with injunctions of despatch;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71726,\n            \"and in the most interesting moment of his passage to England, when the alarm of a French privateer was at the height, she burst through his recital with the proposal of soup.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71799,\n            \"\\u201cStill the same anxiety for everybody\\u2019s comfort, my dear Mrs. Norris,\\u201dwas his answer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75814,\n            \"and is so disposed to look up to you, that I am quite laughed at about it, for everybody considers it as my doing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75841,\n            \"\\u2018 Upon my word, Mrs. Norris,\\u2019said Mrs. Grant the other day, \\u2018 if Mr. Rushworth were a son of your own, he could not hold Sir Thomas in greater respect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81027,\n            \"Mrs. Norris, most happy to assist in the duties of the day, by spending it at the Park to support her sister\\u2019s spirits, and drinking the health of Mr. and Mrs. Rushworth in a supernumerary glass or two, was all joyous delight;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87490,\n            \"for Lady Bertram never thought of being useful to anybody, and Mrs. Norris, when she came on the morrow, in consequence of an early call and invitation from Sir Thomas, was in a very ill humour, and seemed intent only on lessening her niece\\u2019s pleasure, both present and future, as much as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87610,\n            \"for I hope you are aware that there is no real occasion for your going into company in this sort of way, or ever dining out at all;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87672,\n            \"the compliment is intended to your uncle and aunt and me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87741,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Norris had now so ingeniously done away all Mrs. Grant\\u2019s part of the favour, that Fanny, who found herself expected to speak, could only say that she was very much obliged to her aunt Bertram for sparing her, and that she was endeavouring to put her aunt\\u2019s evening work in such a state as to prevent her being missed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87855,\n            \"And I hope you will have a very _ agreeable _ day, and find it all mighty _ delightful _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88034,\n            \"However, you will have dinner enough on it for ten, I dare say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88062,\n            \"\\u201cThe nonsense and folly of people\\u2019s stepping out of their rank and trying to appear above themselves, makes me think it right to give _ you _ a hint, Fanny, now that you are going into company without any of us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88110,\n            \"and I do beseech and entreat you not to be putting yourself forward, and talking and giving your opinion as if you were one of your cousins \\u2014 as if you were dear Mrs. Rushworth or Julia.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88225,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, ma\\u2019am, I should not think of anything else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88241,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd if it should rain, which I think exceedingly likely, for I never saw it more threatening for a wet evening in my life, you must manage as well as you can, and not be expecting the carriage to be sent for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88341,\n            \"She rated her own claims to comfort as low even as Mrs. Norris could;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88496,\n            \"and not bearing to remain with her in what might seem a state of triumph, she followed her uncle out of the room, having staid behind him only long enough to hear these words spoken in angry agitation \\u2014 \\u201cQuite unnecessary!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88579,\n            \"She felt that the carriage was for herself, and herself alone: and her uncle\\u2019s consideration of her, coming immediately after such representations from her aunt, cost her some tears of gratitude when she was alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100612,\n            \"and Sir Thomas, by no means displeased, prolonged the conversation on dancing in general, and was so well engaged in describing the balls of Antigua, and listening to what his nephew could relate of the different modes of dancing which had fallen within his observation, that he had not heard his carriage announced, and was first called to the knowledge of it by the bustle of Mrs. Norris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100717,\n            \"I cannot bear to keep good old Wilcox waiting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101279,\n            \"His daughters absent and herself not consulted!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101340,\n            \"and this reflection quickly restored so much of her good-humour as enabled her to join in with the others, before their happiness and thanks were all expressed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101926,\n            \"The preparations meanwhile went on, and Lady Bertram continued to sit on her sofa without any inconvenience from them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101947,\n            \"She had some extra visits from the housekeeper, and her maid was rather hurried in making up a new dress for her: Sir Thomas gave orders, and Mrs. Norris ran about;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109521,\n            \"she felt it to be indeed very charming, and was actually practising her steps about the drawing-room as long as she could be safe from the notice of her aunt Norris, who was entirely taken up at first in fresh arranging and injuring the noble fire which the butler had prepared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111326,\n            \"Miss Crawford knew Mrs. Norris too well to think of gratifying _ her _ by commendation of Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111377,\n            \"\\u201d and Mrs. Norris paid her with as many smiles and courteous words as she had time for, amid so much occupation as she found for herself in making up card-tables, giving hints to Sir Thomas, and trying to move all the chaperons to a better part of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121998,\n            \"He had a note to deliver from his sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122171,\n            \"so you may smile upon him with your sweetest smiles this afternoon, and send him back to me even happier than he goes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122214,\n            \"for though she read in too much haste and confusion to form the clearest judgment of Miss Crawford\\u2019s meaning, it was evident that she meant to compliment her on her brother\\u2019s attachment, and even to _ appear _ to believe it serious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122466,\n            \"She thought Lady Bertram sat longer than ever, and began to be in despair of ever getting away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122828,\n            \"\\u201cIt is amazing,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201chow much young people cost their friends, what with bringing them up and putting them out in the world!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122900,\n            \"take them all together, I dare say nobody would believe what a sum they cost Sir Thomas every year, to say nothing of what _ I _ do for them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124757,\n            \"but being obliged to speak, she could not forbear, in justice to the aunt she loved best, from saying something in which the words \\u201cmy aunt Norris\\u201dwere distinguishable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124815,\n            \"Your aunt Norris has always been an advocate, and very judiciously, for young people\\u2019s being brought up without unnecessary indulgences;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124848,\n            \"She is also very hardy herself, which of course will influence her in her opinion of the wants of others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125075,\n            \"I am sure you will not disappoint my opinion of you, by failing at any time to treat your aunt Norris with the respect and attention that are due to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128286,\n            \"but when he looked at his niece, and saw the state of feature and complexion which her crying had brought her into, he thought there might be as much lost as gained by an immediate interview.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129072,\n            \"and she felt equal to almost anything that might save her from her aunt Norris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129233,\n            \"\\u201d She saw nothing more of her uncle, nor of her aunt Norris, till they met at dinner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129299,\n            \"but her aunt was soon quarrelling with her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129308,\n            \"and when she found how much and how unpleasantly her having only walked out without her aunt\\u2019s knowledge could be dwelt on, she felt all the reason she had to bless the kindness which saved her from the same spirit of reproach, exerted on a more momentous subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129361,\n            \"\\u201cIf I had known you were going out, I should have got you just to go as far as my house with some orders for Nanny,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cwhich I have since, to my very great inconvenience, been obliged to go and carry myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129414,\n            \"I could very ill spare the time, and you might have saved me the trouble, if you would only have been so good as to let us know you were going out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129697,\n            \"for Mrs. Norris had not discernment enough to perceive, either now, or at any other time, to what degree he thought well of his niece, or how very far he was from wishing to have his own children\\u2019s merits set off by the depreciation of hers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130118,\n            \"but instantly rising, she was preparing to obey, when Mrs. Norris called out, \\u201cStay, stay, Fanny!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130173,\n            \"depend upon it, it is me\\u201d(looking at the butler);\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130297,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Norris, much discontented, was obliged to compose herself to work again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132948,\n            \"She only looked her increased ill-will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133003,\n            \"and, independently of that, she disliked Fanny, because she had neglected her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149143,\n            \"And as to the not missing her, which under Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s discussion was the point attempted to be proved, she set herself very steadily against admitting any such thing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149741,\n            \"and for part of one of those days the young travellers were in a good deal of alarm on the subject of their journey, for when the mode of it came to be talked of, and Mrs. Norris found that all her anxiety to save her brother-in-law\\u2019s money was vain, and that in spite of her wishes and hints for a less expensive conveyance of Fanny, they were to travel post;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149824,\n            \"when she saw Sir Thomas actually give William notes for the purpose, she was struck with the idea of there being room for a third in the carriage, and suddenly seized with a strong inclination to go with them, to go and see her poor dear sister Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156099,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny had indeed nothing to convey from aunt Norris, but a message to say she hoped that her god-daughter was a good girl, and learnt her book.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156392,\n            \"CHAPTER XXXIX Could Sir Thomas have seen all his niece\\u2019s feelings, when she wrote her first letter to her aunt, he would not have despaired;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156928,\n            \"Her disappointment in her mother was greater: _ there _ she had hoped much, and found almost nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156971,\n            \"but, instead of gaining on her affection and confidence, and becoming more and more dear, her daughter never met with greater kindness from her than on the first day of her arrival.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157048,\n            \"Her daughters never had been much to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157057,\n            \"She was fond of her sons, especially of William, but Betsey was the first of her girls whom she had ever much regarded.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157127,\n            \"These shared her heart: her time was given chiefly to her house and her servants.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157215,\n            \"Of her two sisters, Mrs. Price very much more resembled Lady Bertram than Mrs. Norris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157234,\n            \"She was a manager by necessity, without any of Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s inclination for it, or any of her activity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157311,\n            \"She might have made just as good a woman of consequence as Lady Bertram, but Mrs. Norris would have been a more respectable mother of nine children on a small income.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157357,\n            \"She might scruple to make use of the words, but she must and did feel that her mother was a partial, ill-judging parent, a dawdle, a slattern, who neither taught nor restrained her children, whose house was the scene of mismanagement and discomfort from beginning to end, and who had no talent, no conversation, no affection towards herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180649,\n            \"Mrs. Norris, however, as most attached to Maria, was really the greatest sufferer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180726,\n            \"The being left with her sister and nephew, and all the house under her care, had been an advantage entirely thrown away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180798,\n            \"She had done no more for them than they had done for each other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180825,\n            \"and now the arrival of the others only established her superiority in wretchedness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182439,\n            \"His displeasure against herself she trusted, reasoning differently from Mrs. Norris, would now be done away.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 14]\": [\n        [\n            463,\n            \"Lady Bertram, who was a woman of very tranquil feelings, and a temper remarkably easy and indolent, would have contented herself with merely giving up her sister, and thinking no more of the matter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1005,\n            \"Mrs. Norris was often observing to the others that she could not get her poor sister and her family out of her head, and that, much as they had all done for her, she seemed to be wanting to do more;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1145,\n            \"\\u201d Lady Bertram agreed with her instantly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1153,\n            \"\\u201cI think we cannot do better,\\u201dsaid she;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1165,\n            \"\\u201clet us send for the child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1782,\n            \"I only meant to observe that it ought not to be lightly engaged in, and that to make it really serviceable to Mrs. Price, and creditable to ourselves, we must secure to the child, or consider ourselves engaged to secure to her hereafter, as circumstances may arise, the provision of a gentlewoman, if no such establishment should offer as you are so sanguine in expecting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2029,\n            \"So, if you are not against it, I will write to my poor sister tomorrow, and make the proposal;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2094,\n            \"I will send Nanny to London on purpose, and she may have a bed at her cousin the saddler\\u2019s, and the child be appointed to meet her there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2454,\n            \"Under this infatuating principle, counteracted by no real affection for her sister, it was impossible for her to aim at more than the credit of projecting and arranging so expensive a charity;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2768,\n            \"\\u201cThen she had better come to us,\\u201dsaid Lady Bertram, with the utmost composure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2963,\n            \"It will be much the best place for her, so near Miss Lee, and not far from the girls, and close by the housemaids, who could either of them help to dress her, you know, and take care of her clothes, for I suppose you would not think it fair to expect Ellis to wait on her as well as the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3308,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI hope she will not tease my poor pug,\\u201dsaid Lady Bertram;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3337,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere will be some difficulty in our way, Mrs. Norris,\\u201dobserved Sir Thomas, \\u201cas to the distinction proper to be made between the girls as they grow up: how to preserve in the minds of my _ daughters _ the consciousness of what they are, without making them think too lowly of their cousin;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3559,\n            \"Mrs. Price seemed rather surprised that a girl should be fixed on, when she had so many fine boys, but accepted the offer most thankfully, assuring them of her daughter\\u2019s being a very well-disposed, good-humoured girl, and trusting they would never have cause to throw her off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4282,\n            \"in vain did Lady Bertram smile and make her sit on the sofa with herself and pug, and vain was even the sight of a gooseberry tart towards giving her comfort;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6958,\n            \"She was a woman who spent her days in sitting, nicely dressed, on a sofa, doing some long piece of needlework, of little use and no beauty, thinking more of her pug than her children, but very indulgent to the latter when it did not put herself to inconvenience, guided in everything important by Sir Thomas, and in smaller concerns by her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7030,\n            \"Had she possessed greater leisure for the service of her girls, she would probably have supposed it unnecessary, for they were under the care of a governess, with proper masters, and could want nothing more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7070,\n            \"As for Fanny\\u2019s being stupid at learning, \\u201cshe could only say it was very unlucky, but some people _ were _ stupid, and Fanny must take more pains: she did not know what else was to be done;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9272,\n            \"I hope it does not distress you very much, Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9310,\n            \"You know how uncomfortable I feel with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9319,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI can say nothing for her manner to you as a child;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9369,\n            \"I think she is behaving better already;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9425,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAs to your foolishness and awkwardness, my dear Fanny, believe me, you never have a shadow of either, but in using the words so improperly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9475,\n            \"You have good sense, and a sweet temper, and I am sure you have a grateful heart, that could never receive kindness without wishing to return it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9535,\n            \"\\u201chow shall I ever thank you as I ought, for thinking so well of me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9555,\n            \"cousin, if I am to go away, I shall remember your goodness to the last moment of my life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9764,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny sighed, and said, \\u201cI cannot see things as you do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9780,\n            \"but I ought to believe you to be right rather than myself, and I am very much obliged to you for trying to reconcile me to what must be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9983,\n            \"how I have trembled at my uncle\\u2019s opening his lips if horses were talked of), and then think of the kind pains you took to reason and persuade me out of my fears, and convince me that I should like it after a little while, and feel how right you proved to be, I am inclined to hope you may always prophesy as well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10055,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd I am quite convinced that your being with Mrs. Norris will be as good for your mind as riding has been for your health, and as much for your ultimate happiness too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10281,\n            \"Lady Bertram soon brought the matter to a certainty by carelessly observing to Mrs. Norris \\u2014 \\u201cI think, sister, we need not keep Miss Lee any longer, when Fanny goes to live with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10328,\n            \"\\u201cLive with me, dear Lady Bertram!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10352,\n            \"I thought you had settled it with Sir Thomas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10630,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDear sister, if you consider my unhappy state, how can she be any comfort to me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10795,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cLady Bertram, I do not complain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10961,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI dare say you will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10978,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy object, Lady Bertram, is to be of use to those that come after me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11123,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, Lady Bertram,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris, moving to go, \\u201cI can only say that my sole desire is to be of use to your family: and so, if Sir Thomas should ever speak again about my taking Fanny, you will be able to say that my health and spirits put it quite out of the question;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11217,\n            \"\\u201d Lady Bertram repeated enough of this conversation to her husband to convince him how much he had mistaken his sister-in-law\\u2019s views;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11290,\n            \"but, as she took early care to make him, as well as Lady Bertram, understand that whatever she possessed was designed for their family, he soon grew reconciled to a distinction which, at the same time that it was advantageous and complimentary to them, would enable him better to provide for Fanny himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11678,\n            \"She could not enter into the wrongs of an economist, but she felt all the injuries of beauty in Mrs. Grant\\u2019s being so well settled in life without being handsome, and expressed her astonishment on that point almost as often, though not so diffusely, as Mrs. Norris discussed the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11878,\n            \"He could not think Lady Bertram quite equal to supply his place with them, or rather, to perform what should have been her own;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11937,\n            \"Lady Bertram did not at all like to have her husband leave her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12763,\n            \"Lady Bertram did not go into public with her daughters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12874,\n            \"and, as Miss Lee had left Mansfield, she naturally became everything to Lady Bertram during the night of a ball or a party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13089,\n            \"for in spite of the acknowledged importance of her riding on horse-back, no measures were taken for mounting her again, \\u201cbecause,\\u201das it was observed by her aunts, \\u201cshe might ride one of her cousin\\u2019s horses at any time when they did not want them,\\u201dand as the Miss Bertrams regularly wanted their horses every fine day, and had no idea of carrying their obliging manners to the sacrifice of any real pleasure, that time, of course, never came.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13200,\n            \"and Fanny either sat at home the whole day with one aunt, or walked beyond her strength at the instigation of the other: Lady Bertram holding exercise to be as unnecessary for everybody as it was unpleasant to herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13914,\n            \"As the horse continued in name, as well as fact, the property of Edmund, Mrs. Norris could tolerate its being for Fanny\\u2019s use;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13944,\n            \"and had Lady Bertram ever thought about her own objection again, he might have been excused in her eyes for not waiting till Sir Thomas\\u2019 s return in September, for when September came Sir Thomas was still abroad, and without any near prospect of finishing his business.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14267,\n            \"Mr. Rushworth was from the first struck with the beauty of Miss Bertram, and, being inclined to marry, soon fancied himself in love.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14438,\n            \"and, among other means, by seeking an intimacy with the gentleman\\u2019s mother, who at present lived with him, and to whom she even forced Lady Bertram to go through ten miles of indifferent road to pay a morning visit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15937,\n            \"and therefore, Henry, you shall marry the youngest Miss Bertram, a nice, handsome, good-humoured, accomplished girl, who will make you very happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16128,\n            \"If your Miss Bertrams do not like to have their hearts broke, let them avoid Henry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23079,\n            \"\\u201cI shall be most happy to play to you both,\\u201dsaid Miss Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23477,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMiss Price has a brother at sea,\\u201dsaid Edmund, \\u201cwhose excellence as a correspondent makes her think you too severe upon us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24236,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Grant, hearing the latter part of this speech, enforced it warmly, persuaded that no judgment could be equal to her brother\\u2019s;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24266,\n            \"and as Miss Bertram caught at the idea likewise, and gave it her full support, declaring that, in her opinion, it was infinitely better to consult with friends and disinterested advisers, than immediately to throw the business into the hands of a professional man, Mr. Rushworth was very ready to request the favour of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s assistance;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24387,\n            \"when Mrs. Norris, as if reading in her two nieces\\u2019 minds their little approbation of a plan which was to take Mr. Crawford away, interposed with an amendment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24502,\n            \"and, for my own part, I have been long wishing to wait upon your good mother again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24537,\n            \"but now I could go and sit a few hours with Mrs. Rushworth, while the rest of you walked about and settled things, and then we could all return to a late dinner here, or dine at Sotherton, just as might be most agreeable to your mother, and have a pleasant drive home by moonlight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24934,\n            \"With such warm feelings and lively spirits it must be difficult to do justice to her affection for Mrs. Crawford, without throwing a shade on the Admiral.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25595,\n            \"Mrs. Grant and her tambour frame were not without their use: it was all in harmony;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25881,\n            \"neither could she wonder that, when the evening stroll was over, and the two families parted again, he should think it right to attend Mrs. Grant and her sister to their home, while Mr. Crawford was devoted to the ladies of the Park;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26411,\n            \"Fanny was ready and waiting, and Mrs. Norris was beginning to scold her for not being gone, and still no horse was announced, no Edmund appeared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30019,\n            \"and at last, on a hint from Miss Bertram, Mr. Rushworth discovered that the properest thing to be done was for him to walk down to the Parsonage directly, and call on Mr. Crawford, and inquire whether Wednesday would suit him or not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30153,\n            \"and Mrs. Rushworth, a well-meaning, civil, prosing, pompous woman, who thought nothing of consequence, but as it related to her own and her son\\u2019s concerns, had not yet given over pressing Lady Bertram to be of the party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30210,\n            \"but her placid manner of refusal made Mrs. Rushworth still think she wished to come, till Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s more numerous words and louder tone convinced her of the truth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30386,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Rushworth being obliged to yield to Lady Bertram\\u2019s staying at home, could only be sorry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31892,\n            \"Mrs. Grant offered herself as companion for the day to Lady Bertram in lieu of her son, and Dr. Grant was to join them at dinner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31922,\n            \"Lady Bertram was very well pleased to have it so, and the young ladies were in spirits again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32479,\n            \"For the first seven miles Miss Bertram had very little real comfort: her prospect always ended in Mr. Crawford and her sister sitting side by side, full of conversation and merriment;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32687,\n            \"When they came within the influence of Sotherton associations, it was better for Miss Bertram, who might be said to have two strings to her bow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33067,\n            \"she pretty well guessed Miss Bertram\\u2019s feelings, and made it a point of honour to promote her enjoyment to the utmost.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33256,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Bertram could now speak with decided information of what she had known nothing about when Mr. Rushworth had asked her opinion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33338,\n            \"In the drawing-room they were met with equal cordiality by the mother, and Miss Bertram had all the distinction with each that she could wish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33541,\n            \"Her next proposition, of shewing the house to such of them as had not been there before, was more acceptable, for Miss Bertram was pleased to have its size displayed, and all were glad to be doing something.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35092,\n            \"\\u201d Mr. Crawford smiled his acquiescence, and stepping forward to Maria, said, in a voice which she only could hear, \\u201cI do not like to see Miss Bertram so near the altar.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36036,\n            \"Mr. Crawford was soon followed by Miss Bertram and Mr. Rushworth;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50208,\n            \"Tom, returning from them into the drawing-room, where Edmund was standing thoughtfully by the fire, while Lady Bertram was on the sofa at a little distance, and Fanny close beside her arranging her work, thus began as he entered \\u2014 \\u201cSuch a horribly vile billiard-table as ours is not to be met with, I believe, above ground.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50946,\n            \"Well, Edmund,\\u201dhe continued, returning to the former subject, posture, and voice, as soon as Lady Bertram began to nod again, \\u201cbut _ this _ I _ will _ maintain, that we shall be doing no harm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55328,\n            \"When this had lasted some time, the division of the party was completed by Tom Bertram and Mr. Yates walking off together to consult farther in the room now beginning to be called _ the _ _ Theatre _, and Miss Bertram\\u2019s resolving to go down to the Parsonage herself with the offer of Amelia to Miss Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55566,\n            \"and soon after Miss Bertram\\u2019s return from the Parsonage, Mr. Rushworth arrived, and another character was consequently cast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55590,\n            \"He had the offer of Count Cassel and Anhalt, and at first did not know which to chuse, and wanted Miss Bertram to direct him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55664,\n            \"Miss Bertram approved the decision, for the less he had to learn the better;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55680,\n            \"and though she could not sympathise in his wish that the Count and Agatha might be to act together, nor wait very patiently while he was slowly turning over the leaves with the hope of still discovering such a scene, she very kindly took his part in hand, and curtailed every speech that admitted being shortened;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56292,\n            \"In a few minutes Mr. Bertram was called out of the room to satisfy some doubts of the carpenter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56840,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am convinced, madam,\\u201dsaid Edmund, preventing Fanny, \\u201cthat Sir Thomas would not like it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57025,\n            \"\\u201cIf every play is to be objected to, you will act nothing, and the preparations will be all so much money thrown away, and I am sure _ that _ would be a discredit to us all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57130,\n            \"I only wish Tom had known his own mind when the carpenters began, for there was the loss of half a day\\u2019s work about those side-doors.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57172,\n            \"The maids do their work very well, and I think we shall be able to send back some dozens of the rings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57560,\n            \"Mrs. Norris related again her triumph over Dick Jackson, but neither play nor preparation were otherwise much talked of, for Edmund\\u2019s disapprobation was felt even by his brother, though he would not have owned it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57837,\n            \"and Henry Crawford was soon seated with the other three at the table, while his sister made her way to Lady Bertram, and with pleasant attention was complimenting _ her _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57871,\n            \"\\u201cI must really congratulate your ladyship,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201con the play being chosen;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57890,\n            \"for though you have borne it with exemplary patience, I am sure you must be sick of all our noise and difficulties.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57932,\n            \"and I do sincerely give you joy, madam, as well as Mrs. Norris, and everybody else who is in the same predicament,\\u201dglancing half fearfully, half slyly, beyond Fanny to Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57972,\n            \"She was very civilly answered by Lady Bertram, but Edmund said nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65085,\n            \"Lady Bertram seems more of a cipher now than when he is at home;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65111,\n            \"But, Mary, do not fancy that Maria Bertram cares for Henry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65645,\n            \"and Mrs. Norris was too busy in contriving and directing the general little matters of the company, superintending their various dresses with economical expedient, for which nobody thanked her, and saving, with delighted integrity, half a crown here and there to the absent Sir Thomas, to have leisure for watching the behaviour, or guarding the happiness of his daughters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71055,\n            \"and all the little particulars of his proceedings and events, his arrivals and departures, were most promptly delivered, as he sat by Lady Bertram and looked with heartfelt satisfaction on the faces around him \\u2014 interrupting himself more than once, however, to remark on his good fortune in finding them all at home \\u2014 coming unexpectedly as he did \\u2014 all collected together exactly as he could have wished, but dared not depend on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71848,\n            \"suppose you hurry Baddeley a little;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75008,\n            \"She had a great deal to insinuate in her own praise as to _ general _ attention to the interest and comfort of his family, much exertion and many sacrifices to glance at in the form of hurried walks and sudden removals from her own fireside, and many excellent hints of distrust and economy to Lady Bertram and Edmund to detail, whereby a most considerable saving had always arisen, and more than one bad servant been detected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76600,\n            \"But they had seen no one from the Parsonage, not a creature, and had heard no tidings beyond a friendly note of congratulation and inquiry from Mrs. Grant to Lady Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85422,\n            \"\\u201d of some length from the fair lady before she could add, \\u201cYou ought to be in parliament, or you should have gone into the army ten years ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85550,\n            \"\\u201d A look of consciousness as he spoke, and what seemed a consciousness of manner on Miss Crawford\\u2019s side as she made some laughing answer, was sorrowfull food for Fanny\\u2019s observation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87100,\n            \"Mrs. Grant\\u2019s shewing civility to Miss Price, to Lady Bertram\\u2019s niece, could never want explanation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87490,\n            \"for Lady Bertram never thought of being useful to anybody, and Mrs. Norris, when she came on the morrow, in consequence of an early call and invitation from Sir Thomas, was in a very ill humour, and seemed intent only on lessening her niece\\u2019s pleasure, both present and future, as much as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93237,\n            \"This was exactly what Sir Thomas and Edmund had been separately conniving at, as each proved to the other by the sympathetic alacrity with which they both advised Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s continuing where she was, instead of rushing out into the hall as soon as the noises of the arrival reached them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93698,\n            \"ready to think of every member of that home as she directed, or differing only by a less scrupulous opinion, and more noisy abuse of their aunt Norris, and with whom (perhaps the dearest indulgence of the whole) all the evil and good of their earliest years could be gone over again, and every former united pain and pleasure retraced with the fondest recollection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94018,\n            \"and when Mrs. Brown, and the other women at the Commissioner\\u2019s at Gibraltar, appeared in the same trim, I thought they were mad;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94379,\n            \"and though Mrs. Norris could fidget about the room, and disturb everybody in quest of two needlefuls of thread or a second-hand shirt button, in the midst of her nephew\\u2019s account of a shipwreck or an engagement, everybody else was attentive;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94460,\n            \"I wonder anybody can ever go to sea.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95289,\n            \"and the dinner itself was elegant and plentiful, according to the usual style of the Grants, and too much according to the usual habits of all to raise any emotion except in Mrs. Norris, who could never behold either the wide table or the number of dishes on it with patience, and who did always contrive to experience some evil from the passing of the servants behind her chair, and to bring away some fresh conviction of its being impossible among so many dishes but that some must be cold.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95528,\n            \"He was a whist player himself, and perhaps might feel that it would not much amuse him to have her for a partner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95631,\n            \"but upon everybody\\u2019s assuring her that nothing could be so easy, that it was the easiest game on the cards, and Henry Crawford\\u2019s stepping forward with a most earnest request to be allowed to sit between her ladyship and Miss Price, and teach them both, it was so settled;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95824,\n            \"and as for Lady Bertram, he must continue in charge of all her fame and fortune through the whole evening;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98014,\n            \"\\u201d Sotherton was a word to catch Mrs. Norris, and being just then in the happy leisure which followed securing the odd trick by Sir Thomas\\u2019 s capital play and her own against Dr. and Mrs. Grant\\u2019s great hands, she called out, in high good-humour, \\u201cSotherton!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98100,\n            \"but the next time you come, I hope dear Mr. and Mrs. Rushworth will be at home, and I am sure I can answer for your being kindly received by both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98190,\n            \"I do not exactly know the distance, but when you get back to Portsmouth, if it is not very far off, you ought to go over and pay your respects to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98226,\n            \"and I could send a little parcel by you that I want to get conveyed to your cousins.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109231,\n            \"I sent Chapman to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111177,\n            \"Her praise was warm, and he received it as she could wish, joining in it as far as discretion, and politeness, and slowness of speech would allow, and certainly appearing to greater advantage on the subject than his lady did soon afterwards, when Mary, perceiving her on a sofa very near, turned round before she began to dance, to compliment her on Miss Price\\u2019s looks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113289,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s disposition was such that she could never even think of her aunt Norris in the meagreness and cheerlessness of her own small house, without reproaching herself for some little want of attention to her when they had been last together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113414,\n            \"She talked to her aunt Bertram \\u2014 she must talk to somebody of the ball;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113454,\n            \"Lady Bertram was not certain of anybody\\u2019s dress or anybody\\u2019s place at supper but her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113475,\n            \"\\u201cShe could not recollect what it was that she had heard about one of the Miss Maddoxes, or what it was that Lady Prescott had noticed in Fanny: she was not sure whether Colonel Harrison had been talking of Mr. Crawford or of William when he said he was the finest young man in the room \\u2014 somebody had whispered something to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113709,\n            \"Fanny, you must do something to keep me awake.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114232,\n            \"They are all going away, I think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114241,\n            \"I wish they would stay at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114271,\n            \"and as Sir Thomas thought it best for each daughter that the permission should be granted, Lady Bertram, though in her own good-nature she would not have prevented it, was lamenting the change it made in the prospect of Julia\\u2019s return, which would otherwise have taken place about this time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114405,\n            \"and at the end of a quarter of an hour\\u2019s silent consideration spontaneously observed, \\u201cSir Thomas, I have been thinking \\u2014 and I am very glad we took Fanny as we did, for now the others are away we feel the good of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114543,\n            \"\\u201d Sir Thomas paused, half smiled, glanced at his niece, and then gravely replied, \\u201cShe will never leave us, I hope, till invited to some other home that may reasonably promise her greater happiness than she knows here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115396,\n            \"But at last Lady Bertram left the room, and then almost immediately Miss Crawford thus began, with a voice as well regulated as she could \\u2014 \\u201cAnd how do _ you _ like your cousin Edmund\\u2019s staying away so long?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116766,\n            \"Henry had said he should just go and ask the Bertrams how they did, and be back in ten minutes, but he was gone above an hour;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116843,\n            \"\\u201d he had only to say that he had been sitting with Lady Bertram and Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117044,\n            \"Mary was in a state of mind to rejoice in a connexion with the Bertram family, and to be not displeased with her brother\\u2019s marrying a little beneath him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134833,\n            \"\\u201d And by carefully giving way to the inclination of the leaves, he did find it, or within a page or two, quite near enough to satisfy Lady Bertram, who assured him, as soon as he mentioned the name of Cardinal Wolsey, that he had got the very speech.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135120,\n            \"nay, perhaps with greater enjoyment, for it came unexpectedly, and with no such drawback as she had been used to suffer in seeing him on the stage with Miss Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135670,\n            \"\\u201cI wish Sir Thomas had been here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143210,\n            \"She absented herself as little as possible from Lady Bertram, kept away from the East room, and took no solitary walk in the shrubbery, in her caution to avoid any sudden attack.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149049,\n            \"obtaining it rather from submission, however, than conviction, for Lady Bertram was convinced of very little more than that Sir Thomas thought Fanny ought to go, and therefore that she must.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149085,\n            \"In the calmness of her own dressing-room, in the impartial flow of her own meditations, unbiassed by his bewildering statements, she could not acknowledge any necessity for Fanny\\u2019s ever going near a father and mother who had done without her so long, while she was so useful to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149143,\n            \"And as to the not missing her, which under Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s discussion was the point attempted to be proved, she set herself very steadily against admitting any such thing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149281,\n            \"but I am sure I shall miss her very much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149386,\n            \"but this she could easily suppose to have been her own fault or her own fancy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150063,\n            \"that she was a great deal too necessary to Sir Thomas and Lady Bertram for her to be able to answer it to herself to leave them even for a week, and therefore must certainly sacrifice every other pleasure to that of being useful to them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150357,\n            \"Lady Bertram had been telling her niece in the evening to write to her soon and often, and promising to be a good correspondent herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157259,\n            \"Her disposition was naturally easy and indolent, like Lady Bertram\\u2019s;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157311,\n            \"She might have made just as good a woman of consequence as Lady Bertram, but Mrs. Norris would have been a more respectable mother of nine children on a small income.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158131,\n            \"Here everybody was noisy, every voice was loud (excepting, perhaps, her mother\\u2019s, which resembled the soft monotony of Lady Bertram\\u2019s, only worn into fretfulness).\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158277,\n            \"CHAPTER XL Fanny was right enough in not expecting to hear from Miss Crawford now at the rapid rate in which their correspondence had begun;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159151,\n            \"Her correspondence with her aunt Bertram was her only concern of higher interest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164441,\n            \"Her poor mother now did not look so very unworthy of being Lady Bertram\\u2019s sister as she was but too apt to look.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164482,\n            \"to think that where nature had made so little difference, circumstances should have made so much, and that her mother, as handsome as Lady Bertram, and some years her junior, should have an appearance so much more worn and faded, so comfortless, so slatternly, so shabby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171348,\n            \"Everybody at all addicted to letter-writing, without having much to say, which will include a large proportion of the female world at least, must feel with Lady Bertram that she was out of luck in having such a capital piece of Mansfield news as the certainty of the Grants going to Bath, occur at a time when she could make no advantage of it, and will admit that it must have been very mortifying to her to see it fall to the share of her thankless son, and treated as concisely as possible at the end of a long letter, instead of having it to spread over the largest part of a page of her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171474,\n            \"For though Lady Bertram rather shone in the epistolary line, having early in her marriage, from the want of other employment, and the circumstance of Sir Thomas\\u2019 s being in Parliament, got into the way of making and keeping correspondents, and formed for herself a very creditable, common-place, amplifying style, so that a very little matter was enough for her: she could not do entirely without any;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171567,\n            \"and being so soon to lose all the benefit of Dr. Grant\\u2019s gouty symptoms and Mrs. Grant\\u2019s morning calls, it was very hard upon her to be deprived of one of the last epistolary uses she could put them to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171637,\n            \"Within a few days from the receipt of Edmund\\u2019s letter, Fanny had one from her aunt, beginning thus \\u2014 \\u201cMy Dear Fanny, \\u2014 I take up my pen to communicate some very alarming intelligence, which I make no doubt will give you much concern \\u201d.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172183,\n            \"Her aunt did not neglect her: she wrote again and again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172266,\n            \"and she wrote very comfortably about agitation, and anxiety, and poor invalids, till Tom was actually conveyed to Mansfield, and her own eyes had beheld his altered appearance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172515,\n            \"Lady Bertram wrote her daily terrors to her niece, who might now be said to live upon letters, and pass all her time between suffering from that of to-day and looking forward to to-morrow\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172870,\n            \"for being now used to the sight of him in his suffering, helpless state, and hearing only the best, and never thinking beyond what she heard, with no disposition for alarm and no aptitude at a hint, Lady Bertram was the happiest subject in the world for a little medical imposition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173025,\n            \"They judged it best that Lady Bertram should not be harassed by alarms which, it was to be hoped, would prove unfounded;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180583,\n            \"Fanny had scarcely passed the solemn-looking servants, when Lady Bertram came from the drawing-room to meet her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181271,\n            \"Lady Bertram did not think deeply, but, guided by Sir Thomas, she thought justly on all important points;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181366,\n            \"but whenever Lady Bertram _ was _ fixed on the event, she could see it only in one light, as comprehending the loss of a daughter, and a disgrace never to be wiped off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182659,\n            \"and, having reason to think that one interview with Miss Crawford had taken place, from which Edmund derived only increased distress, had been as anxious on that account as on others to get him out of town, and had engaged him in taking Fanny home to her aunt, with a view to his relief and benefit, no less than theirs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183249,\n            \"and regarding it as what was meant to be the last, last interview of friendship, and investing her with all the feelings of shame and wretchedness which Crawford\\u2019s sister ought to have known, he had gone to her in such a state of mind, so softened, so devoted, as made it for a few moments impossible to Fanny\\u2019s fears that it should be the last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183447,\n            \"With a graver look and voice she then added, \\u2018 I do not mean to defend Henry at your sister\\u2019s expense.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186840,\n            \"Too late he became aware how unfavourable to the character of any young people must be the totally opposite treatment which Maria and Julia had been always experiencing at home, where the excessive indulgence and flattery of their aunt had been continually contrasted with his own severity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186889,\n            \"He saw how ill he had judged, in expecting to counteract what was wrong in Mrs. Norris by its reverse in himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186914,\n            \"clearly saw that he had but increased the evil by teaching them to repress their spirits in his presence so as to make their real disposition unknown to him, and sending them for all their indulgences to a person who had been able to attach them only by the blindness of her affection, and the excess of her praise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187824,\n            \"It ended in Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s resolving to quit Mansfield and devote herself to her unfortunate Maria, and in an establishment being formed for them in another country, remote and private, where, shut up together with little society, on one side no affection, on the other no judgment, it may be reasonably supposed that their tempers became their mutual punishment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188818,\n            \"He saw Mrs. Rushworth, was received by her with a coldness which ought to have been repulsive, and have established apparent indifference between them for ever;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188848,\n            \"but he was mortified, he could not bear to be thrown off by the woman whose smiles had been so wholly at his command: he must exert himself to subdue so proud a display of resentment;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188896,\n            \"he must get the better of it, and make Mrs. Rushworth Maria Bertram again in her treatment of himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188952,\n            \"but in triumphing over the discretion which, though beginning in anger, might have saved them both, he had put himself in the power of feelings on her side more strong than he had supposed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188990,\n            \"She loved him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189050,\n            \"Secrecy could not have been more desirable for Mrs. Rushworth\\u2019s credit than he felt it for his own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189072,\n            \"When he returned from Richmond, he would have been glad to see Mrs. Rushworth no more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189101,\n            \"and he went off with her at last, because he could not help it, regretting Fanny even at the moment, but regretting her infinitely more when all the bustle of the intrigue was over, and a very few months had taught him, by the force of contrast, to place a yet higher value on the sweetness of her temper, the purity of her mind, and the excellence of her principles.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189511,\n            \"and Mary had had enough of her own friends, enough of vanity, ambition, love, and disappointment in the course of the last half-year, to be in need of the true kindness of her sister\\u2019s heart, and the rational tranquillity of her ways.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190708,\n            \"Selfishly dear as she had long been to Lady Bertram, she could not be parted with willingly by _ her _.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 15]\": [\n        [\n            726,\n            \"A large and still increasing family, an husband disabled for active service, but not the less equal to company and good liquor, and a very small income to supply their wants, made her eager to regain the friends she had so carelessly sacrificed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            774,\n            \"and she addressed Lady Bertram in a letter which spoke so much contrition and despondence, such a superfluity of children, and such a want of almost everything else, as could not but dispose them all to a reconciliation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            826,\n            \"and after bewailing the circumstance, and imploring their countenance as sponsors to the expected child, she could not conceal how important she felt they might be to the future maintenance of the eight already in being.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1051,\n            \"and at length she could not but own it to be her wish that poor Mrs. Price should be relieved from the charge and expense of one child entirely out of her great number.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1782,\n            \"I only meant to observe that it ought not to be lightly engaged in, and that to make it really serviceable to Mrs. Price, and creditable to ourselves, we must secure to the child, or consider ourselves engaged to secure to her hereafter, as circumstances may arise, the provision of a gentlewoman, if no such establishment should offer as you are so sanguine in expecting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26511,\n            \"and in Dr. Grant\\u2019s meadow she immediately saw the group \\u2014 Edmund and Miss Crawford both on horse-back, riding side by side, Dr. and Mrs. Grant, and Mr. Crawford, with two or three grooms, standing about and looking on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26606,\n            \"she wondered that Edmund should forget her, and felt a pang.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26619,\n            \"She could not turn her eyes from the meadow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26967,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear Miss Price,\\u201dsaid Miss Crawford, as soon as she was at all within hearing, \\u201cI am come to make my own apologies for keeping you waiting;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40937,\n            \"After another pause, he went on \\u2014 \\u201cPray, Miss Price, are you such a great admirer of this Mr. Crawford as some people are?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45049,\n            \"but I wish you a better fate, Miss Price, than to be the wife of a man whose amiableness depends upon his own sermons;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45177,\n            \"when, being earnestly invited by the Miss Bertrams to join in a glee, she tripped off to the instrument, leaving Edmund looking after her in an ecstasy of admiration of all her many virtues, from her obliging manners down to her light and graceful tread.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45271,\n            \"joining them the moment she is asked.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100704,\n            \"Do not you see your aunt is going?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107015,\n            \"and had she known in what light this ball was, in general, considered respecting her, it would very much have lessened her comfort by increasing the fears she already had of doing wrong and being looked at.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109007,\n            \"Her aunt Bertram had recollected her on this occasion with an unusual degree of wakefulness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109023,\n            \"It had really occurred to her, unprompted, that Fanny, preparing for a ball, might be glad of better help than the upper housemaid\\u2019s, and when dressed herself, she actually sent her own maid to assist her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118576,\n            \"\\u201cI cannot admit Mrs. Grant to have an equal claim with Fanny and myself, for we shall both have a right in you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118908,\n            \"\\u201cHenry, I think so highly of Fanny Price, that if I could suppose the next Mrs. Crawford would have half the reason which my poor ill-used aunt had to abhor the very name, I would prevent the marriage, if possible;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119003,\n            \"\\u201d The impossibility of not doing everything in the world to make Fanny Price happy, or of ceasing to love Fanny Price, was of course the groundwork of his eloquent answer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119653,\n            \"The two ladies were together in the breakfast-room, and, fortunately for him, Lady Bertram was on the very point of quitting it as he entered.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119684,\n            \"She was almost at the door, and not chusing by any means to take so much trouble in vain, she still went on, after a civil reception, a short sentence about being waited for, and a \\u201cLet Sir Thomas know\\u201dto the servant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119735,\n            \"Henry, overjoyed to have her go, bowed and watched her off, and without losing another moment, turned instantly to Fanny, and, taking out some letters, said, with a most animated look, \\u201cI must acknowledge myself infinitely obliged to any creature who gives me such an opportunity of seeing you alone: I have been wishing it more than you can have any idea.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130233,\n            \"Sir Thomas wants me, not Miss Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130248,\n            \"\\u201cNo, ma\\u2019am, it is Miss Price;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130260,\n            \"I am certain of its being Miss Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149824,\n            \"when she saw Sir Thomas actually give William notes for the purpose, she was struck with the idea of there being room for a third in the carriage, and suddenly seized with a strong inclination to go with them, to go and see her poor dear sister Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149908,\n            \"she had not seen her poor dear sister Price for more than twenty years;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149946,\n            \"and she could not help thinking her poor dear sister Price would feel it very unkind of her not to come by such an opportunity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150315,\n            \"and Fanny was the more affected from feeling it to be the last time in which Miss Crawford\\u2019s name would ever be mentioned between them with any remains of liberty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161161,\n            \"While trying to keep herself alive, their visitor, who had at first approached her with as animated a countenance as ever, was wisely and kindly keeping his eyes away, and giving her time to recover, while he devoted himself entirely to her mother, addressing her, and attending to her with the utmost politeness and propriety, at the same time with a degree of friendliness, of interest at least, which was making his manner perfect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161246,\n            \"Mrs. Price\\u2019s manners were also at their best.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161258,\n            \"Warmed by the sight of such a friend to her son, and regulated by the wish of appearing to advantage before him, she was overflowing with gratitude \\u2014 artless, maternal gratitude \\u2014 which could not be unpleasing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161299,\n            \"Mr. Price was out, which she regretted very much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161854,\n            \"and such hints producing nothing, he soon proceeded to a positive recommendation to Mrs. Price and her daughters to take their walk without loss of time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161909,\n            \"she owned she could seldom, with her large family, find time for a walk.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161926,\n            \"\\u201cWould she not, then, persuade her daughters to take advantage of such weather, and allow him the pleasure of attending them?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161984,\n            \"and she knew they had some errands in the town, which they would be very glad to do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162055,\n            \"for they were hardly in the High Street before they met her father, whose appearance was not the better from its being Saturday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162222,\n            \"Mr. Crawford probably could not regard his future father-in-law with any idea of taking him for a model in dress;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162248,\n            \"but (as Fanny instantly, and to her great relief, discerned) her father was a very different man, a very different Mr. Price in his behaviour to this most highly respected stranger, from what he was in his own family at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162318,\n            \"his expressions were those of an attached father, and a sensible man;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162354,\n            \"Such was his instinctive compliment to the good manners of Mr. Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162386,\n            \"The conclusion of the two gentlemen\\u2019s civilities was an offer of Mr. Price\\u2019s to take Mr. Crawford into the dockyard, which Mr. Crawford, desirous of accepting as a favour what was intended as such, though he had seen the dockyard again and again, and hoping to be so much the longer with Fanny, was very gratefully disposed to avail himself of, if the Miss Prices were not afraid of the fatigue;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162506,\n            \"and but for Mr. Crawford, Mr. Price would have turned thither directly, without the smallest consideration for his daughters\\u2019 errands in the High Street.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162536,\n            \"He took care, however, that they should be allowed to go to the shops they came out expressly to visit;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162624,\n            \"They were then to set forward for the dockyard at once, and the walk would have been conducted \\u2014 according to Mr. Crawford\\u2019s opinion \\u2014 in a singular manner, had Mr. Price been allowed the entire regulation of it, as the two girls, he found, would have been left to follow, and keep up with them or not, as they could, while they walked on together at their own hasty pace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162736,\n            \"and at any crossing or any crowd, when Mr. Price was only calling out, \\u201cCome, girls;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162785,\n            \"Once fairly in the dockyard, he began to reckon upon some happy intercourse with Fanny, as they were very soon joined by a brother lounger of Mr. Price\\u2019s, who was come to take his daily survey of how things went on, and who must prove a far more worthy companion than himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172660,\n            \"not even Mrs. Price, beyond a brief question or two, if she saw her daughter with a letter in her hand, and now and then the quiet observation of, \\u201cMy poor sister Bertram must be in a great deal of trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172793,\n            \"or perhaps might have caught from Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s lips the cant of its being a very happy thing and a great blessing to their poor dear sister Price to have them so well provided for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177791,\n            \"have not I, Betsey?\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 16]\": [\n        [\n            11480,\n            \"and Mrs. Grant, instead of contriving to gratify him at little expense, gave her cook as high wages as they did at Mansfield Park, and was scarcely ever seen in her offices.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11619,\n            \"_ Her _ store-room, she thought, might have been good enough for Mrs. Grant to go into.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11642,\n            \"Inquire where she would, she could not find out that Mrs. Grant had ever had more than five thousand pounds.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11678,\n            \"She could not enter into the wrongs of an economist, but she felt all the injuries of beauty in Mrs. Grant\\u2019s being so well settled in life without being handsome, and expressed her astonishment on that point almost as often, though not so diffusely, as Mrs. Norris discussed the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15976,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear sister,\\u201dsaid Mary, \\u201cif you can persuade him into anything of the sort, it will be a fresh matter of delight to me to find myself allied to anybody so clever, and I shall only regret that you have not half a dozen daughters to dispose of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16033,\n            \"If you can persuade Henry to marry, you must have the address of a Frenchwoman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16273,\n            \"I assure you he is very detestable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20886,\n            \"If it had not been for _ that _, we should have carried on the garden wall, and made the plantation to shut out the churchyard, just as Dr. Grant has done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20932,\n            \"It was only the spring twelvemonth before Mr. Norris\\u2019 s death that we put in the apricot against the stable wall, which is now grown such a noble tree, and getting to such perfection, sir,\\u201daddressing herself then to Dr. Grant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21142,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThe truth is, ma\\u2019am,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Grant, pretending to whisper across the table to Mrs. Norris, \\u201cthat Dr. Grant hardly knows what the natural taste of our apricot is: he is scarcely ever indulged with one, for it is so valuable a fruit;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44772,\n            \"We cannot attempt to defend Dr. Grant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44781,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo,\\u201dreplied Fanny, \\u201cbut we need not give up his profession for all that;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44825,\n            \"and as he must, either in the navy or army, have had a great many more people under his command than he has now, I think more would have been made unhappy by him as a sailor or soldier than as a clergyman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44951,\n            \"A man \\u2014 a sensible man like Dr. Grant, cannot be in the habit of teaching others their duty every week, cannot go to church twice every Sunday, and preach such very good sermons in so good a manner as he does, without being the better for it himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45012,\n            \"and I have no doubt that he oftener endeavours to restrain himself than he would if he had been anything but a clergyman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85777,\n            \"Dr. Grant was in the vestibule, and as they stopt to speak to him she found, from Edmund\\u2019s manner, that he _ did _ mean to go with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86053,\n            \"\\u201cAnd you know what your dinner will be,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Grant, smiling \\u2014 \\u201cthe turkey, and I assure you a very fine one;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86404,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI cannot imagine why Mrs. Grant should think of asking her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86576,\n            \"and I think he will consider it a right thing by Mrs. Grant, as well as by Fanny, that being the _ first _ invitation it should be accepted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86621,\n            \"But he will be very much surprised that Mrs. Grant should ask Fanny at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87030,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut is it not very natural,\\u201dobserved Edmund, \\u201cthat Mrs. Grant should wish to procure so agreeable a visitor for her sister?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87100,\n            \"Mrs. Grant\\u2019s shewing civility to Miss Price, to Lady Bertram\\u2019s niece, could never want explanation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87574,\n            \"You ought to be very much obliged to Mrs. Grant for thinking of you, and to your aunt for letting you go, and you ought to look upon it as something extraordinary;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87684,\n            \"Mrs. Grant thinks it a civility due to _ us _ to take a little notice of you, or else it would never have come into her head, and you may be very certain that, if your cousin Julia had been at home, you would not have been asked at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87741,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Norris had now so ingeniously done away all Mrs. Grant\\u2019s part of the favour, that Fanny, who found herself expected to speak, could only say that she was very much obliged to her aunt Bertram for sparing her, and that she was endeavouring to put her aunt\\u2019s evening work in such a state as to prevent her being missed.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 17]\": [\n        [\n            324,\n            \"Sir Thomas Bertram had interest, which, from principle as well as pride \\u2014 from a general wish of doing right, and a desire of seeing all that were connected with him in situations of respectability, he would have been glad to exert for the advantage of Lady Bertram\\u2019s sister;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            394,\n            \"and before he had time to devise any other method of assisting them, an absolute breach between the sisters had taken place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            463,\n            \"Lady Bertram, who was a woman of very tranquil feelings, and a temper remarkably easy and indolent, would have contented herself with merely giving up her sister, and thinking no more of the matter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            561,\n            \"and an answer, which comprehended each sister in its bitterness, and bestowed such very disrespectful reflections on the pride of Sir Thomas as Mrs. Norris could not possibly keep to herself, put an end to all intercourse between them for a considerable period.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            609,\n            \"Their homes were so distant, and the circles in which they moved so distinct, as almost to preclude the means of ever hearing of each other\\u2019s existence during the eleven following years, or, at least, to make it very wonderful to Sir Thomas that Mrs. Norris should ever have it in her power to tell them, as she now and then did, in an angry voice, that Fanny had got another child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            774,\n            \"and she addressed Lady Bertram in a letter which spoke so much contrition and despondence, such a superfluity of children, and such a want of almost everything else, as could not but dispose them all to a reconciliation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            895,\n            \"Was there any chance of his being hereafter useful to Sir Thomas in the concerns of his West Indian property?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1225,\n            \"He thought of his own four children, of his two sons, of cousins in love, etc.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1277,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear Sir Thomas, I perfectly comprehend you, and do justice to the generosity and delicacy of your notions, which indeed are quite of a piece with your general conduct;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1312,\n            \"and I entirely agree with you in the main as to the propriety of doing everything one could by way of providing for a child one had in a manner taken into one\\u2019s own hands;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1474,\n            \"A niece of ours, Sir Thomas, I may say, or at least of _ yours _, would not grow up in this neighbourhood without many advantages.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1733,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere is a great deal of truth in what you say,\\u201dreplied Sir Thomas, \\u201cand far be it from me to throw any fanciful impediment in the way of a plan which would be so consistent with the relative situations of each.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1782,\n            \"I only meant to observe that it ought not to be lightly engaged in, and that to make it really serviceable to Mrs. Price, and creditable to ourselves, we must secure to the child, or consider ourselves engaged to secure to her hereafter, as circumstances may arise, the provision of a gentlewoman, if no such establishment should offer as you are so sanguine in expecting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1856,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI thoroughly understand you,\\u201dcried Mrs. Norris, \\u201cyou are everything that is generous and considerate, and I am sure we shall never disagree on this point.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1891,\n            \"Whatever I can do, as you well know, I am always ready enough to do for the good of those I love;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1916,\n            \"and, though I could never feel for this little girl the hundredth part of the regard I bear your own dear children, nor consider her, in any respect, so much my own, I should hate myself if I were capable of neglecting her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1993,\n            \"My dear Sir Thomas, with all my faults I have a warm heart;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2029,\n            \"So, if you are not against it, I will write to my poor sister tomorrow, and make the proposal;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2171,\n            \"\\u201d Except to the attack on Nanny\\u2019s cousin, Sir Thomas no longer made any objection, and a more respectable, though less economical rendezvous being accordingly substituted, everything was considered as settled, and the pleasures of so benevolent a scheme were already enjoyed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2238,\n            \"for Sir Thomas was fully resolved to be the real and consistent patron of the selected child, and Mrs. Norris had not the least intention of being at any expense whatever in her maintenance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2542,\n            \"and, in reply to Lady Bertram\\u2019s calm inquiry of \\u201cWhere shall the child come to first, sister, to you or to us?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2602,\n            \"He had been considering her as a particularly welcome addition at the Parsonage, as a desirable companion to an aunt who had no children of her own;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2699,\n            \"if, indeed, he should ever get well of his gouty complaints, it would be a different matter: she should then be glad to take her turn, and think nothing of the inconvenience;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2737,\n            \"but just now, poor Mr. Norris took up every moment of her time, and the very mention of such a thing she was sure would distract him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3087,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cShould her disposition be really bad,\\u201dsaid Sir Thomas, \\u201cwe must not, for our own children\\u2019s sake, continue her in the family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3170,\n            \"nor, I trust, can they be dangerous for her associates.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3337,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere will be some difficulty in our way, Mrs. Norris,\\u201dobserved Sir Thomas, \\u201cas to the distinction proper to be made between the girls as they grow up: how to preserve in the minds of my _ daughters _ the consciousness of what they are, without making them think too lowly of their cousin;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3808,\n            \"Sir Thomas and Lady Bertram received her very kindly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3818,\n            \"and Sir Thomas, seeing how much she needed encouragement, tried to be all that was conciliating: but he had to work against a most untoward gravity of deportment;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6897,\n            \"Sir Thomas did not know what was wanting, because, though a truly anxious father, he was not outwardly affectionate, and the reserve of his manner repressed all the flow of their spirits before him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6958,\n            \"She was a woman who spent her days in sitting, nicely dressed, on a sofa, doing some long piece of needlework, of little use and no beauty, thinking more of her pug than her children, but very indulgent to the latter when it did not put herself to inconvenience, guided in everything important by Sir Thomas, and in smaller concerns by her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7312,\n            \"In the country, therefore, the Miss Bertrams continued to exercise their memories, practise their duets, and grow tall and womanly: and their father saw them becoming in person, manner, and accomplishments, everything that could satisfy his anxiety.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7374,\n            \"but his other children promised him nothing but good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7384,\n            \"His daughters, he felt, while they retained the name of Bertram, must be giving it new grace, and in quitting it, he trusted, would extend its respectable alliances;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7458,\n            \"Amid the cares and the complacency which his own children suggested, Sir Thomas did not forget to do what he could for the children of Mrs. Price: he assisted her liberally in the education and disposal of her sons as they became old enough for a determinate pursuit;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10352,\n            \"I thought you had settled it with Sir Thomas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10368,\n            \"I never spoke a syllable about it to Sir Thomas, nor he to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10493,\n            \"Sir Thomas is too much my friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10515,\n            \"How came Sir Thomas to speak to you about it?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10535,\n            \"I suppose he thought it best.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10550,\n            \"He could not say he _ wished _ me to take Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10563,\n            \"I am sure in his heart he could not wish me to do it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11073,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWhy, you know, Sir Thomas\\u2019 s means will be rather straitened if the Antigua estate is to make such poor returns.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11112,\n            \"Sir Thomas has been writing about it, I know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11123,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, Lady Bertram,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris, moving to go, \\u201cI can only say that my sole desire is to be of use to your family: and so, if Sir Thomas should ever speak again about my taking Fanny, you will be able to say that my health and spirits put it quite out of the question;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11771,\n            \"Sir Thomas found it expedient to go to Antigua himself, for the better arrangement of his affairs, and he took his eldest son with him, in the hope of detaching him from some bad connexions at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11825,\n            \"The necessity of the measure in a pecuniary light, and the hope of its utility to his son, reconciled Sir Thomas to the effort of quitting the rest of his family, and of leaving his daughters to the direction of others at their present most interesting time of life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11878,\n            \"He could not think Lady Bertram quite equal to supply his place with them, or rather, to perform what should have been her own;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12015,\n            \"Their father was no object of love to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12052,\n            \"and without aiming at one gratification that would probably have been forbidden by Sir Thomas, they felt themselves immediately at their own disposal, and to have every indulgence within their reach.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13635,\n            \"and at length determined on a method of proceeding which would obviate the risk of his father\\u2019s thinking he had done too much, and at the same time procure for Fanny the immediate means of exercise, which he could not bear she should be without.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13944,\n            \"and had Lady Bertram ever thought about her own objection again, he might have been excused in her eyes for not waiting till Sir Thomas\\u2019 s return in September, for when September came Sir Thomas was still abroad, and without any near prospect of finishing his business.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14073,\n            \"Sir Thomas\\u2019 s sending away his son seemed to her so like a parent\\u2019s care, under the influence of a foreboding of evil to himself, that she could not help feeling dreadful presentiments;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14634,\n            \"After dancing with each other at a proper number of balls, the young people justified these opinions, and an engagement, with a due reference to the absent Sir Thomas, was entered into, much to the satisfaction of their respective families, and of the general lookers-on of the neighbourhood, who had, for many weeks past, felt the expediency of Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s marrying Miss Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14726,\n            \"but, in the meanwhile, as no one felt a doubt of his most cordial pleasure in the connexion, the intercourse of the two families was carried on without restraint, and no other attempt made at secrecy than Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s talking of it everywhere as a matter not to be talked of at present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14978,\n            \"He wrote in April, and had strong hopes of settling everything to his entire satisfaction, and leaving Antigua before the end of the summer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42878,\n            \"and to think of their father in England again within a certain period, which these letters obliged them to do, was a most unwelcome exercise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42932,\n            \"His business was so nearly concluded as to justify him in proposing to take his passage in the September packet, and he consequently looked forward with the hope of being with his beloved family again early in November.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42981,\n            \"for to her the father brought a husband, and the return of the friend most solicitous for her happiness would unite her to the lover, on whom she had chosen that happiness should depend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43133,\n            \"Sir Thomas would have been deeply mortified by a suspicion of half that his daughters felt on the subject of his return, and would hardly have found consolation in a knowledge of the interest it excited in the breast of another young lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69931,\n            \"She hailed it as an earnest of the most serious determination, and was equal even to encounter her father.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69992,\n            \"\\u201d but they were no sooner through the door than Henry Crawford undertook to answer the anxious inquiry, and, encouraging him by all means to pay his respects to Sir Thomas without delay, sent him after the others with delighted haste.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70058,\n            \"and as her own opinion of her claims on Sir Thomas\\u2019 s affection was much too humble to give her any idea of classing herself with his children, she was glad to remain behind and gain a little breathing-time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70175,\n            \"She had found a seat, where in excessive trembling she was enduring all these fearful thoughts, while the other three, no longer under any restraint, were giving vent to their feelings of vexation, lamenting over such an unlooked-for premature arrival as a most untoward event, and without mercy wishing poor Sir Thomas had been twice as long on his passage, or were still in Antigua.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70433,\n            \"and therefore, thanking them, said, \\u201che preferred remaining where he was, that he might pay his respects to the old gentleman handsomely since he _ was _ come;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70487,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny was just beginning to collect herself, and to feel that if she staid longer behind it might seem disrespectful, when this point was settled, and being commissioned with the brother and sister\\u2019s apology, saw them preparing to go as she quitted the room herself to perform the dreadful duty of appearing before her uncle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70826,\n            \"He inquired next after her family, especially William: and his kindness altogether was such as made her reproach herself for loving him so little, and thinking his return a misfortune;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70922,\n            \"Sir Thomas was indeed the life of the party, who at his suggestion now seated themselves round the fire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70953,\n            \"and the delight of his sensations in being again in his own house, in the centre of his family, after such a separation, made him communicative and chatty in a very unusual degree;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72130,\n            \"The first day I went over Mansfield Wood, and Edmund took the copses beyond Easton, and we brought home six brace between us, and might each have killed six times as many, but we respect your pheasants, sir, I assure you, as much as you could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72431,\n            \"\\u201d To the theatre he went, and reached it just in time to witness the first meeting of his father and his friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73224,\n            \"It appears a neat job, however, as far as I could judge by candlelight, and does my friend Christopher Jackson credit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73801,\n            \"\\u201cTo own the truth, Sir Thomas, we were in the middle of a rehearsal when you arrived this evening.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73864,\n            \"but if you will give us the honour of your company to-morrow evening, I should not be afraid of the result.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73906,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy indulgence shall be given, sir,\\u201dreplied Sir Thomas gravely, \\u201cbut without any other rehearsal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73987,\n            \"\\u201d Tom was the only one at all ready with an answer, but he being entirely without particular regard for either, without jealousy either in love or acting, could speak very handsomely of both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74189,\n            \"\\u201d Sir Thomas looked again, and then replied with an approving smile, \\u201cI am happy to find our sentiments on this subject so much the same.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74409,\n            \"but by looking, as he really felt, most exceedingly pleased with Sir Thomas\\u2019 s good opinion, and saying scarcely anything, he did his best towards preserving that good opinion a little longer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74447,\n            \"CHAPTER XX Edmund\\u2019s first object the next morning was to see his father alone, and give him a fair statement of the whole acting scheme, defending his own share in it as far only as he could then, in a soberer moment, feel his motives to deserve, and acknowledging, with perfect ingenuousness, that his concession had been attended with such partial good as to make his judgment in it very doubtful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75284,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI know how great, how justly great, your influence is with Lady Bertram and her children, and am the more concerned that it should not have been \\u2014\\u201d\\u201cMy dear Sir Thomas, if you had seen the state of the roads _ that _ day!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76326,\n            \"but there was a something in Sir Thomas, when they sat round the same table, which made Mr. Yates think it wiser to let him pursue his own way, and feel the folly of it without opposition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76368,\n            \"He had known many disagreeable fathers before, and often been struck with the inconveniences they occasioned, but never, in the whole course of his life, had he seen one of that class so unintelligibly moral, so infamously tyrannical as Sir Thomas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76415,\n            \"He was not a man to be endured but for his children\\u2019s sake, and he might be thankful to his fair daughter Julia that Mr. Yates did yet mean to stay a few days longer under his roof.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76472,\n            \"and the music which Sir Thomas called for from his daughters helped to conceal the want of real harmony.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76770,\n            \"Sir Thomas soon appeared, and Maria saw with delight and agitation the introduction of the man she loved to her father.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76793,\n            \"Her sensations were indefinable, and so were they a few minutes afterwards upon hearing Henry Crawford, who had a chair between herself and Tom, ask the latter in an undervoice whether there were any plans for resuming the play after the present happy interruption (with a courteous glance at Sir Thomas), because, in that case, he should make a point of returning to Mansfield at any time required by the party: he was going away immediately, being to meet his uncle at Bath without delay;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76889,\n            \"but if there were any prospect of a renewal of Lovers\\u2019 Vows, he should hold himself positively engaged, he should break through every other claim, he should absolutely condition with his uncle for attending them whenever he might be wanted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77017,\n            \"but as to our play, _ that _ is all over \\u2014 entirely at an end\\u201d(looking significantly at his father).\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77224,\n            \"for, excepting what might be due to his uncle, his engagements were all self-imposed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77620,\n            \"In _ his _ departure Sir Thomas felt the chief interest: wanting to be alone with his family, the presence of a stranger superior to Mr. Yates must have been irksome;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77694,\n            \"Sir Thomas had been quite indifferent to Mr. Crawford\\u2019s going or staying: but his good wishes for Mr. Yates\\u2019 s having a pleasant journey, as he walked with him to the hall-door, were given with genuine satisfaction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77780,\n            \"and Sir Thomas hoped, in seeing him out of it, to be rid of the worst object connected with the scheme, and the last that must be inevitably reminding him of its existence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79149,\n            \"I wonder what she thinks of my father!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79158,\n            \"She must admire him as a fine-looking man, with most gentlemanlike, dignified, consistent manners;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79210,\n            \"He would enjoy her liveliness and she has talents to value his powers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79231,\n            \"I hope she does not suppose there is any dislike on his side.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79279,\n            \"And Sir Thomas\\u2019 s wishing just at first to be only with his family, is so very natural, that she can argue nothing from that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79524,\n            \"He must like him less after to-morrow\\u2019s visit, for we shall be five hours in his company.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79547,\n            \"I should dread the stupidity of the day, if there were not a much greater evil to follow \\u2014 the impression it must leave on Sir Thomas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79616,\n            \"Not all his good-will for Mr. Rushworth, not all Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s deference for him, could prevent him from soon discerning some part of the truth \\u2014 that Mr. Rushworth was an inferior young man, as ignorant in business as in books, with opinions in general unfixed, and without seeming much aware of it himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79683,\n            \"He had expected a very different son-in-law;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80364,\n            \"Had Sir Thomas applied to his daughter within the first three or four days after Henry Crawford\\u2019s leaving Mansfield, before her feelings were at all tranquillised, before she had given up every hope of him, or absolutely resolved on enduring his rival, her answer might have been different;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80885,\n            \"her father gave her away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83985,\n            \"\\u201cMy sister and Mr. Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83993,\n            \"I am so glad your eldest cousin is gone, that he may be Mr. Bertram again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84012,\n            \"There is something in the sound of Mr. _ Edmund _ Bertram so formal, so pitiful, so younger-brother-like, that I detest it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84543,\n            \"But I have long thought Mr. Bertram one of the worst subjects to work on, in any little manoeuvre against common sense, that a woman could be plagued with.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84576,\n            \"I had very little hope of _ him _ from the first;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84742,\n            \"and what is worse, cook has just been telling me that the turkey, which I particularly wished not to be dressed till Sunday, because I know how much more Dr. Grant would enjoy it on Sunday after the fatigues of the day, will not keep beyond to-morrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84840,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy dear child, commend Dr. Grant to the deanery of Westminster or St.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86662,\n            \"but the subject involving, as it did, her own evening\\u2019s comfort for the morrow, was so much uppermost in Lady Bertram\\u2019s mind, that half an hour afterwards, on his looking in for a minute in his way from his plantation to his dressing-room, she called him back again, when he had almost closed the door, with \\u201cSir Thomas, stop a moment \\u2014 I have something to say to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87164,\n            \"But as I conclude that she must wish to go, since all young people like to be together, I can see no reason why she should be denied the indulgence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87197,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut can I do without her, Sir Thomas?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87209,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed I think you may.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87217,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cShe always makes tea, you know, when my sister is not here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93237,\n            \"This was exactly what Sir Thomas and Edmund had been separately conniving at, as each proved to the other by the sympathetic alacrity with which they both advised Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s continuing where she was, instead of rushing out into the hall as soon as the noises of the arrival reached them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93301,\n            \"and Sir Thomas had the pleasure of receiving, in his prot\\u00e9g\\u00e9, certainly a very different person from the one he had equipped seven years ago, but a young man of an open, pleasant countenance, and frank, unstudied, but feeling and respectful manners, and such as confirmed him his friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93518,\n            \"On the morrow they were walking about together with true enjoyment, and every succeeding morrow renewed a _ t\\u00eate-\\u00e0-t\\u00eate _ which Sir Thomas could not but observe with complacency, even before Edmund had pointed it out to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94699,\n            \"and Crawford could mount him without the slightest inconvenience to himself, and with only some scruples to obviate in Sir Thomas, who knew better than his nephew the value of such a loan, and some alarms to reason away in Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95017,\n            \"His mind, now disengaged from the cares which had pressed on him at first, was at leisure to find the Grants and their young inmates really worth visiting;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95048,\n            \"and though infinitely above scheming or contriving for any the most advantageous matrimonial establishment that could be among the apparent possibilities of any one most dear to him, and disdaining even as a littleness the being quick-sighted on such points, he could not avoid perceiving, in a grand and careless way, that Mr. Crawford was somewhat distinguishing his niece \\u2014 nor perhaps refrain (though unconsciously) from giving a more willing assent to invitations on that account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95528,\n            \"He was a whist player himself, and perhaps might feel that it would not much amuse him to have her for a partner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95689,\n            \"and Sir Thomas, Mrs. Norris, and Dr. and Mrs. Grant being seated at the table of prime intellectual state and dignity, the remaining six, under Miss Crawford\\u2019s direction, were arranged round the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95935,\n            \"Twice had Sir Thomas inquired into the enjoyment and success of his lady, but in vain;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98014,\n            \"\\u201d Sotherton was a word to catch Mrs. Norris, and being just then in the happy leisure which followed securing the odd trick by Sir Thomas\\u2019 s capital play and her own against Dr. and Mrs. Grant\\u2019s great hands, she called out, in high good-humour, \\u201cSotherton!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98439,\n            \"but when the whist-table broke up at the end of the second rubber, and leaving Dr. Grant and Mrs. Norris to dispute over their last play, he became a looker-on at the other, he found his niece the object of attentions, or rather of professions, of a somewhat pointed character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98809,\n            \"Finding by whom he was observed, Henry Crawford addressed himself on the same subject to Sir Thomas, in a more everyday tone, but still with feeling.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98839,\n            \"\\u201cI want to be your neighbour, Sir Thomas, as you have, perhaps, heard me telling Miss Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98862,\n            \"May I hope for your acquiescence, and for your not influencing your son against such a tenant?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98881,\n            \"\\u201d Sir Thomas, politely bowing, replied, \\u201cIt is the only way, sir, in which I could _ not _ wish you established as a permanent neighbour;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99043,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWe shall be the losers,\\u201dcontinued Sir Thomas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99075,\n            \"but I should have been deeply mortified if any son of mine could reconcile himself to doing less.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99331,\n            \"\\u201cSir Thomas,\\u201dsaid Edmund, \\u201cundoubtedly understands the duty of a parish priest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99364,\n            \"\\u201d Whatever effect Sir Thomas\\u2019 s little harangue might really produce on Mr. Crawford, it raised some awkward sensations in two of the others, two of his most attentive listeners \\u2014 Miss Crawford and Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99444,\n            \"and the other, startled from the agreeable fancies she had been previously indulging on the strength of her brother\\u2019s description, no longer able, in the picture she had been forming of a future Thornton, to shut out the church, sink the clergyman, and see only the respectable, elegant, modernised, and occasional residence of a man of independent fortune, was considering Sir Thomas, with decided ill-will, as the destroyer of all this, and suffering the more from that involuntary forbearance which his character and manner commanded, and from not daring to relieve herself by a single attempt at throwing ridicule on his cause.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100612,\n            \"and Sir Thomas, by no means displeased, prolonged the conversation on dancing in general, and was so well engaged in describing the balls of Antigua, and listening to what his nephew could relate of the different modes of dancing which had fallen within his observation, that he had not heard his carriage announced, and was first called to the knowledge of it by the bustle of Mrs. Norris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100736,\n            \"My dear Sir Thomas, we have settled it that the carriage should come back for you, and Edmund and William.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101036,\n            \"I believe we must not think of a Northampton ball.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101090,\n            \"If dear Julia were at home, or dearest Mrs. Rushworth at Sotherton, to afford a reason, an occasion for such a thing, you would be tempted to give the young people a dance at Mansfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101167,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy daughters,\\u201dreplied Sir Thomas, gravely interposing, \\u201chave their pleasures at Brighton, and I hope are very happy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101194,\n            \"but the dance which I think of giving at Mansfield will be for their cousins.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101371,\n            \"Edmund, William, and Fanny did, in their different ways, look and speak as much grateful pleasure in the promised ball as Sir Thomas could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101947,\n            \"She had some extra visits from the housekeeper, and her maid was rather hurried in making up a new dress for her: Sir Thomas gave orders, and Mrs. Norris ran about;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109148,\n            \"To the former she was an interesting object, and he saw with pleasure the general elegance of her appearance, and her being in remarkably good looks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109309,\n            \"The very gown you have been taking notice of is your own generous present to her when dear Mrs. Rushworth married.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109354,\n            \"but when they sat down to table the eyes of the two young men assured him that the subject might be gently touched again, when the ladies withdrew, with more success.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110014,\n            \"and she so little understood her own claims as to think that if Mr. Crawford had not asked her, she must have been the last to be sought after, and should have received a partner only through a series of inquiry, and bustle, and interference, which would have been terrible;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110124,\n            \"And though there was no second glance to disturb her, though his object seemed then to be only quietly agreeable, she could not get the better of her embarrassment, heightened as it was by the idea of his perceiving it, and had no composure till he turned away to some one else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110514,\n            \"Sir Thomas brought him to her, saying something which discovered to Fanny, that _ she _ was to lead the way and open the ball;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110712,\n            \"and she found herself the next moment conducted by Mr. Crawford to the top of the room, and standing there to be joined by the rest of the dancers, couple after couple, as they were formed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110851,\n            \"And to have them away when it was given \\u2014 and for _ her _ to be opening the ball \\u2014 and with Mr. Crawford too!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111177,\n            \"Her praise was warm, and he received it as she could wish, joining in it as far as discretion, and politeness, and slowness of speech would allow, and certainly appearing to greater advantage on the subject than his lady did soon afterwards, when Mary, perceiving her on a sofa very near, turned round before she began to dance, to compliment her on Miss Price\\u2019s looks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111377,\n            \"\\u201d and Mrs. Norris paid her with as many smiles and courteous words as she had time for, amid so much occupation as she found for herself in making up card-tables, giving hints to Sir Thomas, and trying to move all the chaperons to a better part of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111470,\n            \"and, misinterpreting Fanny\\u2019s blushes, still thought she must be doing so when she went to her after the two first dances, and said, with a significant look, \\u201cPerhaps _ you _ can tell me why my brother goes to town to-morrow?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111522,\n            \"He says he has business there, but will not tell me what.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111536,\n            \"The first time he ever denied me his confidence!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113172,\n            \"and there her uncle kindly left her to cry in peace, conceiving, perhaps, that the deserted chair of each young man might exercise her tender enthusiasm, and that the remaining cold pork bones and mustard in William\\u2019s plate might but divide her feelings with the broken egg-shells in Mr. Crawford\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113475,\n            \"\\u201cShe could not recollect what it was that she had heard about one of the Miss Maddoxes, or what it was that Lady Prescott had noticed in Fanny: she was not sure whether Colonel Harrison had been talking of Mr. Crawford or of William when he said he was the finest young man in the room \\u2014 somebody had whispered something to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113543,\n            \"she had forgot to ask Sir Thomas what it could be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114079,\n            \"\\u201cWe miss our two young men,\\u201dwas Sir Thomas\\u2019 s observation on both the first and second day, as they formed their very reduced circle after dinner;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114157,\n            \"\\u201cAnd there is no reason to suppose,\\u201dadded Sir Thomas, \\u201cbut that his visits to us may now be tolerably frequent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114271,\n            \"and as Sir Thomas thought it best for each daughter that the permission should be granted, Lady Bertram, though in her own good-nature she would not have prevented it, was lamenting the change it made in the prospect of Julia\\u2019s return, which would otherwise have taken place about this time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114405,\n            \"and at the end of a quarter of an hour\\u2019s silent consideration spontaneously observed, \\u201cSir Thomas, I have been thinking \\u2014 and I am very glad we took Fanny as we did, for now the others are away we feel the good of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114543,\n            \"\\u201d Sir Thomas paused, half smiled, glanced at his niece, and then gravely replied, \\u201cShe will never leave us, I hope, till invited to some other home that may reasonably promise her greater happiness than she knows here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119551,\n            \"True, I believe he is, generally speaking, kind to her, and so is Sir Thomas in his way;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119592,\n            \"What can Sir Thomas and Edmund together do, what _ do _ they do for her happiness, comfort, honour, and dignity in the world, to what I _ shall _ do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119684,\n            \"She was almost at the door, and not chusing by any means to take so much trouble in vain, she still went on, after a civil reception, a short sentence about being waited for, and a \\u201cLet Sir Thomas know\\u201dto the servant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119951,\n            \"The first was from the Admiral to inform his nephew, in a few words, of his having succeeded in the object he had undertaken, the promotion of young Price, and enclosing two more, one from the Secretary of the First Lord to a friend, whom the Admiral had set to work in the business, the other from that friend to himself, by which it appeared that his lordship had the very great happiness of attending to the recommendation of Sir Charles;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120041,\n            \"that Sir Charles was much delighted in having such an opportunity of proving his regard for Admiral Crawford, and that the circumstance of Mr. William Price\\u2019s commission as Second Lieutenant of H.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121395,\n            \"\\u201d She had burst away from him, and at that moment Sir Thomas was heard speaking to a servant in his way towards the room they were in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121472,\n            \"She rushed out at an opposite door from the one her uncle was approaching, and was walking up and down the East room in the utmost confusion of contrary feeling, before Sir Thomas\\u2019 s politeness or apologies were over, or he had reached the beginning of the joyful intelligence which his visitor came to communicate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121750,\n            \"but when convinced of his being gone, she was eager to go down and be with her uncle, and have all the happiness of his joy as well as her own, and all the benefit of his information or his conjectures as to what would now be William\\u2019s destination.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125996,\n            \"\\u201cAm I to understand,\\u201dsaid Sir Thomas, after a few moments\\u2019 silence, \\u201cthat you mean to _ refuse _ Mr. Crawford?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126058,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI \\u2014 I cannot like him, sir, well enough to marry him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126171,\n            \"His sister, moreover, is your intimate friend, and he has been doing _ that _ for your brother, which I should suppose would have been almost sufficient recommendation to you, had there been no other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126277,\n            \"\\u201cYou must have been aware,\\u201dcontinued Sir Thomas presently, \\u201cyou must have been some time aware of a particularity in Mr. Crawford\\u2019s manners to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126326,\n            \"and though you always received them very properly (I have no accusation to make on that head), I never perceived them to be unpleasant to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126356,\n            \"I am half inclined to think, Fanny, that you do not quite know your own feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126397,\n            \"\\u201d Sir Thomas looked at her with deeper surprise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126422,\n            \"Young as you are, and having seen scarcely any one, it is hardly possible that your affections \\u2014\\u201dHe paused and eyed her fixedly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126450,\n            \"He saw her lips formed into a _ no _, though the sound was inarticulate, but her face was like scarlet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126636,\n            \"I am an advocate for early marriages, where there are means in proportion, and would have every young man, with a sufficient income, settle as soon after four-and-twenty as he can.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126676,\n            \"This is so much my opinion, that I am sorry to think how little likely my own eldest son, your cousin, Mr. Bertram, is to marry early;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126770,\n            \"_ He _, indeed, I have lately thought, has seen the woman he could love, which, I am convinced, my eldest son has not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126805,\n            \"Do you agree with me, my dear?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126820,\n            \"\\u201d It was gently, but it was calmly said, and Sir Thomas was easy on the score of the cousins.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126843,\n            \"But the removal of his alarm did his niece no service: as her unaccountableness was confirmed his displeasure increased;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126864,\n            \"and getting up and walking about the room with a frown, which Fanny could picture to herself, though she dared not lift up her eyes, he shortly afterwards, and in a voice of authority, said, \\u201cHave you any reason, child, to think ill of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s temper?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126964,\n            \"Her ill opinion of him was founded chiefly on observations, which, for her cousins\\u2019 sake, she could scarcely dare mention to their father.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127030,\n            \"She had hoped that, to a man like her uncle, so discerning, so honourable, so good, the simple acknowledgment of settled _ dislike _ on her side would have been sufficient.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127077,\n            \"Sir Thomas came towards the table where she sat in trembling wretchedness, and with a good deal of cold sternness, said, \\u201cIt is of no use, I perceive, to talk to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127217,\n            \"I had thought you peculiarly free from wilfulness of temper, self-conceit, and every tendency to that independence of spirit which prevails so much in modern days, even in young women, and which in young women is offensive and disgusting beyond all common offence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127574,\n            \"Gladly would I have bestowed either of my own daughters on him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127592,\n            \"but had Mr. Crawford sought Julia\\u2019s hand, I should have given it to him with superior and more heartfelt satisfaction than I gave Maria\\u2019s to Mr. Rushworth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127627,\n            \"\\u201d After half a moment\\u2019s pause: \\u201cAnd I should have been very much surprised had either of my daughters, on receiving a proposal of marriage at any time which might carry with it only _ half _ the eligibility of _ this _, immediately and peremptorily, and without paying my opinion or my regard the compliment of any consultation, put a decided negative on it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127741,\n            \"You do not owe me the duty of a child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127752,\n            \"But, Fanny, if your heart can acquit you of _ ingratitude _ \\u2014\\u201dHe ceased.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127837,\n            \"He thought her all this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127843,\n            \"She had deceived his expectations;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127849,\n            \"she had lost his good opinion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127889,\n            \"yes, I hope you are sorry;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128025,\n            \"He knew her to be very timid, and exceedingly nervous;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128111,\n            \"and these reflections having passed across his mind and cheered it, \\u201cWell,\\u201dsaid he, in a tone of becoming gravity, but of less anger, \\u201cwell, child, dry up your tears.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128166,\n            \"You must now come downstairs with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128237,\n            \"\\u201d But Fanny shewed such reluctance, such misery, at the idea of going down to him, that Sir Thomas, after a little consideration, judged it better to indulge her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128286,\n            \"but when he looked at his niece, and saw the state of feature and complexion which her crying had brought her into, he thought there might be as much lost as gained by an immediate interview.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128378,\n            \"But her uncle\\u2019s anger gave her the severest pain of all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128432,\n            \"He might have softened his father;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128527,\n            \"she was almost ready to faint at the sight of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128539,\n            \"He spoke calmly, however, without austerity, without reproach, and she revived a little.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128599,\n            \"I do not want to add to anything you may now be feeling, by an account of what he has felt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128655,\n            \"Upon my representation of what you were suffering, he immediately, and with the greatest delicacy, ceased to urge to see you for the present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128696,\n            \"\\u201cOf course,\\u201dcontinued her uncle, \\u201cit cannot be supposed but that he should request to speak with you alone, be it only for five minutes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128781,\n            \"If, as I am willing to suppose, you wish to shew me any observance, you will not give way to these emotions, but endeavour to reason yourself into a stronger frame of mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128819,\n            \"I advise you to go out: the air will do you good;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128945,\n            \"he left her in a glow of gratitude.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128974,\n            \"She walked out directly, as her uncle recommended, and followed his advice throughout, as far as she could;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132703,\n            \"In spite of his intended silence, Sir Thomas found himself once more obliged to mention the subject to his niece, to prepare her briefly for its being imparted to her aunts;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132926,\n            \"He pressed for the strictest forbearance and silence towards their niece;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133230,\n            \"I must just speak of it _ once _, I told Sir Thomas I must _ once _, and then I shall have done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133592,\n            \"I shall tell Sir Thomas that I am sure it was done that evening.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134176,\n            \"His surprise was not so great as his father\\u2019s at her refusing Crawford, because, so far from supposing her to consider him with anything like a preference, he had always believed it to be rather the reverse, and could imagine her to be taken perfectly unprepared, but Sir Thomas could not regard the connexion as more desirable than he did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134251,\n            \"and while honouring her for what she had done under the influence of her present indifference, honouring her in rather stronger terms than Sir Thomas could quite echo, he was most earnest in hoping, and sanguine in believing, that it would be a match at last, and that, united by mutual affection, it would appear that their dispositions were as exactly fitted to make them blessed in each other, as he was now beginning seriously to consider them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134420,\n            \"Crawford called the next day, and on the score of Edmund\\u2019s return, Sir Thomas felt himself more than licensed to ask him to stay dinner;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142928,\n            \"He gave this opinion as the result of the conversation to his father;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148232,\n            \"Sir Thomas retiring from it with some feelings of satisfaction, and views of good over and above what he had communicated to his son;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148258,\n            \"for his prime motive in sending her away had very little to do with the propriety of her seeing her parents again, and nothing at all with any idea of making her happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148293,\n            \"He certainly wished her to go willingly, but he as certainly wished her to be heartily sick of home before her visit ended;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148368,\n            \"It was a medicinal project upon his niece\\u2019s understanding, which he must consider as at present diseased.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148434,\n            \"and he trusted that she would be the wiser and happier woman, all her life, for the experiment he had devised.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170917,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny checked the tendency of these thoughts as well as she could, but she was within half a minute of starting the idea that Sir Thomas was quite unkind, both to her aunt and to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171474,\n            \"For though Lady Bertram rather shone in the epistolary line, having early in her marriage, from the want of other employment, and the circumstance of Sir Thomas\\u2019 s being in Parliament, got into the way of making and keeping correspondents, and formed for herself a very creditable, common-place, amplifying style, so that a very little matter was enough for her: she could not do entirely without any;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171884,\n            \"\\u201cThis distressing intelligence, as you may suppose,\\u201dobserved her ladyship, after giving the substance of it, \\u201chas agitated us exceedingly, and we cannot prevent ourselves from being greatly alarmed and apprehensive for the poor invalid, whose state Sir Thomas fears may be very critical;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171938,\n            \"and Edmund kindly proposes attending his brother immediately, but I am happy to add that Sir Thomas will not leave me on this distressing occasion, as it would be too trying for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171974,\n            \"We shall greatly miss Edmund in our small circle, but I trust and hope he will find the poor invalid in a less alarming state than might be apprehended, and that he will be able to bring him to Mansfield shortly, which Sir Thomas proposes should be done, and thinks best on every account, and I flatter myself the poor sufferer will soon be able to bear the removal without material inconvenience or injury.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172380,\n            \"I am quite grieved for him, and very much frightened, and so is Sir Thomas;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172412,\n            \"But Sir Thomas hopes he will be better to-morrow, and says we must consider his journey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173170,\n            \"His aunt worried him by her cares, and Sir Thomas knew not how to bring down his conversation or his voice to the level of irritation and feebleness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181271,\n            \"Lady Bertram did not think deeply, but, guided by Sir Thomas, she thought justly on all important points;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181416,\n            \"Her aunt was no very methodical narrator, but with the help of some letters to and from Sir Thomas, and what she already knew herself, and could reasonably combine, she was soon able to understand quite as much as she wished of the circumstances attending the story.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181468,\n            \"Mrs. Rushworth had gone, for the Easter holidays, to Twickenham, with a family whom she had just grown intimate with: a family of lively, agreeable manners, and probably of morals and discretion to suit, for to _ their _ house Mr. Crawford had constant access at all times.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181602,\n            \"a removal which her father and mother were now disposed to attribute to some view of convenience on Mr. Yates\\u2019 s account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181627,\n            \"Very soon after the Rushworths\\u2019 return to Wimpole Street, Sir Thomas had received a letter from an old and most particular friend in London, who hearing and witnessing a good deal to alarm him in that quarter, wrote to recommend Sir Thomas\\u2019 s coming to London himself, and using his influence with his daughter to put an end to the intimacy which was already exposing her to unpleasant remarks, and evidently making Mr. Rushworth uneasy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181711,\n            \"Sir Thomas was preparing to act upon this letter, without communicating its contents to any creature at Mansfield, when it was followed by another, sent express from the same friend, to break to him the almost desperate situation in which affairs then stood with the young people.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182121,\n            \"Sir Thomas, however, remained yet a little longer in town, in the hope of discovering and snatching her from farther vice, though all was lost on the side of character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182169,\n            \"There was but one of his children who was not at this time a source of misery to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182189,\n            \"Tom\\u2019s complaints had been greatly heightened by the shock of his sister\\u2019s conduct, and his recovery so much thrown back by it, that even Lady Bertram had been struck by the difference, and all her alarms were regularly sent off to her husband;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182559,\n            \"but Sir Thomas was considering his happiness as very deeply involved in the offence of his sister and friend;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182726,\n            \"Fanny was not in the secret of her uncle\\u2019s feelings, Sir Thomas not in the secret of Miss Crawford\\u2019s character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184713,\n            \"If by any officious exertions of his, she is induced to leave Henry\\u2019s protection, there will be much less chance of his marrying her than if she remain with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186158,\n            \"and when Sir Thomas came back she had every proof that could be given in his then melancholy state of spirits, of his perfect approbation and increased regard;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186306,\n            \"Sir Thomas, poor Sir Thomas, a parent, and conscious of errors in his own conduct as a parent, was the longest to suffer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186346,\n            \"that his daughter\\u2019s sentiments had been sufficiently known to him to render him culpable in authorising it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186678,\n            \"He became what he ought to be: useful to his father, steady and quiet, and not living merely for himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186783,\n            \"These were the circumstances and the hopes which gradually brought their alleviation to Sir Thomas, deadening his sense of what was lost, and in part reconciling him to himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187247,\n            \"She was not to be prevailed on to leave Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187260,\n            \"She hoped to marry him, and they continued together till she was obliged to be convinced that such hope was vain, and till the disappointment and wretchedness arising from the conviction rendered her temper so bad, and her feelings for him so like hatred, as to make them for a while each other\\u2019s punishment, and then induce a voluntary separation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187328,\n            \"She had lived with him to be reproached as the ruin of all his happiness in Fanny, and carried away no better consolation in leaving him than that she _ had _ divided them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187638,\n            \"She persisted in placing his scruples to _ her _ account, though Sir Thomas very solemnly assured her that, had there been no young woman in question, had there been no young person of either sex belonging to him, to be endangered by the society or hurt by the character of Mrs. Rushworth, he would never have offered so great an insult to the neighbourhood as to expect it to notice her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190923,\n            \"In _ her _ usefulness, in Fanny\\u2019s excellence, in William\\u2019s continued good conduct and rising fame, and in the general well-doing and success of the other members of the family, all assisting to advance each other, and doing credit to his countenance and aid, Sir Thomas saw repeated, and for ever repeated, reason to rejoice in what he had done for them all, and acknowledge the advantages of early hardship and discipline, and the consciousness of being born to struggle and endure.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 18]\": [\n        [\n            1916,\n            \"and, though I could never feel for this little girl the hundredth part of the regard I bear your own dear children, nor consider her, in any respect, so much my own, I should hate myself if I were capable of neglecting her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1965,\n            \"Is not she a sister\\u2019s child?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1974,\n            \"and could I bear to see her want while I had a bit of bread to give her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2052,\n            \"and, as soon as matters are settled, _ I _ will engage to get the child to Mansfield;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2094,\n            \"I will send Nanny to London on purpose, and she may have a bed at her cousin the saddler\\u2019s, and the child be appointed to meet her there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2127,\n            \"They may easily get her from Portsmouth to town by the coach, under the care of any creditable person that may chance to be going.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2238,\n            \"for Sir Thomas was fully resolved to be the real and consistent patron of the selected child, and Mrs. Norris had not the least intention of being at any expense whatever in her maintenance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2542,\n            \"and, in reply to Lady Bertram\\u2019s calm inquiry of \\u201cWhere shall the child come to first, sister, to you or to us?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2638,\n            \"Mrs. Norris was sorry to say that the little girl\\u2019s staying with them, at least as things then were, was quite out of the question.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2768,\n            \"\\u201cThen she had better come to us,\\u201dsaid Lady Bertram, with the utmost composure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2808,\n            \"We will endeavour to do our duty by her, and she will, at least, have the advantage of companions of her own age, and of a regular instructress.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2919,\n            \"and Nanny shall fetch her, however it may put me to inconvenience to have my chief counsellor away for three days.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2963,\n            \"It will be much the best place for her, so near Miss Lee, and not far from the girls, and close by the housemaids, who could either of them help to dress her, you know, and take care of her clothes, for I suppose you would not think it fair to expect Ellis to wait on her as well as the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3055,\n            \"\\u201cI hope she will prove a well-disposed girl,\\u201dcontinued Mrs. Norris, \\u201cand be sensible of her uncommon good fortune in having such friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3087,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cShould her disposition be really bad,\\u201dsaid Sir Thomas, \\u201cwe must not, for our own children\\u2019s sake, continue her in the family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3132,\n            \"We shall probably see much to wish altered in her, and must prepare ourselves for gross ignorance, some meanness of opinions, and very distressing vulgarity of manner;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3183,\n            \"Had my daughters been _ younger _ than herself, I should have considered the introduction of such a companion as a matter of very serious moment;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3211,\n            \"but, as it is, I hope there can be nothing to fear for _ them _, and everything to hope for _ her _, from the association.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3270,\n            \"It will be an education for the child, said I, only being with her cousins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3288,\n            \"if Miss Lee taught her nothing, she would learn to be good and clever from _ them _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3308,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI hope she will not tease my poor pug,\\u201dsaid Lady Bertram;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3325,\n            \"\\u201cI have but just got Julia to leave it alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5032,\n            \"or had she quarrelled with Maria and Julia?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5781,\n            \"and with that view endeavoured, in the first place, to lessen her fears of them all, and gave her especially a great deal of good advice as to playing with Maria and Julia, and being as merry as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6958,\n            \"She was a woman who spent her days in sitting, nicely dressed, on a sofa, doing some long piece of needlework, of little use and no beauty, thinking more of her pug than her children, but very indulgent to the latter when it did not put herself to inconvenience, guided in everything important by Sir Thomas, and in smaller concerns by her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7601,\n            \"but William determining, soon after her removal, to be a sailor, was invited to spend a week with his sister in Northamptonshire before he went to sea.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7661,\n            \"as well as the sanguine views and spirits of the boy even to the last, and the misery of the girl when he left her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8591,\n            \"The time was now come when Sir Thomas expected his sister-in-law to claim her share in their niece, the change in Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s situation, and the improvement in Fanny\\u2019s age, seeming not merely to do away any former objection to their living together, but even to give it the most decided eligibility;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8713,\n            \"In the fullness of his belief that such a thing must be, he mentioned its probability to his wife;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8734,\n            \"and the first time of the subject\\u2019s occurring to her again happening to be when Fanny was present, she calmly observed to her, \\u201cSo, Fanny, you are going to leave us, and live with my sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8821,\n            \"You have been five years with us, and my sister always meant to take you when Mr. Norris died.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16686,\n            \"Miss Bertram\\u2019s engagement made him in equity the property of Julia, of which Julia was fully aware;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16707,\n            \"and before he had been at Mansfield a week, she was quite ready to be fallen in love with.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16907,\n            \"But you like Julia best.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16918,\n            \"I like Julia best.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16947,\n            \"She has the advantage in every feature, and I prefer her countenance;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16961,\n            \"but I like Julia best;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16967,\n            \"Miss Bertram is certainly the handsomest, and I have found her the most agreeable, but I shall always like Julia best, because you order me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16996,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI shall not talk to you, Henry, but I know you _ will _ like her best at last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17020,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo not I tell you that I like her best _ at _ _ first _?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17154,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut Miss Bertram does not care three straws for him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17167,\n            \"_ that _ is your opinion of your intimate friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17187,\n            \"I am sure Miss Bertram is very much attached to Mr. Rushworth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17201,\n            \"I could see it in her eyes, when he was mentioned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17214,\n            \"I think too well of Miss Bertram to suppose she would ever give her hand without her heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23913,\n            \"You have been an improver yourself, and from what I hear of Everingham, it may vie with any place in England.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23985,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNothing could be so gratifying to me as to hear your opinion of it,\\u201dwas his answer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24007,\n            \"\\u201cbut I fear there would be some disappointment: you would not find it equal to your present ideas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24599,\n            \"I dare say Mr. Crawford would take my two nieces and me in his barouche, and Edmund can go on horseback, you know, sister, and Fanny will stay at home with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27500,\n            \"\\u201cI was sure she would ride well,\\u201dsaid Julia;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28212,\n            \"For a few minutes the brother and sister were too eager in their praise of the night and their remarks on the stars, to think beyond themselves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28825,\n            \"\\u201cbut I question whether her headache might not be caught _ then _, sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30840,\n            \"\\u201d cried Julia: \\u201cgo boxed up three in a postchaise in this weather, when we may have seats in a barouche!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30877,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBesides,\\u201dsaid Maria, \\u201cI know that Mr. Crawford depends upon taking us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31044,\n            \"I will answer for it that we shall find no inconvenience from narrow roads on Wednesday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32131,\n            \"and as you were saying lately that you wished you could drive, Julia, I think this will be a good opportunity for you to take a lesson.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32514,\n            \"and to see only his expressive profile as he turned with a smile to Julia, or to catch the laugh of the other, was a perpetual source of irritation, which her own sense of propriety could but just smooth over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32558,\n            \"When Julia looked back, it was with a countenance of delight, and whenever she spoke to them, it was in the highest spirits: \\u201cher view of the country was charming, she wished they could all see it,\\u201detc.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35025,\n            \"\\u201d While this was passing, the rest of the party being scattered about the chapel, Julia called Mr. Crawford\\u2019s attention to her sister, by saying, \\u201cDo look at Mr. Rushworth and Maria, standing side by side, exactly as if the ceremony were going to be performed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35092,\n            \"\\u201d Mr. Crawford smiled his acquiescence, and stepping forward to Maria, said, in a voice which she only could hear, \\u201cI do not like to see Miss Bertram so near the altar.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35131,\n            \"\\u201d Starting, the lady instinctively moved a step or two, but recovering herself in a moment, affected to laugh, and asked him, in a tone not much louder, \\u201cIf he would give her away?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35196,\n            \"Julia, joining them at the moment, carried on the joke.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35209,\n            \"\\u201cUpon my word, it is really a pity that it should not take place directly, if we had but a proper licence, for here we are altogether, and nothing in the world could be more snug and pleasant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35253,\n            \"\\u201d And she talked and laughed about it with so little caution as to catch the comprehension of Mr. Rushworth and his mother, and expose her sister to the whispered gallantries of her lover, while Mrs. Rushworth spoke with proper smiles and dignity of its being a most happy event to her whenever it took place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35366,\n            \"Mr. Rushworth and Maria are quite ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35375,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Crawford\\u2019s countenance, as Julia spoke, might have amused a disinterested observer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35409,\n            \"\\u201cHow distressed she will be at what she said just now,\\u201dpassed across her mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36111,\n            \"The remaining three, Mrs. Rushworth, Mrs. Norris, and Julia, were still far behind;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36131,\n            \"for Julia, whose happy star no longer prevailed, was obliged to keep by the side of Mrs. Rushworth, and restrain her impatient feet to that lady\\u2019s slow pace, while her aunt, having fallen in with the housekeeper, who was come out to feed the pheasants, was lingering behind in gossip with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36194,\n            \"Poor Julia, the only one out of the nine not tolerably satisfied with their lot, was now in a state of complete penance, and as different from the Julia of the barouche-box as could well be imagined.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39544,\n            \"You and Julia were laughing the whole way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39577,\n            \"I believe I was relating to her some ridiculous stories of an old Irish groom of my uncle\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39604,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou think her more light-hearted than I am?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39658,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNaturally, I believe, I am as lively as Julia, but I have more to think of now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40232,\n            \"She expected Mr. Rushworth, but it was Julia, who, hot and out of breath, and with a look of disappointment, cried out on seeing her, \\u201cHeyday!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40272,\n            \"I thought Maria and Mr. Crawford were with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40296,\n            \"I cannot see them anywhere,\\u201dlooking eagerly into the park.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40309,\n            \"\\u201cBut they cannot be very far off, and I think I am equal to as much as Maria, even without help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40334,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut, Julia, Mr. Rushworth will be here in a moment with the key.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40378,\n            \"Why, child, I have but this moment escaped from his horrible mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40393,\n            \"Such a penance as I have been enduring, while you were sitting here so composed and so happy!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40413,\n            \"It might have been as well, perhaps, if you had been in my place, but you always contrive to keep out of these scrapes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40471,\n            \"but she felt that it would not last, and therefore, taking no notice, only asked her if she had not seen Mr. Rushworth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40577,\n            \"The mother I could not avoid, as long as my tiresome aunt was dancing about with the housekeeper, but the son I _ can _ get away from.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40696,\n            \"He joined her within five minutes after Julia\\u2019s exit;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40764,\n            \"\\u201cThey desired me to stay \\u2014 my cousin Maria charged me to say that you would find them at that knoll, or thereabouts.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41033,\n            \"In my opinion, these Crawfords are no addition at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41101,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNothing could be more obliging than your manner, I am sure, and I dare say you walked as fast as you could;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41745,\n            \"and since Julia\\u2019s leaving them they had been met by the gardener, with whom she had made a most satisfactory acquaintance, for she had set him right as to his grandson\\u2019s illness, convinced him that it was an ague, and promised him a charm for it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41973,\n            \"She felt, as she looked at Julia and Mr. Rushworth, that hers was not the only dissatisfied bosom amongst them: there was gloom on the face of each.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42138,\n            \"At the same moment Mr. Crawford, approaching Julia, said, \\u201cI hope I am not to lose my companion, unless she is afraid of the evening air in so exposed a seat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42382,\n            \"Your lap seems full of good things, and here is a basket of something between us which has been knocking my elbow unmercifully.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42407,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy dear, it is only a beautiful little heath, which that nice old gardener would make me take;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42430,\n            \"but if it is in your way, I will have it in my lap directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42505,\n            \"I stood out as long as I could, till the tears almost came into her eyes, and I knew it was just the sort that my sister would be delighted with.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46036,\n            \"He went for a fortnight \\u2014 a fortnight of such dullness to the Miss Bertrams as ought to have put them both on their guard, and made even Julia admit, in her jealousy of her sister, the absolute necessity of distrusting his attentions, and wishing him not to return;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46306,\n            \"and Julia, unengaged and unemployed, felt all the right of missing him much more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46330,\n            \"Julia might be justified in so doing by the hints of Mrs. Grant, inclined to credit what she wished, and Maria by the hints of Mr. Crawford himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46623,\n            \"She does not like his unsettled habits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46656,\n            \"Mrs. Grant, I believe, suspects him of a preference for Julia;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46700,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf Miss Bertram were not engaged,\\u201dsaid Fanny cautiously, \\u201cI could sometimes almost think that he admired her more than Julia.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46728,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWhich is, perhaps, more in favour of his liking Julia best, than you, Fanny, may be aware;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46753,\n            \"for I believe it often happens that a man, before he has quite made up his own mind, will distinguish the sister or intimate friend of the woman he is really thinking of more than the woman herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46794,\n            \"Crawford has too much sense to stay here if he found himself in any danger from Maria;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46854,\n            \"but with all that submission to Edmund could do, and all the help of the coinciding looks and hints which she occasionally noticed in some of the others, and which seemed to say that Julia was Mr. Crawford\\u2019s choice, she knew not always what to think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47349,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Bertram did indeed look happy, her eyes were sparkling with pleasure, and she was speaking with great animation, for Julia and her partner, Mr. Crawford, were close to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47585,\n            \"Four thousand a year is a pretty estate, and he seems a very genteel, steady young man, so I hope Miss Julia will be very happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50190,\n            \"Maria, Julia, Henry Crawford, and Mr. Yates were in the billiard-room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53653,\n            \"\\u201cThis is not behaving well by the absent,\\u201dsaid she.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53674,\n            \"Amelia and Agatha may do for Maria and me, but here is nothing for your sister, Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53877,\n            \"\\u201cI must entreat Miss _ Julia _ Bertram,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cnot to engage in the part of Agatha, or it will be the ruin of all my solemnity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54143,\n            \"you had, indeed, Julia.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54329,\n            \"but I mean no disparagement to Julia.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54353,\n            \"and I am sure I set her the example of moderation myself in being satisfied with the old Butler.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54389,\n            \"and if she is so desperately bent against everything humorous, let her take Cottager\\u2019s speeches instead of Cottager\\u2019s wife\\u2019s, and so change the parts all through;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54648,\n            \"\\u201d turning to her with a look of anxious entreaty, which softened her a little;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55061,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo not be afraid of _ my _ wanting the character,\\u201dcried Julia, with angry quickness: \\u201cI am _ not _ to be Agatha, and I am sure I will do nothing else;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55122,\n            \"I quite detest her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55155,\n            \"\\u201d And so saying, she walked hastily out of the room, leaving awkward feelings to more than one, but exciting small compassion in any except Fanny, who had been a quiet auditor of the whole, and who could not think of her as under the agitations of _ jealousy _ without great pity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55222,\n            \"but her brother soon returned to business and Lovers\\u2019 Vows, and was eagerly looking over the play, with Mr. Yates\\u2019 s help, to ascertain what scenery would be necessary \\u2014 while Maria and Henry Crawford conversed together in an under-voice, and the declaration with which she began of, \\u201cI am sure I would give up the part to Julia most willingly, but that though I shall probably do it very ill, I feel persuaded _ she _ would do it worse,\\u201dwas doubtless receiving all the compliments it called for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56907,\n            \"\\u201d cried Edmund, \\u201cif she knew your reasons!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56922,\n            \"she might think the difference between us \\u2014 the difference in our situations \\u2014 that _ she _ need not be so scrupulous as _ I _ might feel necessary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56953,\n            \"I am sure she would argue so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57618,\n            \"Mr. Yates, who was trying to make himself agreeable to Julia, found her gloom less impenetrable on any topic than that of his regret at her secession from their company;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64397,\n            \"Henry Crawford had trifled with her feelings;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64405,\n            \"but she had very long allowed and even sought his attentions, with a jealousy of her sister so reasonable as ought to have been their cure;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64433,\n            \"and now that the conviction of his preference for Maria had been forced on her, she submitted to it without any alarm for Maria\\u2019s situation, or any endeavour at rational tranquillity for herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64616,\n            \"She was not pleased to see Julia excluded from the play, and sitting by disregarded;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64633,\n            \"but as it was not a matter which really involved her happiness, as Henry must be the best judge of his own, and as he did assure her, with a most persuasive smile, that neither he nor Julia had ever had a serious thought of each other, she could only renew her former caution as to the elder sister, entreat him not to risk his tranquillity by too much admiration there, and then gladly take her share in anything that brought cheerfulness to the young people in general, and that did so particularly promote the pleasure of the two so dear to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64745,\n            \"\\u201cI rather wonder Julia is not in love with Henry,\\u201dwas her observation to Mary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64764,\n            \"\\u201cI dare say she is,\\u201dreplied Mary coldly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65125,\n            \"I am sure _ Julia _ does not, or she would not have flirted as she did last night with Mr. Yates;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65254,\n            \"\\u201d Julia _ did _ suffer, however, though Mrs. Grant discerned it not, and though it escaped the notice of many of her own family likewise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65348,\n            \"The sister with whom she was used to be on easy terms was now become her greatest enemy: they were alienated from each other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65374,\n            \"and Julia was not superior to the hope of some distressing end to the attentions which were still carrying on there, some punishment to Maria for conduct so shameful towards herself as well as towards Mr. Rushworth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65484,\n            \"and Julia could never see Maria distinguished by Henry Crawford without trusting that it would create jealousy, and bring a public disturbance at last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65555,\n            \"The inattention of the two brothers and the aunt to Julia\\u2019s discomposure, and their blindness to its true cause, must be imputed to the fullness of their own minds.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69422,\n            \"and being too much engaged in their own noise to be struck by an unusual noise in the other part of the house, had proceeded some way when the door of the room was thrown open, and Julia, appearing at it, with a face all aghast, exclaimed, \\u201cMy father is come!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69713,\n            \"but at the moment of her appearance, Frederick was listening with looks of devotion to Agatha\\u2019s narrative, and pressing her hand to his heart;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69742,\n            \"and as soon as she could notice this, and see that, in spite of the shock of her words, he still kept his station and retained her sister\\u2019s hand, her wounded heart swelled again with injury, and looking as red as she had been white before, she turned out of the room, saying, \\u201c_ I _ need not be afraid of appearing before him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77404,\n            \"and so ended all the hopes his selfish vanity had raised in Maria and Julia Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77421,\n            \"Julia could rejoice that he was gone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77429,\n            \"His presence was beginning to be odious to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77545,\n            \"Mrs. Norris began to look about her, and wonder that his falling in love with Julia had come to nothing;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77673,\n            \"In himself he was wearisome, but as the friend of Tom and the admirer of Julia he became offensive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80758,\n            \"Mrs. Rushworth was quite ready to retire, and make way for the fortunate young woman whom her dear son had selected;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80922,\n            \"Nothing could be objected to when it came under the discussion of the neighbourhood, except that the carriage which conveyed the bride and bridegroom and Julia from the church-door to Sotherton was the same chaise which Mr. Rushworth had used for a twelvemonth before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81091,\n            \"and no one would have supposed, from her confident triumph, that she had ever heard of conjugal infelicity in her life, or could have the smallest insight into the disposition of the niece who had been brought up under her eye.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81203,\n            \"Julia was to go with them to Brighton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87684,\n            \"Mrs. Grant thinks it a civility due to _ us _ to take a little notice of you, or else it would never have come into her head, and you may be very certain that, if your cousin Julia had been at home, you would not have been asked at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88110,\n            \"and I do beseech and entreat you not to be putting yourself forward, and talking and giving your opinion as if you were one of your cousins \\u2014 as if you were dear Mrs. Rushworth or Julia.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88174,\n            \"and though Miss Crawford is in a manner at home at the Parsonage, you are not to be taking place of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89600,\n            \"And Julia is with them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89657,\n            \"I think my friend Julia knows better than to entertain her father with Mr. Yates.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89712,\n            \"Well, I am much mistaken if his lovely Maria will ever want him to make two-and-forty speeches to her \\u201d;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89738,\n            \"adding, with a momentary seriousness, \\u201cShe is too good for him \\u2014 much too good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114271,\n            \"and as Sir Thomas thought it best for each daughter that the permission should be granted, Lady Bertram, though in her own good-nature she would not have prevented it, was lamenting the change it made in the prospect of Julia\\u2019s return, which would otherwise have taken place about this time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146669,\n            \"and your eldest cousin, and the Rushworths, and Julia, I am sure of meeting again and again, and all but you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174488,\n            \"It appeared from one of her aunt\\u2019s letters that Julia had offered to return if wanted, but this was all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175307,\n            \"and Julia is with the cousins who live near Bedford Square, but I forget their name and street.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176538,\n            \"If they are gone, I would lay my life they are only gone to Mansfield Park, and Julia with them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178667,\n            \"She left London a few hours before we entered it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179008,\n            \"Julia\\u2019s elopement could affect her comparatively but little;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179039,\n            \"She was obliged to call herself to think of it, and acknowledge it to be terrible and grievous, or it was escaping her, in the midst of all the agitating pressing joyful cares attending this summons to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181537,\n            \"Mr. Rushworth had been gone at this time to Bath, to pass a few days with his mother, and bring her back to town, and Maria was with these friends without any restraint, without even Julia;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181579,\n            \"for Julia had removed from Wimpole Street two or three weeks before, on a visit to some relations of Sir Thomas;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182240,\n            \"and Julia\\u2019s elopement, the additional blow which had met him on his arrival in London, though its force had been deadened at the moment, must, she knew, be sorely felt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182341,\n            \"He called it a bad thing, done in the worst manner, and at the worst time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182360,\n            \"and though Julia was yet as more pardonable than Maria as folly than vice, he could not but regard the step she had taken as opening the worst probabilities of a conclusion hereafter like her sister\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182400,\n            \"Such was his opinion of the set into which she had thrown herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186441,\n            \"Julia\\u2019s match became a less desperate business than he had considered it at first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186840,\n            \"Too late he became aware how unfavourable to the character of any young people must be the totally opposite treatment which Maria and Julia had been always experiencing at home, where the excessive indulgence and flattery of their aunt had been continually contrasted with his own severity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188141,\n            \"That Julia escaped better than Maria was owing, in some measure, to a favourable difference of disposition and circumstance, but in a greater to her having been less the darling of that very aunt, less flattered and less spoilt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188246,\n            \"She had submitted the best to the disappointment in Henry Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188258,\n            \"After the first bitterness of the conviction of being slighted was over, she had been tolerably soon in a fair way of not thinking of him again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188287,\n            \"and when the acquaintance was renewed in town, and Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s house became Crawford\\u2019s object, she had had the merit of withdrawing herself from it, and of chusing that time to pay a visit to her other friends, in order to secure herself from being again too much attracted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188392,\n            \"and had not her sister\\u2019s conduct burst forth as it did, and her increased dread of her father and of home, on that event, imagining its certain consequence to herself would be greater severity and restraint, made her hastily resolve on avoiding such immediate horrors at all risks, it is probable that Mr. Yates would never have succeeded.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 19]\": [\n        [\n            149670,\n            \"You will tell my mother how it all ought to be, and you will be so useful to Susan, and you will teach Betsey, and make the boys love and mind you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152665,\n            \"\\u201cYou know you had but just settled that my sister Fanny and I should have the other room;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152685,\n            \"and I could not get Rebecca to give me any help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153942,\n            \"_ Within _ the room all was tranquil enough, for Susan having disappeared with the others, there were soon only her father and herself remaining;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154476,\n            \"Susan and an attendant girl, whose inferior appearance informed Fanny, to her great surprise, that she had previously seen the upper servant, brought in everything necessary for the meal;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154510,\n            \"Susan looking, as she put the kettle on the fire and glanced at her sister, as if divided between the agreeable triumph of shewing her activity and usefulness, and the dread of being thought to demean herself by such an office.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154555,\n            \"\\u201cShe had been into the kitchen,\\u201dshe said, \\u201cto hurry Sally and help make the toast, and spread the bread and butter, or she did not know when they should have got tea, and she was sure her sister must want something after her journey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154615,\n            \"She could not but own that she should be very glad of a little tea, and Susan immediately set about making it, as if pleased to have the employment all to herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154650,\n            \"and with only a little unnecessary bustle, and some few injudicious attempts at keeping her brothers in better order than she could, acquitted herself very well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154714,\n            \"she was like William, and Fanny hoped to find her like him in disposition and goodwill towards herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155240,\n            \"The Bertrams were all forgotten in detailing the faults of Rebecca, against whom Susan had also much to depose, and little Betsey a great deal more, and who did seem so thoroughly without a single recommendation, that Fanny could not help modestly presuming that her mother meant to part with her when her year was up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155578,\n            \"While considering her with these ideas, Betsey, at a small distance, was holding out something to catch her eyes, meaning to screen it at the same time from Susan\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155660,\n            \"but the child ran to her mother\\u2019s protection, and Susan could only reproach, which she did very warmly, and evidently hoping to interest Fanny on her side.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155826,\n            \"\\u201cNow, Susan,\\u201dcried Mrs. Price, in a complaining voice, \\u201cnow, how can you be so cross?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155873,\n            \"how cross Susan is to you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155900,\n            \"You know I told you not to touch it, because Susan is so cross about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155958,\n            \"she could but just speak to be heard, and she said so prettily, \\u2018 Let sister Susan have my knife, mama, when I am dead and buried.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156314,\n            \"There was nothing to raise her spirits in the confined and scantily furnished chamber that she was to share with Susan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157805,\n            \"and of Susan\\u2019s temper she had many doubts.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157816,\n            \"Her continual disagreements with her mother, her rash squabbles with Tom and Charles, and petulance with Betsey, were at least so distressing to Fanny that, though admitting they were by no means without provocation, she feared the disposition that could push them to such length must be far from amiable, and from affording any repose to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159319,\n            \"The first solid consolation which Fanny received for the evils of home, the first which her judgment could entirely approve, and which gave any promise of durability, was in a better knowledge of Susan, and a hope of being of service to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159539,\n            \"and that Susan was useful she could perceive;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159584,\n            \"In every argument with her mother, Susan had in point of reason the advantage, and never was there any maternal tenderness to buy her off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159649,\n            \"All this became gradually evident, and gradually placed Susan before her sister as an object of mingled compassion and respect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159721,\n            \"Susan, she found, looked up to her and wished for her good opinion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159737,\n            \"and new as anything like an office of authority was to Fanny, new as it was to imagine herself capable of guiding or informing any one, she did resolve to give occasional hints to Susan, and endeavour to exercise for her advantage the juster notions of what was due to everybody, and what would be wisest for herself, which her own more favoured education had fixed in her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159811,\n            \"Her influence, or at least the consciousness and use of it, originated in an act of kindness by Susan, which, after many hesitations of delicacy, she at last worked herself up to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160020,\n            \"Susan was established in the full possession of her own, Betsey handsomely declaring that now she had got one so much prettier herself, she should never want _ that _ again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160115,\n            \"Susan shewed that she had delicacy: pleased as she was to be mistress of property which she had been struggling for at least two years, she yet feared that her sister\\u2019s judgment had been against her, and that a reproof was designed her for having so struggled as to make the purchase necessary for the tranquillity of the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160342,\n            \"Her greatest wonder on the subject soon became \\u2014 not that Susan should have been provoked into disrespect and impatience against her better knowledge \\u2014 but that so much better knowledge, so many good notions should have been hers at all;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160687,\n            \"Susan had read nothing, and Fanny longed to give her a share in her own first pleasures, and inspire a taste for the biography and poetry which she delighted in herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160930,\n            \"One morning, about this time, Fanny having now been nearly four weeks from Mansfield, a point which she never failed to think over and calculate every day, as she and Susan were preparing to remove, as usual, upstairs, they were stopped by the knock of a visitor, whom they felt they could not avoid, from Rebecca\\u2019s alertness in going to the door, a duty which always interested her beyond any other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162927,\n            \"but he could have wished her sister away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162977,\n            \"He must content himself with being only generally agreeable, and letting Susan have her share of entertainment, with the indulgence, now and then, of a look or hint for the better-informed and conscious Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163065,\n            \"his journeys and his acquaintance were all of use, and Susan was entertained in a way quite new to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165378,\n            \"\\u201d After a moment\\u2019s reflection, Mr. Crawford replied, \\u201cI know Mansfield, I know its way, I know its faults towards _ you _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165410,\n            \"I know the danger of your being so far forgotten, as to have your comforts give way to the imaginary convenience of any single being in the family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165440,\n            \"I am aware that you may be left here week after week, if Sir Thomas cannot settle everything for coming himself, or sending your aunt\\u2019s maid for you, without involving the slightest alteration of the arrangements which he may have laid down for the next quarter of a year.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165515,\n            \"I am considering your sister\\u2019s health,\\u201dsaid he, addressing himself to Susan, \\u201cwhich I think the confinement of Portsmouth unfavourable to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165551,\n            \"When you know her as well as I do, I am sure you will agree that she does, and that she ought never to be long banished from the free air and liberty of the country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165590,\n            \"If, therefore\\u201d(turning again to Fanny), \\u201cyou find yourself growing unwell, and any difficulties arise about your returning to Mansfield, without waiting for the two months to be ended, _ that _ must not be regarded as of any consequence, if you feel yourself at all less strong or comfortable than usual, and will only let my sister know it, give her only the slightest hint, she and I will immediately come down, and take you back to Mansfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167357,\n            \"I ought to have sent you an account of your cousin\\u2019s first party, but I was lazy, and now it is too long ago;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167451,\n            \"I go to Lady Stornaway after Easter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167729,\n            \"My poor aunt always felt affected if within ten miles of the sea, which the Admiral of course never believed, but I know it was so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168477,\n            \"If Mr. Crawford remembered her message to her cousin, she thought it very likely, most likely, that he would write to her at all events;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168586,\n            \"Time did something, her own exertions something more, and she resumed her attentions to Susan, and again awakened the same interest in them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168716,\n            \"What Fanny told her of former times dwelt more on her mind than the pages of Goldsmith;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168734,\n            \"and she paid her sister the compliment of preferring her style to that of any printed author.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168821,\n            \"Susan, who had an innate taste for the genteel and well-appointed, was eager to hear, and Fanny could not but indulge herself in dwelling on so beloved a theme.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168863,\n            \"though, after a time, Susan\\u2019s very great admiration of everything said or done in her uncle\\u2019s house, and earnest longing to go into Northamptonshire, seemed almost to blame her for exciting feelings which could not be gratified.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168909,\n            \"Poor Susan was very little better fitted for home than her elder sister;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168923,\n            \"and as Fanny grew thoroughly to understand this, she began to feel that when her own release from Portsmouth came, her happiness would have a material drawback in leaving Susan behind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170823,\n            \"but your aunt seems to feel out of luck that such an article of Mansfield news should fall to my pen instead of hers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170907,\n            \"And my poor aunt talking of me every hour!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170917,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny checked the tendency of these thoughts as well as she could, but she was within half a minute of starting the idea that Sir Thomas was quite unkind, both to her aunt and to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172613,\n            \"Susan was her only companion and listener on this, as on more common occasions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178773,\n            \"My father wishes you to invite Susan to go with you for a few months.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178940,\n            \"To be going so soon, sent for so kindly, sent for as a comfort, and with leave to take Susan, was altogether such a combination of blessings as set her heart in a glow, and for a time seemed to distance every pain, and make her incapable of suitably sharing the distress even of those whose distress she thought of most.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179167,\n            \"her father and mother must be spoken to, Susan prepared, everything got ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179194,\n            \"The happiness she was imparting, too, happiness very little alloyed by the black communication which must briefly precede it \\u2014 the joyful consent of her father and mother to Susan\\u2019s going with her \\u2014 the general satisfaction with which the going of both seemed regarded, and the ecstasy of Susan herself, was all serving to support her spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179271,\n            \"Mrs. Price talked of her poor sister for a few minutes, but how to find anything to hold Susan\\u2019s clothes, because Rebecca took away all the boxes and spoilt them, was much more in her thoughts: and as for Susan, now unexpectedly gratified in the first wish of her heart, and knowing nothing personally of those who had sinned, or of those who were sorrowing \\u2014 if she could help rejoicing from beginning to end, it was as much as ought to be expected from human virtue at fourteen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179891,\n            \"How her heart swelled with joy and gratitude as she passed the barriers of Portsmouth, and how Susan\\u2019s face wore its broadest smiles, may be easily conceived.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180057,\n            \"Just before their setting out from Oxford, while Susan was stationed at a window, in eager observation of the departure of a large family from the inn, the other two were standing by the fire;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180929,\n            \"She had not spirits to notice her in more than a few repulsive looks, but she felt her as a spy, and an intruder, and an indigent niece, and everything most odious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181085,\n            \"She was now left a good deal to herself, to get acquainted with the house and grounds as she could, and spent her days very happily in so doing, while those who might otherwise have attended to her were shut up, or wholly occupied each with the person quite dependent on them, at this time, for everything like comfort;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190744,\n            \"But it was possible to part with her, because Susan remained to supply her place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190761,\n            \"Susan became the stationary niece, delighted to be so;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190811,\n            \"First as a comfort to Fanny, then as an auxiliary, and last as her substitute, she was established at Mansfield, with every appearance of equal permanency.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190889,\n            \"and after Fanny\\u2019s removal succeeded so naturally to her influence over the hourly comfort of her aunt, as gradually to become, perhaps, the most beloved of the two.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190923,\n            \"In _ her _ usefulness, in Fanny\\u2019s excellence, in William\\u2019s continued good conduct and rising fame, and in the general well-doing and success of the other members of the family, all assisting to advance each other, and doing credit to his countenance and aid, Sir Thomas saw repeated, and for ever repeated, reason to rejoice in what he had done for them all, and acknowledge the advantages of early hardship and discipline, and the consciousness of being born to struggle and endure.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 4]\": [\n        [\n            72668,\n            \"His father\\u2019s looks of solemnity and amazement on this his first appearance on any stage, and the gradual metamorphosis of the impassioned Baron Wildenheim into the well-bred and easy Mr. Yates, making his bow and apology to Sir Thomas Bertram, was such an exhibition, such a piece of true acting, as he would not have lost upon any account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89657,\n            \"I think my friend Julia knows better than to entertain her father with Mr. Yates.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 5]\": [\n        [\n            48497,\n            \"\\u201d CHAPTER XIII The Honourable John Yates, this new friend, had not much to recommend him beyond habits of fashion and expense, and being the younger son of a lord with a tolerable independence;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53253,\n            \"Here are two capital tragic parts for Yates and Crawford, and here is the rhyming Butler for me, if nobody else wants it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57707,\n            \"and the spirits of evening giving fresh courage, Tom, Maria, and Mr. Yates, soon after their being reassembled in the drawing-room, seated themselves in committee at a separate table, with the play open before them, and were just getting deep in the subject when a most welcome interruption was given by the entrance of Mr. and Miss Crawford, who, late and dark and dirty as it was, could not help coming, and were received with the most grateful joy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72668,\n            \"His father\\u2019s looks of solemnity and amazement on this his first appearance on any stage, and the gradual metamorphosis of the impassioned Baron Wildenheim into the well-bred and easy Mr. Yates, making his bow and apology to Sir Thomas Bertram, was such an exhibition, such a piece of true acting, as he would not have lost upon any account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76186,\n            \"He and his friend had been out with their guns the chief of the morning, and Tom had taken the opportunity of explaining, with proper apologies for his father\\u2019s particularity, what was to be expected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76259,\n            \"and his indignation was such, that had it not been for delicacy towards his friend, and his friend\\u2019s youngest sister, he believed he should certainly attack the baronet on the absurdity of his proceedings, and argue him into a little more rationality.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 6]\": [\n        [\n            53253,\n            \"Here are two capital tragic parts for Yates and Crawford, and here is the rhyming Butler for me, if nobody else wants it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55328,\n            \"When this had lasted some time, the division of the party was completed by Tom Bertram and Mr. Yates walking off together to consult farther in the room now beginning to be called _ the _ _ Theatre _, and Miss Bertram\\u2019s resolving to go down to the Parsonage herself with the offer of Amelia to Miss Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57707,\n            \"and the spirits of evening giving fresh courage, Tom, Maria, and Mr. Yates, soon after their being reassembled in the drawing-room, seated themselves in committee at a separate table, with the play open before them, and were just getting deep in the subject when a most welcome interruption was given by the entrance of Mr. and Miss Crawford, who, late and dark and dirty as it was, could not help coming, and were received with the most grateful joy.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 9]\": [\n        [\n            48551,\n            \"Mr. Bertram\\u2019s acquaintance with him had begun at Weymouth, where they had spent ten days together in the same society, and the friendship, if friendship it might be called, had been proved and perfected by Mr. Yates\\u2019 s being invited to take Mansfield in his way, whenever he could, and by his promising to come;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53674,\n            \"Amelia and Agatha may do for Maria and me, but here is nothing for your sister, Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53696,\n            \"\\u201d Mr. Crawford desired _ that _ might not be thought of: he was very sure his sister had no wish of acting but as she might be useful, and that she would not allow herself to be considered in the present case.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70037,\n            \"Fanny was left with only the Crawfords and Mr. Yates.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 12]\": [\n        [\n            50190,\n            \"Maria, Julia, Henry Crawford, and Mr. Yates were in the billiard-room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53674,\n            \"Amelia and Agatha may do for Maria and me, but here is nothing for your sister, Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55222,\n            \"but her brother soon returned to business and Lovers\\u2019 Vows, and was eagerly looking over the play, with Mr. Yates\\u2019 s help, to ascertain what scenery would be necessary \\u2014 while Maria and Henry Crawford conversed together in an under-voice, and the declaration with which she began of, \\u201cI am sure I would give up the part to Julia most willingly, but that though I shall probably do it very ill, I feel persuaded _ she _ would do it worse,\\u201dwas doubtless receiving all the compliments it called for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57707,\n            \"and the spirits of evening giving fresh courage, Tom, Maria, and Mr. Yates, soon after their being reassembled in the drawing-room, seated themselves in committee at a separate table, with the play open before them, and were just getting deep in the subject when a most welcome interruption was given by the entrance of Mr. and Miss Crawford, who, late and dark and dirty as it was, could not help coming, and were received with the most grateful joy.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 13]\": [\n        [\n            71439,\n            \"Not that _ she _ was incommoded by many fears of Sir Thomas\\u2019 s disapprobation when the present state of his house should be known, for her judgment had been so blinded that, except by the instinctive caution with which she had whisked away Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s pink satin cloak as her brother-in-law entered, she could hardly be said to shew any sign of alarm;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 14]\": [\n        [\n            55328,\n            \"When this had lasted some time, the division of the party was completed by Tom Bertram and Mr. Yates walking off together to consult farther in the room now beginning to be called _ the _ _ Theatre _, and Miss Bertram\\u2019s resolving to go down to the Parsonage herself with the offer of Amelia to Miss Crawford;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 17]\": [\n        [\n            70305,\n            \"while Mr. Yates considered it only as a temporary interruption, a disaster for the evening, and could even suggest the possibility of the rehearsal being renewed after tea, when the bustle of receiving Sir Thomas were over, and he might be at leisure to be amused by it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70433,\n            \"and therefore, thanking them, said, \\u201che preferred remaining where he was, that he might pay his respects to the old gentleman handsomely since he _ was _ come;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72399,\n            \"\\u201cThen poor Yates is all alone,\\u201dcried Tom.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72431,\n            \"\\u201d To the theatre he went, and reached it just in time to witness the first meeting of his father and his friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72616,\n            \"At the very moment of Yates perceiving Sir Thomas, and giving perhaps the very best start he had ever given in the whole course of his rehearsals, Tom Bertram entered at the other end of the room;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76326,\n            \"but there was a something in Sir Thomas, when they sat round the same table, which made Mr. Yates think it wiser to let him pursue his own way, and feel the folly of it without opposition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76368,\n            \"He had known many disagreeable fathers before, and often been struck with the inconveniences they occasioned, but never, in the whole course of his life, had he seen one of that class so unintelligibly moral, so infamously tyrannical as Sir Thomas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77620,\n            \"In _ his _ departure Sir Thomas felt the chief interest: wanting to be alone with his family, the presence of a stranger superior to Mr. Yates must have been irksome;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77694,\n            \"Sir Thomas had been quite indifferent to Mr. Crawford\\u2019s going or staying: but his good wishes for Mr. Yates\\u2019 s having a pleasant journey, as he walked with him to the hall-door, were given with genuine satisfaction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77780,\n            \"and Sir Thomas hoped, in seeing him out of it, to be rid of the worst object connected with the scheme, and the last that must be inevitably reminding him of its existence.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 18]\": [\n        [\n            50190,\n            \"Maria, Julia, Henry Crawford, and Mr. Yates were in the billiard-room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53674,\n            \"Amelia and Agatha may do for Maria and me, but here is nothing for your sister, Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55222,\n            \"but her brother soon returned to business and Lovers\\u2019 Vows, and was eagerly looking over the play, with Mr. Yates\\u2019 s help, to ascertain what scenery would be necessary \\u2014 while Maria and Henry Crawford conversed together in an under-voice, and the declaration with which she began of, \\u201cI am sure I would give up the part to Julia most willingly, but that though I shall probably do it very ill, I feel persuaded _ she _ would do it worse,\\u201dwas doubtless receiving all the compliments it called for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57618,\n            \"Mr. Yates, who was trying to make himself agreeable to Julia, found her gloom less impenetrable on any topic than that of his regret at her secession from their company;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89657,\n            \"I think my friend Julia knows better than to entertain her father with Mr. Yates.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188373,\n            \"She had been allowing his attentions some time, but with very little idea of ever accepting him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188392,\n            \"and had not her sister\\u2019s conduct burst forth as it did, and her increased dread of her father and of home, on that event, imagining its certain consequence to herself would be greater severity and restraint, made her hastily resolve on avoiding such immediate horrors at all risks, it is probable that Mr. Yates would never have succeeded.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 9]\": [\n        [\n            81513,\n            \"In that house, which she had hardly entered twice a year since Mr. Norris\\u2019 s death, she became a welcome, an invited guest, and in the gloom and dirt of a November day, most acceptable to Mary Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81954,\n            \"The two sisters were so kind to her, and so pleasant, that Fanny might have enjoyed her visit could she have believed herself not in the way, and could she have foreseen that the weather would certainly clear at the end of the hour, and save her from the shame of having Dr. Grant\\u2019s carriage and horses out to take her home, with which she was threatened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89757,\n            \"\\u201d And then changing his tone again to one of gentle gallantry, and addressing Fanny, he said, \\u201cYou were Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s best friend.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 10]\": [\n        [\n            64811,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou had better tell Miss Bertram to think of Mr. Rushworth.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 12]\": [\n        [\n            79583,\n            \"I am sorry for them all, and would give something that Rushworth and Maria had never met.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79734,\n            \"Her behaviour to Mr. Rushworth was careless and cold.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79745,\n            \"She could not, did not like him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79789,\n            \"Mr. Rushworth had, perhaps, been accepted on too short an acquaintance, and, on knowing him better, she was repenting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79963,\n            \"She had the highest esteem for Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s character and disposition, and could not have a doubt of her happiness with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80057,\n            \"and if Maria could now speak so securely of her happiness with him, speaking certainly without the prejudice, the blindness of love, she ought to be believed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80117,\n            \"and if she could dispense with seeing her husband a leading, shining character, there would certainly be everything else in her favour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80335,\n            \"and retired in proud resolve, determined only to behave more cautiously to Mr. Rushworth in future, that her father might not be again suspecting her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80624,\n            \"To such feelings delay, even the delay of much preparation, would have been an evil, and Mr. Rushworth could hardly be more impatient for the marriage than herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170540,\n            \"I saw him draw back surprised, and I was sorry that Mrs. Rushworth should resent any former supposed slight to Miss Bertram.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 17]\": [\n        [\n            79616,\n            \"Not all his good-will for Mr. Rushworth, not all Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s deference for him, could prevent him from soon discerning some part of the truth \\u2014 that Mr. Rushworth was an inferior young man, as ignorant in business as in books, with opinions in general unfixed, and without seeming much aware of it himself.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 18]\": [\n        [\n            64811,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou had better tell Miss Bertram to think of Mr. Rushworth.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 5]\": [\n        [\n            72668,\n            \"His father\\u2019s looks of solemnity and amazement on this his first appearance on any stage, and the gradual metamorphosis of the impassioned Baron Wildenheim into the well-bred and easy Mr. Yates, making his bow and apology to Sir Thomas Bertram, was such an exhibition, such a piece of true acting, as he would not have lost upon any account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172948,\n            \"Lady Bertram could think nothing less, and Fanny shared her aunt\\u2019s security, till she received a few lines from Edmund, written purposely to give her a clearer idea of his brother\\u2019s situation, and acquaint her with the apprehensions which he and his father had imbibed from the physician with respect to some strong hectic symptoms, which seemed to seize the frame on the departure of the fever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182189,\n            \"Tom\\u2019s complaints had been greatly heightened by the shock of his sister\\u2019s conduct, and his recovery so much thrown back by it, that even Lady Bertram had been struck by the difference, and all her alarms were regularly sent off to her husband;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 6]\": [\n        [\n            96053,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBertram,\\u201dsaid Crawford, some time afterwards, taking the opportunity of a little languor in the game, \\u201cI have never told you what happened to me yesterday in my ride home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97767,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMr. Bertram,\\u201dsaid Miss Crawford, a few minutes afterwards, \\u201cyou know Henry to be such a capital improver, that you cannot possibly engage in anything of the sort at Thornton Lacey without accepting his help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185099,\n            \"all this together most grievously convinced me that I had never understood her before, and that, as far as related to mind, it had been the creature of my own imagination, not Miss Crawford, that I had been too apt to dwell on for many months past.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 8]\": [\n        [\n            89284,\n            \"She could not compliment the newly arrived gentleman, however, with any appearance of interest, in a scheme for extending his stay at Mansfield, and sending for his hunters from Norfolk, which, suggested by Dr. Grant, advised by Edmund, and warmly urged by the two sisters, was soon in possession of his mind, and which he seemed to want to be encouraged even by her to resolve on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89475,\n            \"She heard them spoken of by him only in a general way, till they were all re-assembled in the drawing-room, when Edmund, being engaged apart in some matter of business with Dr. Grant, which seemed entirely to engross them, and Mrs. Grant occupied at the tea-table, he began talking of them with more particularity to his other sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172948,\n            \"Lady Bertram could think nothing less, and Fanny shared her aunt\\u2019s security, till she received a few lines from Edmund, written purposely to give her a clearer idea of his brother\\u2019s situation, and acquaint her with the apprehensions which he and his father had imbibed from the physician with respect to some strong hectic symptoms, which seemed to seize the frame on the departure of the fever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184791,\n            \"\\u2019\\u201dAfter repeating this, Edmund was so much affected that Fanny, watching him with silent, but most tender concern, was almost sorry that the subject had been entered on at all.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 9]\": [\n        [\n            14331,\n            \"Being now in her twenty-first year, Maria Bertram was beginning to think matrimony a duty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42322,\n            \"I am sure you ought to be very much obliged to your aunt Bertram and me for contriving to let you go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89284,\n            \"She could not compliment the newly arrived gentleman, however, with any appearance of interest, in a scheme for extending his stay at Mansfield, and sending for his hunters from Norfolk, which, suggested by Dr. Grant, advised by Edmund, and warmly urged by the two sisters, was soon in possession of his mind, and which he seemed to want to be encouraged even by her to resolve on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89389,\n            \"She could not wish him to stay, and would much rather not have him speak to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89408,\n            \"Her two absent cousins, especially Maria, were much in her thoughts on seeing him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89475,\n            \"She heard them spoken of by him only in a general way, till they were all re-assembled in the drawing-room, when Edmund, being engaged apart in some matter of business with Dr. Grant, which seemed entirely to engross them, and Mrs. Grant occupied at the tea-table, he began talking of them with more particularity to his other sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90182,\n            \"and Fanny, averting her face, said, with a firmer tone than usual, \\u201cAs far as _ I _ am concerned, sir, I would not have delayed his return for a day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90244,\n            \"\\u201d She had never spoken so much at once to him in her life before, and never so angrily to any one;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97952,\n            \"\\u201d As soon as a general buzz gave him shelter, he added, in a low voice, directed solely at Fanny, \\u201cI should be sorry to have my powers of _ planning _ judged of by the day at Sotherton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163812,\n            \"though when the moment was passed, could regret that she had not forced herself into the acknowledged comprehension of one half of his meaning, and encouraged him to say something more of his sister and Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172948,\n            \"Lady Bertram could think nothing less, and Fanny shared her aunt\\u2019s security, till she received a few lines from Edmund, written purposely to give her a clearer idea of his brother\\u2019s situation, and acquaint her with the apprehensions which he and his father had imbibed from the physician with respect to some strong hectic symptoms, which seemed to seize the frame on the departure of the fever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181205,\n            \"To talk over the dreadful business with Fanny, talk and lament, was all Lady Bertram\\u2019s consolation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184791,\n            \"\\u2019\\u201dAfter repeating this, Edmund was so much affected that Fanny, watching him with silent, but most tender concern, was almost sorry that the subject had been entered on at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184837,\n            \"At last, \\u201cNow, Fanny,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cI shall soon have done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184856,\n            \"I have told you the substance of all that she said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185495,\n            \"I had gone a few steps, Fanny, when I heard the door open behind me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185650,\n            \"I thank you for your patience, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185673,\n            \"\\u201d And such was Fanny\\u2019s dependence on his words, that for five minutes she thought they _ had _ done.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 12]\": [\n        [\n            89408,\n            \"Her two absent cousins, especially Maria, were much in her thoughts on seeing him;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 13]\": [\n        [\n            42322,\n            \"I am sure you ought to be very much obliged to your aunt Bertram and me for contriving to let you go.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 14]\": [\n        [\n            172251,\n            \"The sufferings which Lady Bertram did not see had little power over her fancy;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 15]\": [\n        [\n            172660,\n            \"not even Mrs. Price, beyond a brief question or two, if she saw her daughter with a letter in her hand, and now and then the quiet observation of, \\u201cMy poor sister Bertram must be in a great deal of trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172744,\n            \"Mrs. Price did quite as much for Lady Bertram as Lady Bertram would have done for Mrs. Price.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 17]\": [\n        [\n            75284,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI know how great, how justly great, your influence is with Lady Bertram and her children, and am the more concerned that it should not have been \\u2014\\u201d\\u201cMy dear Sir Thomas, if you had seen the state of the roads _ that _ day!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182189,\n            \"Tom\\u2019s complaints had been greatly heightened by the shock of his sister\\u2019s conduct, and his recovery so much thrown back by it, that even Lady Bertram had been struck by the difference, and all her alarms were regularly sent off to her husband;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 18]\": [\n        [\n            40378,\n            \"Why, child, I have but this moment escaped from his horrible mother.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 6]\": [\n        [\n            17927,\n            \"She acknowledged, however, that the Mr. Bertrams were very fine young men, that two such young men were not often seen together even in London, and that their manners, particularly those of the eldest, were very good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18117,\n            \"Miss Crawford soon felt that he and his situation might do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53253,\n            \"Here are two capital tragic parts for Yates and Crawford, and here is the rhyming Butler for me, if nobody else wants it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57707,\n            \"and the spirits of evening giving fresh courage, Tom, Maria, and Mr. Yates, soon after their being reassembled in the drawing-room, seated themselves in committee at a separate table, with the play open before them, and were just getting deep in the subject when a most welcome interruption was given by the entrance of Mr. and Miss Crawford, who, late and dark and dirty as it was, could not help coming, and were received with the most grateful joy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59945,\n            \"The consultation upon the play still went on, and Miss Crawford\\u2019s attention was first called from Fanny by Tom Bertram\\u2019s telling her, with infinite regret, that he found it absolutely impossible for him to undertake the part of Anhalt in addition to the Butler: he had been most anxiously trying to make it out to be feasible, but it would not do;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 8]\": [\n        [\n            8249,\n            \"\\u201cI blush for you, Tom,\\u201dsaid he, in his most dignified manner;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8267,\n            \"\\u201cI blush for the expedient which I am driven on, and I trust I may pity your feelings as a brother on the occasion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8294,\n            \"You have robbed Edmund for ten, twenty, thirty years, perhaps for life, of more than half the income which ought to be his.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8322,\n            \"It may hereafter be in my power, or in yours (I hope it will), to procure him better preferment;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17972,\n            \"_ He _ had been much in London, and had more liveliness and gallantry than Edmund, and must, therefore, be preferred;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47271,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI dare say he did, ma\\u2019am.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50087,\n            \"and though nothing was settled but that Tom Bertram would prefer a comedy, and his sisters and Henry Crawford a tragedy, and that nothing in the world could be easier than to find a piece which would please them all, the resolution to act something or other seemed so decided as to make Edmund quite uncomfortable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50208,\n            \"Tom, returning from them into the drawing-room, where Edmund was standing thoughtfully by the fire, while Lady Bertram was on the sofa at a little distance, and Fanny close beside her arranging her work, thus began as he entered \\u2014 \\u201cSuch a horribly vile billiard-table as ours is not to be met with, I believe, above ground.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50421,\n            \"\\u201d said Edmund, in a low voice, as his brother approached the fire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50441,\n            \"never more so, I assure you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50946,\n            \"Well, Edmund,\\u201dhe continued, returning to the former subject, posture, and voice, as soon as Lady Bertram began to nod again, \\u201cbut _ this _ I _ will _ maintain, that we shall be doing no harm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51209,\n            \"\\u201cI know my father as well as you do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51235,\n            \"Manage your own concerns, Edmund, and I\\u2019ll take care of the rest of the family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51644,\n            \"\\u201d Tom walked out of the room as he said it, and Edmund was left to sit down and stir the fire in thoughtful vexation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55835,\n            \"but when he entered the drawing-room before dinner, the buzz of discussion was high between Tom, Maria, and Mr. Yates;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60157,\n            \"\\u201d While he spoke, Maria was looking apprehensively round at Edmund in full expectation that he must oppose such an enlargement of the plan as this: so contrary to all their first protestations;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60642,\n            \"and if she were applied to again among themselves with all the authoritative urgency that Tom and Maria were capable of, and Edmund perhaps away, what should she do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62049,\n            \"I know no harm of Charles Maddox;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62167,\n            \"I am well aware that nothing else will quiet Tom.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62789,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf you are against me, I ought to distrust myself, and yet \\u2014 But it is absolutely impossible to let Tom go on in this way, riding about the country in quest of anybody who can be persuaded to act \\u2014 no matter whom: the look of a gentleman is to be enough.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63058,\n            \"If Tom is up, I shall go to him directly and get it over, and when we meet at breakfast we shall be all in high good-humour at the prospect of acting the fool together with such unanimity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171938,\n            \"and Edmund kindly proposes attending his brother immediately, but I am happy to add that Sir Thomas will not leave me on this distressing occasion, as it would be too trying for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171974,\n            \"We shall greatly miss Edmund in our small circle, but I trust and hope he will find the poor invalid in a less alarming state than might be apprehended, and that he will be able to bring him to Mansfield shortly, which Sir Thomas proposes should be done, and thinks best on every account, and I flatter myself the poor sufferer will soon be able to bear the removal without material inconvenience or injury.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172112,\n            \"Tom dangerously ill, Edmund gone to attend him, and the sadly small party remaining at Mansfield, were cares to shut out every other care, or almost every other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172948,\n            \"Lady Bertram could think nothing less, and Fanny shared her aunt\\u2019s security, till she received a few lines from Edmund, written purposely to give her a clearer idea of his brother\\u2019s situation, and acquaint her with the apprehensions which he and his father had imbibed from the physician with respect to some strong hectic symptoms, which seemed to seize the frame on the departure of the fever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173070,\n            \"A very few lines from Edmund shewed her the patient and the sickroom in a juster and stronger light than all Lady Bertram\\u2019s sheets of paper could do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173149,\n            \"but when able to talk or be talked to, or read to, Edmund was the companion he preferred.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173371,\n            \"\\u201cOn the subject of my last, I had actually begun a letter when called away by Tom\\u2019s illness, but I have now changed my mind, and fear to trust the influence of friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173411,\n            \"When Tom is better, I shall go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178350,\n            \"Julia\\u2019s, Tom\\u2019s, Edmund\\u2019s;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 9]\": [\n        [\n            48255,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny was led off very willingly, though it was impossible for her to feel much gratitude towards her cousin, or distinguish, as he certainly did, between the selfishness of another person and his own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50208,\n            \"Tom, returning from them into the drawing-room, where Edmund was standing thoughtfully by the fire, while Lady Bertram was on the sofa at a little distance, and Fanny close beside her arranging her work, thus began as he entered \\u2014 \\u201cSuch a horribly vile billiard-table as ours is not to be met with, I believe, above ground.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50886,\n            \"\\u201cTo be sure, my dear mother, your anxiety \\u2014 I was unlucky there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51363,\n            \"and as to such alterations as I was suggesting just now, such as moving a bookcase, or unlocking a door, or even as using the billiard-room for the space of a week without playing at billiards in it, you might just as well suppose he would object to our sitting more in this room, and less in the breakfast-room, than we did before he went away, or to my sister\\u2019s pianoforte being moved from one side of the room to the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51789,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI dare say she would, but she has no influence with either Tom or my sisters that could be of any use;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59338,\n            \"and it was not merely Tom, for the requisition was now backed by Maria, and Mr. Crawford, and Mr. Yates, with an urgency which differed from his but in being more gentle or more ceremonious, and which altogether was quite overpowering to Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59945,\n            \"The consultation upon the play still went on, and Miss Crawford\\u2019s attention was first called from Fanny by Tom Bertram\\u2019s telling her, with infinite regret, that he found it absolutely impossible for him to undertake the part of Anhalt in addition to the Butler: he had been most anxiously trying to make it out to be feasible, but it would not do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63760,\n            \"\\u201cPerhaps,\\u201dsaid Tom, \\u201cFanny may be more disposed to oblige us now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157455,\n            \"Fanny was very anxious to be useful, and not to appear above her home, or in any way disqualified or disinclined, by her foreign education, from contributing her help to its comforts, and therefore set about working for Sam immediately;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157816,\n            \"Her continual disagreements with her mother, her rash squabbles with Tom and Charles, and petulance with Betsey, were at least so distressing to Fanny that, though admitting they were by no means without provocation, she feared the disposition that could push them to such length must be far from amiable, and from affording any repose to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172948,\n            \"Lady Bertram could think nothing less, and Fanny shared her aunt\\u2019s security, till she received a few lines from Edmund, written purposely to give her a clearer idea of his brother\\u2019s situation, and acquaint her with the apprehensions which he and his father had imbibed from the physician with respect to some strong hectic symptoms, which seemed to seize the frame on the departure of the fever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173070,\n            \"A very few lines from Edmund shewed her the patient and the sickroom in a juster and stronger light than all Lady Bertram\\u2019s sheets of paper could do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173551,\n            \"She supposed he could not yet leave his son, but it was a cruel, a terrible delay to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180269,\n            \"Fanny began to dread the meeting with her aunts and Tom, under so dreadful a humiliation;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 11]\": [\n        [\n            8132,\n            \"But Tom\\u2019s extravagance had, previous to that event, been so great as to render a different disposal of the next presentation necessary, and the younger brother must help to pay for the pleasures of the elder.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 12]\": [\n        [\n            55835,\n            \"but when he entered the drawing-room before dinner, the buzz of discussion was high between Tom, Maria, and Mr. Yates;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57707,\n            \"and the spirits of evening giving fresh courage, Tom, Maria, and Mr. Yates, soon after their being reassembled in the drawing-room, seated themselves in committee at a separate table, with the play open before them, and were just getting deep in the subject when a most welcome interruption was given by the entrance of Mr. and Miss Crawford, who, late and dark and dirty as it was, could not help coming, and were received with the most grateful joy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59338,\n            \"and it was not merely Tom, for the requisition was now backed by Maria, and Mr. Crawford, and Mr. Yates, with an urgency which differed from his but in being more gentle or more ceremonious, and which altogether was quite overpowering to Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60157,\n            \"\\u201d While he spoke, Maria was looking apprehensively round at Edmund in full expectation that he must oppose such an enlargement of the plan as this: so contrary to all their first protestations;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60642,\n            \"and if she were applied to again among themselves with all the authoritative urgency that Tom and Maria were capable of, and Edmund perhaps away, what should she do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76983,\n            \"\\u201d It was well at that moment that Tom had to speak, and not his sister.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 13]\": [\n        [\n            14073,\n            \"Sir Thomas\\u2019 s sending away his son seemed to her so like a parent\\u2019s care, under the influence of a foreboding of evil to himself, that she could not help feeling dreadful presentiments;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19974,\n            \"and on their all dining together at the Park soon after his going, she retook her chosen place near the bottom of the table, fully expecting to feel a most melancholy difference in the change of masters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20852,\n            \"He could hardly ever get out, poor man, to enjoy anything, and _ that _ disheartened me from doing several things that Sir Thomas and I used to talk of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60481,\n            \"When the evening was over, she went to bed full of it, her nerves still agitated by the shock of such an attack from her cousin Tom, so public and so persevered in, and her spirits sinking under her aunt\\u2019s unkind reflection and reproach.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180780,\n            \"and neither Lady Bertram nor Tom had received from her the smallest support or attempt at support.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 14]\": [\n        [\n            50208,\n            \"Tom, returning from them into the drawing-room, where Edmund was standing thoughtfully by the fire, while Lady Bertram was on the sofa at a little distance, and Fanny close beside her arranging her work, thus began as he entered \\u2014 \\u201cSuch a horribly vile billiard-table as ours is not to be met with, I believe, above ground.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50946,\n            \"Well, Edmund,\\u201dhe continued, returning to the former subject, posture, and voice, as soon as Lady Bertram began to nod again, \\u201cbut _ this _ I _ will _ maintain, that we shall be doing no harm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57130,\n            \"I only wish Tom had known his own mind when the carpenters began, for there was the loss of half a day\\u2019s work about those side-doors.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172266,\n            \"and she wrote very comfortably about agitation, and anxiety, and poor invalids, till Tom was actually conveyed to Mansfield, and her own eyes had beheld his altered appearance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172870,\n            \"for being now used to the sight of him in his suffering, helpless state, and hearing only the best, and never thinking beyond what she heard, with no disposition for alarm and no aptitude at a hint, Lady Bertram was the happiest subject in the world for a little medical imposition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173070,\n            \"A very few lines from Edmund shewed her the patient and the sickroom in a juster and stronger light than all Lady Bertram\\u2019s sheets of paper could do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180780,\n            \"and neither Lady Bertram nor Tom had received from her the smallest support or attempt at support.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 17]\": [\n        [\n            14016,\n            \"and the very great uncertainty in which everything was then involved determined him on sending home his son, and waiting the final arrangement by himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14043,\n            \"Tom arrived safely, bringing an excellent account of his father\\u2019s health;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14073,\n            \"Sir Thomas\\u2019 s sending away his son seemed to her so like a parent\\u2019s care, under the influence of a foreboding of evil to himself, that she could not help feeling dreadful presentiments;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76793,\n            \"Her sensations were indefinable, and so were they a few minutes afterwards upon hearing Henry Crawford, who had a chair between herself and Tom, ask the latter in an undervoice whether there were any plans for resuming the play after the present happy interruption (with a courteous glance at Sir Thomas), because, in that case, he should make a point of returning to Mansfield at any time required by the party: he was going away immediately, being to meet his uncle at Bath without delay;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171938,\n            \"and Edmund kindly proposes attending his brother immediately, but I am happy to add that Sir Thomas will not leave me on this distressing occasion, as it would be too trying for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171974,\n            \"We shall greatly miss Edmund in our small circle, but I trust and hope he will find the poor invalid in a less alarming state than might be apprehended, and that he will be able to bring him to Mansfield shortly, which Sir Thomas proposes should be done, and thinks best on every account, and I flatter myself the poor sufferer will soon be able to bear the removal without material inconvenience or injury.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172380,\n            \"I am quite grieved for him, and very much frightened, and so is Sir Thomas;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172412,\n            \"But Sir Thomas hopes he will be better to-morrow, and says we must consider his journey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182189,\n            \"Tom\\u2019s complaints had been greatly heightened by the shock of his sister\\u2019s conduct, and his recovery so much thrown back by it, that even Lady Bertram had been struck by the difference, and all her alarms were regularly sent off to her husband;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 18]\": [\n        [\n            178350,\n            \"Julia\\u2019s, Tom\\u2019s, Edmund\\u2019s;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 19]\": [\n        [\n            157816,\n            \"Her continual disagreements with her mother, her rash squabbles with Tom and Charles, and petulance with Betsey, were at least so distressing to Fanny that, though admitting they were by no means without provocation, she feared the disposition that could push them to such length must be far from amiable, and from affording any repose to herself.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 8]\": [\n        [\n            24599,\n            \"I dare say Mr. Crawford would take my two nieces and me in his barouche, and Edmund can go on horseback, you know, sister, and Fanny will stay at home with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25684,\n            \"and to the credit of the lady it may be added that, without his being a man of the world or an elder brother, without any of the arts of flattery or the gaieties of small talk, he began to be agreeable to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25963,\n            \"She was a little surprised that he could spend so many hours with Miss Crawford, and not see more of the sort of fault which he had already observed, and of which _ she _ was almost always reminded by a something of the same nature whenever she was in her company;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26511,\n            \"and in Dr. Grant\\u2019s meadow she immediately saw the group \\u2014 Edmund and Miss Crawford both on horse-back, riding side by side, Dr. and Mrs. Grant, and Mr. Crawford, with two or three grooms, standing about and looking on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26781,\n            \"She could not but think, indeed, that Mr. Crawford might as well have saved him the trouble;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26820,\n            \"but Mr. Crawford, with all his boasted good-nature, and all his coachmanship, probably knew nothing of the matter, and had no active kindness in comparison of Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28113,\n            \"Between ten and eleven Edmund and Julia walked into the drawing-room, fresh with the evening air, glowing and cheerful, the very reverse of what they found in the three ladies sitting there, for Maria would scarcely raise her eyes from her book, and Lady Bertram was half-asleep;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29687,\n            \"He was ashamed to think that for four days together she had not had the power of riding, and very seriously resolved, however unwilling he must be to check a pleasure of Miss Crawford\\u2019s, that it should never happen again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29953,\n            \"Mrs. Norris and her nieces were all well pleased with its revival, and an early day was named and agreed to, provided Mr. Crawford should be disengaged: the young ladies did not forget that stipulation, and though Mrs. Norris would willingly have answered for his being so, they would neither authorise the liberty nor run the risk;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30677,\n            \"On his return to the breakfast-room, he found Mrs. Norris trying to make up her mind as to whether Miss Crawford\\u2019s being of the party were desirable or not, or whether her brother\\u2019s barouche would not be full without her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30761,\n            \"\\u201cBut why is it necessary,\\u201dsaid Edmund, \\u201cthat Crawford\\u2019s carriage, or his _ only _, should be employed?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32348,\n            \"That was the only point of resemblance between her and the lady who sat by her: in everything but a value for Edmund, Miss Crawford was very unlike her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34313,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cEvery generation has its improvements,\\u201dsaid Miss Crawford, with a smile, to Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34347,\n            \"and Edmund, Fanny, and Miss Crawford remained in a cluster together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35322,\n            \"\\u201d cried Julia, and running to where he stood with Miss Crawford and Fanny: \\u201cMy dear Edmund, if you were but in orders now, you might perform the ceremony directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36050,\n            \"and when, after a little time, the others began to form into parties, these three were found in busy consultation on the terrace by Edmund, Miss Crawford, and Fanny, who seemed as naturally to unite, and who, after a short participation of their regrets and difficulties, left them and walked on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36515,\n            \"At length, after a short pause, Miss Crawford began with, \\u201cSo you are to be a clergyman, Mr. Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38173,\n            \"\\u201cI am afraid you are very tired, Fanny,\\u201dsaid Edmund, observing her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38565,\n            \"\\u201d He still reasoned with her, but in vain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40182,\n            \"She could almost have thought that Edmund and Miss Crawford had left it, but that it was impossible for Edmund to forget her so entirely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40608,\n            \"\\u201d And she immediately scrambled across the fence, and walked away, not attending to Fanny\\u2019s last question of whether she had seen anything of Miss Crawford and Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43251,\n            \"but after tea, as Miss Crawford was standing at an open window with Edmund and Fanny looking out on a twilight scene, while the Miss Bertrams, Mr. Rushworth, and Henry Crawford were all busy with candles at the pianoforte, she suddenly revived it by turning round towards the group, and saying, \\u201cHow happy Mr. Rushworth looks!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59751,\n            \"By a look at her brother she prevented any farther entreaty from the theatrical board, and the really good feelings by which she was almost purely governed were rapidly restoring her to all the little she had lost in Edmund\\u2019s favour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60272,\n            \"Let _ him _ be applied to, if you please, for it will be less unpleasant to me than to have a perfect stranger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62421,\n            \"I heard enough of what she said to you last night to understand her unwillingness to be acting with a stranger;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62849,\n            \"I thought _ you _ would have entered more into Miss Crawford\\u2019s feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62910,\n            \"It gave her a very strong claim on my goodwill.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63855,\n            \"Miss Crawford looked very lovely in hers, and entered with such an instantaneous renewal of cheerfulness into the whole affair as could have but one effect on him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63976,\n            \"and even this, when imparted by Edmund, brought a pang with it, for it was Miss Crawford to whom she was obliged \\u2014 it was Miss Crawford whose kind exertions were to excite her gratitude, and whose merit in making them was spoken of with a glow of admiration.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67230,\n            \"Fanny did not share her aunt\\u2019s composure: she thought of the morrow a great deal, for if the three acts were rehearsed, Edmund and Miss Crawford would then be acting together for the first time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68236,\n            \"\\u201d She began, and Fanny joined in with all the modest feeling which the idea of representing Edmund was so strongly calculated to inspire;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68344,\n            \"and as Edmund was come on the very same business that had brought Miss Crawford, consciousness and pleasure were likely to be more than momentary in _ them _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68375,\n            \"He too had his book, and was seeking Fanny, to ask her to rehearse with him, and help him to prepare for the evening, without knowing Miss Crawford to be in the house;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68490,\n            \"Edmund proposed, urged, entreated it, till the lady, not very unwilling at first, could refuse no longer, and Fanny was wanted only to prompt and observe them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84133,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI grant you the name is good in itself, and _ Lord _ Edmund or _ Sir _ Edmund sound delightfully;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88899,\n            \"\\u201d And letting down the side-glass to distinguish, \\u201c\\u2019Tis Crawford\\u2019s, Crawford\\u2019s barouche, I protest!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88954,\n            \"I shall be very glad to see him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89072,\n            \"A very cordial meeting passed between him and Edmund;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89139,\n            \"for though she must submit, as her own propriety of mind directed, in spite of her aunt Norris\\u2019 s opinion, to being the principal lady in company, and to all the little distinctions consequent thereon, she found, while they were at table, such a happy flow of conversation prevailing, in which she was not required to take any part \\u2014 there was so much to be said between the brother and sister about Bath, so much between the two young men about hunting, so much of politics between Mr. Crawford and Dr. Grant, and of everything and all together between Mr. Crawford and Mrs. Grant, as to leave her the fairest prospect of having only to listen in quiet, and of passing a very agreeable day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94604,\n            \"He was roused from the reverie of retrospection and regret produced by it, by some inquiry from Edmund as to his plans for the next day\\u2019s hunting;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97326,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Crawford listened, and Edmund agreed to this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102215,\n            \"and though trusting altogether to her affection, so far as to be resolved \\u2014 almost resolved \\u2014 on bringing it to a decision within a very short time, as soon as the variety of business before him were arranged, and he knew what he had to offer her, he had many anxious feelings, many doubting hours as to the result.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102281,\n            \"His conviction of her regard for him was sometimes very strong;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102293,\n            \"he could look back on a long course of encouragement, and she was as perfect in disinterested attachment as in everything else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102329,\n            \"and when he thought of her acknowledged disinclination for privacy and retirement, her decided preference of a London life, what could he expect but a determined rejection?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102394,\n            \"Did she love him well enough to forego what had used to be essential points?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102410,\n            \"Did she love him well enough to make them no longer essential?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102423,\n            \"And this question, which he was continually repeating to himself, though oftenest answered with a \\u201cYes,\\u201dhad sometimes its \\u201cNo.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102479,\n            \"He had seen her eyes sparkle as she spoke of the dear friend\\u2019s letter, which claimed a long visit from her in London, and of the kindness of Henry, in engaging to remain where he was till January, that he might convey her thither;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102530,\n            \"he had heard her speak of the pleasure of such a journey with an animation which had \\u201cno\\u201din every tone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102591,\n            \"He had since heard her express herself differently, with other feelings, more chequered feelings: he had heard her tell Mrs. Grant that she should leave her with regret;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105173,\n            \"for Edmund was so struck with the circumstance, so delighted with what Miss Crawford had done, so gratified by such a coincidence of conduct between them, that Fanny could not but admit the superior power of one pleasure over his own mind, though it might have its drawback.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105583,\n            \"Miss Crawford\\u2019s attentions to you have been \\u2014 not more than you were justly entitled to \\u2014 I am the last person to think that _ could _ _ be _, but they have been invariable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105878,\n            \"He would marry Miss Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105925,\n            \"Could she believe Miss Crawford to deserve him, it would be \\u2014 oh, how different would it be \\u2014 how far more tolerable!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106084,\n            \"To think of him as Miss Crawford might be justified in thinking, would in her be insanity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106148,\n            \"She would endeavour to be rational, and to deserve the right of judging of Miss Crawford\\u2019s character, and the privilege of true solicitude for him by a sound intellect and an honest heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106529,\n            \"and opened with more kindness to Fanny than such self-willed, unmanageable days often volunteer, for soon after breakfast a very friendly note was brought from Mr. Crawford to William, stating that as he found himself obliged to go to London on the morrow for a few days, he could not help trying to procure a companion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106625,\n            \"Mr. Crawford meant to be in town by his uncle\\u2019s accustomary late dinner-hour, and William was invited to dine with him at the Admiral\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106771,\n            \"and though this offer of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s would rob her of many hours of his company, she was too happy in having William spared from the fatigue of such a journey, to think of anything else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106822,\n            \"His nephew\\u2019s introduction to Admiral Crawford might be of service.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107056,\n            \"To dance without much observation or any extraordinary fatigue, to have strength and partners for about half the evening, to dance a little with Edmund, and not a great deal with Mr. Crawford, to see William enjoy himself, and be able to keep away from her aunt Norris, was the height of her ambition, and seemed to comprehend her greatest possibility of happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107569,\n            \"\\u201cI wished to engage Miss Crawford for the two first dances,\\u201dwas the explanation that followed, and brought Fanny to life again, enabling her, as she found she was expected to speak, to utter something like an inquiry as to the result.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107619,\n            \"\\u201cYes,\\u201dhe answered, \\u201cshe is engaged to me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107633,\n            \"but\\u201d(with a smile that did not sit easy) \\u201cshe says it is to be the last time that she ever will dance with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107668,\n            \"I think, I hope, I am sure she is not serious;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107899,\n            \"I have been pained by her manner this morning, and cannot get the better of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107917,\n            \"I know her disposition to be as sweet and faultless as your own, but the influence of her former companions makes her seem \\u2014 gives to her conversation, to her professed opinions, sometimes a tinge of wrong.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108256,\n            \"\\u201d cried Edmund, pressing her hand to his lips with almost as much warmth as if it had been Miss Crawford\\u2019s, \\u201cyou are all considerate thought!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108408,\n            \"but you have always known my opinion of her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108451,\n            \"I have almost given up every serious idea of her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108594,\n            \"For Fanny\\u2019s present comfort it was concluded, perhaps, at the happiest moment: had he been able to talk another five minutes, there is no saying that he might not have talked away all Miss Crawford\\u2019s faults and his own despondence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108677,\n            \"Since the first joy from Mr. Crawford\\u2019s note to William had worn away, she had been in a state absolutely the reverse;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108858,\n            \"and having, with delightful feelings, joined the chain and the cross \\u2014 those memorials of the two most beloved of her heart, those dearest tokens so formed for each other by everything real and imaginary \\u2014 and put them round her neck, and seen and felt how full of William and Edmund they were, she was able, without an effort, to resolve on wearing Miss Crawford\\u2019s necklace too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110300,\n            \"and her eyes, bright as they had been before, shewing they could yet be brighter, she exclaimed with eager pleasure, \\u201cDid he?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110345,\n            \"I honour him beyond expression.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110351,\n            \"\\u201d And she looked around as if longing to tell him so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110552,\n            \"Whenever she had thought of the minutiae of the evening, it had been as a matter of course that Edmund would begin with Miss Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114918,\n            \"Angry as she was with Edmund for adhering to his own notions, and acting on them in defiance of her (and she had been so angry that they had hardly parted friends at the ball), she could not help thinking of him continually when absent, dwelling on his merit and affection, and longing again for the almost daily meetings they lately had.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114993,\n            \"He should not have planned such an absence \\u2014 he should not have left home for a week, when her own departure from Mansfield was so near.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115096,\n            \"All this was bad, but she had still more to feel when Friday came round again and brought no Edmund;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115126,\n            \"and when, through the slight communication with the other family which Sunday produced, she learned that he had actually written home to defer his return, having promised to remain some days longer with his friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115165,\n            \"If she had felt impatience and regret before \\u2014 if she had been sorry for what she said, and feared its too strong effect on him \\u2014 she now felt and feared it all tenfold more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115235,\n            \"But, at any rate, his staying away at a time when, according to all preceding plans, she was to remove to London, meant something that she could not bear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115270,\n            \"Had Henry returned, as he talked of doing, at the end of three or four days, she should now have been leaving Mansfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115325,\n            \"and she made her way to the Park, through difficulties of walking which she had deemed unconquerable a week before, for the chance of hearing a little in addition, for the sake of at least hearing his name.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120422,\n            \"I would not allow myself yesterday to say how delighted, or to repeat half that the Admiral said in his praise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126593,\n            \"\\u201cIndependently of the interest which Mr. Crawford\\u2019s _ choice _ seemed to justify\\u201dsaid Sir Thomas, beginning again, and very composedly, \\u201chis wishing to marry at all so early is recommendatory to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133672,\n            \"The first that occurred was not least in interest: the appearance of Henry Crawford and his sister walking together through the village as he rode into it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133728,\n            \"He was returning to Mansfield with spirits ready to feed on melancholy remembrances, and tender associations, when her own fair self was before him, leaning on her brother\\u2019s arm, and he found himself receiving a welcome, unquestionably friendly, from the woman whom, two moments before, he had been thinking of as seventy miles off, and as farther, much farther, from him in inclination than any distance could express.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134176,\n            \"His surprise was not so great as his father\\u2019s at her refusing Crawford, because, so far from supposing her to consider him with anything like a preference, he had always believed it to be rather the reverse, and could imagine her to be taken perfectly unprepared, but Sir Thomas could not regard the connexion as more desirable than he did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134420,\n            \"Crawford called the next day, and on the score of Edmund\\u2019s return, Sir Thomas felt himself more than licensed to ask him to stay dinner;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134457,\n            \"He staid of course, and Edmund had then ample opportunity for observing how he sped with Fanny, and what degree of immediate encouragement for him might be extracted from her manners;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134962,\n            \"To _ good _ reading, however, she had been long used: her uncle read well, her cousins all, Edmund very well, but in Mr. Crawford\\u2019s reading there was a variety of excellence beyond what she had ever met with.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135154,\n            \"Edmund watched the progress of her attention, and was amused and gratified by seeing how she gradually slackened in the needlework, which at the beginning seemed to occupy her totally: how it fell from her hand while she sat motionless over it, and at last, how the eyes which had appeared so studiously to avoid him throughout the day were turned and fixed on Crawford \\u2014 fixed on him for minutes, fixed on him, in short, till the attraction drew Crawford\\u2019s upon her, and the book was closed, and the charm was broken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135277,\n            \"but it had been enough to give Edmund encouragement for his friend, and as he cordially thanked him, he hoped to be expressing Fanny\\u2019s secret feelings too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136323,\n            \"and when Crawford proceeded to ask his opinion and give his own as to the properest manner in which particular passages in the service should be delivered, shewing it to be a subject on which he had thought before, and thought with judgment, Edmund was still more and more pleased.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137025,\n            \"and as Edmund perceived, by his drawing in a chair, and sitting down close by her, that it was to be a very thorough attack, that looks and undertones were to be well tried, he sank as quietly as possible into a corner, turned his back, and took up a newspaper, very sincerely wishing that dear little Fanny might be persuaded into explaining away that shake of the head to the satisfaction of her ardent lover;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137160,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny, meanwhile, vexed with herself for not having been as motionless as she was speechless, and grieved to the heart to see Edmund\\u2019s arrangements, was trying by everything in the power of her modest, gentle nature, to repulse Mr. Crawford, and avoid both his looks and inquiries;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138347,\n            \"CHAPTER XXXV Edmund had determined that it belonged entirely to Fanny to chuse whether her situation with regard to Crawford should be mentioned between them or not;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138394,\n            \"but after a day or two of mutual reserve, he was induced by his father to change his mind, and try what his influence might do for his friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138444,\n            \"and Sir Thomas thought it might be as well to make one more effort for the young man before he left Mansfield, that all his professions and vows of unshaken attachment might have as much hope to sustain them as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138487,\n            \"Sir Thomas was most cordially anxious for the perfection of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s character in that point.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138507,\n            \"He wished him to be a model of constancy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138976,\n            \"I dare say that, on a comparison of our opinions, they would be found as much alike as they have been used to be: to the point \\u2014 I consider Crawford\\u2019s proposals as most advantageous and desirable, if you could return his affection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139514,\n            \"I am aware, more aware than Crawford can be, that the man who means to make you love him (you having due notice of his intentions) must have very uphill work, for there are all your early attachments and habits in battle array;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139613,\n            \"I know that the apprehension of being forced to quit Mansfield will for a time be arming you against him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139634,\n            \"I wish he had not been obliged to tell you what he was trying for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139650,\n            \"I wish he had known you as well as I do, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139675,\n            \"My theoretical and his practical knowledge together could not have failed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139687,\n            \"He should have worked upon my plans.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139695,\n            \"I must hope, however, that time, proving him (as I firmly believe it will) to deserve you by his steady affection, will give him his reward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139728,\n            \"I cannot suppose that you have not the _ wish _ to love him \\u2014 the natural wish of gratitude.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140288,\n            \"I must say, cousin, that I cannot approve his character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140598,\n            \"I have heard before from some one of his being in love with Julia;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140622,\n            \"And, Fanny, though I hope I do justice to my sisters\\u2019 good qualities, I think it very possible that they might, one or both, be more desirous of being admired by Crawford, and might shew that desire rather more unguardedly than was perfectly prudent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140674,\n            \"I can remember that they were evidently fond of his society;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140737,\n            \"And I must say, that its being for you has raised him inconceivably in my opinion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140785,\n            \"It proves him, in short, everything that I had been used to wish to believe him, and feared he was not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140829,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cSay, rather, that he has not thought at all upon serious subjects, which I believe to be a good deal the case.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140893,\n            \"Crawford\\u2019s _ feelings _, I am ready to acknowledge, have hitherto been too much his guides.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140990,\n            \"I know he will make you happy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141086,\n            \"I have no common interest in Crawford\\u2019s well-doing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141099,\n            \"Next to your happiness, Fanny, his has the first claim on me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141114,\n            \"You are aware of my having no common interest in Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141201,\n            \"but yet I was afraid of her not estimating your worth to her brother quite as it deserved, and of her regretting that he had not rather fixed on some woman of distinction or fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142175,\n            \"You have now given exactly the explanation which I ventured to make for you to your friend and Mrs. Grant, and they were both better satisfied, though your warm-hearted friend was still run away with a little by the enthusiasm of her fondness for Henry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142775,\n            \"You and Miss Crawford have made me too nice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142864,\n            \"It had been, as he before presumed, too hasty a measure on Crawford\\u2019s side, and time must be given to make the idea first familiar, and then agreeable to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143103,\n            \"The promised visit from \\u201cher friend,\\u201das Edmund called Miss Crawford, was a formidable threat to Fanny, and she lived in continual terror of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147384,\n            \"but the more she recollected and observed, the more deeply was she convinced that everything was now in a fairer train for Miss Crawford\\u2019s marrying Edmund than it had ever been before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147663,\n            \"and she may be forgiven by older sages for looking on the chance of Miss Crawford\\u2019s future improvement as nearly desperate, for thinking that if Edmund\\u2019s influence in this season of love had already done so little in clearing her judgment, and regulating her notions, his worth would be finally wasted on her even in years of matrimony.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147729,\n            \"Experience might have hoped more for any young people so circumstanced, and impartiality would not have denied to Miss Crawford\\u2019s nature that participation of the general nature of women which would lead her to adopt the opinions of the man she loved and respected as her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147806,\n            \"Sir Thomas, meanwhile, went on with his own hopes and his own observations, still feeling a right, by all his knowledge of human nature, to expect to see the effect of the loss of power and consequence on his niece\\u2019s spirits, and the past attentions of the lover producing a craving for their return;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173318,\n            \"but Miss Crawford gave her the idea of being the child of good luck, and to her selfishness and vanity it would be good luck to have Edmund the only son.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174559,\n            \"_ her _ attachment to Edmund had been respectable, the most respectable part of her character;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178281,\n            \"Miss Crawford, herself, Edmund;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182659,\n            \"and, having reason to think that one interview with Miss Crawford had taken place, from which Edmund derived only increased distress, had been as anxious on that account as on others to get him out of town, and had engaged him in taking Fanny home to her aunt, with a view to his relief and benefit, no less than theirs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186188,\n            \"and happy as all this must make her, she would still have been happy without any of it, for Edmund was no longer the dupe of Miss Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189714,\n            \"Scarcely had he done regretting Mary Crawford, and observing to Fanny how impossible it was that he should ever meet with such another woman, before it began to strike him whether a very different kind of woman might not do just as well, or a great deal better: whether Fanny herself were not growing as dear, as important to him in all her smiles and all her ways, as Mary Crawford had ever been;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189872,\n            \"I only entreat everybody to believe that exactly at the time when it was quite natural that it should be so, and not a week earlier, Edmund did cease to care about Miss Crawford, and became as anxious to marry Fanny as Fanny herself could desire.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 9]\": [\n        [\n            18406,\n            \"In a quiet way, very little attended to, she paid her tribute of admiration to Miss Crawford\\u2019s beauty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24599,\n            \"I dare say Mr. Crawford would take my two nieces and me in his barouche, and Edmund can go on horseback, you know, sister, and Fanny will stay at home with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24670,\n            \"CHAPTER VII \\u201cWell, Fanny, and how do you like Miss Crawford _ now _?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24704,\n            \"\\u201cHow did you like her yesterday?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24767,\n            \"But was there nothing in her conversation that struck you, Fanny, as not quite right?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25032,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo not you think,\\u201dsaid Fanny, after a little consideration, \\u201cthat this impropriety is a reflection itself upon Mrs. Crawford, as her niece has been entirely brought up by her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25963,\n            \"She was a little surprised that he could spend so many hours with Miss Crawford, and not see more of the sort of fault which he had already observed, and of which _ she _ was almost always reminded by a something of the same nature whenever she was in her company;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32348,\n            \"That was the only point of resemblance between her and the lady who sat by her: in everything but a value for Edmund, Miss Crawford was very unlike her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32380,\n            \"She had none of Fanny\\u2019s delicacy of taste, of mind, of feeling;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33703,\n            \"On the present occasion she addressed herself chiefly to Miss Crawford and Fanny, but there was no comparison in the willingness of their attention;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34347,\n            \"and Edmund, Fanny, and Miss Crawford remained in a cluster together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35322,\n            \"\\u201d cried Julia, and running to where he stood with Miss Crawford and Fanny: \\u201cMy dear Edmund, if you were but in orders now, you might perform the ceremony directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35405,\n            \"Fanny pitied her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38173,\n            \"\\u201cI am afraid you are very tired, Fanny,\\u201dsaid Edmund, observing her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40086,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny was again left to her solitude, and with no increase of pleasant feelings, for she was sorry for almost all that she had seen and heard, astonished at Miss Bertram, and angry with Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40608,\n            \"\\u201d And she immediately scrambled across the fence, and walked away, not attending to Fanny\\u2019s last question of whether she had seen anything of Miss Crawford and Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43251,\n            \"but after tea, as Miss Crawford was standing at an open window with Edmund and Fanny looking out on a twilight scene, while the Miss Bertrams, Mr. Rushworth, and Henry Crawford were all busy with candles at the pianoforte, she suddenly revived it by turning round towards the group, and saying, \\u201cHow happy Mr. Rushworth looks!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44496,\n            \"\\u201cI have been so little addicted to take my opinions from my uncle,\\u201dsaid Miss Crawford, \\u201cthat I can hardly suppose \\u2014 and since you push me so hard, I must observe, that I am not entirely without the means of seeing what clergymen are, being at this present time the guest of my own brother, Dr. Grant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59796,\n            \"Fanny did not love Miss Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59816,\n            \"and when, from taking notice of her work, and wishing _ she _ could work as well, and begging for the pattern, and supposing Fanny was now preparing for her _ appearance _, as of course she would come out when her cousin was married, Miss Crawford proceeded to inquire if she had heard lately from her brother at sea, and said that she had quite a curiosity to see him, and imagined him a very fine young man, and advised Fanny to get his picture drawn before he went to sea again \\u2014 she could not help admitting it to be very agreeable flattery, or help listening, and answering with more animation than she had intended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59945,\n            \"The consultation upon the play still went on, and Miss Crawford\\u2019s attention was first called from Fanny by Tom Bertram\\u2019s telling her, with infinite regret, that he found it absolutely impossible for him to undertake the part of Anhalt in addition to the Butler: he had been most anxiously trying to make it out to be feasible, but it would not do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60381,\n            \"\\u201cI am not very sanguine as to our play,\\u201dsaid Miss Crawford, in an undervoice to Fanny, after some consideration;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60457,\n            \"\\u201d CHAPTER XVI It was not in Miss Crawford\\u2019s power to talk Fanny into any real forgetfulness of what had passed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62382,\n            \"Put yourself in Miss Crawford\\u2019s place, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62875,\n            \"It must be a great relief to her,\\u201dsaid Fanny, trying for greater warmth of manner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63920,\n            \"One advantage resulted from it to Fanny: at the earnest request of Miss Crawford, Mrs. Grant had, with her usual good-humour, agreed to undertake the part for which Fanny had been wanted;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66240,\n            \"Henry Crawford acted well, and it was a pleasure to _ her _ to creep into the theatre, and attend the rehearsal of the first act, in spite of the feelings it excited in some speeches for Maria.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66324,\n            \"As far as she could judge, Mr. Crawford was considerably the best actor of all: he had more confidence than Edmund, more judgment than Tom, more talent and taste than Mr. Yates.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66363,\n            \"She did not like him as a man, but she must admit him to be the best actor, and on this point there were not many who differed from her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67230,\n            \"Fanny did not share her aunt\\u2019s composure: she thought of the morrow a great deal, for if the three acts were rehearsed, Edmund and Miss Crawford would then be acting together for the first time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67431,\n            \"and about noon she made her escape with her work to the East room, that she might have no concern in another, and, as she deemed it, most unnecessary rehearsal of the first act, which Henry Crawford was just proposing, desirous at once of having her time to herself, and of avoiding the sight of Mr. Rushworth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68236,\n            \"\\u201d She began, and Fanny joined in with all the modest feeling which the idea of representing Edmund was so strongly calculated to inspire;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68375,\n            \"He too had his book, and was seeking Fanny, to ask her to rehearse with him, and help him to prepare for the evening, without knowing Miss Crawford to be in the house;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68490,\n            \"Edmund proposed, urged, entreated it, till the lady, not very unwilling at first, could refuse no longer, and Fanny was wanted only to prompt and observe them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72377,\n            \"\\u201cWhere did you leave Miss Crawford, Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79398,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny could have said a great deal, but it was safer to say nothing, and leave untouched all Miss Crawford\\u2019s resources \\u2014 her accomplishments, her spirits, her importance, her friends, lest it should betray her into any observations seemingly unhandsome.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79448,\n            \"Miss Crawford\\u2019s kind opinion of herself deserved at least a grateful forbearance, and she began to talk of something else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82616,\n            \"Such was the origin of the sort of intimacy which took place between them within the first fortnight after the Miss Bertrams\\u2019 going away \\u2014 an intimacy resulting principally from Miss Crawford\\u2019s desire of something new, and which had little reality in Fanny\\u2019s feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82667,\n            \"Fanny went to her every two or three days: it seemed a kind of fascination: she could not be easy without going, and yet it was without loving her, without ever thinking like her, without any sense of obligation for being sought after now when nobody else was to be had;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89139,\n            \"for though she must submit, as her own propriety of mind directed, in spite of her aunt Norris\\u2019 s opinion, to being the principal lady in company, and to all the little distinctions consequent thereon, she found, while they were at table, such a happy flow of conversation prevailing, in which she was not required to take any part \\u2014 there was so much to be said between the brother and sister about Bath, so much between the two young men about hunting, so much of politics between Mr. Crawford and Dr. Grant, and of everything and all together between Mr. Crawford and Mrs. Grant, as to leave her the fairest prospect of having only to listen in quiet, and of passing a very agreeable day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92384,\n            \"for although there doubtless are such unconquerable young ladies of eighteen (or one should not read about them) as are never to be persuaded into love against their judgment by all that talent, manner, attention, and flattery can do, I have no inclination to believe Fanny one of them, or to think that with so much tenderness of disposition, and so much taste as belonged to her, she could have escaped heart-whole from the courtship (though the courtship only of a fortnight) of such a man as Crawford, in spite of there being some previous ill opinion of him to be overcome, had not her affection been engaged elsewhere.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92509,\n            \"With all the security which love of another and disesteem of him could give to the peace of mind he was attacking, his continued attentions \\u2014 continued, but not obtrusive, and adapting themselves more and more to the gentleness and delicacy of her character \\u2014 obliged her very soon to dislike him less than formerly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92568,\n            \"She had by no means forgotten the past, and she thought as ill of him as ever;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92587,\n            \"but she felt his powers: he was entertaining;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92636,\n            \"and at the end of those few days, circumstances arose which had a tendency rather to forward his views of pleasing her, inasmuch as they gave her a degree of happiness which must dispose her to be pleased with everybody.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92737,\n            \"and when Crawford walked up with the newspaper in his hand, which he had hoped would bring the first tidings, he found her trembling with joy over this letter, and listening with a glowing, grateful countenance to the kind invitation which her uncle was most collectedly dictating in reply.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92791,\n            \"It was but the day before that Crawford had made himself thoroughly master of the subject, or had in fact become at all aware of her having such a brother, or his being in such a ship, but the interest then excited had been very properly lively, determining him on his return to town to apply for information as to the probable period of the Antwerp\\u2019s return from the Mediterranean, etc.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92871,\n            \"and the good luck which attended his early examination of ship news the next morning seemed the reward of his ingenuity in finding out such a method of pleasing her, as well as of his dutiful attention to the Admiral, in having for many years taken in the paper esteemed to have the earliest naval intelligence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92960,\n            \"But his intention, the kindness of his intention, was thankfully acknowledged: quite thankfully and warmly, for she was elevated beyond the common timidity of her mind by the flow of her love for William.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93955,\n            \"He honoured the warm-hearted, blunt fondness of the young sailor, which led him to say, with his hands stretched towards Fanny\\u2019s head, \\u201cDo you know, I begin to like that queer fashion already, though when I first heard of such things being done in England, I could not believe it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94048,\n            \"but Fanny can reconcile me to anything \\u201d;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94699,\n            \"and Crawford could mount him without the slightest inconvenience to himself, and with only some scruples to obviate in Sir Thomas, who knew better than his nephew the value of such a loan, and some alarms to reason away in Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94818,\n            \"nor till he returned safe and well, without accident or discredit, could she be reconciled to the risk, or feel any of that obligation to Mr. Crawford for lending the horse which he had fully intended it should produce.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97875,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny\\u2019s eyes were turned on Crawford for a moment with an expression more than grave \\u2014 even reproachful;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99364,\n            \"\\u201d Whatever effect Sir Thomas\\u2019 s little harangue might really produce on Mr. Crawford, it raised some awkward sensations in two of the others, two of his most attentive listeners \\u2014 Miss Crawford and Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103245,\n            \"\\u201d And as she spoke she was undoing a small parcel, which Fanny had observed in her hand when they met.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103323,\n            \"Such had been the parcel with which Miss Crawford was provided, and such the object of her intended visit: and in the kindest manner she now urged Fanny\\u2019s taking one for the cross and to keep for her sake, saying everything she could think of to obviate the scruples which were making Fanny start back at first with a look of horror at the proposal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103583,\n            \"and though Fanny would have preferred a longer and a plainer chain as more adapted for her purpose, she hoped, in fixing on this, to be chusing what Miss Crawford least wished to keep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105173,\n            \"for Edmund was so struck with the circumstance, so delighted with what Miss Crawford had done, so gratified by such a coincidence of conduct between them, that Fanny could not but admit the superior power of one pleasure over his own mind, though it might have its drawback.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106529,\n            \"and opened with more kindness to Fanny than such self-willed, unmanageable days often volunteer, for soon after breakfast a very friendly note was brought from Mr. Crawford to William, stating that as he found himself obliged to go to London on the morrow for a few days, he could not help trying to procure a companion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107569,\n            \"\\u201cI wished to engage Miss Crawford for the two first dances,\\u201dwas the explanation that followed, and brought Fanny to life again, enabling her, as she found she was expected to speak, to utter something like an inquiry as to the result.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108594,\n            \"For Fanny\\u2019s present comfort it was concluded, perhaps, at the happiest moment: had he been able to talk another five minutes, there is no saying that he might not have talked away all Miss Crawford\\u2019s faults and his own despondence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110282,\n            \"and all her intended compliments and insinuations to Fanny were forgotten: she felt only one thing;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110405,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s heart sunk, but there was no leisure for thinking long even of Miss Crawford\\u2019s feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110552,\n            \"Whenever she had thought of the minutiae of the evening, it had been as a matter of course that Edmund would begin with Miss Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111128,\n            \"Miss Crawford saw much of Sir Thomas\\u2019 s thoughts as he stood, and having, in spite of all his wrongs towards her, a general prevailing desire of recommending herself to him, took an opportunity of stepping aside to say something agreeable of Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111434,\n            \"Miss Crawford blundered most towards Fanny herself in her intentions to please.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115297,\n            \"It became absolutely necessary for her to get to Fanny and try to learn something more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115367,\n            \"The first half-hour was lost, for Fanny and Lady Bertram were together, and unless she had Fanny to herself she could hope for nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116275,\n            \"\\u201d Now Fanny could not bring herself to speak, and Miss Crawford was disappointed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120097,\n            \"While her hand was trembling under these letters, her eye running from one to the other, and her heart swelling with emotion, Crawford thus continued, with unfeigned eagerness, to express his interest in the event \\u2014 \\u201cI will not talk of my own happiness,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cgreat as it is, for I think only of yours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120893,\n            \"He was after her immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120899,\n            \"\\u201cShe must not go, she must allow him five minutes longer,\\u201dand he took her hand and led her back to her seat, and was in the middle of his farther explanation, before she had suspected for what she was detained.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121869,\n            \"This was a most unwelcome hearing, for though he might think nothing of what had passed, it would be quite distressing to her to see him again so soon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123014,\n            \"I think I will have two shawls, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123024,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny, meanwhile, speaking only when she could not help it, was very earnestly trying to understand what Mr. and Miss Crawford were at.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123407,\n            \"At last \\u2014 it seemed an at last to Fanny\\u2019s nervousness, though not remarkably late \\u2014 he began to talk of going away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124073,\n            \"CHAPTER XXXII Fanny had by no means forgotten Mr. Crawford when she awoke the next morning;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124179,\n            \"Fanny had hoped, in the course of his yesterday\\u2019s visit, to hear the day named;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124938,\n            \"but I think too well of you, Fanny, to suppose you will ever harbour resentment on that account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125392,\n            \"He talked, therefore, for several minutes without Fanny\\u2019s daring to interrupt him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125459,\n            \"For a moment he ceased, but she had barely become conscious of it, when, rising from his chair, he said, \\u201cAnd now, Fanny, having performed one part of my commission, and shewn you everything placed on a basis the most assured and satisfactory, I may execute the remainder by prevailing on you to accompany me downstairs, where, though I cannot but presume on having been no unacceptable companion myself, I must submit to your finding one still better worth listening to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125808,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou are mistaken, sir,\\u201dcried Fanny, forced by the anxiety of the moment even to tell her uncle that he was wrong;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126864,\n            \"and getting up and walking about the room with a frown, which Fanny could picture to herself, though she dared not lift up her eyes, he shortly afterwards, and in a voice of authority, said, \\u201cHave you any reason, child, to think ill of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s temper?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127389,\n            \"You think only of yourself, and because you do not feel for Mr. Crawford exactly what a young heated fancy imagines to be necessary for happiness, you resolve to refuse him at once, without wishing even for a little time to consider of it, a little more time for cool consideration, and for really examining your own inclinations;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127533,\n            \"and let me tell you, Fanny, that you may live eighteen years longer in the world without being addressed by a man of half Mr. Crawford\\u2019s estate, or a tenth part of his merits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129474,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI recommended the shrubbery to Fanny as the driest place,\\u201dsaid Sir Thomas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129533,\n            \"Fanny would have had quite as good a walk there, I assure you, with the advantage of being of some use, and obliging her aunt: it is all her fault.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129568,\n            \"If she would but have let us know she was going out but there is a something about Fanny, I have often observed it before \\u2014 she likes to go her own way to work;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129653,\n            \"\\u201d As a general reflection on Fanny, Sir Thomas thought nothing could be more unjust, though he had been so lately expressing the same sentiments himself, and he tried to turn the conversation: tried repeatedly before he could succeed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130314,\n            \"and Fanny, walking off in agitating consciousness, found herself, as she anticipated, in another minute alone with Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131427,\n            \"and he was not so irrational as Fanny considered him, in the professions of persevering, assiduous, and not desponding attachment which closed the interview.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131837,\n            \"Mr. Crawford\\u2019s steadiness was honoured, and Fanny was praised, and the connexion was still the most desirable in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132043,\n            \"Accordingly, on this principle, Sir Thomas took the first opportunity of saying to her, with a mild gravity, intended to be overcoming, \\u201cWell, Fanny, I have seen Mr. Crawford again, and learn from him exactly how matters stand between you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132220,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed, sir,\\u201dsaid Fanny, \\u201cI am very sorry that Mr. Crawford should continue to \\u2014 I know that it is paying me a very great compliment, and I feel most undeservedly honoured;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134457,\n            \"He staid of course, and Edmund had then ample opportunity for observing how he sped with Fanny, and what degree of immediate encouragement for him might be extracted from her manners;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134962,\n            \"To _ good _ reading, however, she had been long used: her uncle read well, her cousins all, Edmund very well, but in Mr. Crawford\\u2019s reading there was a variety of excellence beyond what she had ever met with.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135154,\n            \"Edmund watched the progress of her attention, and was amused and gratified by seeing how she gradually slackened in the needlework, which at the beginning seemed to occupy her totally: how it fell from her hand while she sat motionless over it, and at last, how the eyes which had appeared so studiously to avoid him throughout the day were turned and fixed on Crawford \\u2014 fixed on him for minutes, fixed on him, in short, till the attraction drew Crawford\\u2019s upon her, and the book was closed, and the charm was broken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135277,\n            \"but it had been enough to give Edmund encouragement for his friend, and as he cordially thanked him, he hoped to be expressing Fanny\\u2019s secret feelings too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135837,\n            \"\\u201d And he looked at Fanny with an expressive smile, which evidently meant, \\u201cThat lady will never allow a theatre at Everingham.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136995,\n            \"\\u201d Here Fanny, who could not but listen, involuntarily shook her head, and Crawford was instantly by her side again, entreating to know her meaning;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137025,\n            \"and as Edmund perceived, by his drawing in a chair, and sitting down close by her, that it was to be a very thorough attack, that looks and undertones were to be well tried, he sank as quietly as possible into a corner, turned his back, and took up a newspaper, very sincerely wishing that dear little Fanny might be persuaded into explaining away that shake of the head to the satisfaction of her ardent lover;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137160,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny, meanwhile, vexed with herself for not having been as motionless as she was speechless, and grieved to the heart to see Edmund\\u2019s arrangements, was trying by everything in the power of her modest, gentle nature, to repulse Mr. Crawford, and avoid both his looks and inquiries;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137577,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cPerhaps, sir,\\u201dsaid Fanny, wearied at last into speaking \\u2014 \\u201cperhaps, sir, I thought it was a pity you did not always know yourself as well as you seemed to do at that moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137641,\n            \"and poor Fanny, who had hoped to silence him by such an extremity of reproof, found herself sadly mistaken, and that it was only a change from one object of curiosity and one set of words to another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138347,\n            \"CHAPTER XXXV Edmund had determined that it belonged entirely to Fanny to chuse whether her situation with regard to Crawford should be mentioned between them or not;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139333,\n            \"But\\u201d(with an affectionate smile) \\u201clet him succeed at last, Fanny, let him succeed at last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139650,\n            \"I wish he had known you as well as I do, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139767,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWe are so totally unlike,\\u201dsaid Fanny, avoiding a direct answer, \\u201cwe are so very, very different in all our inclinations and ways, that I consider it as quite impossible we should ever be tolerably happy together, even if I _ could _ like him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139891,\n            \"and, Fanny, who that heard him read, and saw you listen to Shakespeare the other night, will think you unfitted as companions?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140145,\n            \"\\u201d Full well could Fanny guess where his thoughts were now: Miss Crawford\\u2019s power was all returning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140201,\n            \"After leaving him to his happier thoughts for some minutes, Fanny, feeling it due to herself, returned to Mr. Crawford, and said, \\u201cIt is not merely in _ temper _ that I consider him as totally unsuited to myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140622,\n            \"And, Fanny, though I hope I do justice to my sisters\\u2019 good qualities, I think it very possible that they might, one or both, be more desirous of being admired by Crawford, and might shew that desire rather more unguardedly than was perfectly prudent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140686,\n            \"and with such encouragement, a man like Crawford, lively, and it may be, a little unthinking, might be led on to \\u2014 there could be nothing very striking, because it is clear that he had no pretensions: his heart was reserved for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140737,\n            \"And I must say, that its being for you has raised him inconceivably in my opinion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140982,\n            \"He will make you happy, Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140990,\n            \"I know he will make you happy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140998,\n            \"but you will make him everything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141099,\n            \"Next to your happiness, Fanny, his has the first claim on me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141114,\n            \"You are aware of my having no common interest in Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141201,\n            \"but yet I was afraid of her not estimating your worth to her brother quite as it deserved, and of her regretting that he had not rather fixed on some woman of distinction or fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141394,\n            \"and when once we had begun, we had not done with you, Fanny, till Crawford and Dr. Grant came in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141517,\n            \"She is hurt, as you would be for William;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142413,\n            \"and to have Miss Crawford\\u2019s liveliness repeated to her at such a moment, and on such a subject, was a bitter aggravation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142458,\n            \"and not even to mention the name of Crawford again, except as it might be connected with what _ must _ be agreeable to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143103,\n            \"The promised visit from \\u201cher friend,\\u201das Edmund called Miss Crawford, was a formidable threat to Fanny, and she lived in continual terror of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143268,\n            \"and the first misery over, and Miss Crawford looking and speaking with much less particularity of expression than she had anticipated, Fanny began to hope there would be nothing worse to be endured than a half-hour of moderate agitation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143328,\n            \"She was determined to see Fanny alone, and therefore said to her tolerably soon, in a low voice, \\u201cI must speak to you for a few minutes somewhere \\u201d;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143440,\n            \"She immediately shook her head at Fanny with arch, yet affectionate reproach, and taking her hand, seemed hardly able to help beginning directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143467,\n            \"She said nothing, however, but, \\u201cSad, sad girl!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147532,\n            \"and when once with her again, Fanny could not doubt the rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162083,\n            \"and, ungentlemanlike as he looked, Fanny was obliged to introduce him to Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162386,\n            \"The conclusion of the two gentlemen\\u2019s civilities was an offer of Mr. Price\\u2019s to take Mr. Crawford into the dockyard, which Mr. Crawford, desirous of accepting as a favour what was intended as such, though he had seen the dockyard again and again, and hoping to be so much the longer with Fanny, was very gratefully disposed to avail himself of, if the Miss Prices were not afraid of the fatigue;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162912,\n            \"Crawford could not have wished her more fatigued or more ready to sit down;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163902,\n            \"and in the course of their walk back, Mr. Crawford contrived a minute\\u2019s privacy for telling Fanny that his only business in Portsmouth was to see her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163934,\n            \"that he was come down for a couple of days on her account, and hers only, and because he could not endure a longer total separation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163970,\n            \"and yet in spite of this and the two or three other things which she wished he had not said, she thought him altogether improved since she had seen him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169770,\n            \"I cannot give her up, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170087,\n            \"The loss of Mary I must consider as comprehending the loss of Crawford and of Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171195,\n            \"\\u2018 The loss of Mary I must consider as comprehending the loss of Crawford and Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174593,\n            \"It was so long since Fanny had had any letter from her, that she had some reason to think lightly of the friendship which had been so dwelt on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176056,\n            \"She thanked Miss Crawford, but gave a decided negative.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176216,\n            \"CHAPTER XLVI As Fanny could not doubt that her answer was conveying a real disappointment, she was rather in expectation, from her knowledge of Miss Crawford\\u2019s temper, of being urged again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176376,\n            \"and before she had opened the letter, the possibility of Mr. and Miss Crawford\\u2019s having applied to her uncle and obtained his permission was giving her ease.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182659,\n            \"and, having reason to think that one interview with Miss Crawford had taken place, from which Edmund derived only increased distress, had been as anxious on that account as on others to get him out of town, and had engaged him in taking Fanny home to her aunt, with a view to his relief and benefit, no less than theirs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182726,\n            \"Fanny was not in the secret of her uncle\\u2019s feelings, Sir Thomas not in the secret of Miss Crawford\\u2019s character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182752,\n            \"Had he been privy to her conversation with his son, he would not have wished her to belong to him, though her twenty thousand pounds had been forty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182783,\n            \"That Edmund must be for ever divided from Miss Crawford did not admit of a doubt with Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182947,\n            \"Long, long would it be ere Miss Crawford\\u2019s name passed his lips again, or she could hope for a renewal of such confidential intercourse as had been.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183249,\n            \"and regarding it as what was meant to be the last, last interview of friendship, and investing her with all the feelings of shame and wretchedness which Crawford\\u2019s sister ought to have known, he had gone to her in such a state of mind, so softened, so devoted, as made it for a few moments impossible to Fanny\\u2019s fears that it should be the last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189714,\n            \"Scarcely had he done regretting Mary Crawford, and observing to Fanny how impossible it was that he should ever meet with such another woman, before it began to strike him whether a very different kind of woman might not do just as well, or a great deal better: whether Fanny herself were not growing as dear, as important to him in all her smiles and all her ways, as Mary Crawford had ever been;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189872,\n            \"I only entreat everybody to believe that exactly at the time when it was quite natural that it should be so, and not a week earlier, Edmund did cease to care about Miss Crawford, and became as anxious to marry Fanny as Fanny herself could desire.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 10]\": [\n        [\n            123434,\n            \"but the comfort of the sound was impaired by his turning to her the next moment, and saying, \\u201cHave you nothing to send to Mary?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171195,\n            \"\\u2018 The loss of Mary I must consider as comprehending the loss of Crawford and Fanny.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 11]\": [\n        [\n            24808,\n            \"An uncle with whom she has been living so many years, and who, whatever his faults may be, is so very fond of her brother, treating him, they say, quite like a son.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92960,\n            \"But his intention, the kindness of his intention, was thankfully acknowledged: quite thankfully and warmly, for she was elevated beyond the common timidity of her mind by the flow of her love for William.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93955,\n            \"He honoured the warm-hearted, blunt fondness of the young sailor, which led him to say, with his hands stretched towards Fanny\\u2019s head, \\u201cDo you know, I begin to like that queer fashion already, though when I first heard of such things being done in England, I could not believe it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94699,\n            \"and Crawford could mount him without the slightest inconvenience to himself, and with only some scruples to obviate in Sir Thomas, who knew better than his nephew the value of such a loan, and some alarms to reason away in Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94976,\n            \"The return of Henry Crawford, and the arrival of William Price, had much to do with it, but much was still owing to Sir Thomas\\u2019 s more than toleration of the neighbourly attempts at the Parsonage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96953,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Crawford, a little suspicious and resentful of a certain tone of voice, and a certain half-look attending the last expression of his hope, made a hasty finish of her dealings with William Price;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97654,\n            \"but Crawford pursued with \\u201cNo, no, you must not part with the queen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103461,\n            \"But Miss Crawford persevered, and argued the case with so much affectionate earnestness through all the heads of William and the cross, and the ball, and herself, as to be finally successful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107056,\n            \"To dance without much observation or any extraordinary fatigue, to have strength and partners for about half the evening, to dance a little with Edmund, and not a great deal with Mr. Crawford, to see William enjoy himself, and be able to keep away from her aunt Norris, was the height of her ambition, and seemed to comprehend her greatest possibility of happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120605,\n            \"His last journey to London had been undertaken with no other view than that of introducing her brother in Hill Street, and prevailing on the Admiral to exert whatever interest he might have for getting him on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120899,\n            \"\\u201cShe must not go, she must allow him five minutes longer,\\u201dand he took her hand and led her back to her seat, and was in the middle of his farther explanation, before she had suspected for what she was detained.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123617,\n            \"and with only one decided feeling, that of wishing not to appear to think anything really intended, she wrote thus, in great trembling both of spirits and hand \\u2014 \\u201cI am very much obliged to you, my dear Miss Crawford, for your kind congratulations, as far as they relate to my dearest William.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131259,\n            \"and to complete the whole, he was now the Mr. Crawford who had procured William\\u2019s promotion!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131793,\n            \"and when seeing such confidence of success in the principal, Sir Thomas was soon able to depend on it himself.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 12]\": [\n        [\n            46223,\n            \"Maria, with only Mr. Rushworth to attend to her, and doomed to the repeated details of his day\\u2019s sport, good or bad, his boast of his dogs, his jealousy of his neighbours, his doubts of their qualifications, and his zeal after poachers, subjects which will not find their way to female feelings without some talent on one side or some attachment on the other, had missed Mr. Crawford grievously;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46330,\n            \"Julia might be justified in so doing by the hints of Mrs. Grant, inclined to credit what she wished, and Maria by the hints of Mr. Crawford himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47349,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Bertram did indeed look happy, her eyes were sparkling with pleasure, and she was speaking with great animation, for Julia and her partner, Mr. Crawford, were close to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56131,\n            \"Maria blushed in spite of herself as she answered, \\u201cI take the part which Lady Ravenshaw was to have done, and\\u201d(with a bolder eye) \\u201cMiss Crawford is to be Amelia.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57707,\n            \"and the spirits of evening giving fresh courage, Tom, Maria, and Mr. Yates, soon after their being reassembled in the drawing-room, seated themselves in committee at a separate table, with the play open before them, and were just getting deep in the subject when a most welcome interruption was given by the entrance of Mr. and Miss Crawford, who, late and dark and dirty as it was, could not help coming, and were received with the most grateful joy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59608,\n            \"but Miss Crawford, looking for a moment with astonished eyes at Mrs. Norris, and then at Fanny, whose tears were beginning to shew themselves, immediately said, with some keenness, \\u201cI do not like my situation: this _ place _ is too hot for me,\\u201dand moved away her chair to the opposite side of the table, close to Fanny, saying to her, in a kind, low whisper, as she placed herself, \\u201cNever mind, my dear Miss Price, this is a cross evening: everybody is cross and teasing, but do not let us mind them \\u201d;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66490,\n            \"\\u201d From this moment there was a return of his former jealousy, which Maria, from increasing hopes of Crawford, was at little pains to remove;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76501,\n            \"It was of the utmost consequence to her that Crawford should now lose no time in declaring himself, and she was disturbed that even a day should be gone by without seeming to advance that point.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76539,\n            \"She had been expecting to see him the whole morning, and all the evening, too, was still expecting him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127592,\n            \"but had Mr. Crawford sought Julia\\u2019s hand, I should have given it to him with superior and more heartfelt satisfaction than I gave Maria\\u2019s to Mr. Rushworth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140315,\n            \"I then saw him behaving, as it appeared to me, so very improperly and unfeelingly \\u2014 I may speak of it now because it is all over \\u2014 so improperly by poor Mr. Rushworth, not seeming to care how he exposed or hurt him, and paying attentions to my cousin Maria, which \\u2014 in short, at the time of the play, I received an impression which will never be got over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140448,\n            \"Maria was wrong, Crawford was wrong, we were all wrong together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140571,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBefore the play, I am much mistaken if _ Julia _ did not think he was paying her attentions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140598,\n            \"I have heard before from some one of his being in love with Julia;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141201,\n            \"but yet I was afraid of her not estimating your worth to her brother quite as it deserved, and of her regretting that he had not rather fixed on some woman of distinction or fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141354,\n            \"Mrs. Grant laughed at her for her rapidity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141394,\n            \"and when once we had begun, we had not done with you, Fanny, till Crawford and Dr. Grant came in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141517,\n            \"She is hurt, as you would be for William;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 13]\": [\n        [\n            29953,\n            \"Mrs. Norris and her nieces were all well pleased with its revival, and an early day was named and agreed to, provided Mr. Crawford should be disengaged: the young ladies did not forget that stipulation, and though Mrs. Norris would willingly have answered for his being so, they would neither authorise the liberty nor run the risk;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30677,\n            \"On his return to the breakfast-room, he found Mrs. Norris trying to make up her mind as to whether Miss Crawford\\u2019s being of the party were desirable or not, or whether her brother\\u2019s barouche would not be full without her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30727,\n            \"The Miss Bertrams laughed at the idea, assuring her that the barouche would hold four perfectly well, independent of the box, on which _ one _ might go with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59506,\n            \"You see she does not like to act.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59608,\n            \"but Miss Crawford, looking for a moment with astonished eyes at Mrs. Norris, and then at Fanny, whose tears were beginning to shew themselves, immediately said, with some keenness, \\u201cI do not like my situation: this _ place _ is too hot for me,\\u201dand moved away her chair to the opposite side of the table, close to Fanny, saying to her, in a kind, low whisper, as she placed herself, \\u201cNever mind, my dear Miss Price, this is a cross evening: everybody is cross and teasing, but do not let us mind them \\u201d;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75841,\n            \"\\u2018 Upon my word, Mrs. Norris,\\u2019said Mrs. Grant the other day, \\u2018 if Mr. Rushworth were a son of your own, he could not hold Sir Thomas in greater respect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122900,\n            \"take them all together, I dare say nobody would believe what a sum they cost Sir Thomas every year, to say nothing of what _ I _ do for them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125075,\n            \"I am sure you will not disappoint my opinion of you, by failing at any time to treat your aunt Norris with the respect and attention that are due to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129361,\n            \"\\u201cIf I had known you were going out, I should have got you just to go as far as my house with some orders for Nanny,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cwhich I have since, to my very great inconvenience, been obliged to go and carry myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129414,\n            \"I could very ill spare the time, and you might have saved me the trouble, if you would only have been so good as to let us know you were going out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129449,\n            \"It would have made no difference to you, I suppose, whether you had walked in the shrubbery or gone to my house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129495,\n            \"\\u201d said Mrs. Norris, with a moment\\u2019s check, \\u201cthat was very kind of you, Sir Thomas;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129519,\n            \"but you do not know how dry the path is to my house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129697,\n            \"for Mrs. Norris had not discernment enough to perceive, either now, or at any other time, to what degree he thought well of his niece, or how very far he was from wishing to have his own children\\u2019s merits set off by the depreciation of hers.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 14]\": [\n        [\n            24266,\n            \"and as Miss Bertram caught at the idea likewise, and gave it her full support, declaring that, in her opinion, it was infinitely better to consult with friends and disinterested advisers, than immediately to throw the business into the hands of a professional man, Mr. Rushworth was very ready to request the favour of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s assistance;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24387,\n            \"when Mrs. Norris, as if reading in her two nieces\\u2019 minds their little approbation of a plan which was to take Mr. Crawford away, interposed with an amendment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24934,\n            \"With such warm feelings and lively spirits it must be difficult to do justice to her affection for Mrs. Crawford, without throwing a shade on the Admiral.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30019,\n            \"and at last, on a hint from Miss Bertram, Mr. Rushworth discovered that the properest thing to be done was for him to walk down to the Parsonage directly, and call on Mr. Crawford, and inquire whether Wednesday would suit him or not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32479,\n            \"For the first seven miles Miss Bertram had very little real comfort: her prospect always ended in Mr. Crawford and her sister sitting side by side, full of conversation and merriment;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55328,\n            \"When this had lasted some time, the division of the party was completed by Tom Bertram and Mr. Yates walking off together to consult farther in the room now beginning to be called _ the _ _ Theatre _, and Miss Bertram\\u2019s resolving to go down to the Parsonage herself with the offer of Amelia to Miss Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95631,\n            \"but upon everybody\\u2019s assuring her that nothing could be so easy, that it was the easiest game on the cards, and Henry Crawford\\u2019s stepping forward with a most earnest request to be allowed to sit between her ladyship and Miss Price, and teach them both, it was so settled;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134808,\n            \"\\u201cLet me have the pleasure of finishing that speech to your ladyship,\\u201dsaid he.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135720,\n            \"\\u201cYou have a great turn for acting, I am sure, Mr. Crawford,\\u201dsaid her ladyship soon afterwards;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135744,\n            \"\\u201cand I will tell you what, I think you will have a theatre, some time or other, at your house in Norfolk.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135771,\n            \"I mean when you are settled there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135783,\n            \"I think you will fit up a theatre at your house in Norfolk.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182659,\n            \"and, having reason to think that one interview with Miss Crawford had taken place, from which Edmund derived only increased distress, had been as anxious on that account as on others to get him out of town, and had engaged him in taking Fanny home to her aunt, with a view to his relief and benefit, no less than theirs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183249,\n            \"and regarding it as what was meant to be the last, last interview of friendship, and investing her with all the feelings of shame and wretchedness which Crawford\\u2019s sister ought to have known, he had gone to her in such a state of mind, so softened, so devoted, as made it for a few moments impossible to Fanny\\u2019s fears that it should be the last.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 15]\": [\n        [\n            26511,\n            \"and in Dr. Grant\\u2019s meadow she immediately saw the group \\u2014 Edmund and Miss Crawford both on horse-back, riding side by side, Dr. and Mrs. Grant, and Mr. Crawford, with two or three grooms, standing about and looking on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40937,\n            \"After another pause, he went on \\u2014 \\u201cPray, Miss Price, are you such a great admirer of this Mr. Crawford as some people are?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45049,\n            \"but I wish you a better fate, Miss Price, than to be the wife of a man whose amiableness depends upon his own sermons;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45145,\n            \"and Miss Crawford had only time to say, in a pleasant manner, \\u201cI fancy Miss Price has been more used to deserve praise than to hear it \\u201d;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130233,\n            \"Sir Thomas wants me, not Miss Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162386,\n            \"The conclusion of the two gentlemen\\u2019s civilities was an offer of Mr. Price\\u2019s to take Mr. Crawford into the dockyard, which Mr. Crawford, desirous of accepting as a favour what was intended as such, though he had seen the dockyard again and again, and hoping to be so much the longer with Fanny, was very gratefully disposed to avail himself of, if the Miss Prices were not afraid of the fatigue;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 16]\": [\n        [\n            16341,\n            \"\\u201d Dr. Grant laughingly congratulated Miss Crawford on feeling no disinclination to the state herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44825,\n            \"and as he must, either in the navy or army, have had a great many more people under his command than he has now, I think more would have been made unhappy by him as a sailor or soldier than as a clergyman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44872,\n            \"Besides, I cannot but suppose that whatever there may be to wish otherwise in Dr. Grant would have been in a greater danger of becoming worse in a more active and worldly profession, where he would have had less time and obligation \\u2014 where he might have escaped that knowledge of himself, the _ frequency _, at least, of that knowledge which it is impossible he should escape as he is now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45012,\n            \"and I have no doubt that he oftener endeavours to restrain himself than he would if he had been anything but a clergyman.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 17]\": [\n        [\n            42864,\n            \"It was much pleasanter to think of Henry Crawford than of their father;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44565,\n            \"And though Dr. Grant is most kind and obliging to me, and though he is really a gentleman, and, I dare say, a good scholar and clever, and often preaches good sermons, and is very respectable, _ I _ see him to be an indolent, selfish _ bon _ _ vivant _, who must have his palate consulted in everything;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79149,\n            \"I wonder what she thinks of my father!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79158,\n            \"She must admire him as a fine-looking man, with most gentlemanlike, dignified, consistent manners;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94699,\n            \"and Crawford could mount him without the slightest inconvenience to himself, and with only some scruples to obviate in Sir Thomas, who knew better than his nephew the value of such a loan, and some alarms to reason away in Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94976,\n            \"The return of Henry Crawford, and the arrival of William Price, had much to do with it, but much was still owing to Sir Thomas\\u2019 s more than toleration of the neighbourly attempts at the Parsonage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95048,\n            \"and though infinitely above scheming or contriving for any the most advantageous matrimonial establishment that could be among the apparent possibilities of any one most dear to him, and disdaining even as a littleness the being quick-sighted on such points, he could not avoid perceiving, in a grand and careless way, that Mr. Crawford was somewhat distinguishing his niece \\u2014 nor perhaps refrain (though unconsciously) from giving a more willing assent to invitations on that account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98422,\n            \"As yet Sir Thomas had seen nothing to remark in Mr. Crawford\\u2019s behaviour;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99284,\n            \"\\u201cI repeat again,\\u201dadded Sir Thomas, \\u201cthat Thornton Lacey is the only house in the neighbourhood in which I should _ not _ be happy to wait on Mr. Crawford as occupier.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99364,\n            \"\\u201d Whatever effect Sir Thomas\\u2019 s little harangue might really produce on Mr. Crawford, it raised some awkward sensations in two of the others, two of his most attentive listeners \\u2014 Miss Crawford and Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99710,\n            \"himself, in the meanwhile, observed by Sir Thomas, who was standing in chat with Dr. Grant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111128,\n            \"Miss Crawford saw much of Sir Thomas\\u2019 s thoughts as he stood, and having, in spite of all his wrongs towards her, a general prevailing desire of recommending herself to him, took an opportunity of stepping aside to say something agreeable of Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125996,\n            \"\\u201cAm I to understand,\\u201dsaid Sir Thomas, after a few moments\\u2019 silence, \\u201cthat you mean to _ refuse _ Mr. Crawford?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126058,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI \\u2014 I cannot like him, sir, well enough to marry him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126171,\n            \"His sister, moreover, is your intimate friend, and he has been doing _ that _ for your brother, which I should suppose would have been almost sufficient recommendation to you, had there been no other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126212,\n            \"It is very uncertain when my interest might have got William on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126277,\n            \"\\u201cYou must have been aware,\\u201dcontinued Sir Thomas presently, \\u201cyou must have been some time aware of a particularity in Mr. Crawford\\u2019s manners to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126593,\n            \"\\u201cIndependently of the interest which Mr. Crawford\\u2019s _ choice _ seemed to justify\\u201dsaid Sir Thomas, beginning again, and very composedly, \\u201chis wishing to marry at all so early is recommendatory to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126864,\n            \"and getting up and walking about the room with a frown, which Fanny could picture to herself, though she dared not lift up her eyes, he shortly afterwards, and in a voice of authority, said, \\u201cHave you any reason, child, to think ill of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s temper?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126964,\n            \"Her ill opinion of him was founded chiefly on observations, which, for her cousins\\u2019 sake, she could scarcely dare mention to their father.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127533,\n            \"and let me tell you, Fanny, that you may live eighteen years longer in the world without being addressed by a man of half Mr. Crawford\\u2019s estate, or a tenth part of his merits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127574,\n            \"Gladly would I have bestowed either of my own daughters on him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127592,\n            \"but had Mr. Crawford sought Julia\\u2019s hand, I should have given it to him with superior and more heartfelt satisfaction than I gave Maria\\u2019s to Mr. Rushworth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128088,\n            \"If the gentleman would but persevere, if he had but love enough to persevere, Sir Thomas began to have hopes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128557,\n            \"There was comfort, too, in his words, as well as his manner, for he began with, \\u201cMr. Crawford is gone: he has just left me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128599,\n            \"I do not want to add to anything you may now be feeling, by an account of what he has felt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128622,\n            \"Suffice it, that he has behaved in the most gentlemanlike and generous manner, and has confirmed me in a most favourable opinion of his understanding, heart, and temper.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128655,\n            \"Upon my representation of what you were suffering, he immediately, and with the greatest delicacy, ceased to urge to see you for the present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128696,\n            \"\\u201cOf course,\\u201dcontinued her uncle, \\u201cit cannot be supposed but that he should request to speak with you alone, be it only for five minutes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132737,\n            \"a measure which he would still have avoided, if possible, but which became necessary from the totally opposite feelings of Mr. Crawford as to any secrecy of proceeding.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134176,\n            \"His surprise was not so great as his father\\u2019s at her refusing Crawford, because, so far from supposing her to consider him with anything like a preference, he had always believed it to be rather the reverse, and could imagine her to be taken perfectly unprepared, but Sir Thomas could not regard the connexion as more desirable than he did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134420,\n            \"Crawford called the next day, and on the score of Edmund\\u2019s return, Sir Thomas felt himself more than licensed to ask him to stay dinner;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 18]\": [\n        [\n            24599,\n            \"I dare say Mr. Crawford would take my two nieces and me in his barouche, and Edmund can go on horseback, you know, sister, and Fanny will stay at home with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28113,\n            \"Between ten and eleven Edmund and Julia walked into the drawing-room, fresh with the evening air, glowing and cheerful, the very reverse of what they found in the three ladies sitting there, for Maria would scarcely raise her eyes from her book, and Lady Bertram was half-asleep;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30877,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBesides,\\u201dsaid Maria, \\u201cI know that Mr. Crawford depends upon taking us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31000,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat would not be a very handsome reason for using Mr. Crawford\\u2019s,\\u201dsaid Maria;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35322,\n            \"\\u201d cried Julia, and running to where he stood with Miss Crawford and Fanny: \\u201cMy dear Edmund, if you were but in orders now, you might perform the ceremony directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35375,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Crawford\\u2019s countenance, as Julia spoke, might have amused a disinterested observer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35409,\n            \"\\u201cHow distressed she will be at what she said just now,\\u201dpassed across her mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40272,\n            \"I thought Maria and Mr. Crawford were with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40608,\n            \"\\u201d And she immediately scrambled across the fence, and walked away, not attending to Fanny\\u2019s last question of whether she had seen anything of Miss Crawford and Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40967,\n            \"For my part, I can see nothing in him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41009,\n            \"I should not wonder if he is not more than five foot eight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41023,\n            \"I think he is an ill-looking fellow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46036,\n            \"He went for a fortnight \\u2014 a fortnight of such dullness to the Miss Bertrams as ought to have put them both on their guard, and made even Julia admit, in her jealousy of her sister, the absolute necessity of distrusting his attentions, and wishing him not to return;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46330,\n            \"Julia might be justified in so doing by the hints of Mrs. Grant, inclined to credit what she wished, and Maria by the hints of Mr. Crawford himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46794,\n            \"Crawford has too much sense to stay here if he found himself in any danger from Maria;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47349,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Bertram did indeed look happy, her eyes were sparkling with pleasure, and she was speaking with great animation, for Julia and her partner, Mr. Crawford, were close to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47539,\n            \"Miss Julia and Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47585,\n            \"Four thousand a year is a pretty estate, and he seems a very genteel, steady young man, so I hope Miss Julia will be very happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53877,\n            \"\\u201cI must entreat Miss _ Julia _ Bertram,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cnot to engage in the part of Agatha, or it will be the ruin of all my solemnity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53927,\n            \"\\u201cI could not stand your countenance dressed up in woe and paleness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54035,\n            \"and before Julia could command herself enough to speak, her brother gave his weight against her too, by saying, \\u201cOh yes!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54073,\n            \"Though Julia fancies she prefers tragedy, I would not trust her in it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54563,\n            \"I consider Amelia is the most difficult character in the whole piece.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54638,\n            \"You _ will _ undertake it, I hope?\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 19]\": [\n        [\n            162004,\n            \"\\u201d And the consequence was, that Fanny, strange as it was \\u2014 strange, awkward, and distressing \\u2014 found herself and Susan, within ten minutes, walking towards the High Street with Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168477,\n            \"If Mr. Crawford remembered her message to her cousin, she thought it very likely, most likely, that he would write to her at all events;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 9]\": [\n        [\n            8591,\n            \"The time was now come when Sir Thomas expected his sister-in-law to claim her share in their niece, the change in Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s situation, and the improvement in Fanny\\u2019s age, seeming not merely to do away any former objection to their living together, but even to give it the most decided eligibility;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9184,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, Fanny, and if the plan were not unpleasant to you, I should call it an excellent one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11363,\n            \"and her spontaneous, untaught felicity on the discovery, conveyed some consolation to Edmund for his disappointment in what he had expected to be so essentially serviceable to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13277,\n            \"When he returned, to understand how Fanny was situated, and perceived its ill effects, there seemed with him but one thing to be done;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13305,\n            \"and that \\u201cFanny must have a horse\\u201dwas the resolute declaration with which he opposed whatever could be urged by the supineness of his mother, or the economy of his aunt, to make it appear unimportant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13494,\n            \"\\u201cFanny must have a horse,\\u201dwas Edmund\\u2019s only reply.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13635,\n            \"and at length determined on a method of proceeding which would obviate the risk of his father\\u2019s thinking he had done too much, and at the same time procure for Fanny the immediate means of exercise, which he could not bear she should be without.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13914,\n            \"As the horse continued in name, as well as fact, the property of Edmund, Mrs. Norris could tolerate its being for Fanny\\u2019s use;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14824,\n            \"He could allow his sister to be the best judge of her own happiness, but he was not pleased that her happiness should centre in a large income;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21832,\n            \"Whenever I do see it, you will tell me how it has been altered.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23144,\n            \"Now, Mr. Bertram, if you write to your brother, I entreat you to tell him that my harp is come: he heard so much of my misery about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23477,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMiss Price has a brother at sea,\\u201dsaid Edmund, \\u201cwhose excellence as a correspondent makes her think you too severe upon us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23524,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny would rather have had Edmund tell the story, but his determined silence obliged her to relate her brother\\u2019s situation: her voice was animated in speaking of his profession, and the foreign stations he had been on;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24599,\n            \"I dare say Mr. Crawford would take my two nieces and me in his barouche, and Edmund can go on horseback, you know, sister, and Fanny will stay at home with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25373,\n            \"though at this period, and on this subject, there began now to be some danger of dissimilarity, for he was in a line of admiration of Miss Crawford, which might lead him where Fanny could not follow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25846,\n            \"Fanny could not wonder that Edmund was at the Parsonage every morning;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25881,\n            \"neither could she wonder that, when the evening stroll was over, and the two families parted again, he should think it right to attend Mrs. Grant and her sister to their home, while Mr. Crawford was devoted to the ladies of the Park;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25940,\n            \"and if Edmund were not there to mix the wine and water for her, would rather go without it than not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25963,\n            \"She was a little surprised that he could spend so many hours with Miss Crawford, and not see more of the sort of fault which he had already observed, and of which _ she _ was almost always reminded by a something of the same nature whenever she was in her company;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26023,\n            \"Edmund was fond of speaking to her of Miss Crawford, but he seemed to think it enough that the Admiral had since been spared;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26049,\n            \"and she scrupled to point out her own remarks to him, lest it should appear like ill-nature.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26070,\n            \"The first actual pain which Miss Crawford occasioned her was the consequence of an inclination to learn to ride, which the former caught, soon after her being settled at Mansfield, from the example of the young ladies at the Park, and which, when Edmund\\u2019s acquaintance with her increased, led to his encouraging the wish, and the offer of his own quiet mare for the purpose of her first attempts, as the best fitted for a beginner that either stable could furnish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26162,\n            \"No pain, no injury, however, was designed by him to his cousin in this offer: _ she _ was not to lose a day\\u2019s exercise by it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26217,\n            \"and Fanny, on its being first proposed, so far from feeling slighted, was almost over-powered with gratitude that he should be asking her leave for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26267,\n            \"Edmund, who had taken down the mare and presided at the whole, returned with it in excellent time, before either Fanny or the steady old coachman, who always attended her when she rode without her cousins, were ready to set forward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26411,\n            \"Fanny was ready and waiting, and Mrs. Norris was beginning to scold her for not being gone, and still no horse was announced, no Edmund appeared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27059,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny\\u2019s answer was extremely civil, and Edmund added his conviction that she could be in no hurry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27574,\n            \"\\u201d When they parted at night Edmund asked Fanny whether she meant to ride the next day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27627,\n            \"\\u201cbut whenever you are next inclined to stay at home, I think Miss Crawford would be glad to have her a longer time \\u2014 for a whole morning, in short.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27784,\n            \"\\u201d Edmund looked pleased, which must be Fanny\\u2019s comfort, and the ride to Mansfield Common took place the next morning: the party included all the young people but herself, and was much enjoyed at the time, and doubly enjoyed again in the evening discussion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28241,\n            \"but when the first pause came, Edmund, looking around, said, \\u201cBut where is Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28520,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cFanny,\\u201dsaid Edmund, after looking at her attentively, \\u201cI am sure you have the headache.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28661,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, indeed, Edmund,\\u201dadded her ladyship, who had been thoroughly awakened by Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s sharp reprimand to Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29074,\n            \"\\u201d Edmund got up and walked about the room, saying, \\u201cAnd could nobody be employed on such an errand but Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29306,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI wish Fanny had half your strength, ma\\u2019am.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31175,\n            \"\\u201cmy dear Edmund, there is no idea of her going with us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31208,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou can have no reason, I imagine, madam,\\u201dsaid he, addressing his mother, \\u201cfor wishing Fanny _ not _ to be of the party, but as it relates to yourself, to your own comfort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31700,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt seems very odd,\\u201dsaid Maria, \\u201cthat you should be staying at home instead of Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31723,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sure she ought to be very much obliged to you,\\u201dadded Julia, hastily leaving the room as she spoke, from a consciousness that she ought to offer to stay at home herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31764,\n            \"\\u201cFanny will feel quite as grateful as the occasion requires,\\u201dwas Edmund\\u2019s only reply, and the subject dropt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31811,\n            \"She felt Edmund\\u2019s kindness with all, and more than all, the sensibility which he, unsuspicious of her fond attachment, could be aware of;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31841,\n            \"but that he should forego any enjoyment on her account gave her pain, and her own satisfaction in seeing Sotherton would be nothing without him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32292,\n            \"and, in observing the appearance of the country, the bearings of the roads, the difference of soil, the state of the harvest, the cottages, the cattle, the children, she found entertainment that could only have been heightened by having Edmund to speak to of what she felt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32348,\n            \"That was the only point of resemblance between her and the lady who sat by her: in everything but a value for Edmund, Miss Crawford was very unlike her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34347,\n            \"and Edmund, Fanny, and Miss Crawford remained in a cluster together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34492,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201c_ That _ is hardly Fanny\\u2019s idea of a family assembling,\\u201dsaid Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34751,\n            \"Fanny coloured and looked at Edmund, but felt too angry for speech;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35322,\n            \"\\u201d cried Julia, and running to where he stood with Miss Crawford and Fanny: \\u201cMy dear Edmund, if you were but in orders now, you might perform the ceremony directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37641,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy dear Fanny,\\u201dcried Edmund, immediately drawing her arm within his, \\u201chow thoughtless I have been!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37708,\n            \"\\u201d She took it, however, as she spoke, and the gratification of having her do so, of feeling such a connexion for the first time, made him a little forgetful of Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38173,\n            \"\\u201cI am afraid you are very tired, Fanny,\\u201dsaid Edmund, observing her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38718,\n            \"Edmund urged her remaining where she was with an earnestness which she could not resist, and she was left on the bench to think with pleasure of her cousin\\u2019s care, but with great regret that she was not stronger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38782,\n            \"CHAPTER X A quarter of an hour, twenty minutes, passed away, and Fanny was still thinking of Edmund, Miss Crawford, and herself, without interruption from any one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40608,\n            \"\\u201d And she immediately scrambled across the fence, and walked away, not attending to Fanny\\u2019s last question of whether she had seen anything of Miss Crawford and Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41513,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s best consolation was in being assured that Edmund had wished for her very much, and that he should certainly have come back for her, had she not been tired already;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43251,\n            \"but after tea, as Miss Crawford was standing at an open window with Edmund and Fanny looking out on a twilight scene, while the Miss Bertrams, Mr. Rushworth, and Henry Crawford were all busy with candles at the pianoforte, she suddenly revived it by turning round towards the group, and saying, \\u201cHow happy Mr. Rushworth looks!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45304,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny agreed to it, and had the pleasure of seeing him continue at the window with her, in spite of the expected glee;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47395,\n            \"How she had looked before, Fanny could not recollect, for she had been dancing with Edmund herself, and had not thought about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50208,\n            \"Tom, returning from them into the drawing-room, where Edmund was standing thoughtfully by the fire, while Lady Bertram was on the sofa at a little distance, and Fanny close beside her arranging her work, thus began as he entered \\u2014 \\u201cSuch a horribly vile billiard-table as ours is not to be met with, I believe, above ground.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51671,\n            \"Fanny, who had heard it all, and borne Edmund company in every feeling throughout the whole, now ventured to say, in her anxiety to suggest some comfort, \\u201cPerhaps they may not be able to find any play to suit them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51731,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have no hope there, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52055,\n            \"Edmund had little to hope, but he was still urging the subject when Henry Crawford entered the room, fresh from the Parsonage, calling out, \\u201cNo want of hands in our theatre, Miss Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52364,\n            \"CHAPTER XIV Fanny seemed nearer being right than Edmund had supposed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55950,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny\\u2019s eyes followed Edmund, and her heart beat for him as she heard this speech, and saw his look, and felt what his sensations must be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56170,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI should not have thought it the sort of play to be so easily filled up, with _ us _,\\u201dreplied Edmund, turning away to the fire, where sat his mother, aunt, and Fanny, and seating himself with a look of great vexation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56840,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am convinced, madam,\\u201dsaid Edmund, preventing Fanny, \\u201cthat Sir Thomas would not like it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57932,\n            \"and I do sincerely give you joy, madam, as well as Mrs. Norris, and everybody else who is in the same predicament,\\u201dglancing half fearfully, half slyly, beyond Fanny to Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58798,\n            \"for the habit of employing her in that way was not yet overcome, in spite of all that Edmund could do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59100,\n            \"You have only two scenes, and as I shall be Cottager, I\\u2019ll put you in and push you about, and you will do it very well, I\\u2019ll answer for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59266,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou must excuse me, indeed you must excuse me,\\u201dcried Fanny, growing more and more red from excessive agitation, and looking distressfully at Edmund, who was kindly observing her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61559,\n            \"To this nest of comforts Fanny now walked down to try its influence on an agitated, doubting spirit, to see if by looking at Edmund\\u2019s profile she could catch any of his counsel, or by giving air to her geraniums she might inhale a breeze of mental strength herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61911,\n            \"\\u201cCan I speak with you, Fanny, for a few minutes?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62178,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny could not answer him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62765,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cGive me your approbation, then, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63778,\n            \"Perhaps you may persuade _ her _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67230,\n            \"Fanny did not share her aunt\\u2019s composure: she thought of the morrow a great deal, for if the three acts were rehearsed, Edmund and Miss Crawford would then be acting together for the first time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68236,\n            \"\\u201d She began, and Fanny joined in with all the modest feeling which the idea of representing Edmund was so strongly calculated to inspire;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68375,\n            \"He too had his book, and was seeking Fanny, to ask her to rehearse with him, and help him to prepare for the evening, without knowing Miss Crawford to be in the house;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68490,\n            \"Edmund proposed, urged, entreated it, till the lady, not very unwilling at first, could refuse no longer, and Fanny was wanted only to prompt and observe them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69181,\n            \"even Edmund said, \\u201cDo, Fanny, if it is not _ very _ disagreeable to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70130,\n            \"She was nearly fainting: all her former habitual dread of her uncle was returning, and with it compassion for him and for almost every one of the party on the development before him, with solicitude on Edmund\\u2019s account indescribable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70826,\n            \"He inquired next after her family, especially William: and his kindness altogether was such as made her reproach herself for loving him so little, and thinking his return a misfortune;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72130,\n            \"The first day I went over Mansfield Wood, and Edmund took the copses beyond Easton, and we brought home six brace between us, and might each have killed six times as many, but we respect your pheasants, sir, I assure you, as much as you could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75008,\n            \"She had a great deal to insinuate in her own praise as to _ general _ attention to the interest and comfort of his family, much exertion and many sacrifices to glance at in the form of hurried walks and sudden removals from her own fireside, and many excellent hints of distrust and economy to Lady Bertram and Edmund to detail, whereby a most considerable saving had always arisen, and more than one bad servant been detected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78013,\n            \"\\u201cBut they,\\u201dhe observed to Fanny, \\u201chave a claim.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82415,\n            \"And besides, I want to play something more to you \\u2014 a very pretty piece \\u2014 and your cousin Edmund\\u2019s prime favourite.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82441,\n            \"You must stay and hear your cousin\\u2019s favourite.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82459,\n            \"and though she had not waited for that sentence to be thinking of Edmund, such a memento made her particularly awake to his idea, and she fancied him sitting in that room again and again, perhaps in the very spot where she sat now, listening with constant delight to the favourite air, played, as it appeared to her, with superior tone and expression;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85052,\n            \"\\u201d said Edmund, with a look which, to Fanny\\u2019s eye, had a great deal of serious meaning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85550,\n            \"\\u201d A look of consciousness as he spoke, and what seemed a consciousness of manner on Miss Crawford\\u2019s side as she made some laughing answer, was sorrowfull food for Fanny\\u2019s observation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85695,\n            \"and Edmund began at the same time to recollect that his mother had been inquiring for her, and that he had walked down to the Parsonage on purpose to bring her back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85735,\n            \"and without in the least expecting Edmund\\u2019s attendance, she would have hastened away alone;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85777,\n            \"Dr. Grant was in the vestibule, and as they stopt to speak to him she found, from Edmund\\u2019s manner, that he _ did _ mean to go with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85913,\n            \"and while stammering out her great obligation, and her \\u201cbut she did not suppose it would be in her power,\\u201dwas looking at Edmund for his opinion and help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85947,\n            \"But Edmund, delighted with her having such an happiness offered, and ascertaining with half a look, and half a sentence, that she had no objection but on her aunt\\u2019s account, could not imagine that his mother would make any difficulty of sparing her, and therefore gave his decided open advice that the invitation should be accepted;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86012,\n            \"and though Fanny would not venture, even on his encouragement, to such a flight of audacious independence, it was soon settled, that if nothing were heard to the contrary, Mrs. Grant might expect her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86221,\n            \"and, except in the immediate discussion of this engagement, which Edmund spoke of with the warmest satisfaction, as so particularly desirable for her in the intimacy which he saw with so much pleasure established, it was a silent walk;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86349,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf you put such a question to her,\\u201dcried Edmund, preventing his cousin\\u2019s speaking, \\u201cFanny will immediately say No;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86378,\n            \"but I am sure, my dear mother, she would like to go;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86393,\n            \"and I can see no reason why she should not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86576,\n            \"and I think he will consider it a right thing by Mrs. Grant, as well as by Fanny, that being the _ first _ invitation it should be accepted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86947,\n            \"\\u201cEdmund wants her to go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87260,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cVery well, then, Fanny may go, Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87327,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThank you, I am _ so _ glad,\\u201dwas Fanny\\u2019s instinctive reply;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87554,\n            \"\\u201cUpon my word, Fanny, you are in high luck to meet with such attention and indulgence!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88357,\n            \"and when Sir Thomas soon afterwards, just opening the door, said, \\u201cFanny, at what time would you have the carriage come round?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88469,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, sir,\\u201dwas Fanny\\u2019s humble answer, given with the feelings almost of a criminal towards Mrs. Norris;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88678,\n            \"\\u201cNow I must look at you, Fanny,\\u201dsaid Edmund, with the kind smile of an affectionate brother, \\u201cand tell you how I like you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89094,\n            \"and even to _ her _ there might be some advantage in his presence, since every addition to the party must rather forward her favourite indulgence of being suffered to sit silent and unattended to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89139,\n            \"for though she must submit, as her own propriety of mind directed, in spite of her aunt Norris\\u2019 s opinion, to being the principal lady in company, and to all the little distinctions consequent thereon, she found, while they were at table, such a happy flow of conversation prevailing, in which she was not required to take any part \\u2014 there was so much to be said between the brother and sister about Bath, so much between the two young men about hunting, so much of politics between Mr. Crawford and Dr. Grant, and of everything and all together between Mr. Crawford and Mrs. Grant, as to leave her the fairest prospect of having only to listen in quiet, and of passing a very agreeable day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89284,\n            \"She could not compliment the newly arrived gentleman, however, with any appearance of interest, in a scheme for extending his stay at Mansfield, and sending for his hunters from Norfolk, which, suggested by Dr. Grant, advised by Edmund, and warmly urged by the two sisters, was soon in possession of his mind, and which he seemed to want to be encouraged even by her to resolve on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89475,\n            \"She heard them spoken of by him only in a general way, till they were all re-assembled in the drawing-room, when Edmund, being engaged apart in some matter of business with Dr. Grant, which seemed entirely to engross them, and Mrs. Grant occupied at the tea-table, he began talking of them with more particularity to his other sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90027,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWe were unlucky, Miss Price,\\u201dhe continued, in a lower tone, to avoid the possibility of being heard by Edmund, and not at all aware of her feelings, \\u201cwe certainly were very unlucky.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97733,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd Fanny had much rather it were William\\u2019s,\\u201dsaid Edmund, smiling at her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98774,\n            \"She said little, assented only here and there, and betrayed no inclination either of appropriating any part of the compliment to herself, or of strengthening his views in favour of Northamptonshire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100803,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s last feeling in the visit was disappointment: for the shawl which Edmund was quietly taking from the servant to bring and put round her shoulders was seized by Mr. Crawford\\u2019s quicker hand, and she was obliged to be indebted to his more prominent attention.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101371,\n            \"Edmund, William, and Fanny did, in their different ways, look and speak as much grateful pleasure in the promised ball as Sir Thomas could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104519,\n            \"\\u201cFanny,\\u201dsaid he directly, leaving his seat and his pen, and meeting her with something in his hand, \\u201cI beg your pardon for being here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104667,\n            \"I hope you will like the chain itself, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104725,\n            \"\\u201d And so saying, he was hurrying away, before Fanny, overpowered by a thousand feelings of pain and pleasure, could attempt to speak;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104818,\n            \"Your goodness in thinking of me in such a way is beyond \\u2014\\u201d\\u201cIf that is all you have to say, Fanny\\u201dsmiling and turning away again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105173,\n            \"for Edmund was so struck with the circumstance, so delighted with what Miss Crawford had done, so gratified by such a coincidence of conduct between them, that Fanny could not but admit the superior power of one pleasure over his own mind, though it might have its drawback.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106529,\n            \"and opened with more kindness to Fanny than such self-willed, unmanageable days often volunteer, for soon after breakfast a very friendly note was brought from Mr. Crawford to William, stating that as he found himself obliged to go to London on the morrow for a few days, he could not help trying to procure a companion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106855,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s spirits lived on it half the morning, deriving some accession of pleasure from its writer being himself to go away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107535,\n            \"\\u201cYou may guess my errand there, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107545,\n            \"\\u201d And he looked so conscious, that Fanny could think but of one errand, which turned her too sick for speech.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107569,\n            \"\\u201cI wished to engage Miss Crawford for the two first dances,\\u201dwas the explanation that followed, and brought Fanny to life again, enabling her, as she found she was expected to speak, to utter something like an inquiry as to the result.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107742,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny struggled for speech, and said, \\u201cI am very sorry that anything has occurred to distress you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108027,\n            \"for sometimes, Fanny, I own to you, it does appear more than manner: it appears as if the mind itself was tainted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108054,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny imagined this to be an appeal to her judgment, and therefore, after a moment\\u2019s consideration, said, \\u201cIf you only want me as a listener, cousin, I will be as useful as I can;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108418,\n            \"you can bear me witness, Fanny, that I have never been blinded.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108501,\n            \"He had said enough to give Fanny some happier feelings than she had lately known, and with a brighter look, she answered, \\u201cYes, cousin, I am convinced that _ you _ would be incapable of anything else, though perhaps some might not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108594,\n            \"For Fanny\\u2019s present comfort it was concluded, perhaps, at the happiest moment: had he been able to talk another five minutes, there is no saying that he might not have talked away all Miss Crawford\\u2019s faults and his own despondence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109459,\n            \"you must keep two dances for me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109601,\n            \"It was but to think of her conversation with Edmund, and what was the restlessness of Mrs. Norris?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109677,\n            \"Fanny felt that there must be a struggle in Edmund\\u2019s cheerfulness, but it was delightful to see the effort so successfully made.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109805,\n            \"This was a hard duty, and she was never summoned to it without looking at William, as he walked about at his ease in the background of the scene, and longing to be with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109888,\n            \"and, drawing back from the toils of civility, would have been again most happy, could she have kept her eyes from wandering between Edmund and Mary Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110206,\n            \"When the company were moving into the ballroom, she found herself for the first time near Miss Crawford, whose eyes and smiles were immediately and more unequivocally directed as her brother\\u2019s had been, and who was beginning to speak on the subject, when Fanny, anxious to get the story over, hastened to give the explanation of the second necklace: the real chain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110552,\n            \"Whenever she had thought of the minutiae of the evening, it had been as a matter of course that Edmund would begin with Miss Crawford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112011,\n            \"But with _ you _, Fanny, there may be peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114756,\n            \"To Fanny\\u2019s mind, Edmund\\u2019s absence was really, in its cause and its tendency, a relief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115396,\n            \"But at last Lady Bertram left the room, and then almost immediately Miss Crawford thus began, with a voice as well regulated as she could \\u2014 \\u201cAnd how do _ you _ like your cousin Edmund\\u2019s staying away so long?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115460,\n            \"You must miss him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115465,\n            \"Does his staying longer surprise you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119540,\n            \"Her cousin Edmund never forgets her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119551,\n            \"True, I believe he is, generally speaking, kind to her, and so is Sir Thomas in his way;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119592,\n            \"What can Sir Thomas and Edmund together do, what _ do _ they do for her happiness, comfort, honour, and dignity in the world, to what I _ shall _ do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133518,\n            \"\\u201cI will tell you what, Fanny,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cI am sure he fell in love with you at the ball;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133952,\n            \"After dinner, when he and his father were alone, he had Fanny\\u2019s history;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134457,\n            \"He staid of course, and Edmund had then ample opportunity for observing how he sped with Fanny, and what degree of immediate encouragement for him might be extracted from her manners;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134714,\n            \"\\u201cFanny has been reading to me, and only put the book down upon hearing you coming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134962,\n            \"To _ good _ reading, however, she had been long used: her uncle read well, her cousins all, Edmund very well, but in Mr. Crawford\\u2019s reading there was a variety of excellence beyond what she had ever met with.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135154,\n            \"Edmund watched the progress of her attention, and was amused and gratified by seeing how she gradually slackened in the needlework, which at the beginning seemed to occupy her totally: how it fell from her hand while she sat motionless over it, and at last, how the eyes which had appeared so studiously to avoid him throughout the day were turned and fixed on Crawford \\u2014 fixed on him for minutes, fixed on him, in short, till the attraction drew Crawford\\u2019s upon her, and the book was closed, and the charm was broken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135277,\n            \"but it had been enough to give Edmund encouragement for his friend, and as he cordially thanked him, he hoped to be expressing Fanny\\u2019s secret feelings too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135863,\n            \"\\u201d Edmund saw it all, and saw Fanny so determined _ not _ to see it, as to make it clear that the voice was enough to convey the full meaning of the protestation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136277,\n            \"questions, which being made, though with the vivacity of friendly interest and quick taste, without any touch of that spirit of banter or air of levity which Edmund knew to be most offensive to Fanny, he had true pleasure in satisfying;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137025,\n            \"and as Edmund perceived, by his drawing in a chair, and sitting down close by her, that it was to be a very thorough attack, that looks and undertones were to be well tried, he sank as quietly as possible into a corner, turned his back, and took up a newspaper, very sincerely wishing that dear little Fanny might be persuaded into explaining away that shake of the head to the satisfaction of her ardent lover;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137160,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny, meanwhile, vexed with herself for not having been as motionless as she was speechless, and grieved to the heart to see Edmund\\u2019s arrangements, was trying by everything in the power of her modest, gentle nature, to repulse Mr. Crawford, and avoid both his looks and inquiries;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138300,\n            \"But though the conference had seemed full long to him, and though on looking at Fanny he saw rather a flush of vexation, he inclined to hope that so much could not have been said and listened to without some profit to the speaker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138347,\n            \"CHAPTER XXXV Edmund had determined that it belonged entirely to Fanny to chuse whether her situation with regard to Crawford should be mentioned between them or not;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138547,\n            \"he wanted to know Fanny\\u2019s feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138626,\n            \"Fanny estranged from him, silent and reserved, was an unnatural state of things;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138722,\n            \"\\u201cI am come to walk with you, Fanny,\\u201dsaid he.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138780,\n            \"\\u201cBut, Fanny,\\u201dhe presently added, \\u201cin order to have a comfortable walk, something more is necessary than merely pacing this gravel together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138839,\n            \"Am I to hear of it from everybody but Fanny herself?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138851,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny, at once agitated and dejected, replied, \\u201cIf you hear of it from everybody, cousin, there can be nothing for me to tell.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139175,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAs far as you have gone, Fanny, I think you perfectly right.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139650,\n            \"I wish he had known you as well as I do, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139918,\n            \"You forget yourself: there is a decided difference in your tempers, I allow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140489,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAs a bystander,\\u201dsaid Fanny, \\u201cperhaps I saw more than you did;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140622,\n            \"And, Fanny, though I hope I do justice to my sisters\\u2019 good qualities, I think it very possible that they might, one or both, be more desirous of being admired by Crawford, and might shew that desire rather more unguardedly than was perfectly prudent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140737,\n            \"And I must say, that its being for you has raised him inconceivably in my opinion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140990,\n            \"I know he will make you happy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141052,\n            \"Well, though I may not be able to persuade you into different feelings, you will be persuaded into them, I trust.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141077,\n            \"I confess myself sincerely anxious that you may.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141099,\n            \"Next to your happiness, Fanny, his has the first claim on me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141114,\n            \"You are aware of my having no common interest in Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141192,\n            \"I knew she was very fond of you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141201,\n            \"but yet I was afraid of her not estimating your worth to her brother quite as it deserved, and of her regretting that he had not rather fixed on some woman of distinction or fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141551,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy dearest Fanny,\\u201dcried Edmund, pressing her arm closer to him, \\u201cdo not let the idea of her anger distress you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141638,\n            \"And I observed that she always spoke of you as \\u2018 Fanny,\\u2019which she was never used to do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142129,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy dear, dear Fanny, now I have the truth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142440,\n            \"Edmund saw weariness and distress in her face, and immediately resolved to forbear all farther discussion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142735,\n            \"But I am spoilt, Fanny, for common female society.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142834,\n            \"CHAPTER XXXVI Edmund now believed himself perfectly acquainted with all that Fanny could tell, or could leave to be conjectured of her sentiments, and he was satisfied.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142990,\n            \"Edmund\\u2019s account of Fanny\\u2019s disposition he could believe to be just;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143103,\n            \"The promised visit from \\u201cher friend,\\u201das Edmund called Miss Crawford, was a formidable threat to Fanny, and she lived in continual terror of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147248,\n            \"What chiefly surprised Edmund was, that Crawford\\u2019s sister, the friend and companion who had been so much to her, should not be more visibly regretted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147979,\n            \"So the uniform remained at Portsmouth, and Edmund conjectured that before Fanny had any chance of seeing it, all its own freshness and all the freshness of its wearer\\u2019s feelings must be worn away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148064,\n            \"So reasoned Edmund, till his father made him the confidant of a scheme which placed Fanny\\u2019s chance of seeing the second lieutenant of H.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149013,\n            \"and now by dint of long talking on the subject, explaining and dwelling on the duty of Fanny\\u2019s sometimes seeing her family, he did induce his wife to let her go;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149049,\n            \"obtaining it rather from submission, however, than conviction, for Lady Bertram was convinced of very little more than that Sir Thomas thought Fanny ought to go, and therefore that she must.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149085,\n            \"In the calmness of her own dressing-room, in the impartial flow of her own meditations, unbiassed by his bewildering statements, she could not acknowledge any necessity for Fanny\\u2019s ever going near a father and mother who had done without her so long, while she was so useful to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149741,\n            \"and for part of one of those days the young travellers were in a good deal of alarm on the subject of their journey, for when the mode of it came to be talked of, and Mrs. Norris found that all her anxiety to save her brother-in-law\\u2019s money was vain, and that in spite of her wishes and hints for a less expensive conveyance of Fanny, they were to travel post;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165059,\n            \"and considering he was not Edmund, Fanny could not but allow that he was sufficiently open to the charms of nature, and very well able to express his admiration.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169065,\n            \"CHAPTER XLIV Seven weeks of the two months were very nearly gone, when the one letter, the letter from Edmund, so long expected, was put into Fanny\\u2019s hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171195,\n            \"\\u2018 The loss of Mary I must consider as comprehending the loss of Crawford and Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171637,\n            \"Within a few days from the receipt of Edmund\\u2019s letter, Fanny had one from her aunt, beginning thus \\u2014 \\u201cMy Dear Fanny, \\u2014 I take up my pen to communicate some very alarming intelligence, which I make no doubt will give you much concern \\u201d.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172196,\n            \"they were receiving frequent accounts from Edmund, and these accounts were as regularly transmitted to Fanny, in the same diffuse style, and the same medley of trusts, hopes, and fears, all following and producing each other at haphazard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172948,\n            \"Lady Bertram could think nothing less, and Fanny shared her aunt\\u2019s security, till she received a few lines from Edmund, written purposely to give her a clearer idea of his brother\\u2019s situation, and acquaint her with the apprehensions which he and his father had imbibed from the physician with respect to some strong hectic symptoms, which seemed to seize the frame on the departure of the fever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173070,\n            \"A very few lines from Edmund shewed her the patient and the sickroom in a juster and stronger light than all Lady Bertram\\u2019s sheets of paper could do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173441,\n            \"A line occasionally added by Edmund to his mother\\u2019s letter was enough for Fanny\\u2019s information.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175771,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny\\u2019s disgust at the greater part of this letter, with her extreme reluctance to bring the writer of it and her cousin Edmund together, would have made her (as she felt) incapable of judging impartially whether the concluding offer might be accepted or not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175934,\n            \"She had thought better of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175962,\n            \"there was no occasion to determine whether she ought to keep Edmund and Mary asunder or not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179462,\n            \"The girls heard his entrance from above, and Fanny went down.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179529,\n            \"and she found herself pressed to his heart with only these words, just articulate, \\u201cMy Fanny, my only sister;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179860,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s last meal in her father\\u2019s house was in character with her first: she was dismissed from it as hospitably as she had been welcomed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179949,\n            \"Edmund\\u2019s deep sighs often reached Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180001,\n            \"Fanny watched him with never-failing solicitude, and sometimes catching his eye, revived an affectionate smile, which comforted her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180182,\n            \"But _ yours _ \\u2014 your regard was new compared with \\u2014 \\u2014 Fanny, think of _ me _!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180854,\n            \"Edmund was almost as welcome to his brother as Fanny to her aunt;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181151,\n            \"Edmund trying to bury his own feelings in exertions for the relief of his brother\\u2019s, and Fanny devoted to her aunt Bertram, returning to every former office with more than former zeal, and thinking she could never do enough for one who seemed so much to want her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182528,\n            \"She was mistaken, however, in supposing that Edmund gave his father no present pain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182659,\n            \"and, having reason to think that one interview with Miss Crawford had taken place, from which Edmund derived only increased distress, had been as anxious on that account as on others to get him out of town, and had engaged him in taking Fanny home to her aunt, with a view to his relief and benefit, no less than theirs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182985,\n            \"They reached Mansfield on Thursday, and it was not till Sunday evening that Edmund began to talk to her on the subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184481,\n            \"She spoke of it, Fanny, with a steadier voice than I can.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184523,\n            \"\\u2018 and what with honour, and the certainty of having shut himself out for ever from Fanny, I do not despair of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184555,\n            \"I do not think that even _ he _ could now hope to succeed with one of her stamp, and therefore I hope we may find no insuperable difficulty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184791,\n            \"\\u2019\\u201dAfter repeating this, Edmund was so much affected that Fanny, watching him with silent, but most tender concern, was almost sorry that the subject had been entered on at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185775,\n            \"Fanny, now at liberty to speak openly, felt more than justified in adding to his knowledge of her real character, by some hint of what share his brother\\u2019s state of health might be supposed to have in her wish for a complete reconciliation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186011,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s friendship was all that he had to cling to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186752,\n            \"After wandering about and sitting under trees with Fanny all the summer evenings, he had so well talked his mind into submission as to be very tolerably cheerful again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189714,\n            \"Scarcely had he done regretting Mary Crawford, and observing to Fanny how impossible it was that he should ever meet with such another woman, before it began to strike him whether a very different kind of woman might not do just as well, or a great deal better: whether Fanny herself were not growing as dear, as important to him in all her smiles and all her ways, as Mary Crawford had ever been;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189872,\n            \"I only entreat everybody to believe that exactly at the time when it was quite natural that it should be so, and not a week earlier, Edmund did cease to care about Miss Crawford, and became as anxious to marry Fanny as Fanny herself could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190187,\n            \"Even in the midst of his late infatuation, he had acknowledged Fanny\\u2019s mental superiority.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190505,\n            \"and the joyful consent which met Edmund\\u2019s application, the high sense of having realised a great acquisition in the promise of Fanny for a daughter, formed just such a contrast with his early opinion on the subject when the poor little girl\\u2019s coming had been first agitated, as time is for ever producing between the plans and decisions of mortals, for their own instruction, and their neighbours\\u2019 entertainment.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 10]\": [\n        [\n            114787,\n            \"She felt the want of his society every day, almost every hour, and was too much in want of it to derive anything but irritation from considering the object for which he went.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147329,\n            \"If she could have believed Mary\\u2019s future fate as unconnected with Mansfield as she was determined the brother\\u2019s should be, if she could have hoped her return thither to be as distant as she was much inclined to think his, she would have been light of heart indeed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175962,\n            \"there was no occasion to determine whether she ought to keep Edmund and Mary asunder or not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189594,\n            \"for Mary, though perfectly resolved against ever attaching herself to a younger brother again, was long in finding among the dashing representatives, or idle heir-apparents, who were at the command of her beauty, and her \\u00a320, 000, any one who could satisfy the better taste she had acquired at Mansfield, whose character and manners could authorise a hope of the domestic happiness she had there learned to estimate, or put Edmund Bertram sufficiently out of her head.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189683,\n            \"Edmund had greatly the advantage of her in this respect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189694,\n            \"He had not to wait and wish with vacant affections for an object worthy to succeed her in them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190505,\n            \"and the joyful consent which met Edmund\\u2019s application, the high sense of having realised a great acquisition in the promise of Fanny for a daughter, formed just such a contrast with his early opinion on the subject when the poor little girl\\u2019s coming had been first agitated, as time is for ever producing between the plans and decisions of mortals, for their own instruction, and their neighbours\\u2019 entertainment.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 11]\": [\n        [\n            5314,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut William will write to you, I dare say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7709,\n            \"and he told her such charming things of what William was to do, and be hereafter, in consequence of his profession, as made her gradually admit that the separation might have some use.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7972,\n            \"In return for such services she loved him better than anybody in the world except William: her heart was divided between the two.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23144,\n            \"Now, Mr. Bertram, if you write to your brother, I entreat you to tell him that my harp is come: he heard so much of my misery about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23179,\n            \"And you may say, if you please, that I shall prepare my most plaintive airs against his return, in compassion to his feelings, as I know his horse will lose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100736,\n            \"My dear Sir Thomas, we have settled it that the carriage should come back for you, and Edmund and William.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101371,\n            \"Edmund, William, and Fanny did, in their different ways, look and speak as much grateful pleasure in the promised ball as Sir Thomas could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102917,\n            \"and as Edmund and William were gone to Northampton, and she had reason to think Mr. Crawford likewise out, she walked down to the Parsonage without much fear of wanting an opportunity for private discussion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104594,\n            \"but I can now speak my business, which is merely to beg your acceptance of this little trifle \\u2014 a chain for William\\u2019s cross.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107056,\n            \"To dance without much observation or any extraordinary fatigue, to have strength and partners for about half the evening, to dance a little with Edmund, and not a great deal with Mr. Crawford, to see William enjoy himself, and be able to keep away from her aunt Norris, was the height of her ambition, and seemed to comprehend her greatest possibility of happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133901,\n            \"William\\u2019s promotion, with all its particulars, he was soon master of;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148622,\n            \"Afterwards, when familiarised with the visions of enjoyment so suddenly opened, she could speak more largely to William and Edmund of what she felt;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149824,\n            \"when she saw Sir Thomas actually give William notes for the purpose, she was struck with the idea of there being room for a third in the carriage, and suddenly seized with a strong inclination to go with them, to go and see her poor dear sister Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150223,\n            \"but he could not leave his father and mother just when everybody else of most importance to their comfort was leaving them;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 12]\": [\n        [\n            13521,\n            \"Lady Bertram did: she entirely agreed with her son as to the necessity of it, and as to its being considered necessary by his father;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13558,\n            \"she only wanted him to wait till Sir Thomas\\u2019 s return, and then Sir Thomas might settle it all himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13601,\n            \"Though Edmund was much more displeased with his aunt than with his mother, as evincing least regard for her niece, he could not help paying more attention to what she said;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47395,\n            \"How she had looked before, Fanny could not recollect, for she had been dancing with Edmund herself, and had not thought about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52140,\n            \"\\u201d Maria gave Edmund a glance, which meant, \\u201cWhat say you now?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55835,\n            \"but when he entered the drawing-room before dinner, the buzz of discussion was high between Tom, Maria, and Mr. Yates;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56121,\n            \"\\u201d said Edmund gravely, and looking at Maria.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56365,\n            \"but I must now, my dear Maria, tell _ you _, that I think it exceedingly unfit for private representation, and that I hope you will give it up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56399,\n            \"I cannot but suppose you _ will _ when you have read it carefully over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56436,\n            \"It will not be necessary to send you to your _ father\\u2019s _ judgment, I am convinced.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56469,\n            \"\\u201cI am perfectly acquainted with the play, I assure you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56509,\n            \"and _ I _ am not the _ only _ young woman you find who thinks it very fit for private representation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56629,\n            \"and with far more good-humour she answered, \\u201cI am much obliged to you, Edmund;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56649,\n            \"you mean very well, I am sure: but I still think you see things too strongly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56697,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo you imagine that I could have such an idea in my head?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56864,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere, my dear, do you hear what Edmund says?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59481,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo not urge her, madam,\\u201dsaid Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60157,\n            \"\\u201d While he spoke, Maria was looking apprehensively round at Edmund in full expectation that he must oppose such an enlargement of the plan as this: so contrary to all their first protestations;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60321,\n            \"and though Julia, who had scarcely opened her lips before, observed, in a sarcastic manner, and with a glance first at Maria and then at Edmund, that \\u201cthe Mansfield theatricals would enliven the whole neighbourhood exceedingly,\\u201dEdmund still held his peace, and shewed his feelings only by a determined gravity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60642,\n            \"and if she were applied to again among themselves with all the authoritative urgency that Tom and Maria were capable of, and Edmund perhaps away, what should she do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140539,\n            \"I am shocked whenever I think that Maria could be capable of it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140598,\n            \"I have heard before from some one of his being in love with Julia;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141154,\n            \"Edmund first began again \\u2014 \\u201cI was very much pleased by her manner of speaking of it yesterday, particularly pleased, because I had not depended upon her seeing everything in so just a light.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141192,\n            \"I knew she was very fond of you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141201,\n            \"but yet I was afraid of her not estimating your worth to her brother quite as it deserved, and of her regretting that he had not rather fixed on some woman of distinction or fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141238,\n            \"I was afraid of the bias of those worldly maxims, which she has been too much used to hear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141277,\n            \"She desires the connexion as warmly as your uncle or myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141297,\n            \"I should not have mentioned the subject, though very anxious to know her sentiments;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141313,\n            \"but I had not been in the room five minutes before she began introducing it with all that openness of heart, and sweet peculiarity of manner, that spirit and ingenuousness which are so much a part of herself.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 13]\": [\n        [\n            8591,\n            \"The time was now come when Sir Thomas expected his sister-in-law to claim her share in their niece, the change in Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s situation, and the improvement in Fanny\\u2019s age, seeming not merely to do away any former objection to their living together, but even to give it the most decided eligibility;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11905,\n            \"but, in Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s watchful attention, and in Edmund\\u2019s judgment, he had sufficient confidence to make him go without fears for their conduct.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12403,\n            \"and Lady Bertram was soon astonished to find how very well they did even without his father, how well Edmund could supply his place in carving, talking to the steward, writing to the attorney, settling with the servants, and equally saving her from all possible fatigue or exertion in every particular but that of directing her letters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12486,\n            \"though not before Mrs. Norris had been indulging in very dreadful fears, and trying to make Edmund participate them whenever she could get him alone;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14804,\n            \"but no representation of his aunt\\u2019s could induce him to find Mr. Rushworth a desirable companion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21732,\n            \"\\u2019\\u201dHe smiled as he answered, \\u201cI am afraid the avenue stands a bad chance, Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28614,\n            \"to be sure she did,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris: \\u201cwould you have her stay within such a fine day as this?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28661,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, indeed, Edmund,\\u201dadded her ladyship, who had been thoroughly awakened by Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s sharp reprimand to Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28718,\n            \"and very pleasant it was, I assure you, but very hot.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29099,\n            \"Upon my word, ma\\u2019am, it has been a very ill-managed business.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29306,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI wish Fanny had half your strength, ma\\u2019am.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29432,\n            \"Between ourselves, Edmund,\\u201dnodding significantly at his mother, \\u201cit was cutting the roses, and dawdling about in the flower-garden, that did the mischief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29614,\n            \"Vexed as Edmund was with his mother and aunt, he was still more angry with himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29892,\n            \"While she was gone Mr. Rushworth arrived, escorting his mother, who came to be civil and to shew her civility especially, in urging the execution of the plan for visiting Sotherton, which had been started a fortnight before, and which, in consequence of her subsequent absence from home, had since lain dormant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29953,\n            \"Mrs. Norris and her nieces were all well pleased with its revival, and an early day was named and agreed to, provided Mr. Crawford should be disengaged: the young ladies did not forget that stipulation, and though Mrs. Norris would willingly have answered for his being so, they would neither authorise the liberty nor run the risk;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30349,\n            \"and as for Edmund, as he is not here to speak for himself, I will answer for his being most happy to join the party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30677,\n            \"On his return to the breakfast-room, he found Mrs. Norris trying to make up her mind as to whether Miss Crawford\\u2019s being of the party were desirable or not, or whether her brother\\u2019s barouche would not be full without her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30911,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd, my dear Edmund,\\u201dadded Mrs. Norris, \\u201ctaking out _ two _ carriages when _ one _ will do, would be trouble for nothing;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31208,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou can have no reason, I imagine, madam,\\u201dsaid he, addressing his mother, \\u201cfor wishing Fanny _ not _ to be of the party, but as it relates to yourself, to your own comfort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31524,\n            \"but her opposition to Edmund _ now _, arose more from partiality for her own scheme, because it _ was _ her own, than from anything else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31575,\n            \"When Edmund, therefore, told her in reply, as he did when she would give him the hearing, that she need not distress herself on Mrs. Rushworth\\u2019s account, because he had taken the opportunity, as he walked with her through the hall, of mentioning Miss Price as one who would probably be of the party, and had directly received a very sufficient invitation for his cousin, Mrs. Norris was too much vexed to submit with a very good grace, and would only say, \\u201cVery well, very well, just as you chuse, settle it your own way, I am sure I do not care about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59481,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo not urge her, madam,\\u201dsaid Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88469,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, sir,\\u201dwas Fanny\\u2019s humble answer, given with the feelings almost of a criminal towards Mrs. Norris;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88496,\n            \"and not bearing to remain with her in what might seem a state of triumph, she followed her uncle out of the room, having staid behind him only long enough to hear these words spoken in angry agitation \\u2014 \\u201cQuite unnecessary!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88579,\n            \"She felt that the carriage was for herself, and herself alone: and her uncle\\u2019s consideration of her, coming immediately after such representations from her aunt, cost her some tears of gratitude when she was alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88636,\n            \"and as the lady had, with a most scrupulous fear of being late, been many minutes seated in the drawing-room, Sir Thomas saw them off in as good time as his own correctly punctual habits required.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149741,\n            \"and for part of one of those days the young travellers were in a good deal of alarm on the subject of their journey, for when the mode of it came to be talked of, and Mrs. Norris found that all her anxiety to save her brother-in-law\\u2019s money was vain, and that in spite of her wishes and hints for a less expensive conveyance of Fanny, they were to travel post;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149824,\n            \"when she saw Sir Thomas actually give William notes for the purpose, she was struck with the idea of there being room for a third in the carriage, and suddenly seized with a strong inclination to go with them, to go and see her poor dear sister Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180854,\n            \"Edmund was almost as welcome to his brother as Fanny to her aunt;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 14]\": [\n        [\n            13521,\n            \"Lady Bertram did: she entirely agreed with her son as to the necessity of it, and as to its being considered necessary by his father;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13914,\n            \"As the horse continued in name, as well as fact, the property of Edmund, Mrs. Norris could tolerate its being for Fanny\\u2019s use;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23477,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMiss Price has a brother at sea,\\u201dsaid Edmund, \\u201cwhose excellence as a correspondent makes her think you too severe upon us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23878,\n            \"and Mrs. Grant could not help addressing her brother, though it was calling his attention from Miss Julia Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25881,\n            \"neither could she wonder that, when the evening stroll was over, and the two families parted again, he should think it right to attend Mrs. Grant and her sister to their home, while Mr. Crawford was devoted to the ladies of the Park;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26411,\n            \"Fanny was ready and waiting, and Mrs. Norris was beginning to scold her for not being gone, and still no horse was announced, no Edmund appeared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26442,\n            \"To avoid her aunt, and look for him, she went out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50208,\n            \"Tom, returning from them into the drawing-room, where Edmund was standing thoughtfully by the fire, while Lady Bertram was on the sofa at a little distance, and Fanny close beside her arranging her work, thus began as he entered \\u2014 \\u201cSuch a horribly vile billiard-table as ours is not to be met with, I believe, above ground.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50946,\n            \"Well, Edmund,\\u201dhe continued, returning to the former subject, posture, and voice, as soon as Lady Bertram began to nod again, \\u201cbut _ this _ I _ will _ maintain, that we shall be doing no harm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56840,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am convinced, madam,\\u201dsaid Edmund, preventing Fanny, \\u201cthat Sir Thomas would not like it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57560,\n            \"Mrs. Norris related again her triumph over Dick Jackson, but neither play nor preparation were otherwise much talked of, for Edmund\\u2019s disapprobation was felt even by his brother, though he would not have owned it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57932,\n            \"and I do sincerely give you joy, madam, as well as Mrs. Norris, and everybody else who is in the same predicament,\\u201dglancing half fearfully, half slyly, beyond Fanny to Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57972,\n            \"She was very civilly answered by Lady Bertram, but Edmund said nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85550,\n            \"\\u201d A look of consciousness as he spoke, and what seemed a consciousness of manner on Miss Crawford\\u2019s side as she made some laughing answer, was sorrowfull food for Fanny\\u2019s observation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87490,\n            \"for Lady Bertram never thought of being useful to anybody, and Mrs. Norris, when she came on the morrow, in consequence of an early call and invitation from Sir Thomas, was in a very ill humour, and seemed intent only on lessening her niece\\u2019s pleasure, both present and future, as much as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93237,\n            \"This was exactly what Sir Thomas and Edmund had been separately conniving at, as each proved to the other by the sympathetic alacrity with which they both advised Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s continuing where she was, instead of rushing out into the hall as soon as the noises of the arrival reached them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115396,\n            \"But at last Lady Bertram left the room, and then almost immediately Miss Crawford thus began, with a voice as well regulated as she could \\u2014 \\u201cAnd how do _ you _ like your cousin Edmund\\u2019s staying away so long?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137724,\n            \"Lady Bertram\\u2019s being just on the other side of the table was a trifle, for she might always be considered as only half-awake, and Edmund\\u2019s advertisements were still of the first utility.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149049,\n            \"obtaining it rather from submission, however, than conviction, for Lady Bertram was convinced of very little more than that Sir Thomas thought Fanny ought to go, and therefore that she must.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149085,\n            \"In the calmness of her own dressing-room, in the impartial flow of her own meditations, unbiassed by his bewildering statements, she could not acknowledge any necessity for Fanny\\u2019s ever going near a father and mother who had done without her so long, while she was so useful to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149178,\n            \"Sir Thomas had appealed to her reason, conscience, and dignity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150063,\n            \"that she was a great deal too necessary to Sir Thomas and Lady Bertram for her to be able to answer it to herself to leave them even for a week, and therefore must certainly sacrifice every other pleasure to that of being useful to them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171637,\n            \"Within a few days from the receipt of Edmund\\u2019s letter, Fanny had one from her aunt, beginning thus \\u2014 \\u201cMy Dear Fanny, \\u2014 I take up my pen to communicate some very alarming intelligence, which I make no doubt will give you much concern \\u201d.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173070,\n            \"A very few lines from Edmund shewed her the patient and the sickroom in a juster and stronger light than all Lady Bertram\\u2019s sheets of paper could do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181151,\n            \"Edmund trying to bury his own feelings in exertions for the relief of his brother\\u2019s, and Fanny devoted to her aunt Bertram, returning to every former office with more than former zeal, and thinking she could never do enough for one who seemed so much to want her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182659,\n            \"and, having reason to think that one interview with Miss Crawford had taken place, from which Edmund derived only increased distress, had been as anxious on that account as on others to get him out of town, and had engaged him in taking Fanny home to her aunt, with a view to his relief and benefit, no less than theirs.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 15]\": [\n        [\n            26442,\n            \"To avoid her aunt, and look for him, she went out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26511,\n            \"and in Dr. Grant\\u2019s meadow she immediately saw the group \\u2014 Edmund and Miss Crawford both on horse-back, riding side by side, Dr. and Mrs. Grant, and Mr. Crawford, with two or three grooms, standing about and looking on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26606,\n            \"she wondered that Edmund should forget her, and felt a pang.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27146,\n            \"I wish _ you _ may not be fatigued by so much exercise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45177,\n            \"when, being earnestly invited by the Miss Bertrams to join in a glee, she tripped off to the instrument, leaving Edmund looking after her in an ecstasy of admiration of all her many virtues, from her obliging manners down to her light and graceful tread.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45279,\n            \"What a pity,\\u201dhe added, after an instant\\u2019s reflection, \\u201cthat she should have been in such hands!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149824,\n            \"when she saw Sir Thomas actually give William notes for the purpose, she was struck with the idea of there being room for a third in the carriage, and suddenly seized with a strong inclination to go with them, to go and see her poor dear sister Price.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 16]\": [\n        [\n            85777,\n            \"Dr. Grant was in the vestibule, and as they stopt to speak to him she found, from Edmund\\u2019s manner, that he _ did _ mean to go with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85826,\n            \"In the moment of parting, Edmund was invited by Dr. Grant to eat his mutton with him the next day;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86012,\n            \"and though Fanny would not venture, even on his encouragement, to such a flight of audacious independence, it was soon settled, that if nothing were heard to the contrary, Mrs. Grant might expect her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86576,\n            \"and I think he will consider it a right thing by Mrs. Grant, as well as by Fanny, that being the _ first _ invitation it should be accepted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87030,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut is it not very natural,\\u201dobserved Edmund, \\u201cthat Mrs. Grant should wish to procure so agreeable a visitor for her sister?\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 17]\": [\n        [\n            13521,\n            \"Lady Bertram did: she entirely agreed with her son as to the necessity of it, and as to its being considered necessary by his father;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13558,\n            \"she only wanted him to wait till Sir Thomas\\u2019 s return, and then Sir Thomas might settle it all himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13635,\n            \"and at length determined on a method of proceeding which would obviate the risk of his father\\u2019s thinking he had done too much, and at the same time procure for Fanny the immediate means of exercise, which he could not bear she should be without.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70826,\n            \"He inquired next after her family, especially William: and his kindness altogether was such as made her reproach herself for loving him so little, and thinking his return a misfortune;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72130,\n            \"The first day I went over Mansfield Wood, and Edmund took the copses beyond Easton, and we brought home six brace between us, and might each have killed six times as many, but we respect your pheasants, sir, I assure you, as much as you could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74447,\n            \"CHAPTER XX Edmund\\u2019s first object the next morning was to see his father alone, and give him a fair statement of the whole acting scheme, defending his own share in it as far only as he could then, in a soberer moment, feel his motives to deserve, and acknowledging, with perfect ingenuousness, that his concession had been attended with such partial good as to make his judgment in it very doubtful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93237,\n            \"This was exactly what Sir Thomas and Edmund had been separately conniving at, as each proved to the other by the sympathetic alacrity with which they both advised Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s continuing where she was, instead of rushing out into the hall as soon as the noises of the arrival reached them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98862,\n            \"May I hope for your acquiescence, and for your not influencing your son against such a tenant?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98914,\n            \"but I hope, and believe, that Edmund will occupy his own house at Thornton Lacey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98971,\n            \"\\u201cCertainly, sir, I have no idea but of residence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99331,\n            \"\\u201cSir Thomas,\\u201dsaid Edmund, \\u201cundoubtedly understands the duty of a parish priest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100736,\n            \"My dear Sir Thomas, we have settled it that the carriage should come back for you, and Edmund and William.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101371,\n            \"Edmund, William, and Fanny did, in their different ways, look and speak as much grateful pleasure in the promised ball as Sir Thomas could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119592,\n            \"What can Sir Thomas and Edmund together do, what _ do _ they do for her happiness, comfort, honour, and dignity in the world, to what I _ shall _ do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126593,\n            \"\\u201cIndependently of the interest which Mr. Crawford\\u2019s _ choice _ seemed to justify\\u201dsaid Sir Thomas, beginning again, and very composedly, \\u201chis wishing to marry at all so early is recommendatory to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126709,\n            \"but at present, as far as I can judge, matrimony makes no part of his plans or thoughts.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126730,\n            \"I wish he were more likely to fix.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126747,\n            \"\\u201cEdmund, I consider, from his dispositions and habits, as much more likely to marry early than his brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126770,\n            \"_ He _, indeed, I have lately thought, has seen the woman he could love, which, I am convinced, my eldest son has not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134176,\n            \"His surprise was not so great as his father\\u2019s at her refusing Crawford, because, so far from supposing her to consider him with anything like a preference, he had always believed it to be rather the reverse, and could imagine her to be taken perfectly unprepared, but Sir Thomas could not regard the connexion as more desirable than he did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134420,\n            \"Crawford called the next day, and on the score of Edmund\\u2019s return, Sir Thomas felt himself more than licensed to ask him to stay dinner;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148128,\n            \"It had occurred to Sir Thomas, in one of his dignified musings, as a right and desirable measure;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148149,\n            \"but before he absolutely made up his mind, he consulted his son.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171974,\n            \"We shall greatly miss Edmund in our small circle, but I trust and hope he will find the poor invalid in a less alarming state than might be apprehended, and that he will be able to bring him to Mansfield shortly, which Sir Thomas proposes should be done, and thinks best on every account, and I flatter myself the poor sufferer will soon be able to bear the removal without material inconvenience or injury.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184682,\n            \"What I advise is, that your father be quiet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186707,\n            \"and quite as soon as Sir Thomas could place dependence on such sources of good, Edmund was contributing to his father\\u2019s ease by improvement in the only point in which he had given him pain before \\u2014 improvement in his spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190923,\n            \"In _ her _ usefulness, in Fanny\\u2019s excellence, in William\\u2019s continued good conduct and rising fame, and in the general well-doing and success of the other members of the family, all assisting to advance each other, and doing credit to his countenance and aid, Sir Thomas saw repeated, and for ever repeated, reason to rejoice in what he had done for them all, and acknowledge the advantages of early hardship and discipline, and the consciousness of being born to struggle and endure.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 18]\": [\n        [\n            8591,\n            \"The time was now come when Sir Thomas expected his sister-in-law to claim her share in their niece, the change in Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s situation, and the improvement in Fanny\\u2019s age, seeming not merely to do away any former objection to their living together, but even to give it the most decided eligibility;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8713,\n            \"In the fullness of his belief that such a thing must be, he mentioned its probability to his wife;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23985,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNothing could be so gratifying to me as to hear your opinion of it,\\u201dwas his answer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24599,\n            \"I dare say Mr. Crawford would take my two nieces and me in his barouche, and Edmund can go on horseback, you know, sister, and Fanny will stay at home with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27976,\n            \"Edmund and Julia were invited to dine at the Parsonage, and _ she _ was excluded.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28113,\n            \"Between ten and eleven Edmund and Julia walked into the drawing-room, fresh with the evening air, glowing and cheerful, the very reverse of what they found in the three ladies sitting there, for Maria would scarcely raise her eyes from her book, and Lady Bertram was half-asleep;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28212,\n            \"For a few minutes the brother and sister were too eager in their praise of the night and their remarks on the stars, to think beyond themselves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29614,\n            \"Vexed as Edmund was with his mother and aunt, he was still more angry with himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31700,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt seems very odd,\\u201dsaid Maria, \\u201cthat you should be staying at home instead of Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31723,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sure she ought to be very much obliged to you,\\u201dadded Julia, hastily leaving the room as she spoke, from a consciousness that she ought to offer to stay at home herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32514,\n            \"and to see only his expressive profile as he turned with a smile to Julia, or to catch the laugh of the other, was a perpetual source of irritation, which her own sense of propriety could but just smooth over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35322,\n            \"\\u201d cried Julia, and running to where he stood with Miss Crawford and Fanny: \\u201cMy dear Edmund, if you were but in orders now, you might perform the ceremony directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40608,\n            \"\\u201d And she immediately scrambled across the fence, and walked away, not attending to Fanny\\u2019s last question of whether she had seen anything of Miss Crawford and Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46612,\n            \"\\u201cand I dare say it gives his sister pleasure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46656,\n            \"Mrs. Grant, I believe, suspects him of a preference for Julia;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46753,\n            \"for I believe it often happens that a man, before he has quite made up his own mind, will distinguish the sister or intimate friend of the woman he is really thinking of more than the woman herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46812,\n            \"and I am not at all afraid for her, after such a proof as she has given that her feelings are not strong.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46854,\n            \"but with all that submission to Edmund could do, and all the help of the coinciding looks and hints which she occasionally noticed in some of the others, and which seemed to say that Julia was Mr. Crawford\\u2019s choice, she knew not always what to think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49950,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNow, Edmund, do not be disagreeable,\\u201dsaid Julia.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56907,\n            \"\\u201d cried Edmund, \\u201cif she knew your reasons!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178350,\n            \"Julia\\u2019s, Tom\\u2019s, Edmund\\u2019s;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 19]\": [\n        [\n            179976,\n            \"but Susan\\u2019s presence drove him quite into himself, and his attempts to talk on indifferent subjects could never be long supported.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190923,\n            \"In _ her _ usefulness, in Fanny\\u2019s excellence, in William\\u2019s continued good conduct and rising fame, and in the general well-doing and success of the other members of the family, all assisting to advance each other, and doing credit to his countenance and aid, Sir Thomas saw repeated, and for ever repeated, reason to rejoice in what he had done for them all, and acknowledge the advantages of early hardship and discipline, and the consciousness of being born to struggle and endure.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 10]\": [\n        [\n            92339,\n            \"\\u201d And without attempting any farther remonstrance, she left Fanny to her fate, a fate which, had not Fanny\\u2019s heart been guarded in a way unsuspected by Miss Crawford, might have been a little harder than she deserved;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114697,\n            \"What was tranquillity and comfort to Fanny was tediousness and vexation to Mary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116944,\n            \"No: you must be aware that I am quite determined to marry Fanny Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117728,\n            \"Mary, she is not like her cousins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118237,\n            \"\\u201d Well might his sister, believing as she really did that his opinion of Fanny Price was scarcely beyond her merits, rejoice in her prospects.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118576,\n            \"\\u201cI cannot admit Mrs. Grant to have an equal claim with Fanny and myself, for we shall both have a right in you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118603,\n            \"Fanny will be so truly your sister!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118846,\n            \"You must not prejudice Fanny against him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119446,\n            \"Yes, Mary, my Fanny will feel a difference indeed: a daily, hourly difference, in the behaviour of every being who approaches her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143982,\n            \"Yet, Fanny, do not imagine I would now speak disrespectfully of Sir Thomas, though I certainly did hate him for many a week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144044,\n            \"\\u201d And having said so, with a degree of tenderness and consciousness which Fanny had never seen in her before, and now thought only too becoming, she turned away for a moment to recover herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144083,\n            \"\\u201cI have had a little fit since I came into this room, as you may perceive,\\u201dsaid she presently, with a playful smile, \\u201cbut it is over now;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144128,\n            \"for as to scolding you, Fanny, which I came fully intending to do, I have not the heart for it when it comes to the point.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144540,\n            \"\\u201d After this speech the two girls sat many minutes silent, each thoughtful: Fanny meditating on the different sorts of friendship in the world, Mary on something of less philosophic tendency.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146152,\n            \"I leave him entirely to your mercy, and when he has got you at Everingham, I do not care how much you lecture him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146229,\n            \"And I do seriously and truly believe that he is attached to you in a way that he never was to any woman before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146274,\n            \"If any man ever loved a woman for ever, I think Henry will do as much for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146339,\n            \"\\u201d She had made a sure push at Fanny\\u2019s feelings here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146487,\n            \"and she sat thinking deeply of it till Mary, who had been first watching her complacently, and then musing on something else, suddenly called her attention by saying: \\u201cI should like to sit talking with you here all day, but we must not forget the ladies below, and so good-bye, my dear, my amiable, my excellent Fanny, for though we shall nominally part in the breakfast-parlour, I must take leave of you here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146695,\n            \"I have two favours to ask, Fanny: one is your correspondence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155995,\n            \"she was so fond of it, Fanny, that she would have it lay by her in bed, all through her illness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156099,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny had indeed nothing to convey from aunt Norris, but a message to say she hoped that her god-daughter was a good girl, and learnt her book.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158516,\n            \"But there he is, and, by the bye, his absence may sufficiently account for any remissness of his sister\\u2019s in writing, for there has been no \\u2018 Well, Mary, when do you write to Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158560,\n            \"Is not it time for you to write to Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165590,\n            \"If, therefore\\u201d(turning again to Fanny), \\u201cyou find yourself growing unwell, and any difficulties arise about your returning to Mansfield, without waiting for the two months to be ended, _ that _ must not be regarded as of any consequence, if you feel yourself at all less strong or comfortable than usual, and will only let my sister know it, give her only the slightest hint, she and I will immediately come down, and take you back to Mansfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165767,\n            \"for so long only as you positively say, in every letter to Mary, \\u2018 I am well,\\u2019and I know you cannot speak or write a falsehood, so long only shall you be considered as well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171195,\n            \"\\u2018 The loss of Mary I must consider as comprehending the loss of Crawford and Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175478,\n            \"\\u2014 Yours ever, Mary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175962,\n            \"there was no occasion to determine whether she ought to keep Edmund and Mary asunder or not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188663,\n            \"Would he have persevered, and uprightly, Fanny must have been his reward, and a reward very voluntarily bestowed, within a reasonable period from Edmund\\u2019s marrying Mary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190505,\n            \"and the joyful consent which met Edmund\\u2019s application, the high sense of having realised a great acquisition in the promise of Fanny for a daughter, formed just such a contrast with his early opinion on the subject when the poor little girl\\u2019s coming had been first agitated, as time is for ever producing between the plans and decisions of mortals, for their own instruction, and their neighbours\\u2019 entertainment.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 11]\": [\n        [\n            12326,\n            \"though, I fear, he must find his sister at sixteen in some respects too much like his sister at ten.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23144,\n            \"Now, Mr. Bertram, if you write to your brother, I entreat you to tell him that my harp is come: he heard so much of my misery about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23446,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWhen they are at a distance from all their family,\\u201dsaid Fanny, colouring for William\\u2019s sake, \\u201cthey can write long letters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44458,\n            \"He has met with great kindness from the chaplain of the Antwerp,\\u201dwas a tender apostrophe of Fanny\\u2019s, very much to the purpose of her own feelings if not of the conversation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92791,\n            \"It was but the day before that Crawford had made himself thoroughly master of the subject, or had in fact become at all aware of her having such a brother, or his being in such a ship, but the interest then excited had been very properly lively, determining him on his return to town to apply for information as to the probable period of the Antwerp\\u2019s return from the Mediterranean, etc.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92960,\n            \"But his intention, the kindness of his intention, was thankfully acknowledged: quite thankfully and warmly, for she was elevated beyond the common timidity of her mind by the flow of her love for William.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93029,\n            \"and as his parents, from living on the spot, must already have seen him, and be seeing him perhaps daily, his direct holidays might with justice be instantly given to the sister, who had been his best correspondent through a period of seven years, and the uncle who had done most for his support and advancement;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93092,\n            \"and accordingly the reply to her reply, fixing a very early day for his arrival, came as soon as possible;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93115,\n            \"and scarcely ten days had passed since Fanny had been in the agitation of her first dinner-visit, when she found herself in an agitation of a higher nature, watching in the hall, in the lobby, on the stairs, for the first sound of the carriage which was to bring her a brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93184,\n            \"and there being neither ceremony nor fearfulness to delay the moment of meeting, she was with him as he entered the house, and the first minutes of exquisite feeling had no interruption and no witnesses, unless the servants chiefly intent upon opening the proper doors could be called such.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93294,\n            \"William and Fanny soon shewed themselves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93391,\n            \"it was some time even before her happiness could be said to make her happy, before the disappointment inseparable from the alteration of person had vanished, and she could see in him the same William as before, and talk to him, as her heart had been yearning to do through many a past year.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93450,\n            \"That time, however, did gradually come, forwarded by an affection on his side as warm as her own, and much less encumbered by refinement or self-distrust.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93483,\n            \"She was the first object of his love, but it was a love which his stronger spirits, and bolder temper, made it as natural for him to express as to feel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93563,\n            \"Excepting the moments of peculiar delight, which any marked or unlooked-for instance of Edmund\\u2019s consideration of her in the last few months had excited, Fanny had never known so much felicity in her life, as in this unchecked, equal, fearless intercourse with the brother and friend who was opening all his heart to her, telling her all his hopes and fears, plans, and solicitudes respecting that long thought of, dearly earned, and justly valued blessing of promotion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93955,\n            \"He honoured the warm-hearted, blunt fondness of the young sailor, which led him to say, with his hands stretched towards Fanny\\u2019s head, \\u201cDo you know, I begin to like that queer fashion already, though when I first heard of such things being done in England, I could not believe it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94699,\n            \"and Crawford could mount him without the slightest inconvenience to himself, and with only some scruples to obviate in Sir Thomas, who knew better than his nephew the value of such a loan, and some alarms to reason away in Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94744,\n            \"She feared for William;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94862,\n            \"When it was proved, however, to have done William no harm, she could allow it to be a kindness, and even reward the owner with a smile when the animal was one minute tendered to his use again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95769,\n            \"for though it was impossible for Fanny not to feel herself mistress of the rules of the game in three minutes, he had yet to inspirit her play, sharpen her avarice, and harden her heart, which, especially in any competition with William, was a work of some difficulty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97612,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny gave a quick negative, and tried to hide her interest in the subject by an eager attention to her brother, who was driving as hard a bargain, and imposing on her as much as he could;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97714,\n            \"The game will be yours,\\u201dturning to her again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97733,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd Fanny had much rather it were William\\u2019s,\\u201dsaid Edmund, smiling at her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99894,\n            \"But never mind it, William\\u201d(her own cheeks in a glow of indignation as she spoke).\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100856,\n            \"CHAPTER XXVI William\\u2019s desire of seeing Fanny dance made more than a momentary impression on his uncle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101371,\n            \"Edmund, William, and Fanny did, in their different ways, look and speak as much grateful pleasure in the promised ball as Sir Thomas could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112495,\n            \"yes, sir,\\u201dcried Fanny, rising eagerly from her seat to be nearer her uncle;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112652,\n            \"\\u201d And in a lower tone to Fanny, \\u201cI shall have only a desolate house to hurry from.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113144,\n            \"After seeing William to the last moment, Fanny walked back to the breakfast-room with a very saddened heart to grieve over the melancholy change;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113475,\n            \"\\u201cShe could not recollect what it was that she had heard about one of the Miss Maddoxes, or what it was that Lady Prescott had noticed in Fanny: she was not sure whether Colonel Harrison had been talking of Mr. Crawford or of William when he said he was the finest young man in the room \\u2014 somebody had whispered something to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120778,\n            \"but her heart was so full and her senses still so astonished, that she could listen but imperfectly even to what he told her of William, and saying only when he paused, \\u201cHow kind!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120899,\n            \"\\u201cShe must not go, she must allow him five minutes longer,\\u201dand he took her hand and led her back to her seat, and was in the middle of his farther explanation, before she had suspected for what she was detained.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120947,\n            \"When she did understand it, however, and found herself expected to believe that she had created sensations which his heart had never known before, and that everything he had done for William was to be placed to the account of his excessive and unequalled attachment to her, she was exceedingly distressed, and for some moments unable to speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121113,\n            \"While her heart was still bounding with joy and gratitude on William\\u2019s behalf, she could not be severely resentful of anything that injured only herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121335,\n            \"Your kindness to William makes me more obliged to you than words can express;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121616,\n            \"She would not have him be serious, and yet what could excuse the use of such words and offers, if they meant but to trifle?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121700,\n            \"and in that case, how gratefully she could esteem him for his friendship to William!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121750,\n            \"but when convinced of his being gone, she was eager to go down and be with her uncle, and have all the happiness of his joy as well as her own, and all the benefit of his information or his conjectures as to what would now be William\\u2019s destination.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121821,\n            \"and she had so comfortable a talk with him about William as to make her feel as if nothing had occurred to vex her, till she found, towards the close, that Mr. Crawford was engaged to return and dine there that very day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121948,\n            \"She could not have supposed it in the power of any concurrence of circumstances to give her so many painful sensations on the first day of hearing of William\\u2019s promotion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122072,\n            \"\\u201cMY DEAR FANNY, \\u2014 for so I may now always call you, to the infinite relief of a tongue that has been stumbling at _ Miss _ _ Price _ for at least the last six weeks \\u2014 I cannot let my brother go without sending you a few lines of general congratulation, and giving my most joyful consent and approval.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122171,\n            \"so you may smile upon him with your sweetest smiles this afternoon, and send him back to me even happier than he goes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122966,\n            \"Fanny, William must not forget my shawl if he goes to the East Indies;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149972,\n            \"William and Fanny were horror-struck at the idea.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150175,\n            \"Edmund\\u2019s plans were affected by this Portsmouth journey, this absence of Fanny\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150284,\n            \"He told Fanny of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150384,\n            \"and Edmund, at a convenient moment, then added in a whisper, \\u201cAnd _ I _ shall write to you, Fanny, when I have anything worth writing about, anything to say that I think you will like to hear, and that you will not hear so soon from any other quarter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150683,\n            \"and when the small, diminished party met at breakfast, William and Fanny were talked of as already advanced one stage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150706,\n            \"CHAPTER XXXVIII The novelty of travelling, and the happiness of being with William, soon produced their natural effect on Fanny\\u2019s spirits, when Mansfield Park was fairly left behind;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150795,\n            \"Everything supplied an amusement to the high glee of William\\u2019s mind, and he was full of frolic and joke in the intervals of their higher-toned subjects, all of which ended, if they did not begin, in praise of the Thrush, conjectures how she would be employed, schemes for an action with some superior force, which (supposing the first lieutenant out of the way, and William was not very merciful to the first lieutenant) was to give himself the next step as soon as possible, or speculations upon prize-money, which was to be generously distributed at home, with only the reservation of enough to make the little cottage comfortable, in which he and Fanny were to pass all their middle and later life together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151719,\n            \"\\u201d A stare or two at Fanny, as William helped her out of the carriage, was all the voluntary notice which this brother bestowed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153241,\n            \"\\u201cit is so dark you do not see her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153252,\n            \"\\u201d With an acknowledgment that he had quite forgot her, Mr. Price now received his daughter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153271,\n            \"and having given her a cordial hug, and observed that she was grown into a woman, and he supposed would be wanting a husband soon, seemed very much inclined to forget her again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153308,\n            \"Fanny shrunk back to her seat, with feelings sadly pained by his language and his smell of spirits;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153328,\n            \"and he talked on only to his son, and only of the Thrush, though William, warmly interested as he was in that subject, more than once tried to make his father think of Fanny, and her long absence and long journey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154361,\n            \"\\u201d This threat was so palpably disregarded, that though within five minutes afterwards the three boys all burst into the room together and sat down, Fanny could not consider it as a proof of anything more than their being for the time thoroughly fagged, which their hot faces and panting breaths seemed to prove, especially as they were still kicking each other\\u2019s shins, and hallooing out at sudden starts immediately under their father\\u2019s eye.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154714,\n            \"she was like William, and Fanny hoped to find her like him in disposition and goodwill towards herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154754,\n            \"He, complete in his lieutenant\\u2019s uniform, looking and moving all the taller, firmer, and more graceful for it, and with the happiest smile over his face, walked up directly to Fanny, who, rising from her seat, looked at him for a moment in speechless admiration, and then threw her arms round his neck to sob out her various emotions of pain and pleasure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156666,\n            \"He stepped back again to the door to say, \\u201cTake care of Fanny, mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156700,\n            \"I charge you, take care of Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156709,\n            \"\\u201d William was gone: and the home he had left her in was, Fanny could not conceal it from herself, in almost every respect the very reverse of what she could have wished.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 12]\": [\n        [\n            42356,\n            \"\\u201d Maria was just discontented enough to say directly, \\u201cI think _ you _ have done pretty well yourself, ma\\u2019am.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47395,\n            \"How she had looked before, Fanny could not recollect, for she had been dancing with Edmund herself, and had not thought about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52025,\n            \"and Maria evidently considered her engagement as only raising her so much more above restraint, and leaving her less occasion than Julia to consult either father or mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53629,\n            \"when Julia, meaning, like her sister, to be Agatha, began to be scrupulous on Miss Crawford\\u2019s account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53674,\n            \"Amelia and Agatha may do for Maria and me, but here is nothing for your sister, Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59338,\n            \"and it was not merely Tom, for the requisition was now backed by Maria, and Mr. Crawford, and Mr. Yates, with an urgency which differed from his but in being more gentle or more ceremonious, and which altogether was quite overpowering to Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60940,\n            \"The East room, as it had been called ever since Maria Bertram was sixteen, was now considered Fanny\\u2019s, almost as decidedly as the white attic: the smallness of the one making the use of the other so evidently reasonable that the Miss Bertrams, with every superiority in their own apartments which their own sense of superiority could demand, were entirely approving it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66282,\n            \"Maria, she also thought, acted well, too well;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69335,\n            \"Fanny, I am sure you know the part.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75120,\n            \"She took to herself all the credit of bringing Mr. Rushworth\\u2019s admiration of Maria to any effect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89408,\n            \"Her two absent cousins, especially Maria, were much in her thoughts on seeing him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133607,\n            \"\\u201d And still pursuing the same cheerful thoughts, she soon afterwards added, \\u201cAnd I will tell you what, Fanny, which is more than I did for Maria: the next time Pug has a litter you shall have a puppy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141192,\n            \"I knew she was very fond of you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141201,\n            \"but yet I was afraid of her not estimating your worth to her brother quite as it deserved, and of her regretting that he had not rather fixed on some woman of distinction or fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141265,\n            \"She spoke of you, Fanny, just as she ought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141394,\n            \"and when once we had begun, we had not done with you, Fanny, till Crawford and Dr. Grant came in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141448,\n            \"You will see her, however, before she goes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141459,\n            \"She is very angry with you, Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141475,\n            \"She calls herself very angry, but you can imagine her anger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141517,\n            \"She is hurt, as you would be for William;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141528,\n            \"but she loves and esteems you with all her heart.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 13]\": [\n        [\n            502,\n            \"but Mrs. Norris had a spirit of activity, which could not be satisfied till she had written a long and angry letter to Fanny, to point out the folly of her conduct, and threaten her with all its possible ill consequences.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            609,\n            \"Their homes were so distant, and the circles in which they moved so distinct, as almost to preclude the means of ever hearing of each other\\u2019s existence during the eleven following years, or, at least, to make it very wonderful to Sir Thomas that Mrs. Norris should ever have it in her power to tell them, as she now and then did, in an angry voice, that Fanny had got another child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4345,\n            \"\\u201cThis is not a very promising beginning,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris, when Fanny had left the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4489,\n            \"\\u201d It required a longer time, however, than Mrs. Norris was inclined to allow, to reconcile Fanny to the novelty of Mansfield Park, and the separation from everybody she had been used to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8591,\n            \"The time was now come when Sir Thomas expected his sister-in-law to claim her share in their niece, the change in Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s situation, and the improvement in Fanny\\u2019s age, seeming not merely to do away any former objection to their living together, but even to give it the most decided eligibility;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10093,\n            \"\\u201d So ended their discourse, which, for any very appropriate service it could render Fanny, might as well have been spared, for Mrs. Norris had not the smallest intention of taking her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10254,\n            \"or, perhaps, her very display of the importance of a spare room might have misled Sir Thomas to suppose it really intended for Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10281,\n            \"Lady Bertram soon brought the matter to a certainty by carelessly observing to Mrs. Norris \\u2014 \\u201cI think, sister, we need not keep Miss Lee any longer, when Fanny goes to live with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11123,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, Lady Bertram,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris, moving to go, \\u201cI can only say that my sole desire is to be of use to your family: and so, if Sir Thomas should ever speak again about my taking Fanny, you will be able to say that my health and spirits put it quite out of the question;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11192,\n            \"besides that, I really should not have a bed to give her, for I must keep a spare room for a friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11267,\n            \"He could not but wonder at her refusing to do anything for a niece whom she had been so forward to adopt;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12852,\n            \"but she enjoyed being avowedly useful as her aunt\\u2019s companion when they called away the rest of the family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13404,\n            \"She could not but consider it as absolutely unnecessary, and even improper, that Fanny should have a regular lady\\u2019s horse of her own, in the style of her cousins.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28291,\n            \"\\u201d Her own gentle voice speaking from the other end of the room, which was a very long one, told them that she was on the sofa.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28472,\n            \"and Julia, who was in high good-humour, from the pleasures of the day, did her the justice of exclaiming, \\u201cI must say, ma\\u2019am, that Fanny is as little upon the sofa as anybody in the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28661,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, indeed, Edmund,\\u201dadded her ladyship, who had been thoroughly awakened by Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s sharp reprimand to Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28698,\n            \"I sat three-quarters of an hour in the flower-garden, while Fanny cut the roses;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29241,\n            \"And as for Fanny\\u2019s just stepping down to my house for me \\u2014 it is not much above a quarter of a mile \\u2014 I cannot think I was unreasonable to ask it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29306,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI wish Fanny had half your strength, ma\\u2019am.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31208,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou can have no reason, I imagine, madam,\\u201dsaid he, addressing his mother, \\u201cfor wishing Fanny _ not _ to be of the party, but as it relates to yourself, to your own comfort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31357,\n            \"She has not often a gratification of the kind, and I am sure, ma\\u2019am, you would be glad to give her the pleasure now?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31402,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Norris was very ready with the only objection which could remain \\u2014 their having positively assured Mrs. Rushworth that Fanny could not go, and the very strange appearance there would consequently be in taking her, which seemed to her a difficulty quite impossible to be got over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31504,\n            \"Mrs. Norris had no affection for Fanny, and no wish of procuring her pleasure at any time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42282,\n            \"\\u201cWell, Fanny, this has been a fine day for you, upon my word,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris, as they drove through the park.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42322,\n            \"I am sure you ought to be very much obliged to your aunt Bertram and me for contriving to let you go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42356,\n            \"\\u201d Maria was just discontented enough to say directly, \\u201cI think _ you _ have done pretty well yourself, ma\\u2019am.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59389,\n            \"and before she could breathe after it, Mrs. Norris completed the whole by thus addressing her in a whisper at once angry and audible \\u2014 \\u201cWhat a piece of work here is about nothing: I am quite ashamed of you, Fanny, to make such a difficulty of obliging your cousins in a trifle of this sort \\u2014 so kind as they are to you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61011,\n            \"and Mrs. Norris, having stipulated for there never being a fire in it on Fanny\\u2019s account, was tolerably resigned to her having the use of what nobody else wanted, though the terms in which she sometimes spoke of the indulgence seemed to imply that it was the best room in the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88407,\n            \"\\u201d cried Mrs. Norris, red with anger, \\u201cFanny can walk.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88469,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, sir,\\u201dwas Fanny\\u2019s humble answer, given with the feelings almost of a criminal towards Mrs. Norris;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109287,\n            \"Only think, my dear Sir Thomas, what extraordinary advantages you and I have been the means of giving her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109521,\n            \"she felt it to be indeed very charming, and was actually practising her steps about the drawing-room as long as she could be safe from the notice of her aunt Norris, who was entirely taken up at first in fresh arranging and injuring the noble fire which the butler had prepared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109601,\n            \"It was but to think of her conversation with Edmund, and what was the restlessness of Mrs. Norris?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111087,\n            \"and without attributing all her personal beauty, as Mrs. Norris seemed to do, to her transplantation to Mansfield, he was pleased with himself for having supplied everything else: education and manners she owed to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111326,\n            \"Miss Crawford knew Mrs. Norris too well to think of gratifying _ her _ by commendation of Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122072,\n            \"\\u201cMY DEAR FANNY, \\u2014 for so I may now always call you, to the infinite relief of a tongue that has been stumbling at _ Miss _ _ Price _ for at least the last six weeks \\u2014 I cannot let my brother go without sending you a few lines of general congratulation, and giving my most joyful consent and approval.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122171,\n            \"so you may smile upon him with your sweetest smiles this afternoon, and send him back to me even happier than he goes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122966,\n            \"Fanny, William must not forget my shawl if he goes to the East Indies;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129751,\n            \"She was talking _ at _ Fanny, and resenting this private walk half through the dinner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130118,\n            \"but instantly rising, she was preparing to obey, when Mrs. Norris called out, \\u201cStay, stay, Fanny!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132844,\n            \"though, on Fanny\\u2019s account, he almost dreaded the effect of the communication to Mrs. Norris as much as Fanny herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132964,\n            \"but she was more angry with Fanny for having received such an offer than for refusing it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133003,\n            \"and, independently of that, she disliked Fanny, because she had neglected her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133053,\n            \"and Fanny could have blessed her for allowing her only to see her displeasure, and not to hear it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149210,\n            \"But Mrs. Norris wanted to persuade her that Fanny could be very well spared \\u2014 _ she _ being ready to give up all her own time to her as requested \\u2014 and, in short, could not really be wanted or missed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149741,\n            \"and for part of one of those days the young travellers were in a good deal of alarm on the subject of their journey, for when the mode of it came to be talked of, and Mrs. Norris found that all her anxiety to save her brother-in-law\\u2019s money was vain, and that in spite of her wishes and hints for a less expensive conveyance of Fanny, they were to travel post;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157037,\n            \"she had neither leisure nor affection to bestow on Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180854,\n            \"Edmund was almost as welcome to his brother as Fanny to her aunt;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182439,\n            \"His displeasure against herself she trusted, reasoning differently from Mrs. Norris, would now be done away.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 14]\": [\n        [\n            7070,\n            \"As for Fanny\\u2019s being stupid at learning, \\u201cshe could only say it was very unlucky, but some people _ were _ stupid, and Fanny must take more pains: she did not know what else was to be done;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9272,\n            \"I hope it does not distress you very much, Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9519,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou are too kind,\\u201dsaid Fanny, colouring at such praise;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9764,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny sighed, and said, \\u201cI cannot see things as you do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10281,\n            \"Lady Bertram soon brought the matter to a certainty by carelessly observing to Mrs. Norris \\u2014 \\u201cI think, sister, we need not keep Miss Lee any longer, when Fanny goes to live with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10630,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDear sister, if you consider my unhappy state, how can she be any comfort to me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11123,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, Lady Bertram,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris, moving to go, \\u201cI can only say that my sole desire is to be of use to your family: and so, if Sir Thomas should ever speak again about my taking Fanny, you will be able to say that my health and spirits put it quite out of the question;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12874,\n            \"and, as Miss Lee had left Mansfield, she naturally became everything to Lady Bertram during the night of a ball or a party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13200,\n            \"and Fanny either sat at home the whole day with one aunt, or walked beyond her strength at the instigation of the other: Lady Bertram holding exercise to be as unnecessary for everybody as it was unpleasant to herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13914,\n            \"As the horse continued in name, as well as fact, the property of Edmund, Mrs. Norris could tolerate its being for Fanny\\u2019s use;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23477,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMiss Price has a brother at sea,\\u201dsaid Edmund, \\u201cwhose excellence as a correspondent makes her think you too severe upon us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25881,\n            \"neither could she wonder that, when the evening stroll was over, and the two families parted again, he should think it right to attend Mrs. Grant and her sister to their home, while Mr. Crawford was devoted to the ladies of the Park;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26411,\n            \"Fanny was ready and waiting, and Mrs. Norris was beginning to scold her for not being gone, and still no horse was announced, no Edmund appeared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30517,\n            \"Lady Bertram could not possibly spare her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50208,\n            \"Tom, returning from them into the drawing-room, where Edmund was standing thoughtfully by the fire, while Lady Bertram was on the sofa at a little distance, and Fanny close beside her arranging her work, thus began as he entered \\u2014 \\u201cSuch a horribly vile billiard-table as ours is not to be met with, I believe, above ground.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56840,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am convinced, madam,\\u201dsaid Edmund, preventing Fanny, \\u201cthat Sir Thomas would not like it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57932,\n            \"and I do sincerely give you joy, madam, as well as Mrs. Norris, and everybody else who is in the same predicament,\\u201dglancing half fearfully, half slyly, beyond Fanny to Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85422,\n            \"\\u201d of some length from the fair lady before she could add, \\u201cYou ought to be in parliament, or you should have gone into the army ten years ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85550,\n            \"\\u201d A look of consciousness as he spoke, and what seemed a consciousness of manner on Miss Crawford\\u2019s side as she made some laughing answer, was sorrowfull food for Fanny\\u2019s observation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95578,\n            \"I know nothing about it, but Fanny must teach me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109217,\n            \"\\u201cYes,\\u201dsaid Lady Bertram, \\u201cshe looks very well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109231,\n            \"I sent Chapman to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109739,\n            \"and besides the gravity and formality of the first great circle, which the manners of neither Sir Thomas nor Lady Bertram were of a kind to do away, she found herself occasionally called on to endure something worse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111177,\n            \"Her praise was warm, and he received it as she could wish, joining in it as far as discretion, and politeness, and slowness of speech would allow, and certainly appearing to greater advantage on the subject than his lady did soon afterwards, when Mary, perceiving her on a sofa very near, turned round before she began to dance, to compliment her on Miss Price\\u2019s looks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113289,\n            \"Fanny\\u2019s disposition was such that she could never even think of her aunt Norris in the meagreness and cheerlessness of her own small house, without reproaching herself for some little want of attention to her when they had been last together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113475,\n            \"\\u201cShe could not recollect what it was that she had heard about one of the Miss Maddoxes, or what it was that Lady Prescott had noticed in Fanny: she was not sure whether Colonel Harrison had been talking of Mr. Crawford or of William when he said he was the finest young man in the room \\u2014 somebody had whispered something to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113709,\n            \"Fanny, you must do something to keep me awake.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113734,\n            \"\\u201d The cards were brought, and Fanny played at cribbage with her aunt till bedtime;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114405,\n            \"and at the end of a quarter of an hour\\u2019s silent consideration spontaneously observed, \\u201cSir Thomas, I have been thinking \\u2014 and I am very glad we took Fanny as we did, for now the others are away we feel the good of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114543,\n            \"\\u201d Sir Thomas paused, half smiled, glanced at his niece, and then gravely replied, \\u201cShe will never leave us, I hope, till invited to some other home that may reasonably promise her greater happiness than she knows here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115367,\n            \"The first half-hour was lost, for Fanny and Lady Bertram were together, and unless she had Fanny to herself she could hope for nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115396,\n            \"But at last Lady Bertram left the room, and then almost immediately Miss Crawford thus began, with a voice as well regulated as she could \\u2014 \\u201cAnd how do _ you _ like your cousin Edmund\\u2019s staying away so long?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116843,\n            \"\\u201d he had only to say that he had been sitting with Lady Bertram and Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135120,\n            \"nay, perhaps with greater enjoyment, for it came unexpectedly, and with no such drawback as she had been used to suffer in seeing him on the stage with Miss Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135685,\n            \"If Lady Bertram, with all her incompetency and languor, could feel this, the inference of what her niece, alive and enlightened as she was, must feel, was elevating.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149049,\n            \"obtaining it rather from submission, however, than conviction, for Lady Bertram was convinced of very little more than that Sir Thomas thought Fanny ought to go, and therefore that she must.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149085,\n            \"In the calmness of her own dressing-room, in the impartial flow of her own meditations, unbiassed by his bewildering statements, she could not acknowledge any necessity for Fanny\\u2019s ever going near a father and mother who had done without her so long, while she was so useful to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149210,\n            \"But Mrs. Norris wanted to persuade her that Fanny could be very well spared \\u2014 _ she _ being ready to give up all her own time to her as requested \\u2014 and, in short, could not really be wanted or missed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164482,\n            \"to think that where nature had made so little difference, circumstances should have made so much, and that her mother, as handsome as Lady Bertram, and some years her junior, should have an appearance so much more worn and faded, so comfortless, so slatternly, so shabby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171637,\n            \"Within a few days from the receipt of Edmund\\u2019s letter, Fanny had one from her aunt, beginning thus \\u2014 \\u201cMy Dear Fanny, \\u2014 I take up my pen to communicate some very alarming intelligence, which I make no doubt will give you much concern \\u201d.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172299,\n            \"Then a letter which she had been previously preparing for Fanny was finished in a different style, in the language of real feeling and alarm;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173070,\n            \"A very few lines from Edmund shewed her the patient and the sickroom in a juster and stronger light than all Lady Bertram\\u2019s sheets of paper could do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180583,\n            \"Fanny had scarcely passed the solemn-looking servants, when Lady Bertram came from the drawing-room to meet her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180978,\n            \"Lady Bertram could not give her much time, or many words, but she felt her, as Fanny\\u2019s sister, to have a claim at Mansfield, and was ready to kiss and like her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181151,\n            \"Edmund trying to bury his own feelings in exertions for the relief of his brother\\u2019s, and Fanny devoted to her aunt Bertram, returning to every former office with more than former zeal, and thinking she could never do enough for one who seemed so much to want her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182659,\n            \"and, having reason to think that one interview with Miss Crawford had taken place, from which Edmund derived only increased distress, had been as anxious on that account as on others to get him out of town, and had engaged him in taking Fanny home to her aunt, with a view to his relief and benefit, no less than theirs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183249,\n            \"and regarding it as what was meant to be the last, last interview of friendship, and investing her with all the feelings of shame and wretchedness which Crawford\\u2019s sister ought to have known, he had gone to her in such a state of mind, so softened, so devoted, as made it for a few moments impossible to Fanny\\u2019s fears that it should be the last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187612,\n            \"and Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s anger against Fanny was so much the greater, from considering _ her _ residence there as the motive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189101,\n            \"and he went off with her at last, because he could not help it, regretting Fanny even at the moment, but regretting her infinitely more when all the bustle of the intrigue was over, and a very few months had taught him, by the force of contrast, to place a yet higher value on the sweetness of her temper, the purity of her mind, and the excellence of her principles.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 15]\": [\n        [\n            109023,\n            \"It had really occurred to her, unprompted, that Fanny, preparing for a ball, might be glad of better help than the upper housemaid\\u2019s, and when dressed herself, she actually sent her own maid to assist her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119003,\n            \"\\u201d The impossibility of not doing everything in the world to make Fanny Price happy, or of ceasing to love Fanny Price, was of course the groundwork of his eloquent answer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119735,\n            \"Henry, overjoyed to have her go, bowed and watched her off, and without losing another moment, turned instantly to Fanny, and, taking out some letters, said, with a most animated look, \\u201cI must acknowledge myself infinitely obliged to any creature who gives me such an opportunity of seeing you alone: I have been wishing it more than you can have any idea.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150315,\n            \"and Fanny was the more affected from feeling it to be the last time in which Miss Crawford\\u2019s name would ever be mentioned between them with any remains of liberty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162248,\n            \"but (as Fanny instantly, and to her great relief, discerned) her father was a very different man, a very different Mr. Price in his behaviour to this most highly respected stranger, from what he was in his own family at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162386,\n            \"The conclusion of the two gentlemen\\u2019s civilities was an offer of Mr. Price\\u2019s to take Mr. Crawford into the dockyard, which Mr. Crawford, desirous of accepting as a favour what was intended as such, though he had seen the dockyard again and again, and hoping to be so much the longer with Fanny, was very gratefully disposed to avail himself of, if the Miss Prices were not afraid of the fatigue;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162785,\n            \"Once fairly in the dockyard, he began to reckon upon some happy intercourse with Fanny, as they were very soon joined by a brother lounger of Mr. Price\\u2019s, who was come to take his daily survey of how things went on, and who must prove a far more worthy companion than himself;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 16]\": [\n        [\n            44781,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo,\\u201dreplied Fanny, \\u201cbut we need not give up his profession for all that;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85777,\n            \"Dr. Grant was in the vestibule, and as they stopt to speak to him she found, from Edmund\\u2019s manner, that he _ did _ mean to go with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85849,\n            \"and Fanny had barely time for an unpleasant feeling on the occasion, when Mrs. Grant, with sudden recollection, turned to her and asked for the pleasure of her company too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86012,\n            \"and though Fanny would not venture, even on his encouragement, to such a flight of audacious independence, it was soon settled, that if nothing were heard to the contrary, Mrs. Grant might expect her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86280,\n            \"CHAPTER XXIII \\u201cBut why should Mrs. Grant ask Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86404,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI cannot imagine why Mrs. Grant should think of asking her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86576,\n            \"and I think he will consider it a right thing by Mrs. Grant, as well as by Fanny, that being the _ first _ invitation it should be accepted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86621,\n            \"But he will be very much surprised that Mrs. Grant should ask Fanny at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86920,\n            \"Mrs. Grant has asked Fanny to dinner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87020,\n            \"for Mrs. Grant never used to ask her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87293,\n            \"\\u201cWell, Fanny, it is all happily settled, and without the smallest hesitation on your uncle\\u2019s side.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 17]\": [\n        [\n            609,\n            \"Their homes were so distant, and the circles in which they moved so distinct, as almost to preclude the means of ever hearing of each other\\u2019s existence during the eleven following years, or, at least, to make it very wonderful to Sir Thomas that Mrs. Norris should ever have it in her power to tell them, as she now and then did, in an angry voice, that Fanny had got another child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10254,\n            \"or, perhaps, her very display of the importance of a spare room might have misled Sir Thomas to suppose it really intended for Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10550,\n            \"He could not say he _ wished _ me to take Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11123,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, Lady Bertram,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris, moving to go, \\u201cI can only say that my sole desire is to be of use to your family: and so, if Sir Thomas should ever speak again about my taking Fanny, you will be able to say that my health and spirits put it quite out of the question;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13635,\n            \"and at length determined on a method of proceeding which would obviate the risk of his father\\u2019s thinking he had done too much, and at the same time procure for Fanny the immediate means of exercise, which he could not bear she should be without.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70130,\n            \"She was nearly fainting: all her former habitual dread of her uncle was returning, and with it compassion for him and for almost every one of the party on the development before him, with solicitude on Edmund\\u2019s account indescribable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70175,\n            \"She had found a seat, where in excessive trembling she was enduring all these fearful thoughts, while the other three, no longer under any restraint, were giving vent to their feelings of vexation, lamenting over such an unlooked-for premature arrival as a most untoward event, and without mercy wishing poor Sir Thomas had been twice as long on his passage, or were still in Antigua.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70487,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny was just beginning to collect herself, and to feel that if she staid longer behind it might seem disrespectful, when this point was settled, and being commissioned with the brother and sister\\u2019s apology, saw them preparing to go as she quitted the room herself to perform the dreadful duty of appearing before her uncle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70628,\n            \"Sir Thomas was at that moment looking round him, and saying, \\u201cBut where is Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70647,\n            \"Why do not I see my little Fanny?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70712,\n            \"He had never been so kind, so _ very _ kind to her in his life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70759,\n            \"He led her nearer the light and looked at her again \\u2014 inquired particularly after her health, and then, correcting himself, observed that he need not inquire, for her appearance spoke sufficiently on that point.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70799,\n            \"A fine blush having succeeded the previous paleness of her face, he was justified in his belief of her equal improvement in health and beauty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70826,\n            \"He inquired next after her family, especially William: and his kindness altogether was such as made her reproach herself for loving him so little, and thinking his return a misfortune;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72130,\n            \"The first day I went over Mansfield Wood, and Edmund took the copses beyond Easton, and we brought home six brace between us, and might each have killed six times as many, but we respect your pheasants, sir, I assure you, as much as you could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86961,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cShe will be late,\\u201dsaid Sir Thomas, taking out his watch;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94699,\n            \"and Crawford could mount him without the slightest inconvenience to himself, and with only some scruples to obviate in Sir Thomas, who knew better than his nephew the value of such a loan, and some alarms to reason away in Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95689,\n            \"and Sir Thomas, Mrs. Norris, and Dr. and Mrs. Grant being seated at the table of prime intellectual state and dignity, the remaining six, under Miss Crawford\\u2019s direction, were arranged round the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99364,\n            \"\\u201d Whatever effect Sir Thomas\\u2019 s little harangue might really produce on Mr. Crawford, it raised some awkward sensations in two of the others, two of his most attentive listeners \\u2014 Miss Crawford and Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99444,\n            \"and the other, startled from the agreeable fancies she had been previously indulging on the strength of her brother\\u2019s description, no longer able, in the picture she had been forming of a future Thornton, to shut out the church, sink the clergyman, and see only the respectable, elegant, modernised, and occasional residence of a man of independent fortune, was considering Sir Thomas, with decided ill-will, as the destroyer of all this, and suffering the more from that involuntary forbearance which his character and manner commanded, and from not daring to relieve herself by a single attempt at throwing ridicule on his cause.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100856,\n            \"CHAPTER XXVI William\\u2019s desire of seeing Fanny dance made more than a momentary impression on his uncle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101371,\n            \"Edmund, William, and Fanny did, in their different ways, look and speak as much grateful pleasure in the promised ball as Sir Thomas could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109148,\n            \"To the former she was an interesting object, and he saw with pleasure the general elegance of her appearance, and her being in remarkably good looks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109177,\n            \"The neatness and propriety of her dress was all that he would allow himself to commend in her presence, but upon her leaving the room again soon afterwards, he spoke of her beauty with very decided praise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109287,\n            \"Only think, my dear Sir Thomas, what extraordinary advantages you and I have been the means of giving her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109309,\n            \"The very gown you have been taking notice of is your own generous present to her when dear Mrs. Rushworth married.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109739,\n            \"and besides the gravity and formality of the first great circle, which the manners of neither Sir Thomas nor Lady Bertram were of a kind to do away, she found herself occasionally called on to endure something worse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109936,\n            \"Her own musings were brought to an end on perceiving Mr. Crawford before her, and her thoughts were put into another channel by his engaging her almost instantly for the first two dances.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110014,\n            \"and she so little understood her own claims as to think that if Mr. Crawford had not asked her, she must have been the last to be sought after, and should have received a partner only through a series of inquiry, and bustle, and interference, which would have been terrible;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110071,\n            \"but at the same time there was a pointedness in his manner of asking her which she did not like, and she saw his eye glancing for a moment at her necklace, with a smile \\u2014 she thought there was a smile \\u2014 which made her blush and feel wretched.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110124,\n            \"And though there was no second glance to disturb her, though his object seemed then to be only quietly agreeable, she could not get the better of her embarrassment, heightened as it was by the idea of his perceiving it, and had no composure till he turned away to some one else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110467,\n            \"In a few minutes Sir Thomas came to her, and asked if she were engaged;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110514,\n            \"Sir Thomas brought him to her, saying something which discovered to Fanny, that _ she _ was to lead the way and open the ball;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110620,\n            \"To be urging her opinion against Sir Thomas\\u2019 s was a proof of the extremity of the case;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110640,\n            \"but such was her horror at the first suggestion, that she could actually look him in the face and say that she hoped it might be settled otherwise;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110670,\n            \"in vain, however: Sir Thomas smiled, tried to encourage her, and then looked too serious, and said too decidedly, \\u201cIt must be so, my dear,\\u201dfor her to hazard another word;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110712,\n            \"and she found herself the next moment conducted by Mr. Crawford to the top of the room, and standing there to be joined by the rest of the dancers, couple after couple, as they were formed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110851,\n            \"And to have them away when it was given \\u2014 and for _ her _ to be opening the ball \\u2014 and with Mr. Crawford too!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111066,\n            \"Sir Thomas himself was watching her progress down the dance with much complacency;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111080,\n            \"he was proud of his niece;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111087,\n            \"and without attributing all her personal beauty, as Mrs. Norris seemed to do, to her transplantation to Mansfield, he was pleased with himself for having supplied everything else: education and manners she owed to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111128,\n            \"Miss Crawford saw much of Sir Thomas\\u2019 s thoughts as he stood, and having, in spite of all his wrongs towards her, a general prevailing desire of recommending herself to him, took an opportunity of stepping aside to say something agreeable of Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111177,\n            \"Her praise was warm, and he received it as she could wish, joining in it as far as discretion, and politeness, and slowness of speech would allow, and certainly appearing to greater advantage on the subject than his lady did soon afterwards, when Mary, perceiving her on a sofa very near, turned round before she began to dance, to compliment her on Miss Price\\u2019s looks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111470,\n            \"and, misinterpreting Fanny\\u2019s blushes, still thought she must be doing so when she went to her after the two first dances, and said, with a significant look, \\u201cPerhaps _ you _ can tell me why my brother goes to town to-morrow?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113475,\n            \"\\u201cShe could not recollect what it was that she had heard about one of the Miss Maddoxes, or what it was that Lady Prescott had noticed in Fanny: she was not sure whether Colonel Harrison had been talking of Mr. Crawford or of William when he said he was the finest young man in the room \\u2014 somebody had whispered something to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113806,\n            \"shall I deal for you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114405,\n            \"and at the end of a quarter of an hour\\u2019s silent consideration spontaneously observed, \\u201cSir Thomas, I have been thinking \\u2014 and I am very glad we took Fanny as we did, for now the others are away we feel the good of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114543,\n            \"\\u201d Sir Thomas paused, half smiled, glanced at his niece, and then gravely replied, \\u201cShe will never leave us, I hope, till invited to some other home that may reasonably promise her greater happiness than she knows here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114636,\n            \"and I am sure she is better off here;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114646,\n            \"and besides, I cannot do without her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119551,\n            \"True, I believe he is, generally speaking, kind to her, and so is Sir Thomas in his way;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119592,\n            \"What can Sir Thomas and Edmund together do, what _ do _ they do for her happiness, comfort, honour, and dignity in the world, to what I _ shall _ do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121395,\n            \"\\u201d She had burst away from him, and at that moment Sir Thomas was heard speaking to a servant in his way towards the room they were in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121472,\n            \"She rushed out at an opposite door from the one her uncle was approaching, and was walking up and down the East room in the utmost confusion of contrary feeling, before Sir Thomas\\u2019 s politeness or apologies were over, or he had reached the beginning of the joyful intelligence which his visitor came to communicate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121750,\n            \"but when convinced of his being gone, she was eager to go down and be with her uncle, and have all the happiness of his joy as well as her own, and all the benefit of his information or his conjectures as to what would now be William\\u2019s destination.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126356,\n            \"I am half inclined to think, Fanny, that you do not quite know your own feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126864,\n            \"and getting up and walking about the room with a frown, which Fanny could picture to herself, though she dared not lift up her eyes, he shortly afterwards, and in a voice of authority, said, \\u201cHave you any reason, child, to think ill of Mr. Crawford\\u2019s temper?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127077,\n            \"Sir Thomas came towards the table where she sat in trembling wretchedness, and with a good deal of cold sternness, said, \\u201cIt is of no use, I perceive, to talk to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127138,\n            \"I will, therefore, only add, as thinking it my duty to mark my opinion of your conduct, that you have disappointed every expectation I had formed, and proved yourself of a character the very reverse of what I had supposed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127184,\n            \"For I _ had _, Fanny, as I think my behaviour must have shewn, formed a very favourable opinion of you from the period of my return to England.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127217,\n            \"I had thought you peculiarly free from wilfulness of temper, self-conceit, and every tendency to that independence of spirit which prevails so much in modern days, even in young women, and which in young women is offensive and disgusting beyond all common offence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127267,\n            \"But you have now shewn me that you can be wilful and perverse;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127312,\n            \"You have shewn yourself very, very different from anything that I had imagined.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127533,\n            \"and let me tell you, Fanny, that you may live eighteen years longer in the world without being addressed by a man of half Mr. Crawford\\u2019s estate, or a tenth part of his merits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127741,\n            \"You do not owe me the duty of a child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127752,\n            \"But, Fanny, if your heart can acquit you of _ ingratitude _ \\u2014\\u201dHe ceased.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127771,\n            \"Fanny was by this time crying so bitterly that, angry as he was, he would not press that article farther.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128860,\n            \"And, Fanny\\u201d(turning back again for a moment), \\u201cI shall make no mention below of what has passed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132844,\n            \"though, on Fanny\\u2019s account, he almost dreaded the effect of the communication to Mrs. Norris as much as Fanny herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171884,\n            \"\\u201cThis distressing intelligence, as you may suppose,\\u201dobserved her ladyship, after giving the substance of it, \\u201chas agitated us exceedingly, and we cannot prevent ourselves from being greatly alarmed and apprehensive for the poor invalid, whose state Sir Thomas fears may be very critical;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181416,\n            \"Her aunt was no very methodical narrator, but with the help of some letters to and from Sir Thomas, and what she already knew herself, and could reasonably combine, she was soon able to understand quite as much as she wished of the circumstances attending the story.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181526,\n            \"His having been in the same neighbourhood Fanny already knew.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181889,\n            \"Sir Thomas set off, Edmund would go with him, and the others had been left in a state of wretchedness, inferior only to what followed the receipt of the next letters from London.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182156,\n            \"_ His _ present state Fanny could hardly bear to think of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182479,\n            \"but this, though most material to herself, would be poor consolation to Sir Thomas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182726,\n            \"Fanny was not in the secret of her uncle\\u2019s feelings, Sir Thomas not in the secret of Miss Crawford\\u2019s character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184713,\n            \"If by any officious exertions of his, she is induced to leave Henry\\u2019s protection, there will be much less chance of his marrying her than if she remain with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187328,\n            \"She had lived with him to be reproached as the ruin of all his happiness in Fanny, and carried away no better consolation in leaving him than that she _ had _ divided them.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 18]\": [\n        [\n            8591,\n            \"The time was now come when Sir Thomas expected his sister-in-law to claim her share in their niece, the change in Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s situation, and the improvement in Fanny\\u2019s age, seeming not merely to do away any former objection to their living together, but even to give it the most decided eligibility;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8734,\n            \"and the first time of the subject\\u2019s occurring to her again happening to be when Fanny was present, she calmly observed to her, \\u201cSo, Fanny, you are going to leave us, and live with my sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16686,\n            \"Miss Bertram\\u2019s engagement made him in equity the property of Julia, of which Julia was fully aware;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24599,\n            \"I dare say Mr. Crawford would take my two nieces and me in his barouche, and Edmund can go on horseback, you know, sister, and Fanny will stay at home with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28472,\n            \"and Julia, who was in high good-humour, from the pleasures of the day, did her the justice of exclaiming, \\u201cI must say, ma\\u2019am, that Fanny is as little upon the sofa as anybody in the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31700,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt seems very odd,\\u201dsaid Maria, \\u201cthat you should be staying at home instead of Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31723,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sure she ought to be very much obliged to you,\\u201dadded Julia, hastily leaving the room as she spoke, from a consciousness that she ought to offer to stay at home herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35322,\n            \"\\u201d cried Julia, and running to where he stood with Miss Crawford and Fanny: \\u201cMy dear Edmund, if you were but in orders now, you might perform the ceremony directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40441,\n            \"\\u201d This was a most unjust reflection, but Fanny could allow for it, and let it pass: Julia was vexed, and her temper was hasty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40608,\n            \"\\u201d And she immediately scrambled across the fence, and walked away, not attending to Fanny\\u2019s last question of whether she had seen anything of Miss Crawford and Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41973,\n            \"She felt, as she looked at Julia and Mr. Rushworth, that hers was not the only dissatisfied bosom amongst them: there was gloom on the face of each.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42430,\n            \"but if it is in your way, I will have it in my lap directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46700,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf Miss Bertram were not engaged,\\u201dsaid Fanny cautiously, \\u201cI could sometimes almost think that he admired her more than Julia.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46728,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWhich is, perhaps, more in favour of his liking Julia best, than you, Fanny, may be aware;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50809,\n            \"Lady Bertram, sunk back in one corner of the sofa, the picture of health, wealth, ease, and tranquillity, was just falling into a gentle doze, while Fanny was getting through the few difficulties of her work for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53674,\n            \"Amelia and Agatha may do for Maria and me, but here is nothing for your sister, Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65510,\n            \"Fanny saw and pitied much of this in Julia;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65529,\n            \"Julia made no communication, and Fanny took no liberties.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181537,\n            \"Mr. Rushworth had been gone at this time to Bath, to pass a few days with his mother, and bring her back to town, and Maria was with these friends without any restraint, without even Julia;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 19]\": [\n        [\n            152665,\n            \"\\u201cYou know you had but just settled that my sister Fanny and I should have the other room;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154476,\n            \"Susan and an attendant girl, whose inferior appearance informed Fanny, to her great surprise, that she had previously seen the upper servant, brought in everything necessary for the meal;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154714,\n            \"she was like William, and Fanny hoped to find her like him in disposition and goodwill towards herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155240,\n            \"The Bertrams were all forgotten in detailing the faults of Rebecca, against whom Susan had also much to depose, and little Betsey a great deal more, and who did seem so thoroughly without a single recommendation, that Fanny could not help modestly presuming that her mother meant to part with her when her year was up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155516,\n            \"Fanny in those early days had preferred her to Susan;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155660,\n            \"but the child ran to her mother\\u2019s protection, and Susan could only reproach, which she did very warmly, and evidently hoping to interest Fanny on her side.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156700,\n            \"I charge you, take care of Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157590,\n            \"and though spurning the remonstrances of Susan, given as they were, though very reasonable in themselves, with ill-timed and powerless warmth, was beginning to be influenced by Fanny\\u2019s services and gentle persuasions;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157816,\n            \"Her continual disagreements with her mother, her rash squabbles with Tom and Charles, and petulance with Betsey, were at least so distressing to Fanny that, though admitting they were by no means without provocation, she feared the disposition that could push them to such length must be far from amiable, and from affording any repose to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159319,\n            \"The first solid consolation which Fanny received for the evils of home, the first which her judgment could entirely approve, and which gave any promise of durability, was in a better knowledge of Susan, and a hope of being of service to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159671,\n            \"That her manner was wrong, however, at times very wrong, her measures often ill-chosen and ill-timed, and her looks and language very often indefensible, Fanny could not cease to feel;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159737,\n            \"and new as anything like an office of authority was to Fanny, new as it was to imagine herself capable of guiding or informing any one, she did resolve to give occasional hints to Susan, and endeavour to exercise for her advantage the juster notions of what was due to everybody, and what would be wisest for herself, which her own more favoured education had fixed in her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160458,\n            \"Fanny had peace, and Susan learned to think it no misfortune to be quietly employed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160687,\n            \"Susan had read nothing, and Fanny longed to give her a share in her own first pleasures, and inspire a taste for the biography and poetry which she delighted in herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160930,\n            \"One morning, about this time, Fanny having now been nearly four weeks from Mansfield, a point which she never failed to think over and calculate every day, as she and Susan were preparing to remove, as usual, upstairs, they were stopped by the knock of a visitor, whom they felt they could not avoid, from Rebecca\\u2019s alertness in going to the door, a duty which always interested her beyond any other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162004,\n            \"\\u201d And the consequence was, that Fanny, strange as it was \\u2014 strange, awkward, and distressing \\u2014 found herself and Susan, within ten minutes, walking towards the High Street with Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162977,\n            \"He must content himself with being only generally agreeable, and letting Susan have her share of entertainment, with the indulgence, now and then, of a look or hint for the better-informed and conscious Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165590,\n            \"If, therefore\\u201d(turning again to Fanny), \\u201cyou find yourself growing unwell, and any difficulties arise about your returning to Mansfield, without waiting for the two months to be ended, _ that _ must not be regarded as of any consequence, if you feel yourself at all less strong or comfortable than usual, and will only let my sister know it, give her only the slightest hint, she and I will immediately come down, and take you back to Mansfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168690,\n            \"Fanny was her oracle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168716,\n            \"What Fanny told her of former times dwelt more on her mind than the pages of Goldsmith;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168821,\n            \"Susan, who had an innate taste for the genteel and well-appointed, was eager to hear, and Fanny could not but indulge herself in dwelling on so beloved a theme.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168923,\n            \"and as Fanny grew thoroughly to understand this, she began to feel that when her own release from Portsmouth came, her happiness would have a material drawback in leaving Susan behind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170917,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny checked the tendency of these thoughts as well as she could, but she was within half a minute of starting the idea that Sir Thomas was quite unkind, both to her aunt and to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180978,\n            \"Lady Bertram could not give her much time, or many words, but she felt her, as Fanny\\u2019s sister, to have a claim at Mansfield, and was ready to kiss and like her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190811,\n            \"First as a comfort to Fanny, then as an auxiliary, and last as her substitute, she was established at Mansfield, with every appearance of equal permanency.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190889,\n            \"and after Fanny\\u2019s removal succeeded so naturally to her influence over the hourly comfort of her aunt, as gradually to become, perhaps, the most beloved of the two.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 13]\": [\n        [\n            156099,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny had indeed nothing to convey from aunt Norris, but a message to say she hoped that her god-daughter was a good girl, and learnt her book.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 14]\": [\n        [\n            65111,\n            \"But, Mary, do not fancy that Maria Bertram cares for Henry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111177,\n            \"Her praise was warm, and he received it as she could wish, joining in it as far as discretion, and politeness, and slowness of speech would allow, and certainly appearing to greater advantage on the subject than his lady did soon afterwards, when Mary, perceiving her on a sofa very near, turned round before she began to dance, to compliment her on Miss Price\\u2019s looks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117044,\n            \"Mary was in a state of mind to rejoice in a connexion with the Bertram family, and to be not displeased with her brother\\u2019s marrying a little beneath him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189511,\n            \"and Mary had had enough of her own friends, enough of vanity, ambition, love, and disappointment in the course of the last half-year, to be in need of the true kindness of her sister\\u2019s heart, and the rational tranquillity of her ways.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 15]\": [\n        [\n            118290,\n            \"and though I should never have selected Fanny Price as the girl most likely to attach you, I am now persuaded she is the very one to make you happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118576,\n            \"\\u201cI cannot admit Mrs. Grant to have an equal claim with Fanny and myself, for we shall both have a right in you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118908,\n            \"\\u201cHenry, I think so highly of Fanny Price, that if I could suppose the next Mrs. Crawford would have half the reason which my poor ill-used aunt had to abhor the very name, I would prevent the marriage, if possible;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 16]\": [\n        [\n            15976,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear sister,\\u201dsaid Mary, \\u201cif you can persuade him into anything of the sort, it will be a fresh matter of delight to me to find myself allied to anybody so clever, and I shall only regret that you have not half a dozen daughters to dispose of.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 17]\": [\n        [\n            111177,\n            \"Her praise was warm, and he received it as she could wish, joining in it as far as discretion, and politeness, and slowness of speech would allow, and certainly appearing to greater advantage on the subject than his lady did soon afterwards, when Mary, perceiving her on a sofa very near, turned round before she began to dance, to compliment her on Miss Price\\u2019s looks.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 18]\": [\n        [\n            16967,\n            \"Miss Bertram is certainly the handsomest, and I have found her the most agreeable, but I shall always like Julia best, because you order me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16996,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI shall not talk to you, Henry, but I know you _ will _ like her best at last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64745,\n            \"\\u201cI rather wonder Julia is not in love with Henry,\\u201dwas her observation to Mary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64764,\n            \"\\u201cI dare say she is,\\u201dreplied Mary coldly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64811,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou had better tell Miss Bertram to think of Mr. Rushworth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146669,\n            \"and your eldest cousin, and the Rushworths, and Julia, I am sure of meeting again and again, and all but you.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 19]\": [\n        [\n            155516,\n            \"Fanny in those early days had preferred her to Susan;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155958,\n            \"she could but just speak to be heard, and she said so prettily, \\u2018 Let sister Susan have my knife, mama, when I am dead and buried.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165341,\n            \"I have heard nothing about it yet from my aunt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165440,\n            \"I am aware that you may be left here week after week, if Sir Thomas cannot settle everything for coming himself, or sending your aunt\\u2019s maid for you, without involving the slightest alteration of the arrangements which he may have laid down for the next quarter of a year.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165515,\n            \"I am considering your sister\\u2019s health,\\u201dsaid he, addressing himself to Susan, \\u201cwhich I think the confinement of Portsmouth unfavourable to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165551,\n            \"When you know her as well as I do, I am sure you will agree that she does, and that she ought never to be long banished from the free air and liberty of the country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165590,\n            \"If, therefore\\u201d(turning again to Fanny), \\u201cyou find yourself growing unwell, and any difficulties arise about your returning to Mansfield, without waiting for the two months to be ended, _ that _ must not be regarded as of any consequence, if you feel yourself at all less strong or comfortable than usual, and will only let my sister know it, give her only the slightest hint, she and I will immediately come down, and take you back to Mansfield.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[11, 13]\": [\n        [\n            100612,\n            \"and Sir Thomas, by no means displeased, prolonged the conversation on dancing in general, and was so well engaged in describing the balls of Antigua, and listening to what his nephew could relate of the different modes of dancing which had fallen within his observation, that he had not heard his carriage announced, and was first called to the knowledge of it by the bustle of Mrs. Norris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122171,\n            \"so you may smile upon him with your sweetest smiles this afternoon, and send him back to me even happier than he goes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122214,\n            \"for though she read in too much haste and confusion to form the clearest judgment of Miss Crawford\\u2019s meaning, it was evident that she meant to compliment her on her brother\\u2019s attachment, and even to _ appear _ to believe it serious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122723,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am glad you gave him something considerable,\\u201dsaid Lady Bertram, with most unsuspicious calmness, \\u201cfor _ I _ gave him only \\u00a310.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122766,\n            \"\\u201cUpon my word, he must have gone off with his pockets well lined, and at no expense for his journey to London either!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122966,\n            \"Fanny, William must not forget my shawl if he goes to the East Indies;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122982,\n            \"and I shall give him a commission for anything else that is worth having.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122997,\n            \"I wish he may go to the East Indies, that I may have my shawl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149824,\n            \"when she saw Sir Thomas actually give William notes for the purpose, she was struck with the idea of there being room for a third in the carriage, and suddenly seized with a strong inclination to go with them, to go and see her poor dear sister Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157057,\n            \"She was fond of her sons, especially of William, but Betsey was the first of her girls whom she had ever much regarded.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157091,\n            \"William was her pride;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[11, 14]\": [\n        [\n            11951,\n            \"but she was not disturbed by any alarm for his safety, or solicitude for his comfort, being one of those persons who think nothing can be dangerous, or difficult, or fatiguing to anybody but themselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98190,\n            \"I do not exactly know the distance, but when you get back to Portsmouth, if it is not very far off, you ought to go over and pay your respects to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98226,\n            \"and I could send a little parcel by you that I want to get conveyed to your cousins.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98293,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Norris was beginning an eager assurance of the affability he might depend on, when she was stopped by Sir Thomas\\u2019 s saying with authority, \\u201cI do not advise your going to Brighton, William, as I trust you may soon have more convenient opportunities of meeting;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122723,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am glad you gave him something considerable,\\u201dsaid Lady Bertram, with most unsuspicious calmness, \\u201cfor _ I _ gave him only \\u00a310.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[11, 15]\": [\n        [\n            149824,\n            \"when she saw Sir Thomas actually give William notes for the purpose, she was struck with the idea of there being room for a third in the carriage, and suddenly seized with a strong inclination to go with them, to go and see her poor dear sister Price.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161258,\n            \"Warmed by the sight of such a friend to her son, and regulated by the wish of appearing to advantage before him, she was overflowing with gratitude \\u2014 artless, maternal gratitude \\u2014 which could not be unpleasing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161388,\n            \"They talked of William, a subject on which Mrs. Price could never tire;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[11, 17]\": [\n        [\n            7358,\n            \"His eldest son was careless and extravagant, and had already given him much uneasiness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93518,\n            \"On the morrow they were walking about together with true enjoyment, and every succeeding morrow renewed a _ t\\u00eate-\\u00e0-t\\u00eate _ which Sir Thomas could not but observe with complacency, even before Edmund had pointed it out to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94226,\n            \"His recitals were amusing in themselves to Sir Thomas, but the chief object in seeking them was to understand the reciter, to know the young man by his histories;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94258,\n            \"and he listened to his clear, simple, spirited details with full satisfaction, seeing in them the proof of good principles, professional knowledge, energy, courage, and cheerfulness, everything that could deserve or promise well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94699,\n            \"and Crawford could mount him without the slightest inconvenience to himself, and with only some scruples to obviate in Sir Thomas, who knew better than his nephew the value of such a loan, and some alarms to reason away in Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94976,\n            \"The return of Henry Crawford, and the arrival of William Price, had much to do with it, but much was still owing to Sir Thomas\\u2019 s more than toleration of the neighbourly attempts at the Parsonage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98293,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Norris was beginning an eager assurance of the affability he might depend on, when she was stopped by Sir Thomas\\u2019 s saying with authority, \\u201cI do not advise your going to Brighton, William, as I trust you may soon have more convenient opportunities of meeting;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100612,\n            \"and Sir Thomas, by no means displeased, prolonged the conversation on dancing in general, and was so well engaged in describing the balls of Antigua, and listening to what his nephew could relate of the different modes of dancing which had fallen within his observation, that he had not heard his carriage announced, and was first called to the knowledge of it by the bustle of Mrs. Norris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100736,\n            \"My dear Sir Thomas, we have settled it that the carriage should come back for you, and Edmund and William.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100856,\n            \"CHAPTER XXVI William\\u2019s desire of seeing Fanny dance made more than a momentary impression on his uncle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100933,\n            \"and having thought the matter over, and taken his resolution in quiet independence, the result of it appeared the next morning at breakfast, when, after recalling and commending what his nephew had said, he added, \\u201cI do not like, William, that you should leave Northamptonshire without this indulgence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101371,\n            \"Edmund, William, and Fanny did, in their different ways, look and speak as much grateful pleasure in the promised ball as Sir Thomas could desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113475,\n            \"\\u201cShe could not recollect what it was that she had heard about one of the Miss Maddoxes, or what it was that Lady Prescott had noticed in Fanny: she was not sure whether Colonel Harrison had been talking of Mr. Crawford or of William when he said he was the finest young man in the room \\u2014 somebody had whispered something to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114157,\n            \"\\u201cAnd there is no reason to suppose,\\u201dadded Sir Thomas, \\u201cbut that his visits to us may now be tolerably frequent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121750,\n            \"but when convinced of his being gone, she was eager to go down and be with her uncle, and have all the happiness of his joy as well as her own, and all the benefit of his information or his conjectures as to what would now be William\\u2019s destination.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[11, 18]\": [\n        [\n            7601,\n            \"but William determining, soon after her removal, to be a sailor, was invited to spend a week with his sister in Northamptonshire before he went to sea.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7661,\n            \"as well as the sanguine views and spirits of the boy even to the last, and the misery of the girl when he left her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61433,\n            \"and its greatest elegancies and ornaments were a faded footstool of Julia\\u2019s work, too ill done for the drawing-room, three transparencies, made in a rage for transparencies, for the three lower panes of one window, where Tintern Abbey held its station between a cave in Italy and a moonlight lake in Cumberland, a collection of family profiles, thought unworthy of being anywhere else, over the mantelpiece, and by their side, and pinned against the wall, a small sketch of a ship sent four years ago from the Mediterranean by William, with H.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[11, 19]\": [\n        [\n            152636,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI was upstairs, mama, moving my things,\\u201dsaid Susan, in a fearless, self-defending tone, which startled Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154714,\n            \"she was like William, and Fanny hoped to find her like him in disposition and goodwill towards herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156700,\n            \"I charge you, take care of Fanny.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 13]\": [\n        [\n            115,\n            \"and such of their acquaintance as thought Miss Ward and Miss Frances quite as handsome as Miss Maria, did not scruple to predict their marrying with almost equal advantage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191,\n            \"Mr. Norris, a friend of her brother-in-law, with scarcely any private fortune, and Miss Frances fared yet worse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14169,\n            \"and in the course of their progress, her mind became so pleasantly occupied in superintending the fortunes of her eldest niece, as tolerably to quiet her nerves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42356,\n            \"\\u201d Maria was just discontented enough to say directly, \\u201cI think _ you _ have done pretty well yourself, ma\\u2019am.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59481,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo not urge her, madam,\\u201dsaid Edmund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59608,\n            \"but Miss Crawford, looking for a moment with astonished eyes at Mrs. Norris, and then at Fanny, whose tears were beginning to shew themselves, immediately said, with some keenness, \\u201cI do not like my situation: this _ place _ is too hot for me,\\u201dand moved away her chair to the opposite side of the table, close to Fanny, saying to her, in a kind, low whisper, as she placed herself, \\u201cNever mind, my dear Miss Price, this is a cross evening: everybody is cross and teasing, but do not let us mind them \\u201d;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180649,\n            \"Mrs. Norris, however, as most attached to Maria, was really the greatest sufferer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180667,\n            \"Maria was her first favourite, the dearest of all;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 14]\": [\n        [\n            4118,\n            \"Julia Bertram was only twelve, and Maria but a year older.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13521,\n            \"Lady Bertram did: she entirely agreed with her son as to the necessity of it, and as to its being considered necessary by his father;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56791,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo not act anything improper, my dear,\\u201dsaid Lady Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187575,\n            \"Mrs. Norris, whose attachment seemed to augment with the demerits of her niece, would have had her received at home and countenanced by them all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187612,\n            \"and Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s anger against Fanny was so much the greater, from considering _ her _ residence there as the motive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187824,\n            \"It ended in Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s resolving to quit Mansfield and devote herself to her unfortunate Maria, and in an establishment being formed for them in another country, remote and private, where, shut up together with little society, on one side no affection, on the other no judgment, it may be reasonably supposed that their tempers became their mutual punishment.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 17]\": [\n        [\n            218,\n            \"Miss Ward\\u2019s match, indeed, when it came to the point, was not contemptible: Sir Thomas being happily able to give his friend an income in the living of Mansfield;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13521,\n            \"Lady Bertram did: she entirely agreed with her son as to the necessity of it, and as to its being considered necessary by his father;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13558,\n            \"she only wanted him to wait till Sir Thomas\\u2019 s return, and then Sir Thomas might settle it all himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42981,\n            \"for to her the father brought a husband, and the return of the friend most solicitous for her happiness would unite her to the lover, on whom she had chosen that happiness should depend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76793,\n            \"Her sensations were indefinable, and so were they a few minutes afterwards upon hearing Henry Crawford, who had a chair between herself and Tom, ask the latter in an undervoice whether there were any plans for resuming the play after the present happy interruption (with a courteous glance at Sir Thomas), because, in that case, he should make a point of returning to Mansfield at any time required by the party: he was going away immediately, being to meet his uncle at Bath without delay;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79754,\n            \"Sir Thomas resolved to speak seriously to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79815,\n            \"With solemn kindness Sir Thomas addressed her: told her his fears, inquired into her wishes, entreated her to be open and sincere, and assured her that every inconvenience should be braved, and the connexion entirely given up, if she felt herself unhappy in the prospect of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79878,\n            \"Maria had a moment\\u2019s struggle as she listened, and only a moment\\u2019s: when her father ceased, she was able to give her answer immediately, decidedly, and with no apparent agitation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80364,\n            \"Had Sir Thomas applied to his daughter within the first three or four days after Henry Crawford\\u2019s leaving Mansfield, before her feelings were at all tranquillised, before she had given up every hope of him, or absolutely resolved on enduring his rival, her answer might have been different;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187638,\n            \"She persisted in placing his scruples to _ her _ account, though Sir Thomas very solemnly assured her that, had there been no young woman in question, had there been no young person of either sex belonging to him, to be endangered by the society or hurt by the character of Mrs. Rushworth, he would never have offered so great an insult to the neighbourhood as to expect it to notice her.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 18]\": [\n        [\n            7198,\n            \"There was no positive ill-nature in Maria or Julia;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40309,\n            \"\\u201cBut they cannot be very far off, and I think I am equal to as much as Maria, even without help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40564,\n            \"I am not obliged to punish myself for _ her _ sins.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40577,\n            \"The mother I could not avoid, as long as my tiresome aunt was dancing about with the housekeeper, but the son I _ can _ get away from.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40764,\n            \"\\u201cThey desired me to stay \\u2014 my cousin Maria charged me to say that you would find them at that knoll, or thereabouts.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42972,\n            \"Maria was more to be pitied than Julia;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46330,\n            \"Julia might be justified in so doing by the hints of Mrs. Grant, inclined to credit what she wished, and Maria by the hints of Mr. Crawford himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47349,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Bertram did indeed look happy, her eyes were sparkling with pleasure, and she was speaking with great animation, for Julia and her partner, Mr. Crawford, were close to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50190,\n            \"Maria, Julia, Henry Crawford, and Mr. Yates were in the billiard-room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53674,\n            \"Amelia and Agatha may do for Maria and me, but here is nothing for your sister, Mr. Crawford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53989,\n            \"She saw a glance at Maria which confirmed the injury to herself: it was a scheme, a trick;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54010,\n            \"she was slighted, Maria was preferred;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54922,\n            \"Maria\\u2019s countenance was to decide it: if she were vexed and alarmed \\u2014 but Maria looked all serenity and satisfaction, and Julia well knew that on this ground Maria could not be happy but at her expense.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55222,\n            \"but her brother soon returned to business and Lovers\\u2019 Vows, and was eagerly looking over the play, with Mr. Yates\\u2019 s help, to ascertain what scenery would be necessary \\u2014 while Maria and Henry Crawford conversed together in an under-voice, and the declaration with which she began of, \\u201cI am sure I would give up the part to Julia most willingly, but that though I shall probably do it very ill, I feel persuaded _ she _ would do it worse,\\u201dwas doubtless receiving all the compliments it called for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56878,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf I were to decline the part,\\u201dsaid Maria, with renewed zeal, \\u201cJulia would certainly take it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65348,\n            \"The sister with whom she was used to be on easy terms was now become her greatest enemy: they were alienated from each other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65374,\n            \"and Julia was not superior to the hope of some distressing end to the attentions which were still carrying on there, some punishment to Maria for conduct so shameful towards herself as well as towards Mr. Rushworth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65470,\n            \"Maria felt her triumph, and pursued her purpose, careless of Julia;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65484,\n            \"and Julia could never see Maria distinguished by Henry Crawford without trusting that it would create jealousy, and bring a public disturbance at last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77404,\n            \"and so ended all the hopes his selfish vanity had raised in Maria and Julia Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81271,\n            \"and Julia was quite as eager for novelty and pleasure as Maria, though she might not have struggled through so much to obtain them, and could better bear a subordinate situation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188141,\n            \"That Julia escaped better than Maria was owing, in some measure, to a favourable difference of disposition and circumstance, but in a greater to her having been less the darling of that very aunt, less flattered and less spoilt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188196,\n            \"She had been always used to think herself a little inferior to Maria.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188485,\n            \"Maria\\u2019s guilt had induced Julia\\u2019s folly.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[13, 14]\": [\n        [\n            958,\n            \"Sir Thomas sent friendly advice and professions, Lady Bertram dispatched money and baby-linen, and Mrs. Norris wrote the letters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1005,\n            \"Mrs. Norris was often observing to the others that she could not get her poor sister and her family out of her head, and that, much as they had all done for her, she seemed to be wanting to do more;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2942,\n            \"I suppose, sister, you will put the child in the little white attic, near the old nurseries.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2963,\n            \"It will be much the best place for her, so near Miss Lee, and not far from the girls, and close by the housemaids, who could either of them help to dress her, you know, and take care of her clothes, for I suppose you would not think it fair to expect Ellis to wait on her as well as the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3033,\n            \"Indeed, I do not see that you could possibly place her anywhere else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3337,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere will be some difficulty in our way, Mrs. Norris,\\u201dobserved Sir Thomas, \\u201cas to the distinction proper to be made between the girls as they grow up: how to preserve in the minds of my _ daughters _ the consciousness of what they are, without making them think too lowly of their cousin;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3541,\n            \"It will be readily believed that Mrs. Norris did not write to her sister in vain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9237,\n            \"She is choosing a friend and companion exactly where she ought, and I am glad her love of money does not interfere.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9310,\n            \"You know how uncomfortable I feel with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10055,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd I am quite convinced that your being with Mrs. Norris will be as good for your mind as riding has been for your health, and as much for your ultimate happiness too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10281,\n            \"Lady Bertram soon brought the matter to a certainty by carelessly observing to Mrs. Norris \\u2014 \\u201cI think, sister, we need not keep Miss Lee any longer, when Fanny goes to live with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11123,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, Lady Bertram,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris, moving to go, \\u201cI can only say that my sole desire is to be of use to your family: and so, if Sir Thomas should ever speak again about my taking Fanny, you will be able to say that my health and spirits put it quite out of the question;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11217,\n            \"\\u201d Lady Bertram repeated enough of this conversation to her husband to convince him how much he had mistaken his sister-in-law\\u2019s views;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11290,\n            \"but, as she took early care to make him, as well as Lady Bertram, understand that whatever she possessed was designed for their family, he soon grew reconciled to a distinction which, at the same time that it was advantageous and complimentary to them, would enable him better to provide for Fanny himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11678,\n            \"She could not enter into the wrongs of an economist, but she felt all the injuries of beauty in Mrs. Grant\\u2019s being so well settled in life without being handsome, and expressed her astonishment on that point almost as often, though not so diffusely, as Mrs. Norris discussed the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13944,\n            \"and had Lady Bertram ever thought about her own objection again, he might have been excused in her eyes for not waiting till Sir Thomas\\u2019 s return in September, for when September came Sir Thomas was still abroad, and without any near prospect of finishing his business.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14199,\n            \"\\u201cIf poor Sir Thomas were fated never to return, it would be peculiarly consoling to see their dear Maria well married,\\u201dshe very often thought;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14438,\n            \"and, among other means, by seeking an intimacy with the gentleman\\u2019s mother, who at present lived with him, and to whom she even forced Lady Bertram to go through ten miles of indifferent road to pay a morning visit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30153,\n            \"and Mrs. Rushworth, a well-meaning, civil, prosing, pompous woman, who thought nothing of consequence, but as it related to her own and her son\\u2019s concerns, had not yet given over pressing Lady Bertram to be of the party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30210,\n            \"but her placid manner of refusal made Mrs. Rushworth still think she wished to come, till Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s more numerous words and louder tone convinced her of the truth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122723,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am glad you gave him something considerable,\\u201dsaid Lady Bertram, with most unsuspicious calmness, \\u201cfor _ I _ gave him only \\u00a310.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149143,\n            \"And as to the not missing her, which under Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s discussion was the point attempted to be proved, she set herself very steadily against admitting any such thing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149210,\n            \"But Mrs. Norris wanted to persuade her that Fanny could be very well spared \\u2014 _ she _ being ready to give up all her own time to her as requested \\u2014 and, in short, could not really be wanted or missed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149256,\n            \"\\u201cThat may be, sister,\\u201dwas all Lady Bertram\\u2019s reply.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149272,\n            \"\\u201cI dare say you are very right;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157311,\n            \"She might have made just as good a woman of consequence as Lady Bertram, but Mrs. Norris would have been a more respectable mother of nine children on a small income.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180780,\n            \"and neither Lady Bertram nor Tom had received from her the smallest support or attempt at support.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[13, 15]\": [\n        [\n            149824,\n            \"when she saw Sir Thomas actually give William notes for the purpose, she was struck with the idea of there being room for a third in the carriage, and suddenly seized with a strong inclination to go with them, to go and see her poor dear sister Price.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[13, 16]\": [\n        [\n            11678,\n            \"She could not enter into the wrongs of an economist, but she felt all the injuries of beauty in Mrs. Grant\\u2019s being so well settled in life without being handsome, and expressed her astonishment on that point almost as often, though not so diffusely, as Mrs. Norris discussed the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20932,\n            \"It was only the spring twelvemonth before Mr. Norris\\u2019 s death that we put in the apricot against the stable wall, which is now grown such a noble tree, and getting to such perfection, sir,\\u201daddressing herself then to Dr. Grant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20982,\n            \"\\u201cThe tree thrives well, beyond a doubt, madam,\\u201dreplied Dr. Grant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21082,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou were imposed on, ma\\u2019am,\\u201dreplied Dr. Grant: \\u201cthese potatoes have as much the flavour of a Moor Park apricot as the fruit from that tree.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21142,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThe truth is, ma\\u2019am,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Grant, pretending to whisper across the table to Mrs. Norris, \\u201cthat Dr. Grant hardly knows what the natural taste of our apricot is: he is scarcely ever indulged with one, for it is so valuable a fruit;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21264,\n            \"Dr. Grant and Mrs. Norris were seldom good friends;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87897,\n            \"and I cannot but be surprised that such an _ elegant _ lady as Mrs. Grant should not contrive better!\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[13, 17]\": [\n        [\n            561,\n            \"and an answer, which comprehended each sister in its bitterness, and bestowed such very disrespectful reflections on the pride of Sir Thomas as Mrs. Norris could not possibly keep to herself, put an end to all intercourse between them for a considerable period.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            609,\n            \"Their homes were so distant, and the circles in which they moved so distinct, as almost to preclude the means of ever hearing of each other\\u2019s existence during the eleven following years, or, at least, to make it very wonderful to Sir Thomas that Mrs. Norris should ever have it in her power to tell them, as she now and then did, in an angry voice, that Fanny had got another child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            958,\n            \"Sir Thomas sent friendly advice and professions, Lady Bertram dispatched money and baby-linen, and Mrs. Norris wrote the letters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1246,\n            \"\\u2014 but no sooner had he deliberately begun to state his objections, than Mrs. Norris interrupted him with a reply to them all, whether stated or not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1856,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI thoroughly understand you,\\u201dcried Mrs. Norris, \\u201cyou are everything that is generous and considerate, and I am sure we shall never disagree on this point.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2238,\n            \"for Sir Thomas was fully resolved to be the real and consistent patron of the selected child, and Mrs. Norris had not the least intention of being at any expense whatever in her maintenance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2571,\n            \"\\u201d Sir Thomas heard with some surprise that it would be totally out of Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s power to take any share in the personal charge of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2669,\n            \"Poor Mr. Norris\\u2019 s indifferent state of health made it an impossibility: he could no more bear the noise of a child than he could fly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3337,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere will be some difficulty in our way, Mrs. Norris,\\u201dobserved Sir Thomas, \\u201cas to the distinction proper to be made between the girls as they grow up: how to preserve in the minds of my _ daughters _ the consciousness of what they are, without making them think too lowly of their cousin;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10254,\n            \"or, perhaps, her very display of the importance of a spare room might have misled Sir Thomas to suppose it really intended for Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11123,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, Lady Bertram,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris, moving to go, \\u201cI can only say that my sole desire is to be of use to your family: and so, if Sir Thomas should ever speak again about my taking Fanny, you will be able to say that my health and spirits put it quite out of the question;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13439,\n            \"She was sure Sir Thomas had never intended it: and she must say that, to be making such a purchase in his absence, and adding to the great expenses of his stable, at a time when a large part of his income was unsettled, seemed to her very unjustifiable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13944,\n            \"and had Lady Bertram ever thought about her own objection again, he might have been excused in her eyes for not waiting till Sir Thomas\\u2019 s return in September, for when September came Sir Thomas was still abroad, and without any near prospect of finishing his business.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14073,\n            \"Sir Thomas\\u2019 s sending away his son seemed to her so like a parent\\u2019s care, under the influence of a foreboding of evil to himself, that she could not help feeling dreadful presentiments;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14199,\n            \"\\u201cIf poor Sir Thomas were fated never to return, it would be peculiarly consoling to see their dear Maria well married,\\u201dshe very often thought;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14726,\n            \"but, in the meanwhile, as no one felt a doubt of his most cordial pleasure in the connexion, the intercourse of the two families was carried on without restraint, and no other attempt made at secrecy than Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s talking of it everywhere as a matter not to be talked of at present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101081,\n            \"I knew what you were going to say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101131,\n            \"I know you would.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101249,\n            \"She saw decision in his looks, and her surprise and vexation required some minutes\\u2019 silence to be settled into composure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101442,\n            \"Sir Thomas engaged for its giving her very little trouble;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101453,\n            \"and she assured him \\u201cthat she was not at all afraid of the trouble;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101480,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Norris was ready with her suggestions as to the rooms he would think fittest to be used, but found it all prearranged;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101544,\n            \"and as soon as she would listen quietly, could read his list of the families to be invited, from whom he calculated, with all necessary allowance for the shortness of the notice, to collect young people enough to form twelve or fourteen couple: and could detail the considerations which had induced him to fix on the 22nd as the most eligible day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101947,\n            \"She had some extra visits from the housekeeper, and her maid was rather hurried in making up a new dress for her: Sir Thomas gave orders, and Mrs. Norris ran about;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111087,\n            \"and without attributing all her personal beauty, as Mrs. Norris seemed to do, to her transplantation to Mansfield, he was pleased with himself for having supplied everything else: education and manners she owed to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111377,\n            \"\\u201d and Mrs. Norris paid her with as many smiles and courteous words as she had time for, amid so much occupation as she found for herself in making up card-tables, giving hints to Sir Thomas, and trying to move all the chaperons to a better part of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128286,\n            \"but when he looked at his niece, and saw the state of feature and complexion which her crying had brought her into, he thought there might be as much lost as gained by an immediate interview.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128325,\n            \"With a few words, therefore, of no particular meaning, he walked off by himself, leaving his poor niece to sit and cry over what had passed, with very wretched feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128885,\n            \"I shall not even tell your aunt Bertram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132816,\n            \"When Sir Thomas understood this, he felt the necessity of making his own wife and sister-in-law acquainted with the business without delay;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132844,\n            \"though, on Fanny\\u2019s account, he almost dreaded the effect of the communication to Mrs. Norris as much as Fanny herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132870,\n            \"He deprecated her mistaken but well-meaning zeal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132880,\n            \"Sir Thomas, indeed, was, by this time, not very far from classing Mrs. Norris as one of those well-meaning people who are always doing mistaken and very disagreeable things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132917,\n            \"Mrs. Norris, however, relieved him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133038,\n            \"Sir Thomas gave her more credit for discretion on the occasion than she deserved;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[13, 18]\": [\n        [\n            2238,\n            \"for Sir Thomas was fully resolved to be the real and consistent patron of the selected child, and Mrs. Norris had not the least intention of being at any expense whatever in her maintenance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2571,\n            \"\\u201d Sir Thomas heard with some surprise that it would be totally out of Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s power to take any share in the personal charge of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2638,\n            \"Mrs. Norris was sorry to say that the little girl\\u2019s staying with them, at least as things then were, was quite out of the question.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2919,\n            \"and Nanny shall fetch her, however it may put me to inconvenience to have my chief counsellor away for three days.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2942,\n            \"I suppose, sister, you will put the child in the little white attic, near the old nurseries.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2963,\n            \"It will be much the best place for her, so near Miss Lee, and not far from the girls, and close by the housemaids, who could either of them help to dress her, you know, and take care of her clothes, for I suppose you would not think it fair to expect Ellis to wait on her as well as the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3033,\n            \"Indeed, I do not see that you could possibly place her anywhere else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3055,\n            \"\\u201cI hope she will prove a well-disposed girl,\\u201dcontinued Mrs. Norris, \\u201cand be sensible of her uncommon good fortune in having such friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3270,\n            \"It will be an education for the child, said I, only being with her cousins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8591,\n            \"The time was now come when Sir Thomas expected his sister-in-law to claim her share in their niece, the change in Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s situation, and the improvement in Fanny\\u2019s age, seeming not merely to do away any former objection to their living together, but even to give it the most decided eligibility;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8821,\n            \"You have been five years with us, and my sister always meant to take you when Mr. Norris died.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28472,\n            \"and Julia, who was in high good-humour, from the pleasures of the day, did her the justice of exclaiming, \\u201cI must say, ma\\u2019am, that Fanny is as little upon the sofa as anybody in the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28825,\n            \"\\u201cbut I question whether her headache might not be caught _ then _, sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28960,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Norris was talking to Julia, and did not hear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29614,\n            \"Vexed as Edmund was with his mother and aunt, he was still more angry with himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41745,\n            \"and since Julia\\u2019s leaving them they had been met by the gardener, with whom she had made a most satisfactory acquaintance, for she had set him right as to his grandson\\u2019s illness, convinced him that it was an ague, and promised him a charm for it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42382,\n            \"Your lap seems full of good things, and here is a basket of something between us which has been knocking my elbow unmercifully.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[13, 19]\": [\n        [\n            180966,\n            \"By her other aunt, Susan was received with quiet kindness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181018,\n            \"and Susan was more than satisfied, for she came perfectly aware that nothing but ill-humour was to be expected from aunt Norris;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[14, 15]\": [\n        [\n            1782,\n            \"I only meant to observe that it ought not to be lightly engaged in, and that to make it really serviceable to Mrs. Price, and creditable to ourselves, we must secure to the child, or consider ourselves engaged to secure to her hereafter, as circumstances may arise, the provision of a gentlewoman, if no such establishment should offer as you are so sanguine in expecting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26442,\n            \"To avoid her aunt, and look for him, she went out.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[14, 16]\": [\n        [\n            11678,\n            \"She could not enter into the wrongs of an economist, but she felt all the injuries of beauty in Mrs. Grant\\u2019s being so well settled in life without being handsome, and expressed her astonishment on that point almost as often, though not so diffusely, as Mrs. Norris discussed the other.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[14, 17]\": [\n        [\n            463,\n            \"Lady Bertram, who was a woman of very tranquil feelings, and a temper remarkably easy and indolent, would have contented herself with merely giving up her sister, and thinking no more of the matter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            958,\n            \"Sir Thomas sent friendly advice and professions, Lady Bertram dispatched money and baby-linen, and Mrs. Norris wrote the letters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1782,\n            \"I only meant to observe that it ought not to be lightly engaged in, and that to make it really serviceable to Mrs. Price, and creditable to ourselves, we must secure to the child, or consider ourselves engaged to secure to her hereafter, as circumstances may arise, the provision of a gentlewoman, if no such establishment should offer as you are so sanguine in expecting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2029,\n            \"So, if you are not against it, I will write to my poor sister tomorrow, and make the proposal;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3337,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere will be some difficulty in our way, Mrs. Norris,\\u201dobserved Sir Thomas, \\u201cas to the distinction proper to be made between the girls as they grow up: how to preserve in the minds of my _ daughters _ the consciousness of what they are, without making them think too lowly of their cousin;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3850,\n            \"and Lady Bertram, without taking half so much trouble, or speaking one word where he spoke ten, by the mere aid of a good-humoured smile, became immediately the less awful character of the two.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6958,\n            \"She was a woman who spent her days in sitting, nicely dressed, on a sofa, doing some long piece of needlework, of little use and no beauty, thinking more of her pug than her children, but very indulgent to the latter when it did not put herself to inconvenience, guided in everything important by Sir Thomas, and in smaller concerns by her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7236,\n            \"From about the time of her entering the family, Lady Bertram, in consequence of a little ill-health, and a great deal of indolence, gave up the house in town, which she had been used to occupy every spring, and remained wholly in the country, leaving Sir Thomas to attend his duty in Parliament, with whatever increase or diminution of comfort might arise from her absence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10352,\n            \"I thought you had settled it with Sir Thomas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11123,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, Lady Bertram,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Norris, moving to go, \\u201cI can only say that my sole desire is to be of use to your family: and so, if Sir Thomas should ever speak again about my taking Fanny, you will be able to say that my health and spirits put it quite out of the question;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11878,\n            \"He could not think Lady Bertram quite equal to supply his place with them, or rather, to perform what should have been her own;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13521,\n            \"Lady Bertram did: she entirely agreed with her son as to the necessity of it, and as to its being considered necessary by his father;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13944,\n            \"and had Lady Bertram ever thought about her own objection again, he might have been excused in her eyes for not waiting till Sir Thomas\\u2019 s return in September, for when September came Sir Thomas was still abroad, and without any near prospect of finishing his business.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14199,\n            \"\\u201cIf poor Sir Thomas were fated never to return, it would be peculiarly consoling to see their dear Maria well married,\\u201dshe very often thought;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95134,\n            \"His readiness, however, in agreeing to dine at the Parsonage, when the general invitation was at last hazarded, after many debates and many doubts as to whether it were worth while, \\u201cbecause Sir Thomas seemed so ill inclined, and Lady Bertram was so indolent!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95495,\n            \"\\u201cWhat shall I do, Sir Thomas?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95528,\n            \"He was a whist player himself, and perhaps might feel that it would not much amuse him to have her for a partner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98014,\n            \"\\u201d Sotherton was a word to catch Mrs. Norris, and being just then in the happy leisure which followed securing the odd trick by Sir Thomas\\u2019 s capital play and her own against Dr. and Mrs. Grant\\u2019s great hands, she called out, in high good-humour, \\u201cSotherton!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98293,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Norris was beginning an eager assurance of the affability he might depend on, when she was stopped by Sir Thomas\\u2019 s saying with authority, \\u201cI do not advise your going to Brighton, William, as I trust you may soon have more convenient opportunities of meeting;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111177,\n            \"Her praise was warm, and he received it as she could wish, joining in it as far as discretion, and politeness, and slowness of speech would allow, and certainly appearing to greater advantage on the subject than his lady did soon afterwards, when Mary, perceiving her on a sofa very near, turned round before she began to dance, to compliment her on Miss Price\\u2019s looks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113475,\n            \"\\u201cShe could not recollect what it was that she had heard about one of the Miss Maddoxes, or what it was that Lady Prescott had noticed in Fanny: she was not sure whether Colonel Harrison had been talking of Mr. Crawford or of William when he said he was the finest young man in the room \\u2014 somebody had whispered something to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114271,\n            \"and as Sir Thomas thought it best for each daughter that the permission should be granted, Lady Bertram, though in her own good-nature she would not have prevented it, was lamenting the change it made in the prospect of Julia\\u2019s return, which would otherwise have taken place about this time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114330,\n            \"A great deal of good sense followed on Sir Thomas\\u2019 s side, tending to reconcile his wife to the arrangement.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114405,\n            \"and at the end of a quarter of an hour\\u2019s silent consideration spontaneously observed, \\u201cSir Thomas, I have been thinking \\u2014 and I am very glad we took Fanny as we did, for now the others are away we feel the good of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114543,\n            \"\\u201d Sir Thomas paused, half smiled, glanced at his niece, and then gravely replied, \\u201cShe will never leave us, I hope, till invited to some other home that may reasonably promise her greater happiness than she knows here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181271,\n            \"Lady Bertram did not think deeply, but, guided by Sir Thomas, she thought justly on all important points;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187894,\n            \"Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s removal from Mansfield was the great supplementary comfort of Sir Thomas\\u2019 s life.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[14, 18]\": [\n        [\n            2094,\n            \"I will send Nanny to London on purpose, and she may have a bed at her cousin the saddler\\u2019s, and the child be appointed to meet her there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2768,\n            \"\\u201cThen she had better come to us,\\u201dsaid Lady Bertram, with the utmost composure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2942,\n            \"I suppose, sister, you will put the child in the little white attic, near the old nurseries.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2963,\n            \"It will be much the best place for her, so near Miss Lee, and not far from the girls, and close by the housemaids, who could either of them help to dress her, you know, and take care of her clothes, for I suppose you would not think it fair to expect Ellis to wait on her as well as the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3033,\n            \"Indeed, I do not see that you could possibly place her anywhere else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3308,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI hope she will not tease my poor pug,\\u201dsaid Lady Bertram;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6958,\n            \"She was a woman who spent her days in sitting, nicely dressed, on a sofa, doing some long piece of needlework, of little use and no beauty, thinking more of her pug than her children, but very indulgent to the latter when it did not put herself to inconvenience, guided in everything important by Sir Thomas, and in smaller concerns by her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35092,\n            \"\\u201d Mr. Crawford smiled his acquiescence, and stepping forward to Maria, said, in a voice which she only could hear, \\u201cI do not like to see Miss Bertram so near the altar.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114271,\n            \"and as Sir Thomas thought it best for each daughter that the permission should be granted, Lady Bertram, though in her own good-nature she would not have prevented it, was lamenting the change it made in the prospect of Julia\\u2019s return, which would otherwise have taken place about this time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188346,\n            \"This had been her motive in going to her cousin\\u2019s.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[14, 19]\": [\n        [\n            171554,\n            \"she must have something to write about, even to her niece;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180978,\n            \"Lady Bertram could not give her much time, or many words, but she felt her, as Fanny\\u2019s sister, to have a claim at Mansfield, and was ready to kiss and like her;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[15, 17]\": [\n        [\n            774,\n            \"and she addressed Lady Bertram in a letter which spoke so much contrition and despondence, such a superfluity of children, and such a want of almost everything else, as could not but dispose them all to a reconciliation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1782,\n            \"I only meant to observe that it ought not to be lightly engaged in, and that to make it really serviceable to Mrs. Price, and creditable to ourselves, we must secure to the child, or consider ourselves engaged to secure to her hereafter, as circumstances may arise, the provision of a gentlewoman, if no such establishment should offer as you are so sanguine in expecting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119684,\n            \"She was almost at the door, and not chusing by any means to take so much trouble in vain, she still went on, after a civil reception, a short sentence about being waited for, and a \\u201cLet Sir Thomas know\\u201dto the servant.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[15, 19]\": [\n        [\n            162936,\n            \"A quick-looking girl of Susan\\u2019s age was the very worst third in the world: totally different from Lady Bertram, all eyes and ears;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[16, 18]\": [\n        [\n            87684,\n            \"Mrs. Grant thinks it a civility due to _ us _ to take a little notice of you, or else it would never have come into her head, and you may be very certain that, if your cousin Julia had been at home, you would not have been asked at all.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[17, 18]\": [\n        [\n            1916,\n            \"and, though I could never feel for this little girl the hundredth part of the regard I bear your own dear children, nor consider her, in any respect, so much my own, I should hate myself if I were capable of neglecting her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2238,\n            \"for Sir Thomas was fully resolved to be the real and consistent patron of the selected child, and Mrs. Norris had not the least intention of being at any expense whatever in her maintenance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2542,\n            \"and, in reply to Lady Bertram\\u2019s calm inquiry of \\u201cWhere shall the child come to first, sister, to you or to us?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2571,\n            \"\\u201d Sir Thomas heard with some surprise that it would be totally out of Mrs. Norris\\u2019 s power to take any share in the personal charge of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2787,\n            \"After a short pause Sir Thomas added with dignity, \\u201cYes, let her home be in this house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3087,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cShould her disposition be really bad,\\u201dsaid Sir Thomas, \\u201cwe must not, for our own children\\u2019s sake, continue her in the family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6958,\n            \"She was a woman who spent her days in sitting, nicely dressed, on a sofa, doing some long piece of needlework, of little use and no beauty, thinking more of her pug than her children, but very indulgent to the latter when it did not put herself to inconvenience, guided in everything important by Sir Thomas, and in smaller concerns by her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114271,\n            \"and as Sir Thomas thought it best for each daughter that the permission should be granted, Lady Bertram, though in her own good-nature she would not have prevented it, was lamenting the change it made in the prospect of Julia\\u2019s return, which would otherwise have taken place about this time.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[17, 19]\": [\n        [\n            165440,\n            \"I am aware that you may be left here week after week, if Sir Thomas cannot settle everything for coming himself, or sending your aunt\\u2019s maid for you, without involving the slightest alteration of the arrangements which he may have laid down for the next quarter of a year.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170917,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny checked the tendency of these thoughts as well as she could, but she was within half a minute of starting the idea that Sir Thomas was quite unkind, both to her aunt and to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190923,\n            \"In _ her _ usefulness, in Fanny\\u2019s excellence, in William\\u2019s continued good conduct and rising fame, and in the general well-doing and success of the other members of the family, all assisting to advance each other, and doing credit to his countenance and aid, Sir Thomas saw repeated, and for ever repeated, reason to rejoice in what he had done for them all, and acknowledge the advantages of early hardship and discipline, and the consciousness of being born to struggle and endure.\"\n        ]\n    ]\n}"